<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE>Introduction of IAEA Director General  to a Panel on Non-Proliferation at the Annual Conference of Japan Atomic Industrial Forum, April 1993</TITLE>
<BODY>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Introduction of IAEA Director General to a Panel on Non-Proliferation at the Annual Conference of Japan Atomic Industrial Forum, April 1993</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Panel on Non-Proliferation at the Annual Conference of Japan Atomic Industrial Forum, April 1993</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Yokohama, Japan</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>16 April 1993</H4>
<P><HR>I should like to limit my remarks in this first round of the panel to questions of verification of non-proliferation commitments - essentially the safeguards system of the IAEA.  I must stress, however, that the verification system is only one component among many to prevent a spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.  I should also stress that safeguards inspectors area not nuclear policemen who can physically intervene and stop proliferation.  They are observers reporting.
<P>The most important barriers to proliferation lie in the technological and political-security fields.  Some 150 States have adhered to the Non-Proliferation Treaty.  Most of the developing countries parties are not able technologically to develop nuclear weapons.  A concern, however, is that more and more States in this group are rising to the technological level where the option to make nuclear weapons may be available - if the wish is there.  Many States - industrialized and developing alike - have adhered because they feel no political-security need for the weapons.  They may, for instance, through membership in an alliance be protected by a nuclear umbrella.  Some countries have concluded that, although nuclear weapons might offer them some advantages, on balance it might be more dangerous to have these weapons than not to have them.  We are often inclined to kill a poisonous snake whether it is attacking or not.
<P>Against this background we can conclude that detente - globally and regionally - is the most important political means to reduce the motivation to go for nuclear weapons.  Export restrictions are another important factor that may make acquisition of weapons capacity more difficult, if the will to acquire them has not been neutralized.
<P>Let me  now focus on verification.<BR>
<P>Many international treaty commitments do not have any specific arrangements for verification of compliance. Assurance about full respect for commitments regarding non-proliferation, however, is so important that treaties on this subject contain arrangements for verification.  For practically all countries that pledge themselves not to acquire nuclear weapons it is important to feel sure that other countries which have made similar pledges - notably those in the same region - actually respect their pledges.
<P>The task of international verification - safeguards - has been entrusted to the International Atomic Energy Agency, which is located in Vienna.  But I should also mention that the European Community has its own internal safeguards which interact with those of the IAEA.  Further, Argentina and Brazil have a joint bilateral verification mechanism which is to co-operate with the IAEA.  And the Republic of Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea are negotiating - so far without agreement - about mutual inspections under the agreement on a  denuclearized Korean peninsula.
<P>IAEA inspection is thus not the only possible verification mechanism - but it is the most important. The Agency's Safeguards Department has a staff of about 500 people, of whom some 200 are inspectors.  There is an office in Tokyo with a few resident inspectors and another one in Toronto but most inspectors are resident in Vienna and travel to the nuclear installations they inspect in various parts of the world.  The annual cost of the IAEA safeguards is about US $60 million - about one percent of the cost of  B2 bomber.  We are under constant pressure from our Member States to cut the costs.  At the same time, we have the obligation to perform the safeguards in any State that submits installations for verification.  Thus, the Agency is now asked to verify all nuclear installations in South Africa and it is expected soon to do so in Argentina and Brazil.  When Ukraine joins the NPT - as it is expected to do - a large number of nuclear installations will have to be inspected.  The Agency is preparing for it.
<P>Now let me turn to the effects that the case of Iraq has had on the safeguards verification system.
<P>At the end of the Gulf War, the Security Council adopted resolution 687 under which Iraq was to accept not to possess any capacity to make nuclear weapons or nuclear-weapons-usable material and the Agency was given the task to ensure destruction or removal or rendering harmless anything incompatible with the resolution.  Like the United Nations Special Commission for Iraq, the Agency was given extensive rights for inspection and these rights were expressly accepted by Iraq in an exchange of letters.
<P>Already the analysis of the results of the first IAEA inspection in Iraq showed that Iraq had been engaged in a secret programme of enrichment of uranium and further inspections gradually mapped a broad secret programme in the field of enrichment and weaponization.
<P>Iraq was - and is - a party to the Treaty of the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the IAEA had carried out safeguards inspections at the Tuwaitha nuclear centre for many years.  Thus, side by side with declared and inspected activities, Iraq had been carrying out a large secret programme in violation of the NPT - since it obviously aimed at the making of nuclear weapons, and in violation of the safeguards agreement - since it should have been declared.  It should be noted that Iraq had not made use of any of the quantities which it had declared of highly enriched uranium for its bomb programme.  What had been placed under safeguards inspection had been left untouched, presumably in the awareness that any violation in this regard would have been reported immediately and led to some international reaction.
<P>The discovery of the secret programme in Iraq led to serious questions about the verification system.  Although some critics have wanted to see in this discovery a failure of the system, it would be more exact to say that the discovery demonstrated the limitations which existed in the system - as it was organized and practiced.
<P>The system was geared to control and verify nuclear material and nuclear installations declared by the inspected State.  What then about the possibility of secret non-declared installations?  The inspectors cannot roam large territories in blind search of non-declared nuclear installations and the Agency has no espionage organization or satellites.
<P>What the case of Iraq showed was above all the effect of the limitation on information upon the safeguards system.  It does verify that hundreds of declared nuclear installations and vast quantities of declared nuclear material around the world remains in exclusively peaceful use.  It is quite important to know that there is no diversion of material from the peaceful civilian sector to a secret weapons sector.
<P>The questions that the case of Iraq evoked were, first, are there more cases like Iraq and, second, what can be done to strengthen the safeguards system so that it may discover nuclear material and installations which have not been declared.
<P>I have said in response to the second question that the IAEA needs three kinds of access.  We must first have access to information to know where to go.
<P>In this respect, important things have been done in the Agency since Iraq.  A system under which States report to the IAEA on exports of and imports of nuclear material and equipment has been adopted and recommended to Members.  Had we had such a system before the Gulf War, it is possible that a pattern of procurement would have become visible which would have led to serious questions.  Secondly, while before Iraq the Agency was not informed by Members about findings from satellites or other national means of detection, it now does receive such information.  Some Members have felt uneasy about the Agency receiving "intelligence" and it is clear that all information must be critically analysed because there is much disinformation circulating.  However, if the Agency is to be a watchdog - and not an ostrich - it must be able to receive information from Members and make use of it.
<P>The second important measure taken in the Agency is to assert the right to access for inspectors to any site which the Agency has reasons to believe is safeguards relevant - regardless of whether it has been declared.  This is what has happened in the case of the DPRK.  The Agency has very good reason to believe that two sites which it has learnt about are nuclear-waste-related and safeguards relevant and it insists upon its right of inspecting them.  When this right has not been granted so far by DPRK, the Agency's Board of Governors has made of the third kind of access which I referred to - namely access to the Security Council.  I hope it will be possible to resume inspections and make all the inspections we have requested in the DPRK without any need for action by the Security Council, but the Council is the competent body to act regarding international peace and security and full acceptance of the safeguards verification system is an issue that the Council will not - for sure - ignore.
<P>In conclusion, while the case of Iraq demonstrated the limitations which existed on the safeguards verification system, the case of the DPRK shows the greater capacity of the strengthened verification system.  It would be rash to guarantee that any violation of non-proliferation pledges would be discovered with 100% certainty - but I think one can assert that the chance of detection of secret programmes or even some lesser violations are much greater today than before the Iraq case.<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
