<HTML>
<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE>Non-Proliferation:  Past, Present and Future</TITLE>
<BODY>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Non-Proliferation:  Past, Present and Future</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address of IAEA Director General at the International Conference Nuclear Technology and Politics</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Rjukan, Norway</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>17 June 1993</H4>
<P><HR>Especially after the discovery of the secret nuclear weapons programme of Iraq and the break-up of the Soviet Union we have seen many warnings that the Non-Proliferation Treaty and other barriers against nuclear proliferation are insufficient.  Without ignoring the specific new risks that can be identified, one can - and I do - take a much more optimistic view, namely that it should be possible to consolidate the present non-proliferation commitments, to universalize them and to achieve a rollback in the case of non-declared de facto nuclear-weapon States - and to bring about far-reaching nuclear disarmament among the nuclear-weapon States.
<P>Some experts seem to think that the break-down of the cold war has destroyed order and discipline and can lead to nuclear "recklessness" among "client States" which were formerly held in tight reins.  Whatever the truth - if any - in this gloomy vision, it is offset by the expanding active co-operation of the nuclear-weapon States in favour of non-proliferation and many other things.  I would worry more about a possible change of regime in Russia and China, and a break down of the non-ideological pragmatic co-operation between major powers which we now witness daily.
<P>Is there justification for the optimism which I express and which is in line with even more daring recent visions of Robert McNamara, Gerard Smith and others of a nuclear-weapon-free world?  We must recognize, of course, that when we look back into the past, we find that the early optimism and idealism which characterized the Baruch plan proved unrealistic.  The antagonistic world immediately after the second world war was not a possible framework for international control of all nuclear material and facilities - nor has the present world reached a level of co-operation that would allow such a scheme.
<P>The "Atoms for Peace" plan declared by President Eisenhower was certainly less radical than the Baruch plan, but still overoptimistic for its time in projecting an international agency to remove fissionable material from the stockpiles of the three weapons States then existing and distribute them to others for peaceful use.  It is nevertheless to the "Atoms for Peace" plan that we owe a central part of the non-proliferation strategy of the last 40 years, namely the sharing of peaceful nuclear technology in return for pledges of peaceful use.  This dual approach characterizes the IAEA Statute with its objectives of enlarging the contribution of atomic energy to peace on the one hand and of ensuring "so far as it is able" that the transfer of technology will not serve any military purpose.  The provisions of the Statute which allow the Agency to "acquire or establish" "facilities, plants and equipment" in the nuclear field (Art. III: A:7) or to "establish control over the use of special fissionable materials received by the Agency, in order to ensure that these materials are used only for peaceful purposes" are echoes of the early internationalism.  They have not been used so far, but might conceivably become practicable if we continue ambitiously to move toward a nuclear-weapon-free world.
<P>Before I describe how in the coming years we might come back to the optimistic ambitions of the early days in the nuclear field, I must, however, discuss the approach which has been developed to non-proliferation during the many years in between - originally modest, with time increasingly stronger.
<P>President Kennedy's gloomy vision of a world of dozens of nuclear-weapon States assumed that States would acquire nuclear weapons if they reached the technical level which enabled them to do so.  That this pessimistic vision did not come true is due to the realistic and tenacious work which has resulted in what we today term "the non-proliferation regime".  It builds to a great extent but not exclusively on incentives and disincentives.  The central idea of the Atoms for Peace is an incentive to non-proliferation in the shape of offers of nuclear technology on condition of pledges of exclusively peaceful use.  A continuation of the earlier American policy of secrecy would most certainly have provided an incentive for many States to develop enrichment and nuclear power technology indigenously - without any non-proliferation pledges.
<P>Originally, of course, the pledges of exclusively peaceful use had regard to the particular nuclear technology or nuclear material imported.  With the Non-Proliferation Treaty a quantum leap was taken and the required pledge of exclusively peaceful use was extended to cover all nuclear installations and material, in return for pledges of facilitation of the transfer of nuclear technology and of efforts at disarmament.  With this development non-proliferation graduated from having been a condition attached to the export of individual items to a comprehensive general policy of mutually reinforcing elements.
<P>Underlying the non-proliferation regime is the understanding that the major incentive to acquire nuclear weapons is national security concerns.  To eliminate the incentives the concerns must be allayed.  In the case of many countries the concerns were met through the nuclear umbrellas offered by alliances.  Other countries - like Sweden and Switzerland - concluded themselves that it might be even more dangerous to have than not to have nuclear weapons and renounced such weapons out of fear of being subject to pre-emptive nuclear strikes in a crisis.  Other countries were given a measure of assurance by the declarations made by nuclear-weapon States in the Security Council, promising non-use of nuclear weapons against non-nuclear-weapon States.  To the vast majority of developing countries nuclear weapons were not in 1970 a realistic security tool.
<P>There has sometimes been a tendency to describe comprehensive IAEA safeguards as  the key barrier to proliferation.  I would certainly not underestimate the role of the IAEA safeguards system, but it is important to recognize that the creation and maintenance of political-security incentives to non-proliferation is the most crucial factor.  Safeguards are not in themselves an incentive to non-proliferation, but through the confidence which effective verification creates, they help to eliminate security concerns which might otherwise arise about neighbours or other States perceived as potential adversaries.
<P>It must be remembered, however, that if a State begins to perceive a strong security need for nuclear weapons, its formal adherence to the NPT and the application of full-scope safeguards may not prevent it either from withdrawing from the NPT or from trying secretly to develop or acquire the weapons.  One must therefore in no case lose sight of the importance of maintaining the political/security disincentive to nuclear weapons acquisition.  The main reason for my optimism about non-proliferation lies precisely in the detente of today and the consequent reduction in political/security incentives to acquire nuclear weapons.  With the drastically reduced risk of a general nuclear conflagration and with accelerating nuclear disarmament there is no general political/security incentive for non-nuclear-weapon States to abandon their status.  This perception may well have helped Argentina and Brazil to renounce any nuclear weapon option in favour of non-proliferation pledges.  South Africa's decision to adhere to the NPT and to terminate its own weapons programme is evidently linked to the writing off of any threat from Communist-inspired countries.
<P>We can also see how the remaining principal proliferation problems are linked to perceived political/security considerations - in the Middle East, on the Indian sub-continent and on the Korean peninsula.  It is evident then that the main effort to prevent further proliferation and to achieve a rollback, as in South Africa, must be made in the political/security sphere and consist in the creation of peace and detente and in security guarantees.
<P>Let me turn, however, to the role of international verification.  Confidence about an exclusively peaceful use of nuclear installations and material can only come from transparency.  The safeguards system may be said to be a  form of institutionalized transparency.
<P>The technical objective of safeguards verification has been stated to be to "deter from diversion by risk of detection".  This formulation creates the impression that the system is a genuine barrier, deterring proliferation.  It is true, of course, that some State which might have become tempted to develop nuclear weapons after once having renounced them and having accepted safeguards, might be deterred from the temptation because it would know that the reactions of other States would be very strong if the safeguards system reported diversion.  In most cases, however, the function of the system is to provide the confidence that the State cannot itself create by its own declarations that its material and installations under safeguards are used only for peaceful purposes.
<P>The verification system, operated by the IAEA, now costing some $65 million per year and currently employing some 500 people of whom some 200 are inspectors, is essentially an audit system.  Safeguards operated under the NPT focus on nuclear material and its basic features are material accountancy supplemented by containment and surveillance.  This focus on the nuclear material - as the crucial material for weapons - emanated from a wish to minimize intrusion and to guard against industrial espionage by inspectors.  Regrettably the approach does somewhat limit the vision of the inspectors.  This might be one feature which should be taken into account in efforts to increase confidence by greater transparency.  Inspectors should have greater freedom of movement.
<P>Other limitations upon the safeguards system relate to its capacity of detection.  It is geared to detect so-called "significant quantities" of nuclear material - some 8 kg of Pu or 25 kg of HEU - not gram quantities.  Both in the case of Iraq and in the case of Romania gram quantities of Pu were separated without being detected by safeguards.  The same might be the case in the DPRK.  This is a consciously introduced limitation.  If it were at all possible to design - and it probably is not - a fine-meshed verification system that would detect very small quantities of diversion it would be unacceptably costly.  Moreover it could give rise to a disturbingly high number of false alarms.  No one has therefore suggested such a sharpening of the system.
<P>Another limitation is that the safeguards system can only assure us about non-diversion here and now.  It is like a radar scanning the horizon.  It does not tell us about the intentions of governments - what they might do tomorrow.
<P>A further limitation, which became evident in the case of Iraq, was that the system has been limited, in practice, to declared programmes.  This limitation has been well understood by governments, but it was the cause of a lot of criticism after the revelation of the secret programme in Iraq.  The Agency, not knowing and reporting about the existence and locations of the facilities in the Iraqi enrichment programme, has even been accused of giving Iraq a "clean bill of health" before the Gulf War.  This is an exaggerated criticism.  The careful reader would have seen that the Agency only reported that "all material under safeguards has been accounted for".  In fact, Iraq did not, as was feared by some, divert any of this material to its weapon programme.  In this sense safeguards acted as the deterrent they were intended to be.
<P>After the revelations in Iraq, which raised the question as to whether the increasing number of adherents to the NPT on the one end masked increasing disregard on the other, the demands on the safeguards system have changed.  Increased assurance is now sought against the existence of undeclared material and facilities and with the political momentum created by the shock of Iraq the Agency's Board of Governors and Secretariat have taken a number of steps designed to enhance the Agency's ability to uncover non-declared nuclear installations and material.  I have referred to the need for three types of access:  access to information, access to sites and access to the Security Council.
<P>The most crucial element for discovering secret nuclear activities is access to information.  If the State accepting safeguards withholds information about some nuclear activities, the information must come from somewhere else.  International inspectors cannot roam vast territories in blind search for secret installations or hidden material.  They must be directed to specific places and installations - as they were in Iraq thanks to information obtained through defectors and satellites.  The IAEA has neither satellites nor spies.  However, it amasses a lot of information from its overall verification activities; it is beginning to obtain a lot of information from Member States about exports and imports of nuclear material and equipment; it seeks to extract clues from an analysis of media and other open sources, and - since Iraq - it does receive some information which Member States have obtained through national means, e.g. satellites.  Some Members have not been comfortable with the idea that the Agency might receive "intelligence" information  - and the DPRK has denounced the reliance on satellite imagery.  I have taken the view, supported by most Members, that the Agency cannot ignore any relevant information.   However, in view of the existence of much disinformation and erroneous information, the Agency must critically examine all information available to it.
<P>Secondly, there must be a right of access to sites about which relevant information has been obtained.  In the case of Iraq, that right was founded upon cease-fire conditions and is unlimited.  For NPT-type safeguards the IAEA is now stressing its right to undertake so-called special inspections.  Despite strong resistance the Agency has asserted that right in the DPRK.  To those who point out that the Agency never asserted a right of special inspection of a non-declared location prior to the case of the DPRK, I would respond that this is simply because we have not previously been in possession of any information about non-declared sites meriting such inspection.
<P>Thirdly where access to information and to sites is not forthcoming, access to the Security Council assumes particular importance.  The relationship agreement between the United Nations and the Agency provides for prompt interaction between the two organizations, including the Security Council.  The Agency is obliged to refer cases of non-compliance with a safeguards agreement to the Security Council which may then decide to take enforcement action.  In the Gulf War and its aftermath, the Security Council's use of its power as the primary repositary of enforcement action in the UN system resulted, inter alia, in Iraq having to concede far-reaching rights of inspection for the IAEA and the dismantling of its nuclear-weapons-related programme.
<P>It may be unrealistic to assume - and it is at least uncertain - that the Security Council would marshall substantial military might in every case which appeared to involve nuclear proliferation.  We can, however, be sure that the Council will be firm in taking whatever measures it deems fit in the event of further breaches of agreement.  Here I should recall the Council's Summit Statement of 31 January 1992 which emphasized not only the integral role of fully effective IAEA safeguards in implementing the NPT but the Council's readiness to take "appropriate measures in the case of any violations notified to them by the IAEA".  The Council is acutely conscious of the risks inherent in proliferation, of the need for Agency safeguards to be sufficiently effective to uncover any breaches or concealment with a high degree of probability and that the international community must be able to continue to trust in the credibility  of safeguards.
<P>Some have argued that the Security Council should itself take charge of nuclear inspections, saying that it can be "a far tougher force than the IAEA" (Wall Street Journal, 1993-03-18).  However, the Council has shown no signs of wishing to take over such a function and we have noted from its Summit Statement that it can be expected to continue to rely on the IAEA in this respect.  I would also say that the issue is not "either" the IAEA or the Council.  Events have shown that both may be involved.  The particular characteristics of any inspection undertaken are less dependent upon the body mandating the inspection, than on the extent of the rights which the inspectors are given.  In Iraq, defeated in war, these rights are unlimited.  In the DPRK they are laid down in the safeguards agreement.
<P>I would conclude my comments on the safeguards system by suggesting that the case of the DPRK illustrates the changes that have taken place since the revelations in Iraq.  In the case of Iraq information about a vast secret programme was missing.  In the case of the DPRK, advanced methods of chemical analysis of material from inspected installations plus satellite imagery have provided much relevant information.  In Iraq no requests were made for special inspections to non-declared sites because the sites were unknown.  In the DPRK such requests were made when proposals for other types of visits were turned down.  Lastly, in the DPRK as in Iraq the Security Council is, in the last resort, the authority which has to ensure access for verification, where access is not willingly granted.
<P>I am not asserting that the safeguards system of the IAEA is now perfect.  A number of improvements still need to be made.  The system was designed some 30 years ago as the world's first on-site inspection system.  States have since then become more accustomed to confidence-building measures in the form of international inspection.  The long negotiated Chemical Weapons Convention contains some features - notably regarding practicalities of access - which appear to be advances over nuclear safeguards.  Such features, in my view, should be transposed to IAEA safeguards.  There is also room for governments to agree on greater degrees of nuclear transparency by adding new features to the safeguards system, e.g. fuller reporting about their nuclear programmes, wider access of inspectors to installations, and perhaps acceptance of so-called environmental monitoring, i.e. the taking of samples of soil and water for radiological analysis.  Whether, in order to economize, it will be possible to "individualize" the inspection effort according to country, is more questionable.  The safeguards system must continue to be non-discriminatory - like the security screening of airline passengers.  Governments will hardly accept being treated differently.
<P>The criticism which has been voiced by a handful of writers of the safeguards inspections as sleepy and ineffective stands in sharp contrast to the praise expressed by governments.  Perhaps this criticism is based on a lack of understanding that a system that is to verify thousands of installations around the world must have some routines, some log sheet, some order.  But I agree it remains important at the same time to maintain the curiosity and alertness of the inspector, to fully use the human resource that he or she represent.
<P><B>Export Controls</B>
<P>I have commented at length on safeguards verification because that is where I have most knowledge.  As I said, however, safeguards are a confidence-building measure more than a barrier to proliferation.  NPT and safeguards agreements can theoretically be denounced as we have recently seen.  Export controls, on the other hand, are designed to make the acquisition or development of nuclear weapons more difficult, where the political/security disincentives may not have worked.  The case of Iraq showed that there was room for considerable improvements in export controls and that the system is now being strengthened.
<P><B>Non-Proliferation in the Future</B>
<P>I started on an optimistic note and I shall also conclude on a hopeful tone.  A climate of detente, stability and nuclear disarmament will lead to diminished general interest in nuclear weapons acquisition.  However, for the universalization of non-proliferation and the unlimited extension of commitments several things are needed.  There is global detente, but some regions remain very tense.  Drastic nuclear disarmament has been agreed, but it is not yet accomplished.  International verification is being much strengthened to provide the confidence that States need so as to dare to live without, or with few, nuclear weapons - but the safeguards strengthening process is not yet finished.  It is not naive to aim at the universalization of non-proliferation and at an unlimited extension of the NPT but it is prudent to be aware of the considerable hurdles.
<P>Accelerated nuclear disarmament measures by the nuclear-weapon States have a great value per se and will also much facilitate the NPT Conference in 1995.  I am not sure that the absence of a complete test ban agreement would block success, but I am sure that the conclusion of such an agreement would be of great help.  A cut-off in the production of direct use nuclear material for weapons purposes would also seem a plausible proposition at a time when the US and Russia seem to have much more such material than they need.  A verified cut-off might also be an interesting venture for countries like Israel, India and Pakistan.
<P>To universalize reliable non-proliferation pledges detente will be needed in the Middle East, on the Indian subcontinent, the Korean peninsula and in the region of the former Soviet Union.  Tailor-made solutions above and beyond adherence to NPT may be needed in several of these cases.  We have already seen how North and South Korea have agreed to renounce enrichment and reprocessing capacity.  Such agreement obviously goes beyond the NPT and some such arrangement may well be needed in the Middle East where no legitimate peaceful need can be seen for such capacity at present.  A nuclear-weapon-free zone in the Middle East  would certainly only come about in the context of a peace settlement in that region.  It would in turn be of importance for the extension of the NPT.  Unless it comes about and comprises all relevant States including Israel, there is a possibility that Arab States will be reluctant to commit themselves to non-proliferation for an unlimited period of time.  I should add that a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the Middle East would require far-reaching arrangements for verification - perhaps combining international verification with some arrangements for mutual verification.
<P><B>IAEA's Role</B>
<P>I have repeatedly stressed that the primary factors for success lie in political/security considerations.  However, the need for confidence that commitments are being respected will continue to result in the need for effective on-site inspection.  Some have suggested that the NPT-type safeguards agreements should be renegotiated in the light of recent experiences.  I do not think this is either realistic or risk-free in the immediate future.  The approach, I think, is more likely to continue to be incremental.
<P>Provided that the safeguards system of the IAEA is further strengthened, developed and given adequate resources it is not far-fetched to believe that it could be used to verify the peaceful storage or use of nuclear material - highly enriched uranium or plutonium - once the material has been recovered from dismantled weapons and moved to the civilian sector.  In fact this is what now is happening in South Africa.  The safeguards system is likely to be used in further nuclear-weapon-free zones - as it is now used in the Tlatelolco and Raratonga Treaties.
<P>The safeguards system might also be used to verify a cut-off - a task that would be both very difficult and resource demanding, involving as it would large bulk-handling facilities.
<P>Even a complete test ban, it has recently been suggested, could be anchored in the IAEA.  Obviously some new department would be needed in the Agency for co-ordination of reports from national systems of seismological surveillance.  However, the nuclear expertise of the Agency could be of direct use in identifying the radioactive traces of any test explosion.  Furthermore, the Board of Governors of the IAEA with its balance between North and South and special representation of States which are advanced in the technology of atomic energy, would seem to be a well designed body to supervise the implementation of a test ban treaty.  It is not necessary to create new international organizations for every new task.
<P>In conclusion, new verification tasks will continue to arise with further measures in the nuclear arms control and disarmament field.  Safeguards are dynamic, not static.  Personnel with new expertise can be recruited for new functions.  Were some or all of the political developments which I have outlined to come to fruition, the IAEA could be faced with significant new challenges.<HR>
