<TITLE>Prospects of Multilateralism in the Non-Proliferation Regime </TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Prospects of Multilateralism in the Non-Proliferation Regime </H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Hans Blix<BR>Director General,<BR>International Atomic Energy Agency<BR></H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Bonn, Germany </H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>April 1993</H4>
<P><HR>The era of the cold war is over, and with it almost four decades of dominant bipolarity and ideologically coloured struggles.  In many ways this makes the competition between States less dangerous and the multilateral regulation of problems less difficult.  This, indeed, in turn, permits and demands new and constructive thinking and action in the fields of security, disarmament and international organization.
<P>Non-proliferation - preventing the spread of nuclear weapons to more countries - was comparatively less hampered by the cold war than many other desirable international measures, because here the interests of the two superpowers mostly coincided.  A good deal of success was achieved, but much more needs and can be done as we approach the Conference of the Non-Proliferation Treaty in 1995.
<P>What is often termed “the non-proliferation regime” consists of many approaches and components.  They can be examined from different perspectives.  One is to identify different barriers, the first being political and consisting in the absence of an incentive to acquire nuclear weapons or the presence of an incentive not to acquire such weapons.  Détente in a region, the absence of any neighbour who has or is acquiring nuclear arms, will reduce a State's incentive to acquire them.  Security guarantees will have the same effect.  For some developing countries promises of assistance in return for a non-proliferation commitment may constitute a significant incentive to make such commitments.
<P>Nuclear disarmament by nuclear-weapon States will tend to make the use of nuclear weapons a more remote option and will thereby encourage others to remain non-nuclear.  By contrast, the opposite effect can be expected from retention and further development of nuclear weapons and a broad deployment of “mini-nukes” that would blur the distinction with conventional weapons and make the use of nuclear weapons more likely.
<P>A second barrier may be seen in the legal commitment entered into under a treaty.  States do break treaties sometimes, but there is a certain inhibition against doing so.  It is likely that the arguments of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) for withdrawing from the NPT will be found inadequate by most States and that the world will seek to induce DPRK to maintain the legal commitment it entered into when acceding to the NPT.
<P>A third barrier is the verification system linked to the legal commitments - in most cases IAEA inspection.  To be sure, the inspectors are not police that will stop a transgressor.  Rather it has been said that the purpose of safeguards is to “deter from diversion by risk of detection.”  Of course, the overwhelming majority of States concluding safeguards agreements with the Agency do not do so in order to deter themselves from any future temptation.  They do so because they want to create maximum confidence that they are not developing nuclear weapons.  It remains true, nevertheless, that safeguards must be sufficiently effective to uncover any significant breaches with a high degree of probability and that any State tempted to violate its commitment must be aware of - and hopefully deterred by - this risk of detection.
<P>A barrier of a different kind is control of the export of nuclear material and equipment.  It is recognized today that almost any State at a certain technological level could develop nuclear weapons, provided that it is able and willing to devote  the necessary resources.  Thus, if the barriers which I have described fail, a State's  ambition to develop nuclear weapons may still run into practical obstacles as a result of  export restrictions on nuclear technology, hardware and material. This may at least considerably delay weapons development.
<P>One may choose other criteria for analysing the non-proliferation regime.  I shall seek here to distinguish between a relatively easily identifiable multilateral approach and another approach that may be said to be bilateral.  The simplest illustration is the difference between the NPT, the pre-eminent multilateral approach, and the bilateral agreement between the DPRK and the Republic of Korea on a nuclear-weapon-free Korea.
<P>The reason why I address non-proliferation efforts from this angle is not that there is any sudden new enthusiasm for bilateral approaches, but rather a scepticism in some quarters about the effectiveness of the multilateral approach.
<P>There is a good reason, in my view, to follow a multilateral approach to non-proliferation, as the incentive to acquire nuclear weapons chiefly lies in the fear that others have them or may acquire them.  Hence credible pledges to forego the nuclear weapon option - especially among neighbours and in regions - tend to reinforce each other.  The NPT and the Treaties of Tlatelolco and Raratonga represent the multilateral approach.
<P>The multilateral treaties under which non-proliferation is pledged are complemented by multilaterally organized verification:  IAEA safeguards.  The inspection regime for each country is laid down in a bilateral agreement with the IAEA, but it follows a set pattern and the IAEA applies the safeguards on behalf of the international community.
<P>There is no tendency to abandon the multilateral approach - whether in commitments, in verification or in export restrictions.  On the contrary, the new political climate is allowing a further significant extension and strengthening of the multilateral regime.  At the same time, however, the discovery of the clandestine Iraqi nuclear programme and the emergence from the Soviet Union of a dozen new States with little experience of their own in nuclear accountancy have pointed to some weaknesses in the present multilateral system.  All this has led to consideration of remedies within the multilateral context, of limits in what the system may realistically achieve and of supplementary bilateral or regional approaches.
<P>Let me first discuss the extension of commitments under the multilateral regime, the shortfalls and weaknesses found in it, and how it could be supplemented by bilateral approaches.  I shall then discuss the recent criticism of safeguards verification, how this verification is being strengthened and how it can be supplemented by bilateral measures.
<P><B>More commitments</B><BR>
Although the Tlatelolco Treaty has still not entered into force, considerable progress toward its entry into force was made when Argentina and Brazil decided bilaterally to open up their nuclear sectors to each other and, in addition, to accept comprehensive international verification.  With the recent adoption of a number of amendments to the Tlatelolco Treaty, and with new hopes that Cuba may join, there is an expectation that this multilateral treaty will enter into force for all of its parties in the not too distant future.  This would, indeed, be an important accomplishment.  Several factors would have contributed to it, one being the reduced importance generally attributed to nuclear weapons in the new international climate.
<P>South Africa's adherence to the NPT may also be seen as a fruit of the new political climate.  As explained by the President of South Africa in a speech on 24 March 1993, the perceived threat of communism no longer being present, the reason for maintaining a nuclear-weapon option disappeared.  Once South Africa had joined the NPT, a number of African countries followed, and the prospect of an African nuclear-weapon-free zone became a distinct possibility - whether de facto, through universal adherence of African States to the NPT, or through an additional treaty.  A second continent would be completely committed to nuclear non-proliferation.
<P>China's and France's adherences to the NPT mean that all declared nuclear-weapon States now firmly and formally support the objective of non-proliferation and the means specified in the NPT to attain it.
<P><B> Shortfalls in adherence</B>
<P>The number of countries still outside all the non-proliferation treaties is getting smaller.  In the Middle East and Arab world, the significant ones are Israel and Algeria.  In Asia, they are India and Pakistan.  Also, some former members of the Soviet Union have not yet joined.  While Israel's adherence to the NPT is eagerly demanded and would be welcomed by all, it must be noted that accession alone would probably not be enough to create confidence in this region of conflict.  Accession to the NPT would oblige Israel to dismantle any nuclear weapons it might have and to abandon any nuclear weapons intentions - as South Africa declared it did.  However, it is not clear that it would oblige the country to abandon its reprocessing activities or the plutonium it is assumed to have - only to declare what it has and to open everything for inspection.  As neither Israel nor any other country in this region has a nuclear power reactor, let alone breeders, any reprocessing and enrichment activities would appear intended for weapons purposes.  In an agreement on a nuclear-weapon-free zone, the parties might proscribe such activities or prescribe a moratorium on them until there would be an identifiably peaceful need for them and - perhaps - multinationally-controlled installations for them.
<P>It is improbable that either India or Pakistan would join the NPT without the other State also joining.  There is a strong bilateral element that would have to be satisfied.  Here again, however, there are not only bilateral questions.  India has consistently linked its stand on non-proliferation to global progress in disarmament.  It may be assumed that, in particular, measures by China in the sphere of nuclear disarmament would be important to India.  Security guarantees might also be of importance to both India and Pakistan.  In addition, the question of the existing enrichment capacity in both countries, the reprocessing capacity in India, and the stocks of highly enriched uranium and plutonium would require solutions that satisfy both parties and the international community.  A special regime would be needed.  Acceptance of NPT obligations alone would hardly be enough.
<P>The cases of North and South Korea show two parties in a tension-ridden area seeking to solidify their declared nuclear weapon-free status with a bilateral accord under which they committed themselves to abstain from acquiring enrichment and reprocessing capability - for which there would hardly be a convincing economic rationale.  Mutual confidence was also to be strengthened by adding bilateral mutual inspections to IAEA safeguards.  Although at the time of this writing (September 1993) North Kroea's continued adherence to the NPT is somewhat uncertain, it is very much to be hoped that the combination of a multilateral and a tailor-made bilateral regime will become reality.
<P>I leave aside the cases of Ukraine and Kazakhstan which, hopefully, perhaps with some special security guarantees and appropriate economic arrangements, will adhere to the NPT as non-nuclear-weapon States in due course.
<P><B>Weaknesses in the multilateral non-proliferation regime, including safeguards</B>
<P>Apart from the non-adherence of some crucial States to the non-proliferation regime, two further threats to the regime are often pointed to at the present time.  One is the threat that nuclear material and technology as well as nuclear engineers and scientists might trickle out from the former Soviet Union to States interested in acquiring a nuclear-weapon capacity.  The remedies lie in effective export controls, new jobs in CIS States and in creating disincentives to proliferation in the potential recipient States.  This problem is not exclusively one for the former Soviet States.  It should be noted, however, that there would be no customers for any “trickling,” if non-proliferation commitments were solid, reliable and universal.  The concern about “trickling” thus points directly to the other weaknesses presently perceived in the non-proliferation regime - that of more Iraqs.
<P>When the NPT was concluded, the fear was that industrially advanced countries might feel inclined to acquire nuclear weapons.  Today, the situation in this group of countries appears stable.  Many of them would be capable of making nuclear weapons, but they have decided against it.  The fear is rather that many developing countries may now have reached such a technological level that they could develop nuclear weapons - if they were to so decide.  Iraq was the rude awakening.
<P>It is clearly the case of Iraq that has given rise to doubts whether the impressive non-proliferation edifice is solid.  The number of parties to the NPT has been increasing continuously, yes, but is the adherence genuine or in some cases just a cover for secret ambitions?  The IAEA's comprehensive safeguards regime is expanding with each new party to the NPT, yes, but are there more Iraqs evading IAEA verification and secretly preparing for bomb-making?  Is the DPRK another country party to the NPT with bomb-ambitions and perhaps trying to evade IAEA controls?  So it is asked.
<P>It seems clear that the dominant opinion in the CIA is that there is a growing - not diminishing - threat of nuclear proliferation.  In remarks on 15 December 1992, Mr. Robert Gates, then Director of the CIA, warned that “the increased instability of the new world order has encouraged an increasing number of States to distrust alliances and seek advanced weapons of their own.”  He referred specifically to Iran, Iraq and the DPRK as countries which are actively seeking to acquire nuclear weapons capacity.  President Clinton's appointee as Director of the CIA, Mr. Woolsey, is reported to have said in a Senate Committee hearing on 26 February 1993 that more than twenty-five countries were engaged in the development of nuclear, biological or chemical weapons - without, however, specifying how many were working on nuclear weapons.  It is not helpful to lump all these weapons together as “weapons of mass destruction.”  Nuclear weapons present an incomparably greater threat and must be viewed separately.
<P>While some US officials have been pointing to the risk of more States seeking nuclear weapons, a number of American non-officials specializing in the subject of nuclear proliferation have been, in addition, exceedingly - not to say excessively - critical of the IAEA safeguards as a means of verification and some of them have suggested that verification measures might be better conducted under the responsibility of the Security Council.
<P>The New York Times was fair enough to write in an editorial on 15 February 1993 that as the IAEA had not been provided with any intelligence about Iraq's clandestine programme by any Member because they did not know about it, it was not the Agency's fault that the programme was undetected.  Gary Milhollin, in an amazing New Yorker article (1 February 1993) that seems saturated by aversion against the IAEA, is not so generous.  He cites an “American official” as saying about Agency inspections under the Security Council:  “the IAEA missed the Iraqi bomb before the war, and it's missing it again.”  The statement quoted, not substantiated by credible evidence, stands in stark contrast to the testimony given by Assistant Secretary of State Gallucci - former Vice-Chairman of the Special Commission in Congress on 29 June 1993.  He said: “Along with the damage inflicted by the war and subsequent military actions, we believe these [IAEA] inspections have effectively put the Iraqi nuclear weapons program out of business - at least for the near term.”
<P>A high point in Mr. Milhollin's article is another quote from an anonymous participant in one of the early Iraq inspections under resolution 687 saying that “It is against the IAEA's culture to find anything.”  Why?  Because, in his view, the Agency was given the job to spread nuclear technology to developing countries and, at the same time, to check that nuclear exports were not used to make atomic bombs.  “The conflict of interest is obvious,” says the author, “if the Agency catches somebody making bombs, it means that the nuclear exports ... should not have been promoted.”  It is, in short, insinuated that safeguards inspections are a deliberate sham, because they might otherwise discover something that should not have been exported.
<P>It is worth noting at this point that there may be a convergence between criticism of the Agency by hawks and greens.  Both are against the dissemination of nuclear technologies to developing countries, the hawks for fear that such technology might be helpful on the road to bombs and the greens because of blind aversion at least to nuclear power.  In a recent letter to the New York Times (1993-02-28), Gordon Thompson, who in 1992 made a study of the Agency for Greenpeace, urged that “the Agency should shed its nuclear power promotion function, which conflicts with its mission of preventing proliferation.”  An alliance of greens and hawks pressing this line, if successful, would erode the support for the NPT that has slowly grown among developing countries.
<P>It is important to ask where this pessimistic view of the multilateral non-proliferation regime leads its critics?  It seems clear that some of the critics feel that the only real protection against proliferating “rogue States” is military hardware.  In an article in the British paper, The Guardian, on 5 January 1993, Paul Rogers, Professor of Conflict Analysis at Bradford University,  writes as follows:
“US nuclear planners, like their Russian counterparts, simply do not believe that the proliferation of nuclear weapons will be controlled.  They envisage within a decade a world with many more nuclear States, most of them in the Third World, and they believe that strategies and weapons must be developed in the expectation that ‘small nuclear wars in far-off places' may become a feature of 21st century conflicts.”
<P>One of the means devised to meet the proliferation danger perceived is GPALS, Global Protection Against Limited Strikes, a modest successor to the Strategic Defense Initiative, consisting of lots of super-versions of the Patriot missiles to meet the few nuclear-armed missiles that might be launched from some third world country.  According to an article in the Sunday Telegraph (1992-12-13) by its Defence Correspondent, Christy Campbell, there is already co-operation between the US and Russia on GPALS, Russia fearing “breakaway nuclear powers such as Ukraine and the potential new ones, including Iran and Iraq.”  Mr. Campbell reports that GPALS is meant to be able to shoot down 200 warheads and that Britain, like the US and Russia, is looking at strategic defences against maverick new nuclear powers.
<P>This approach, however, is also meeting criticism.  In an article in Arms Control Today (September 1991), Thomas W. Graham states as follows:
“Building limited missile defense - as part of an approach to 'manage nuclear proliferation' - a step advocated by top Pentagon officials, though not by some other proponents of the management approach - would probably cost more in a single year than all US non-proliferation efforts have to date, while still not providing protection against many of the most likely means of delivery.”
<P>Mr. Graham argues that one should “think more about winning the non-proliferation battle than managing the consequences of losing it.”  He says - and I agree - that it is now time to think big “concerning a multilateral initiative to 'solve' the proliferation problem” in the rather small number of States which cause concern.  He seems to favour inter alia a comprehensive test ban, a verified cut-off of operation and production of weapons-grade material and, ultimately, a “changed security environment” in  which “nuclear weapons programs can be rolled back (emphasis supplied), following the precedent of South Africa.”
<P>I shall revert to this vision of a “changed security environment” but first discuss ideas which have been advanced on how to develop a substitute for  IAEA safeguards.
<P>In the opinion of Milhollin, Leventhal, Kay and other critics of the IAEA, the task of verifying nuclear non-proliferation should be entrusted to the
Security Council and be performed by some subsidiary organ like UNSCOM (the Special Commission for Iraq).  To Leventhal the Board of Governors
of the IAEA is a bunch of officials promoting nuclear power and caring little about proliferation, while the Security Council consists of Ambassadors
who have broader perspectives - a view that ignores the simple reality that the  delegations to each organization receive their instructions from the
same source.
<P>In an article about the DPRK, David Kay suggested that “the decision of how to respond should be moved immediately from the IAEA in
Vienna to the far more serious (sic) forum of the UN Security Council.  The Security Council has shown in Iraq that it can be a far tougher force than
the IAEA ...” (Wall Street Journal, 1993-03-18).  Indeed, the Security Council is the sole repository of military enforcement power in the UN system,
and in Iraq it made use of this power.  But it is not certain that it will marshal half a million men in every conflict.  Nor is it easy to see that it is a “more
serious forum” than the IAEA.  In the case of the DPRK, the Council has chosen, at any rate initially, the path of persuasion rather than displaying
tough force.
<P>To the critics, IAEA inspectors are timid diplomats visiting locations agreed upon by the host States, while UNSCOM inspectors descend in
surprise missions uncovering clandestine activities, material and equipment.
<P>It is not worth the effort of trying to find who are the originators of this caricature of IAEA inspections in Iraq.  Some staff of the Special
Commission and some of the Commission's friends in the US intelligence community and defence establishment were never very happy about the
Security Council having given the Agency direct responsibility for the nuclear inspections.  Attempts were made by various means not only to assist
and support the Agency - as the resolution required - but also to direct and control it in its task, and this led to friction.  Over time an accommodation
occurred and there is no doubt that the assistance from the Commission has been both necessary and valuable.  An objective analysis of the working
methods and styles of the inspection teams of the two organizations, I think, will not reveal significant differences in approach or style.  The Agency
had the advantage of being able to draw on an existing organizational infrastructure, on a large, trained inspectorate of its own and to use analytical
laboratories of its own.
<P>In criticism of IAEA inspections the most diverse points have been made:  for instance, that Agency inspectors not coming from nuclear-
weapon States would not recognize a nuclear bomb if they stumbled on one, the implication being, I suppose, that inspectors should be drawn from
nuclear-weapon States.  However, these are mostly silly points.  There has been no difficulty in supplementing in-house inspectors with all kinds of
expert inspectors from Member governments.  Another matter would be if inspections requested by the Security Council were to have some
paramilitary character.  Although a few inspections undertaken in Iraq under the Agency's responsibility had almost such a character, it might be
argued with some reason that, should paramilitary operations be necessary, another type of  organization than the IAEA would be more appropriate.
<P>It should be well understood that in the case of inspections under Security Council resolution 687, Iraq formally agreed, as a part of a cease
fire, to grant very special and extensive rights to UNSCOM and IAEA. The inspection rights of the IAEA pursuant to NPT as set forth in INFCIRC/153,
on the other hand, were freely negotiated by many governments and show how far free governments wanted nuclear inspections to go in 1971.  In a
renegotiation today they might go a little further - as they have done in the Chemical Weapons Convention  (CWC) - but not much and it is, indeed,
very hard to understand why any NPT inspections, in which there is so much experience in the IAEA, and for which it has some 500 staff and a large
laboratory, should be placed under some subsidiary organ of the Security Council.  This conclusion was also reached by the New York Times in its
editorial of 15 February 1992:
<P>. . . it's difficult to see how replacing the IAEA with a new agency, as some suggest, would keep Iraq under better surveillance or stop the next
nuclear renegade . . .
<P>It is amazing that this suggestion could get so far as to be discussed seriously in the New York Times.  In the Agency's Board of Governors,
its General Conference, in the Security Council and in the General Assembly there has never been anything but solid praise for the Agency's way of
handling inspections.  The Agency's verification activities are ultimately controlled by a 35-member Board of Governors, in which all the five nuclear-
weapon States, as well as nuclear-advanced non-nuclear-weapon States, participate and in which, in addition, there is a certain North/South balance.
The consensus support which this representative structure gives to safeguards is valuable and not easily replicated  elsewhere.
<P>Subordinating the IAEA to an UNSCOM type of organ or setting up a nuclear inspectorate under the Security Council may not appear as more
than a bizarre idea that has obtained more publicity than it deserves.  This does not, mean, however, that all criticism of the safeguards system is
unfounded.  Some important proposals for changes in the system were advanced well before the armed action in Iraq, notably during the 1990 NPT
Review Conference. I myself outlined a programme of changes at the IAEA February Board in 1991 before the clandestine programme in Iraq had
been discovered.
<P>NPT-type safeguards were designed primarily with open industrialized countries in mind. There was concern about the risk of revelation of
industrial secrets and of impediments to nuclear research and production.  Over the years these concerns have proved  to be largely unfounded.
However, they were responsible for an approach concentrating on so-called strategic points and on declared nuclear material, rather than on
installations.  The comment has also been made that the system was somewhat mechanistic, with check lists and log sheets for routine data collection
and too little room for initiative and spontaneous inquisitiveness by inspectors.
<P>Some critics will contrast this “bureaucratic” IAEA system with the daring, dashing inspections carried out by the IAEA under Security Council
auspices and during which the Iraqis were taken by surprise and important evidence was secured.  This is not a meaningful comparison, however,
because no universal system of inspection will provide for the kind of access rights that were imposed upon the defeated Iraq.
<P>It is more meaningful to examine what, after years of negotiation, was obtained for the verification system of the brand new Chemical
Weapons Convention (CWC).  Such an examination will show the level of intrusiveness that governments are ready to accept today.  There are,
indeed, some important differences between inspections under NPT-type safeguards and those under the CWC.  Designations of inspectors are
deemed accepted under the CWC, unless expressly rejected; visas must be granted for multiple entry of inspectors; the inspectors have an express
right to use their own means of communication and of being taken to the site of inspection without delay.  Finally, parties to the CWC may request
challenge inspections of any location; such a request can only be ruled out by a decision of a qualified ¾ majority of the Board of the organization.
Acceptance by IAEA members of some of these features would clearly improve the safeguards system.  It must be noted, however, that any system
that has the task of visiting hundreds of installations, verifying many thousands of records, and of analysing vast numbers of samples, must have
some order, some routines.  With hundreds of inspectors the system cannot be left to their individual intuition.  At the same time it is important that the
system should not stifle the inspectors' imagination and individual initiative and lead the inspector to the conviction that because a thousand
inspections have not uncovered any violations,  the next one could not do it.  The Agency's Board and Secretariat and its advisory organ on
safeguards are at present (Autumn 1993) engaged in exploring how routine safeguards inspections might be reduced, and  compensated by greater
transparency in the nuclear programmes of States and wider rights of access for the Agency short-notice inspections.
<P>It is rather widely recognized that the safeguards system, as practised before the Iraq revelations, was effective in verifying non-diversion of
declared nuclear material at declared nuclear installations.  It was - and is - a good audit system.  Indeed, it worked also in Iraq as well, where no
safeguarded nuclear material was directed to the weapons programme.  What was less widely understood before the Iraq revelations was that the
system was not really equipped to discover clandestine programmes.  What has been done to equip it better for this purpose?
<P>In the summer of 1991 I said in the Board of Governors that three forms of access were of crucial importance to strengthen safeguards:
access to information, access to sites and access to the Security Council.
<P>Provided that you have information about where to look, the right to access to sites for inspection becomes meaningful.  In the case of Iraq
this right is unlimited.  In the case of NPT-type safeguards the Agency has asserted - and in the case of the DPRK, the Board has supported this
assertion - a right of access through special inspection to any site which it has reason to believe is nuclear-related and relevant to safeguards,
regardless of whether it is military.  We have stated to the DPRK, however, that we are willing to discuss inspection arrangements that would minimize
legitimate security concerns.
<P>There are several differences between IAEA special inspections and the CWC challenge inspections.  The latter can only be undertaken at
the initiative of a member, while the Secretariat of the Agency can demand a special inspection.  On the other hand the IAEA Secretariat must have
reason to believe that a site is nuclear-related and safeguards-relevant before requesting a special inspection, while a challenge inspection may be
prompted by mere doubts or suspicions.
<P>Those critics of the IAEA safeguards system who advocate that nuclear non-proliferation verification should be placed under the authority of
the Security Council do not seem to have noticed that the Council is free at any time, under its authority to maintain peace and security, to request the
IAEA - or some ad hoc body if it so wished - to perform inspections.  Conversely, the IAEA is free - indeed, in case of a State's non-compliance with a
safeguards agreement, obliged - to refer safeguards issues to the Council, which alone in the UN system can take enforcement action to induce a
State, if need be, to accept inspection.
<P>Even with a substantially strengthened safeguards system it can hardly be 100% guaranteed that every case of clandestine nuclear
programme would be detected, but there should be a substantial improvement compared with the pre-Iraq situation.  It is possible that there will be an
insistence on supplementary bilateral inspections in some sensitive areas.  Such inspections have been discussed between North and South Korea  -
but have not been agreed on.  In the Middle East it seems likely that both Israel and the Arab States may demand that verification in a nuclear-
weapon-free zone should have a large component of bilateralism.
<P>In a thoughtful article in the journal Foreign Affairs, John Deutch, now Undersecretary in the U.S. Department of Defense writes as follows:
“Conventional IAEA inspections serve a useful role, and there are no significant examples of diversion from safeguarded facilities.  Expanding
IAEA inspections to suspect sites is also welcome.  But since IAEA inspections are not designed to detect covert programs, there should be realistic
expectations about how much warning the IAEA can provide, even with expanded authority for challenge inspections.  These limitations make it
necessary to maintain the option of insisting on inspections outside the IAEA framework.  This could be done through bilateral arrangements, such as
the United States is encouraging between North and South Korea and like Brazil's and Argentina's agreement under the 1968 Treaty of Tlatelolco.  It
could also be done, perhaps, under the direct auspices of the UN Security Council”  (Foreign Affairs, Fall 1992).
<P>It should be noted, however, that although Argentina and Brazil, two countries with close, friendly relations, have agreed to open up their
nuclear activities to each other, it may not prove quite so easy for antagonistic countries to accept mutual inspections or for the Security Council to
negotiate intensive inspection of the kind accepted by Iraq after defeat in war in order to obtain a cease-fire.
<P>What are the means of attaining a world free from the risk of nuclear proliferation?
<P>It is an interesting sign of the post-cold-war climate that even some very experienced diplomats and statesmen are beginning to think aloud
about a nuclear-weapon-free world.  Gerard Smith, in an article in the Bulletin for Atomic Scientists (December 1990) describes a scenario under
which national nuclear forces would be sharply cut back in a first phase and the testing, production and deployment of nuclear weapons would be
halted.  In a second phase, the remaining small forces would be assigned to a multilateral force.  Nations would have custody of them but any decision
on their use would be taken by the supplying nations jointly, and only in retaliation for aggression.  In a third, rather long and final phase, an
international organization would become the “safe deposit” for nuclear weapons until they were abolished.
<P>Robert McNamara , in an article in the International Herald Tribune on 1993-02-24 similarly argues a return to a non-nuclear world, “insofar as
it is possible.  One or more declared nuclear-weapon States - or an international agency - he says would have to retain a small nuclear force, with a
maximum of 100-200 warheads, as protection against blackmail.  In the shorter term he advocates a strong role for the Security Council, which should
agree to prohibit the development, production and purchase of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and ballistic missiles “by countries which do
not have them.  Countries which violated such prohibitions would be subject to economic sanctions.  If this had no effect “a UN military force would be
given a mandate to eliminate the production capability and destroy any stocks produced or bought.”  “Countries that have such weapons - including
both declared and undeclared nuclear powers such as India, Pakistan and Israel - would be subject to inspection and control, and would be asked to
approve a treaty prohibiting the first use of nuclear weapons.”
<P>I cite these writings to show that there is no lack of long-term “big thinking” at present.  I should like to conclude, however, with some “big
thinking on the near-term perspective  of 1995.
<P>Gerard Smith writes that the challenge for today is to develop “anti-proliferation strategies,” including the “rollback” of instances of proliferation
which have occurred, e.g. in Israel, India and Pakistan. Ambassador Smith is thus more ambitious than Mr. McNamara.
<P>For 1995 many express the hope for universalization and an open-ended extension of the NPT.  There is hope that the drastic nuclear
disarmament agreements will come into effect and that both a complete test-ban and a verified cut-off of production of nuclear material for weapons
use might be attained.  Such results would certainly go far beyond the wildest hopes that might have been entertained only a few years ago.  It is
probable that such a general disarmament climate would have a positive influence on the previously intractable areas, the Indian sub-continent and
the Middle East.  However, a growing political détente will be needed if proliferation rollbacks are to take place in these areas.  Bilateral and regional
measures will be needed in addition to universal ones.  A Middle East nuclear-weapon-free zone - as a part of a zone free of weapons of mass
destruction for that area - may also prove to be important for the extension of the NPT.  It might prove difficult for Arab parties to the NPT to accept an
extension that binds them for an unlimited time unless Israel has taken decisive steps to “roll back.”
<P>To conclude:  I do not see any retreat from the multilateral approach - neither from the NPT, nor from IAEA safeguards - but I do see some
bilateral and regional measures supplementing the multilateral ones.  In his testimony to a US Senate Committee, Mr. Woolsey, the new CIA Director,
referred to “an expanding role for multilateral agreements and international organizations in stemming worldwide arms proliferation” (Washington
Weekly Report, 26 February 1993).  I am sure there will be a continued important role for IAEA verification.  NPT-type safeguards are being
strengthened.  They are part of the wider concept of nuclear transparency, which will remain essential for building confidence.  There is some
discussion of using IAEA safeguards to verify that nuclear material recovered in the context of disarmament is used only for peaceful purposes; there
is renewed discussion of an international regime for the management of plutonium to give assurances that this material is not misused; and there are
suggestions that the IAEA might play a verification role in a cut-off of production of weapons-usable nuclear material.  Lastly, it has been proposed that
the IAEA might be entrusted with the operation of a complete test ban agreement.  I am confident that, given resources and assuming that the present
efforts to strengthen the safeguards system are successfully completed, the IAEA would have the ability to assume roles such as these.<HR>
</DOC>
