<HEAD></HEAD>
<BODY>
<TITLE>"Ist das safeguards system noch effizient?" (Is the Safeguards System still Efficient?) Hans Blix Director General International Atomic Energy Agency</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>"Ist das safeguards system noch effizient?" <BR> (Is the Safeguards System still Efficient?)<BR>Hans Blix<BR>
Director General<BR>International Atomic Energy Agency</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Deutsches Atomforum Jahrestagung Kerntechnik '93</H3>
<P><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Koeln, Germany</H3>
<P><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>25 May 1993</H3>
<P><HR>In today's world the situation of the nuclear industry in any country is highly dependent upon nuclear events in other countries.  The stagnation in the growth of nuclear power in the western industrialized world can be traced not only to lower than expected electricity demands, but also to the powerful psychological impact of the Chernobyl disaster.  In order to revive, the nuclear industry in each country must put not only its own house in good order but also help ensure that all the world's nuclear industries are in good order.  
<P>In my view the global revival of the nuclear power option is of crucial importance as a means of adding to the world's supply of energy without adding to the supply of CO2.  Awareness of this need is increasing but broad acceptance of nuclear power in Europe and the US will require further efforts in the fields of safety, waste disposal and non-proliferation.  There must be no more big accidents.  And we need to phase out the nuclear weapons era.
<P>The IAEA as an intergovernmental instrument is deeply involved in the efforts to strengthen nuclear safety, notably in Eastern and Central Europe and in the former Soviet Union.  It is engaged - at the initiative of Minister Töpfer - in the working out of an international nuclear safety convention; it is active in drafting international standards for the safe disposal of nuclear waste; and it is contributing through its safeguards operations to the international efforts to prevent a spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.  Success in all this international work is of importance for the acceptance of nuclear energy.
<P>In the post cold war world we have reason to be optimistic, both about nuclear disarmament and about non-proliferation.  I shall discuss one component of the efforts to prevent proliferation, the IAEA safeguards system - its achievements, limitations and potential.  Before I do so I must, however, place it in perspective among the several other measures which together seek to prevent a spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.
<P><B>Barriers to nuclear proliferation</B>
<P>The most reliable means of preventing nuclear proliferation lie in creating such military and political conditions, locally, regionally and globally that States do not feel any need to acquire or develop nuclear weapons.
<P>Alliances and security guarantees - nuclear umbrellas - have convinced many industrially advanced States, for instance within NATO, that they did not need any nuclear weapons.  Some other States, like Sweden, have felt that it might be more dangerous to have nuclear weapons than not to have such weapons.
<P><B>Détente</B>
<P>The global détente that has come with the end of the cold war is not only leading the US and Russia to withdraw tactical nuclear weapons from deployment and to dismantle many thousands of nuclear warheads, but also leading many other States to downgrade the value of the nuclear weapon option.  As the Swedish Prime Minister said recently, the magic substance today is not plutonium but silicon.  In this new political climate it is not surprising that Argentina and Brazil - earlier often mentioned as potential proliferators - are renouncing the nuclear weapon option and opening all their nuclear installations to inspection.  Nor is it surprising that South Africa, freed from the fear of cold war confrontations, has decided of its own will to roll back from a weapons capacity which it possessed - the first country to do so.
<P>It is true, of course, that once you have learnt how to make a nuclear bomb you cannot unlearn, but you can destroy the tools and invite continuous inspection to create confidence about your non-nuclear-weapon status.  The IAEA is now invited to South Africa precisely for this purpose and to verify, as it must under the safeguards agreement, that all the highly enriched uranium which was contained in the South African nuclear devices has been included in the nuclear material which South Africa declared when it joined the NPT.  And in Iraq the Agency is asked by the Security Council to monitor on a long-term basis that the scientific knowledge and engineering know-how which remains in the country do not again result in uranium enrichment and nuclear weapons programmes.  Absolute confirmation that the last gram of enriched uranium in a country has been declared and that not a single engineer is designing a centrifuge is not possible.  What can be achieved, if there is full co-operation and transparency, is a high degree of assurance that comes from extensive inspection and analysis based on information from a range of activities.
<P>The areas of the world where the risk of proliferation is the greatest are those where international tension and conflict still prevail - the Middle East, the Indian subcontinent and the Korean peninsula.  Here, as elsewhere, the creation of détente is the best means of securing non-proliferation. 
<P><B>Export Restrictions</B>
<P>We must recognize, of course, that in the short and even medium term, détente and peace may be elusive in some regions.  Accordingly there must be policies and measures to prevent and impede nuclear proliferation also where tension continues to provide States with inducements to develop or acquire nuclear weapons.  Even in these situations, some types of international co-operation can make proliferation more difficult, notably restrictions on the export of certain sensitive technology and equipment.  After the discoveries through IAEA inspectors that Iraq had imported crucial equipment and material for its uranium enrichment programme, a widening group of nuclear supplier countries have strengthened their nuclear export restrictions.
<P><B>Limitations in technological capacity</B>
<P>Most developing countries in the world are still without the industrial and technological base which would enable them to embark on a nuclear weapons programme, even if they wished to do so.  One lesson of the case of Iraq was, however, that a growing number of developing countries are attaining a technological level which might enable them to pursue the nuclear weapons option.  When the NPT was concluded, the fears were about industrialized countries.  Today the fears are rather about developing countries.  The most effective way to counter such risk is to establish and maintain détente to eliminate any incentive to develop a nuclear weapon capacity.  The provision of assistance and co-operation of various kinds, e.g. peaceful nuclear techniques for medicine, agriculture and industry, as well as in the development of nuclear energy, as rewards for non-proliferation commitments may also strengthen the reliability of these commitments without significantly adding knowledge that could be used to pursue a nuclear weapons option.
<P><B>Risk of "trickling" from former Soviet Union</B>
<P>Another new nuclear proliferation fear is that the combination of economic strain and loosening discipline and control in the former Soviet Union may lead to a trickling of nuclear material, equipment and engineers to potentially proliferating countries.  Fortunately so far these fears have not become reality.  We often see news items about the smuggling of uranium or plutonium.  The swindlers who are peddling this stuff have an interest in advertising it as bomb grade material.  When we have checked the stories, however, we have found so far that they are about natural uranium, depleted uranium or low enriched uranium or about minute quantities of plutonium.  However, a continued vigilance is needed to guard against the emergence of any black market.  The IAEA is now continuously monitoring media news in this field and following up reports with relevant national authorities.
<P>To sum up what I have said so far, détente and security guarantees may remove incentives to develop nuclear weapons. Moreover, export restrictions and the technological underdevelopment of many countries remain obstacles to proliferation.  What do safeguards do?
<P><B>The role of safeguards</B>
<P>I should like to begin by stressing the positive role of safeguards.  States accept safeguards on their nuclear material and installations normally to demonstrate to their own public opinion, to their neighbours and to the international community that they fully abide by their non-proliferation commitments. Testimony by an independent international organization has a much greater credibility than assurances given by any national authority.  It is in many cases a precondition for the supply of nuclear material and equipment from other countries.  Without safeguards there would not be much international nuclear trade!
<P>The purpose of safeguards may thus be seen, in most cases, as being one of confidence-building.  However, to create confidence, safeguards verification must be sufficiently reliable to detect any violation with a degree of probability that is so high that it would even deter from violations, if a State were so tempted.
<P>It is often stated that the technical objective of safeguards is to deter States from diverting nuclear material from civilian to military use by the risk of detection.  The thought is that a State may be deterred from misusing nuclear material by an awareness that other States would be alerted through safeguards reporting about a diversion - or even about a possible diversion - and would react.  Although inspectors cannot physically stop proliferation, awareness of the consequences of any report that signals possible proliferation may be an important disincentive to proliferation.  The case of the DPRK today shows that other States are, indeed, sensitive not only to proven diversions but even to uncertainty and to lack of compliance with safeguards obligations.  And we can note with some satisfaction that Iraq did not divert any of the quantities of highly enriched uranium which were under IAEA safeguards.  Iraq was fully aware that using that material would have been immediately reported by the IAEA and would have triggered an alarm.
<P><B>Some facts about safeguards</B>
<P>Before going further, it may be appropriate to note some basic facts.  First, safeguards verification is entrusted to the IAEA under the NPT - with some 154 parties - under the Treaty of Tlatelolco for Latin America with 24 parties - and under the Treaty of Raratonga for the South Pacific - with 11 parties.
<P>International safeguards are a sizeable activity, yet in relation to the importance of the task it is modest in cost.  The Agency's Safeguards Department has a staff of about 500 people, of whom some 200 are inspectors.  There is an office in Tokyo with a few resident inspectors and another one in Toronto but most inspectors are resident in Vienna and travel to the nuclear installations which they inspect in various parts of the world.  The annual cost of the IAEA safeguards is about US $60 million.  We are under constant pressure from our Member States to cut the costs.  At the same time, we have the obligation to perform the safeguards in any State that submits installations for verification.  Thus, the Agency is now asked to verify all nuclear installations in South Africa and it is expected soon to do so in Argentina and Brazil.  When Ukraine joins the NPT - as it is expected to do - a large number of nuclear installations will have to be inspected.  The Agency is preparing for all this.  Fortunately a recent arrangement with the European Community has enabled the IAEA to reduce inspection in community countries while maintaining our ability to obtain independent conclusions and this gives the Agency sufficient capacity for the time being  -just to manage the safeguards obligations laid upon us.
<P>It is desirable that the safeguards system be subjected to constructive criticism so that we may improve it.  However, some limitations are inevitable and it is necessary to be aware of them.  There is no point in expecting the system to do things it cannot do.
<P><B>Inevitable limitations</B>
<P>We are sometimes asked why the IAEA does not inspect all nuclear installations in Israel, India or Pakistan.  The answer is, of course, that these States have not adhered to the NPT, nor have they accepted comprehensive safeguards.   NPT adherence and safeguards still remain voluntary acts - which some States are not yet willing to undertake.  No changes in the system would bring these States to accept safeguards over all their nuclear activities.  The solutions lie in foreign policy and regional security accommodations, e.g. a peace settlement and a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the Middle East.
<P>Especially after some dramatic situations in Iraq there have been exaggerated ideas about the ways in which inspections can be conducted.  Safeguards inspectors are not international nuclear policemen who can shoot their way into facilities or seize undeclared nuclear material. We conduct inspection in sovereign States which have full control of their territory and of the installations on them.  We rely on these States to observe their international commitments and to facilitate our work.  However, if a State does not comply with its safeguards obligations regarding inspection this would be reported within the IAEA and from the IAEA to the Security Council of the UN, which could enforce the right of inspection.
<P>Another well-known limitation upon the safeguards system surfaced with full visibility in the case of Iraq:  a few grams of plutonium had been separated from irradiated fuel under safeguards without the required reporting to the IAEA.  It could have been done legally, but Iraq had chosen to do it secretly - and it was not discovered until after the Gulf War.  It appears to have been an isolated experiment.  No larger scale reprocessing activities have been uncovered.
<P>Although it would certainly be desirable for the safeguards system to discover such experiments, it is not deemed possible within reasonable costs to devise a system that is so finely meshed that it would discover very minor diversions.  The system is geared to discover the diversion of what is called a significant quantity of enriched uranium or plutonium - a quantity with which a nuclear explosive device can be made.  This is certainly a limitation on the system but a limitation which has so far been deemed tolerable.
<P>The various limitations on the safeguards system which I have mentioned do not deprive it of value.  Safeguards do verify that hundreds of declared nuclear installations and vast quantities of declared nuclear material around the world remain in exclusively peaceful use.  It is important for governments and the public to feel confident that there is no diversion of material from the big civilian nuclear sector to a secret weapons sector.  International verification offers an additional impartial check over and above the national or regional systems of accounting and control.  Between States only an international system will have good credibility.
<P>Let me now turn to some shortcomings which are being remedied in the international safeguards system.
<P><B>Secret nuclear programmes</B>
<P>The criticism which has been voiced that IAEA safeguards inspection had given Iraq a "clean bill of health" before the Gulf War is not correct.  It had merely been concluded that "all material under safeguards" had been accounted for.  However, this very sentence illustrated that the safeguards system, as practiced, was performed only on nuclear material and installations which had been declared by the inspected State itself and that little was done to give assurance that no secret nuclear installations existed.  It raises the question whether there are more Iraqs that we don't know about and whether safeguards are lulling us into confidence that is not justified?
<P>Can safeguards be sharpened to discover secret programmes and offer warnings about them?  This is the most important safeguards question which the Agency has been grappling with since the discovery of the secret nuclear weapon programme in Iraq.
<P><B>The information basis of safeguards</B>
<P>There can be no doubt that, if any one factor should be singled out as essential for uncovering secret programmes, it would be information.  International inspectors cannot roam vast territories in a blind search of secret installations or hidden material.  They must be directed to specific places and installations.  If a host country hides material and installations, the information must come from other sources.  The IAEA does not have any satellites or spies, but there are things that can be done and are now being done to strengthen the Agency's information basis.
<P>Firstly, more extensive use is being made of data collected by the Agency itself.  New analytical methods permit conclusions about the presence and absence of various radionuclides even when only tiny samples, e.g. from smear tests, are available.  Such samples can be taken by inspectors at declared sites and analysed at the Agency's laboratories.
<P>Secondly, a scheme under which governments will report exports and imports of nuclear material and equipment has been approved by the IAEA Board of Governors and may help the Agency to check the consistency between a State's declared nuclear programme and the pattern of the State's imports.  Had such a system functioned before the Gulf War, the Iraqi programme for uranium enrichment might have been more strongly suspected and led to questions by the Agency.
<P>Thirdly, systematic scanning of the media will make available a wealth of observations by reporters around the world.  Admittedly such scanning also makes available a wealth of misunderstandings but it may sometimes offer useful clues.
<P>Fourthly, the Agency now receives some information obtained by Member States through national means, e.g. through satellite surveillance.  Some members of the IAEA Board of Governors have not been comfortable with the idea that the Agency might receive "intelligence" information and the DPRK has vehemently objected to the use of US satellite pictures.  For my part I have taken the view that the IAEA cannot possibly close its eyes to any credible safeguards relevant information.  The Agency is expected to be a watchdog, not an ostrich!  Another matter is that all information must be critically analysed before any use is made of it.  There is much disinformation around and many misunderstandings.
<P>It is important for all to understand and respect that the information flow must be a one-way traffic.  The Agency is only in a position to receive information, pictures, data to make use thereof in its safeguards operations and assessment.  It must respect its own rules on the confidentiality of data and is not in a position to give any confidential data back to individual States supplying information, not even where such feedback would help to bring further information.
<P><B>The right of access for inspection</B>
<P>If access to information about where to look is the most important precondition for a successful search by inspectors for possible hidden material or secret installations, inspectors' right of access to sites and installations is a second vital precondition.  In the case of the IAEA inspections in Iraq, this right of access was made unlimited and has been effectively backed up by the Security Council.  In NPT-type safeguards agreements there is a right for the IAEA to so-called "special inspections" to any location which the Agency has reason to believe it needs to visit to obtain additional information relevant to safeguards.  It is such a right that the IAEA Board of Governors has asserted in relation to the DPRK and the implementation of which the Security Council is now dealing with.  It is true, as noted by some, that this right had never been asserted by the Agency with regard to a non-declared location before this was done in the case of the DPRK.  The reason, I think, was not timidity but rather that the Agency had not been in possession of any information about non-declared sites meriting visit.
<P><B>The role of the Security Council</B>
<P>Some critics of the IAEA have suggested that the Security Council rather than the IAEA should have responsibility for inspections, because
the Council has shown in Iraq - I quote - "that it can be a far tougher force than the IAEA .  .  ."  . (Wall Street Journal, 1993-03-18).  I submit the issue
is not either/or.  Indeed, both may be involved.  The Security Council is the primary repository of enforcement action in the UN system, and in the Gulf
War it made use of this power.
<P>One can be sure that the Council will remain very firm in taking measures to prevent nuclear proliferation.  There is no indication, however,
that the Council would like to take charge of nuclear inspections.  On the contrary, there is every indication that the Council will rely on the IAEA for
inspections.  The Council stresses the integral role of IAEA safeguards in the implementation of the NPT.  The establishment of United Nations
Special Commission under the Iraq resolution was a consequence of the need for mapping and neutralizing Iraq's capacity regarding other weapons
of mass destruction - biological and chemical - and missiles, matters not falling under the competence of the IAEA.
<P>As it has demonstrated in the case of the DPRK the Agency will turn to the Security Council to report on any significant non-compliance with
safeguards.  There is no simple answer how the Council will back up IAEA safeguards implementation in individual situations.  We can expect that
each case will be examined on its own merits and in its own particular  political, military and security context.
<P><B>The further strengthening of safeguards</B>
<P>The safeguards system of the IAEA was the world's first on-site inspection system.  It has grown tremendously and become more
sophisticated.  However, even with the measures introduced after the revelations in Iraq, the system is not perfect.  Further improvements can be
made.  Some have suggested that the model safeguards agreement pursuant to NPT should be renegotiated in connection with the NPT Conference
in 1995.  However, renegotiation is a somewhat risky process.  Perhaps it would be wiser to progress, as we have done so far, by introducing
voluntary additional features.
<P><B>Transparency</B>
<P>It is important always to remember that the purpose of safeguards inspection is to create confidence that nuclear material and installations are
used only for peaceful purposes  - and to uncover the opposite, should it occur.  Transparency of nuclear activities enables the world to verify that they
are peaceful.  Safeguards may be seen as a form of institutionalized transparency.  Nothing prevents a State from going further in transparency than
what this system currently requires, e.g. by offering very full information about the nuclear activities in the country.
<P><B>Visits to any site, any time</B>
<P>Under NPT-type safeguards routine access is limited to so-called "strategic points" out of concern for industrial and commercial secrets.  It is
generally recognized that these concerns were exaggerated.  States may choose to be more open than is required by the  agreements.  A practice is
now developing that States may voluntarily offer the Agency access to any site at any time, regardless of provisions of safeguards agreement.  Such
offers have been given - in chronological order - by Iran, Libya, the DPRK and South Africa.  Such offers may be made by States to allow visits in
order to allay suspicions which they consider unjustified.  They may be used by the Agency to visit sites which are of interest for one reason or another
but which would not normally justify a formal request for an inspection under safeguards.  Obviously such offers of transparency are only of value if, in
fact, lived up to.  Missions using such offers have gone to Iran and to South Africa.  In South Africa even military sites were visited.  One such visit was
also made in the DPRK, before the current restrictions on inspections and visits were introduced in that country.
<P><B>Environmental sampling</B>
<P>Invitations to take samples of water and air anywhere in a State may prove to be another - not very painful - means of showing transparency
and may help to confirm the absence of reprocessing activities.  It has been suggested that such measures of transparency might reduce the need for
some routine inspection that is now carried out.
<P><B>Are IAEA inspections too "soft"?</B>
<P>It has been claimed by some critics that IAEA safeguards inspections tend to be too "soft",  or to lead to too "cosy" relations between the
inspectorate and the inspected country.  One writer recently referred to "the IAEA, with its inherited ethos of trust in those it monitors." (Foreign Affairs,
Spring 1993, p. 147)
<P>I do not personally think a very serious problem looms in this sector, certainly not compared to the very real limitations which have followed
from lack of information about secret installations.  It is true that when several thousand individual inspections are carried out per year without
uncovering any diversions, one could expect trust to develop.  However, I do not think this is the case.  The frame of mind is neither trust or mistrust.
Inspectors are looking at data, material and equipment.  They do find inconsistencies and discrepancies - which are investigated and fully explained in
most cases - or else reported.  The inspectors are like the pilots in the cockpit, systematically checking a large number of instruments.  Normally
everything is okay, but nothing is taken for granted.  If something unusual is found, it must be fully explored.
<P>The difficulties which I can see lie elsewhere.  First, although States are anxious that other States be fully inspected, they may wish to get
away with a minimum of inspection for themselves.  As States are both the members and masters of the IAEA, they may sometimes utilize this status
to try to assert their views in inspection matters.  And any concession made for some special reason to any inspected party will be invoked by others -
as if a most favoured nation clause existed.  The Secretariat needs clear regulations to withstand such pressures and a readiness to submit problems
to the Board of Governors, which may uphold the collective interest of effective inspection against the interest of individual States in lighter or fewer
inspections.
<P><B>Designation rules and visas</B>
<P>Even as a collectivity States insist on some features which, although not crippling, nevertheless somewhat reduce the effectiveness of
safeguards.  States may reject inspectors from non-NPT countries or countries with which they have no diplomatic relations - or without giving any
reasons.  In many cases visas are still required for each inspection mission.
<P>In my view inspectors should be regarded as the international civil servants they are and have the right of access, when on duty, with only a
UN laissez-passer and a letter of instruction from the Agency.  States have not been willing to go so far yet.  Similarly the inspectors' freedom of
movement and right of speedy access should be improved.  The Chemical Weapons Convention marks some progress in these regards and these
features should be accepted by States within the IAEA as well.  They do not give as far-reaching rights to the inspectorate as in the case of Iraq, but
they are better than the normal safeguards conditions now prevailing.
<P><B>The capacity of the inspector</B>
<P>	Another question relates to the full use of the individual inspector.  A large organization with thousands of inspections must have order and
effective routines.  It cannot rely on the curiosity and intuition of the inspector, alone.  But it should also not lose this invaluable asset.  Hence
activating and motivating the individual inspector remains very important, while demanding at the same time that he fulfils all routines and reports fully
on his log sheet.
<P><B>Adequate resources</B>
<P>Yet another matter relates to resources.  Although governments in principle affirm the vital interest they have in effective safeguards, the fiscal
interest of minimum cost is vigorously asserted.  It is not, in my view, sensible that the IAEA should need to feel budgetary  restraints when it
schedules inspections or decides on the numbers of inspectors to send.  The Agency should also have ample laboratory capacity of its own to perform
most of the advanced analysis it needs.
<P><B>Potential use of stronger safeguards</B>
<P>I should like to end on a less lamenting and more forward-looking note.  The revelations about the secret nuclear programme in Iraq which has
shocked the world has given the political push that was needed to strengthen the system.  The case of the DPRK - with more effective information and
analysis and assertion of the right to special inspections  - demonstrates the stronger safeguards that have resulted and the scope for interaction with
the Security Council.  I do not think that any international verification system can attain 100% certainty, but I am sure that the system which is now
emerging, if it has the full support of members, will offer a much higher degree of certainty than was possible to attain earlier.  This progress is
needed.  We are dealing with matters vital to the security of States and the more nuclear disarmament progresses the more important it will become
that no proliferation occurs.
<P>Given the requisite resources I do not see any strong reason why the strengthened international safeguards system of the IAEA should not be
used to verify the peaceful storage and use of nuclear material recovered from nuclear disarmament or to verify a cut-off in the production of highly
enriched uranium or plutonium for weapons use.  Nor do I see any insuperable obstacles in making the IAEA the international body responsible for the
administration of a complete test ban.  The tasks under a test ban would be a good deal different from the safeguards tasks, but they would still fall in
the nuclear field and there may be great advantages in expanding the role of an existing organization rather than creating a new one.
<P>What is vitally important is that we should all use the time between now and the conference in 1995 on the extension of the Non-Proliferation
Treaty to seek the universalization of non-proliferation commitments, effectively verified.  We should also seek accelerated nuclear disarmament and a
complete test ban both for their own sake and because such measures will strengthen support for and reliability of the non-proliferation regime.<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
