<HEAD></HEAD>
<BODY>
<TITLE>Nuclear Energy and the Environment</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Nuclear Energy and the Environment</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>by Dr. Hans Blix<BR>Director General<BR>International Atomic Energy Agency<BR>
<P>Nuclear Energy and Human Safety<BR>IV Annual Scientific & Technical Conference of the Nuclear Society<BR></H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Nizhny Novgorod, Russia</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>28 June 1993</H4>
<P><HR>Mr. Chairman, Ladies and Gentlemen,
<P>In my home country, Sweden, there is an association of some thousands of environmentalists who favour  nuclear energy, but there are also much larger environmental groups which are critical of nuclear power.  Such groups may have a healthy influence in focussing society's attention on safety issues in nuclear operations and on issues relating to  disposal of nuclear waste.  Opinions and opposition are needed in all societies.  In my view, environmental groups go against their own real interests, however, when they blindly oppose the use of nuclear power.  I came myself to support nuclear power for environmental reasons, and these reasons remain the main motivation for me to support a continued and  expanding role for nuclear power.  It would be very unwise for the world to turn its back on nuclear power and nuclear techniques, which now give it 17% of all its electricity, which form a growing part of modern medicine, and which help us to increase food production at competitive costs.  We must utilize nuclear energy and nuclear techniques for our benefit, not least to reduce the threats to the environment.  In my view these threats may in the future pose greater problems to humanity than the threats of conflicts between States, now that the Cold War is over.  We must, however, use nuclear energy responsibly and prudently and correct the errors of the past.
<P>Environmental destruction is not a new phenomenon.  Our ancestors achieved a lot of environmental destruction, e.g. deforestation through excessive logging for shipbuilding.  However, our ancestors were far fewer than we are and their tools were not so powerful as ours.  Our ancestors inflicted damage on a local and regional scale.  We are degrading the environment on a truly global scale.  The feared global warming through a `Greenhouse Effect', caused, inter alia, by our excessive use of fossil fuels, is an example.
<P><B>The population increase</B>
<P>It must be stated at the outset that the increase in the global population is a critical element in the environmental threat.  It is we and not the animals that destroy the world.  The more numerous we are, the more we destroy, pollute and consume.  It is calculated that at the time of Christ the population of the Earth was about 350 million; in 1900 it was 1.5 billion; in 1990 it was about 5 billion; and in the year 2000 it is expected to be about 6 billion.  Thus, in the last 10 years of this century the world's population will increase by almost as much as it did in the 1900 years from the time of Christ to the year 1900.  
<P>Erosion, desertification and other environmental problems will push people to emigrate, and there are no new continents, no virgin lands, so they will try to go to areas which are already well populated - with the risk of ethnic frictions and conflicts.  The demand for an acceptable standard of living by an ever increasing number of people is already placing great strain on resources of land and fresh water.  In my view none of the problems anticipated to be central in the next century - and certainly not the major environmental problems - can be tackled with any hope of success unless the global population can be stabilized.
<P><B>The Rio Conference</B>
<P>Awareness of the environmental threats is growing rapidly.  No international conference has been attended by so many Heads of State and of government as that on Environment and Development held in Rio de Janeiro in 1992.  At this "green" conference many positive words were not said about nuclear energy.  It was the more important therefore that the IAEA presented a report on `Nuclear Power, Nuclear Techniques and Sustainable Development', which focused on the contribution that the use of nuclear energy and nuclear techniques can make to protecting the environment.  
<P><B>Nuclear energy and sustainable development</B>
<P>There are, indeed, many nuclear techniques that directly serve environmental protection and effective resource utilization.  In agriculture, new strains of seeds are created through mutations induced by irradiation, strains that may be more pest-resistant or drought-resistant or have other desirable features.  To take two examples, cotton crops in Pakistan and rice crops in Indonesia have increased enormously thanks to the use of mutant strains.  Through the use of radioisotopes, difficult and important measurements can be performed which help identify water resources or paths of pollution, or measure the uptake of fertilizer in plants.  In the Libyan Arab Jamahiriya the FAO and the IAEA helped, through a nuclear technique, to eradicate an infestation of the New World screwworm, a pest which kills cattle as well as wild animals.  The technique consisted in releasing millions of insects which had been sterilized by irradiation so that no offspring resulted when these mated with fertile insects.  The insect population was eradicated in less than one year.  The benefit/cost ratio of this successful campaign was calculated to be 50 to 1.
<P>In industry, nuclear techniques offer unique ways of making exact measurements which save raw materials and resources.  A nuclear technique is even being tested to reduce pollutants arising from the burning of coal.  Flue gases from the burning coal are mixed with ammonia and irradiated by electron beams from an accelerator.  The result is that most of the SO2 and NOx is removed from the gases and converted to substances that can be used as fertilizers - ammonium sulphate and ammonium nitrate. 
<P>I need hardly remind you of the many uses of nuclear techniques in modern medicine, not only to combat cancer, where radiation remains a principal method of treatment, but also in many new forms of diagnostic imaging.  Today, computer tomography, gamma cameras and nuclear magnetic imaging are invaluable tools in hospitals.
<P>Few people perhaps are ready to turn their backs on nuclear techniques such as these.  Indeed, relatively few are aware of the wide range of nuclear techniques which serve us in today's world.
<P><B>The risks of nuclear energy</B>
<P>We must, of course, analyse the risks that are connected with the various uses of nuclear energy.  We must also ask what risks are acceptable to society, and what risks we would be taking by relying on possible alternative means of energy generation, or by refraining from expanding energy use.  And we must ask to what extent risks connected with nuclear power can be further reduced.
<P><B>What level of risk is acceptable?</B>
<P>The question of what level of risk is acceptable to society in various activities - how safe is safe enough? - is not technical but political.  Technical data, while not irrelevant in the answering of this question, are only a small part of the input.  Let me give an example:  many pesticides are used extensively and are accepted - but the use of them has considerable negative consequences as well.
<P>A publication by the WHO (1990) on the "Public Health Impact of Pesticides used in Agriculture" estimates the global number of annual unintentional deaths caused by pesticide poisoning in 1985 at 20 000 and the total number of unintentional non-fatal poisonings caused by pesticides in 1985 at 1 million!  One terrible accident was the methyl mercury contamination of seeds in Iraq in which over 6000 people were affected and over 400 died.  Another example was the parathion-contaminated flour in Colombia which affected 600 people and caused 88 deaths. As pesticides continue to be used on a large scale without global protests, we must conclude that these high numbers of casualties are "accepted" by governments and public opinion because of the vital importance of pesticides to food production.  The Bhopal accident - with about 2500 dead - shocked the world, but no one suggested a moratorium on the production of pesticides.
<P>Similarly use of automobiles and coal mining are not questioned by public opinion, despite the heavy toll of lives these activities take.  However, the reliance on nuclear power is questioned, and in several States there are formal or informal moratoria on the construction of new nuclear plants.  Why this difference in opinion?  There can be no doubt that the opinion about nuclear power has been influenced by occurrence of the accidents at Three Mile Island - where there were hardly any radioactive releases to the environment - and Chernobyl, where there were large releases.  Opinion has no doubt been influenced also by the fear that radioactive wastes could leak now or in the future from waste disposal sites.
<P>The health and environmental impacts of the Chernobyl accident and the irresponsible handling of radioactive wastes that has occurred in the military sectors both in the former Soviet Union and in the US should not be ignored.  It is interesting, however, to read the conclusions of a Senior Expert Symposium on Electricity and the Environment which was organized by eleven international organizations, including the IAEA, and which took place in Helsinki in 1991.  The Symposium compared the health and environmental impacts of different electricity generating systems and considered the impacts of the systems from beginning to end, for example from fuel extraction to waste disposal.  With some reservations due to incompleteness of data, it concluded that:"under routine operation conditions, nuclear power and renewable systems tend to be in the lower spectrum of health risk and ... energy systems based on coal and oil are in the higher spectrum of health risk"; and that
<P>"human health risks from severe accidents from nuclear, oil and natural gas are of the same order of magnitude and two orders of magnitude smaller than those from the hydroelectric option."
<P>The second conclusion may appear surprising; however, we should recall that not so few hydropower dams have failed over the years, drowning many thousands of people.  These factual conclusions of an expert symposium deserve to be cited as they contrast with commonly held perceptions
<P><B>Increasing use of energy</B>
<P>Some environmentalists think that the environmental problems linked to our energy use - like the greenhouse effect - can be reduced simply by the use of less energy.  While all are agreed that energy conservation is necessary and should be vigorously pursued, it is not realistic to think that the global use of energy can be reduced.  Energy is the lifeblood of modern societies.  It is evident that developing countries in particular will seek to use much more energy than they do today.  The average North American now uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent in energy per year; the average Chinese uses 590 kg and the average Indian makes do with 280 kg of oil equivalent per year.  China is at present planning to double its use of coal by the year 2000.  The World Energy Council has estimated that global energy consumption can be expected to increase by 50-75% by the year 2020 - even assuming vigorous efforts to increase energy efficiency.
<P>The increasing CO2 emissions and the use of nuclear power to contain them If fears about a global warming effect from the so-called greenhouse gases, notably CO2, are confirmed to be justified, we will face a dilemma: how to reconcile the predicted greater use of energy with the need to limit CO2 emissions.  Asia's CO2 emissions are for example expected to increase by a factor of 30% by the year 2000.  
<P>In this dilemma, the nuclear power option may prove of great importance;  firstly since it is used primarily to generate electricity, which is the fastest growing form of energy use, and secondly because nuclear power plants do not emit CO2 or any other substances which might affect the climate globally.
<P>It has been suggested that nuclear power, which accounts for about 5% of the world's energy and 17% of its electricity - a little less than hydropower's 20% of electricity - is too small a source to be of any importance to global CO2 emissions.  It is true that nuclear power, alone, cannot avert the threat of global warming, but it is probably also true that the problem of global warming cannot be tackled without reliance on nuclear power.  It has been calculated that if today's 400 or so nuclear power plants were closed and the electricity generated by them were instead generated by coal-fired plants, total global CO2 emissions would increase by some 7%.  The awareness is increasing among governments that the use of nuclear power is highly relevant to the efforts to prevent global warming.
 <P>The relevance of nuclear power to CO2 emissions can also be illustrated by a comparison between the United Kingdom and France.  In the United Kingdom, where about 70% of electricity comes from coal burning, average CO2 emission per kWh was 0.78 kg.  In France, where more than 70% of electricity comes from nuclear power, the CO2 emissions per kWh are about one tenth of the British value (0.086 kg).  This is a positive feature.  Moreover, according to a recent study by the French government, nuclear power will remain the cheapest centralized source of new baseload power for France into the next century.  France's fifty fourth PWR went critical in May this year.
<P><B>Energy savings and renewable sources to reduce CO2 emissions</B>
<P>It is often claimed that we can could reduce CO2 emissions without reliance on nuclear energy, either through energy savings or through greater reliance on renewable sources of energy.  Although both increased energy efficiency and the development of solar power and other renewable sources are desirable, neither can realistically be expected to offer an alternative to nuclear power as a base load for electrical production.  The 15th Congress of the World Energy Council held in Madrid last year put the contributions of renewable sources of energy - excluding hydro - at around 3% by the year 2020.  
<P>The present alternative to nuclear is thus not solar power or, for that matter, wind power.  It is fossil fuels.  When Austrians decided in a referendum several years back not to make use of a 725 MW(e) nuclear plant that had already been built, the country did not rely on wind or solar power or energy saving, but built instead a 724 MW(e) coal plant.  And when the Belgian Government refused permission to build another nuclear plant, it granted instead permission for the construction of gas-fired generating capacity.  In my own country, Sweden, a decision was taken after the Chernobyl accident to close two of Sweden's nuclear power plants in 1995 and 1996.  It turned out, however, that the substitute was not to be biomass, solar or wind power, but natural gas.  The phase-out decision was cancelled after an intensive public debate in which possible higher electricity prices and the effects of increased CO2 emissions from the burning of gas were important elements.
<P><B>Climate Change</B>
<P>In Rio de Janeiro a Framework Convention on Climate Change was concluded.  It had been proposed that it should stipulate that CO2
emissions should  be reduced by 2005 to the levels of 1990.  This proposal could not win a consensus.  However, the convention adopted  as an
ultimate objective the stabilization of greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere at a level that would prevent dangerous effects on the climate
system.  The Conference and Convention did not state how this was to be achieved.  Further discussions on CO2 emissions and energy sources -
including the merits of nuclear power - therefore lie before us.  My own belief is that the industrially advanced States will have to consider a continued,
indeed, expanded use of nuclear power in order to enable many developing countries to expand their use of less demanding fossil fuel based
technologies.  I believe we must also develop nuclear power plants which are easier to operate for eventual use by developing countries.  There may
also be scope for greater reliance on nuclear power for the production of industrial heat.
<P><B>Nuclear Waste</B>
<P>The two principal matters which cause scepticism about nuclear power are waste disposal and operational safety.  I have already pointed out
that radioactive waste does not contribute to acid rain or global warming.  Although nuclear waste is dangerous, it has the great merit of being so
limited in volume that it can be disposed of and isolated in its entirety.  This is the great environmental value of nuclear waste.  Some figures
comparing the volume of coal fuel and waste and nuclear fuel and waste may be helpful.  A coal-fuelled plant of 1000 MW(e) will require about 7000
tonnes of coal per day - i.e. about five train loads.  A nuclear plant of the same electric capacity will use some 80 kilograms of uranium per day.  Even
with the best available flue gas cleaning equipment the coal plant will annually emit some 9000 tonnes of SO2, 4500 tonnes of NOx,  and no less than
6.5 million tonnes of CO2. It will also produce some 400 tonnes of various toxic heavy metals in the ash.  The nuclear plant will produce 30 tonnes of
highly radioactive spent fuel per year.
<P>The methods for the disposal of the limited amounts of nuclear waste are intended to ensure isolation for tens of thousands of years.  This
contrasts with our current free release of most of the waste resulting from the burning of fossil fuels.  For fossil fuels the final waste disposal site is the
ground and the atmosphere.  It would seem desirable, however, that the consensus which exists on responsible management, transport and disposal
of nuclear wastes should be laid down in international standards for both civilian and military wastes.  Such standards are, in fact, being elaborated by
the IAEA, and a binding convention is also likely to be worked out within some years.
<P><B>Nuclear Safety</B>
<P>In the matter of safety, it is understood by the nuclear power industry that the level worldwide must be so high that accidents with significant
releases into the environment will virtually never occur.  National and international authorities are dedicated to achieving this, and there is an
intensification of international co-operation.  To existing non-binding standards for nuclear safety there may soon be added an international convention
containing safety fundamentals, which will become legally binding upon States adhering to it.
<P>The IAEA is promoting nuclear safety in several ways other than by the conclusion of binding international conventions.
<P>The Agency has developed a comprehensive set of Nuclear Safety Standards (NUSS) comprising some sixty publications in five subject
areas associated with nuclear power.  Following the Chernobyl accident, relevant standards were updated to take account of experience from the
accident and advances in knowledge and approaches.  The NUSS publications reflect an international consensus on the requirements for nuclear
safety and form a basis on which national requirements can be built.
<P>Since the 1980s, the Agency has also provided a growing number of advisory expert services to improve safety at specific nuclear
installations.
<P>In 1985, the IAEA established a high-level International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group (INSAG), composed of senior safety experts, to give
independent advice on nuclear safety issues.  INSAG produced, in 1988, a particularly important, comprehensive set of Basic Safety Principles for
Nuclear Power Plants.  Included in these principles is the goal that existing nuclear power plants should have a probability of a severe accident not
greater than one in 10,000 operating years.  The probability of an accident requiring protective measures off the site should not exceed one in 100,000
operating years.  Future nuclear plants should be safer than this by a factor of at least ten.  The present goal is considered achievable through good
safety management and a `safety culture'.
<P>The design safety goal set by INSAG for new plants is easily surpassed by most  emerging designs.  These designs often include passive
safety features and seek to achieve a design level of safety at which the risks of an accident are determined mainly be external events such as
possible airplane crashes or earthquakes rather than internal plant faults.  The IAEA is seeking further international agreement on more detailed safety
objectives for future plants based on these new designs.
<P>The IAEA has also developed an International Nuclear Event Scale (INES) - to classify the severity of nuclear accidents and incidents in a
manner that is understandable to news media and the public.  This event scale may help to show to the public that most nuclear incidents and events
are trivial.  This may be important because the public's attitude to nuclear power is based on its perceptions of how well nuclear power functions.
<P>If an excellent international operating record is attained over a period of time for nuclear power plants worldwide, and if this is perceived by the
public, I think we will find that the expanded use of nuclear power, which may prove to be indispensable from the environmental point of view, may
also be fully acceptable to the public.
<P>It is clearly a great challenge for you in Russia to make nuclear energy safe and environmentally acceptable in the Russian Federation - not
least to clean up after accidents and imprudent waste handling.  The IAEA is working to assist you in this vital work to improve nuclear safety and
restore the environment.
<P>I should now like to use a few minutes to talk about recent IAEA work outside the themes of nuclear power and the environment - especially
as this work has regard to the countries of the former Soviet Union.
<P>The growing acceptance of IAEA full-scope safeguards - e.g. in Argentina, Brazil and South Africa - is giving the Agency more installations
and ever-growing quantities of nuclear material to safeguard.  An even greater challenge has arisen from the expectation of the public and of
governments, after the events in Iraq, that full-scope safeguards should be strengthened to detect and deter any non-declared secret nuclear
activities.
<P><B>Safeguards in the Newly Independent States (NIS)</B>
<P>The IAEA is now preparing for the application of safeguards in the newly independent states of the former Soviet Union.  According to
information provided to us by the depositaries of the NPT, currently four of these States - Azerbaijan, Estonia, Lithuania and Uzbekistan - have joined
to the NPT.  Safeguards agreements have been or are in the process of being concluded with these States.  Already safeguards are being introduced
at the Ignalina nuclear power plant in Lithuania and we expect work to begin soon on verification of the initial inventory for Lithuania.  In the remaining
States of the former Soviet Union - apart from Russia - the Agency has continued activities to prepare for the future application of safeguards.
<P>The Agency has obtained information about nuclear materials, identified safeguards equipment needs, and verified inventories of nuclear
material.  Almost all of the major nuclear facilities and installations in Latvia, Belarus, Ukraine and Kazakhstan have now been visited by Agency
experts.  Thus, it is expected that all preparatory activities for the future application of safeguards will be completed soon in these States.  However,
for the Agency to actually apply safeguards, the conclusion of safeguards agreements will be required and this will occur after accession to the NPT.
<P><B>Radiation Protection in the NIS</B>
<P>In response to requests from several countries of the former Soviet Union, the Agency has developed an international initiative aimed at
strengthening national infrastructures for radiation protection and nuclear safety in countries of the former Soviet Union.  The Secretariat of the Agency
and the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) worked out a proposal designed to address problems not covered by other international
initiatives to date, notably the safety issues related to research reactors, uranium mining and milling, and installations using radiation sources in
medicine, agriculture and industry.
<P>The initiative comprises three phases: (1) a meeting for the exchange of information; (2) the development of projects, consisting of assistance
packages for individual countries or for groups of countries with similar needs; and (3) the actual implementation of these assistance packages.
<P>The meeting which took place in Vienna from 4 to 7 May was attended by representatives of Russia and most of the former States members
of the Soviet Union.  UNDP financed this first phase of the project and has indicated that up to $300,000 may be made available soon to implement
the second phase of the initiative, project developments and some of the immediate actions.
<P><B>The accident at Tomsk</B>
<P>Last April the Agency was invited to visit the nuclear centre, Tomsk-7, in Siberia, where an accident at a reprocessing plant had taken place a
few days earlier.  The purpose was to provide representatives of the international community with first hand information about the radiological situation
in the area of the accident and its consequences for the population and the environment.  Less than 24 hours after the invitation had arrived at the
Agency, we had experts on their way to Siberia.  The team undertook a preliminary assessment of the radiological situation.  Some samples of soil,
vegetation, water and snow, collected by the team of experts which inspected the site of the accident, were analysed at the Agency's laboratories in
Seibersdorf.  The measurements confirmed the absence of radiologically significant amounts of caesium isotopes.  The amount of plutonium in
vegetation and soil was also found to be negligible.  The measurements also confirmed the data communicated by the Russian officials on the relative
composition of the four fission products: zirconium-95, ruthenium-103, ruthenium-106 and niobium-95.  A report containing a number of
recommendations was submitted to the Russian authorities.
<P><B>Visit to St. Petersburg</B>
<P>In May 1993 the Agency's Assessment of Safety Significant Events Team (ASSET) carried out a two week visit to the Leningrad Nuclear
Power Plant.  Since the Chernobyl accident, a great number of safety improvements have been carried out at the plant, however the ASSET team
found that the training of the operators and maintenance personnel could be improved and the failure of the electrical, control and instrumentation
systems is occurring too frequently.  More recently a large team of experts under Agency auspices visited the Smolensk nuclear power plant Nr. 3 and
had useful discussions with their Russian counterparts.
<P><B>Nuclear dumping in the sea</B>
<P>The issue of nuclear waste dumping in the Arctic Seas by the former Soviet Union has attracted much international public attention and the
Agency seeks to help establish the facts.  A project has been launched which seeks to evaluate the possible health and environmental effects of the
dumping.  Secondly the Agency is directly involved in the Norwegian-Russian exploratory visits to the Barents and Kara Seas through the participation
of staff of the Monaco Laboratory.  More information has still to be obtained before a reliable assessment of the potential impact of the dumping can be
made, but it is hoped that the work can be completed and reported to the London Convention within three years.
<P><B>Let me sum up:</B>
<OL>
<LI>The environmental problems which are facing us have gone from local to becoming regional and global and now threaten to have a
serious impact on the global climate.  The wastes from our energy use are an important part of the problem, in particular the CO2, SO2 and NOx from
fossil fuels.
<LI>	Many nuclear techniques are of direct help to avoid environmental damage and to use natural resources more efficiently.  We must
make more efforts to demystify nuclear energy to the public and explain that we can use it and are using it to the benefit of the world.
<LI>	We must explain in particular that nuclear power, used safely, gives us great amounts of energy without causing acid rains or global
warming.  The limited volumes of waste which it produces can be altogether isolated from the biosphere.
<LI>	We must further show in practice that the nuclear waste can be safely handled and clean up where it has been imprudently handled,
especially in the military sphere.
<LI>	We must show, through coming years of good nuclear operations around the whole world, that nuclear power is one of the safest
ways of generating energy.
<LI>	Lastly through nuclear disarmament and successful non-proliferation we must ensure that nuclear energy becomes an exclusively
peaceful power.
</OL>
In the matter of safety, it is understood by the nuclear power industry that the level worldwide must be so high that accidents with significant
releases into the environment will virtually never occur.  National and international authorities are dedicated to achieving this, and there is an
intensification of international co-operation.  To existing non-binding standards for nuclear safety there may soon be added an international convention
containing safety fundamentals, which will become legally binding upon States adhering to it.
<P>The IAEA is promoting nuclear safety in several ways other than by the conclusion of binding international conventions.
<P>The Agency has developed a comprehensive set of Nuclear Safety Standards (NUSS) comprising some sixty publications in five subject
areas associated with nuclear power.  Following the Chernobyl accident, relevant standards were updated to take account of experience from the
accident and advances in knowledge and approaches.  The NUSS publications reflect an international consensus on the requirements for nuclear
safety and form a basis on which national requirements can be built.
<P>Since the 1980s, the Agency has also provided a growing number of advisory expert services to improve safety at specific nuclear
installations.
<P>In 1985, the IAEA established a high-level International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group (INSAG), composed of senior safety experts, to give
independent advice on nuclear safety issues.  INSAG produced, in 1988, a particularly important, comprehensive set of Basic Safety Principles for
Nuclear Power Plants.  Included in these principles is the goal that existing nuclear power plants should have a probability of a severe accident not
