operating years.  Future nuclear plants should be safer than this by a factor of at least ten.  The present goal is considered achievable through good
safety management and a `safety culture'.
<P>The design safety goal set by INSAG for new plants is easily surpassed by most  emerging designs.  These designs often include passive
safety features and seek to achieve a design level of safety at which the risks of an accident are determined mainly be external events such as
possible airplane crashes or earthquakes rather than internal plant faults.  The IAEA is seeking further international agreement on more detailed safety
objectives for future plants based on these new designs.
<P>The IAEA has also developed an International Nuclear Event Scale (INES) - to classify the severity of nuclear accidents and incidents in a
manner that is understandable to news media and the public.  This event scale may help to show to the public that most nuclear incidents and events
are trivial.  This may be important because the public's attitude to nuclear power is based on its perceptions of how well nuclear power functions.
<P>If an excellent international operating record is attained over a period of time for nuclear power plants worldwide, and if this is perceived by the
public, I think we will find that the expanded use of nuclear power, which may prove to be indispensable from the environmental point of view, may
also be fully acceptable to the public.
<P>It is clearly a great challenge for you in Russia to make nuclear energy safe and environmentally acceptable in the Russian Federation - not
least to clean up after accidents and imprudent waste handling.  The IAEA is working to assist you in this vital work to improve nuclear safety and
restore the environment.
<P>I should now like to use a few minutes to talk about recent IAEA work outside the themes of nuclear power and the environment - especially
as this work has regard to the countries of the former Soviet Union.
<P>The growing acceptance of IAEA full-scope safeguards - e.g. in Argentina, Brazil and South Africa - is giving the Agency more installations
and ever-growing quantities of nuclear material to safeguard.  An even greater challenge has arisen from the expectation of the public and of
governments, after the events in Iraq, that full-scope safeguards should be strengthened to detect and deter any non-declared secret nuclear
activities.
