<P>The Agency has obtained information about nuclear materials, identified safeguards equipment needs, and verified inventories of nuclear
material.  Almost all of the major nuclear facilities and installations in Latvia, Belarus, Ukraine and Kazakhstan have now been visited by Agency
experts.  Thus, it is expected that all preparatory activities for the future application of safeguards will be completed soon in these States.  However,
for the Agency to actually apply safeguards, the conclusion of safeguards agreements will be required and this will occur after accession to the NPT.
<P><B>Radiation Protection in the NIS</B>
<P>In response to requests from several countries of the former Soviet Union, the Agency has developed an international initiative aimed at
strengthening national infrastructures for radiation protection and nuclear safety in countries of the former Soviet Union.  The Secretariat of the Agency
and the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) worked out a proposal designed to address problems not covered by other international
initiatives to date, notably the safety issues related to research reactors, uranium mining and milling, and installations using radiation sources in
medicine, agriculture and industry.
<P>The initiative comprises three phases: (1) a meeting for the exchange of information; (2) the development of projects, consisting of assistance
packages for individual countries or for groups of countries with similar needs; and (3) the actual implementation of these assistance packages.
<P>The meeting which took place in Vienna from 4 to 7 May was attended by representatives of Russia and most of the former States members
of the Soviet Union.  UNDP financed this first phase of the project and has indicated that up to $300,000 may be made available soon to implement
the second phase of the initiative, project developments and some of the immediate actions.
<P><B>The accident at Tomsk</B>
<P>Last April the Agency was invited to visit the nuclear centre, Tomsk-7, in Siberia, where an accident at a reprocessing plant had taken place a
few days earlier.  The purpose was to provide representatives of the international community with first hand information about the radiological situation
in the area of the accident and its consequences for the population and the environment.  Less than 24 hours after the invitation had arrived at the
Agency, we had experts on their way to Siberia.  The team undertook a preliminary assessment of the radiological situation.  Some samples of soil,
vegetation, water and snow, collected by the team of experts which inspected the site of the accident, were analysed at the Agency's laboratories in
Seibersdorf.  The measurements confirmed the absence of radiologically significant amounts of caesium isotopes.  The amount of plutonium in
vegetation and soil was also found to be negligible.  The measurements also confirmed the data communicated by the Russian officials on the relative
composition of the four fission products: zirconium-95, ruthenium-103, ruthenium-106 and niobium-95.  A report containing a number of
recommendations was submitted to the Russian authorities.
<P><B>Visit to St. Petersburg</B>
<P>In May 1993 the Agency's Assessment of Safety Significant Events Team (ASSET) carried out a two week visit to the Leningrad Nuclear
Power Plant.  Since the Chernobyl accident, a great number of safety improvements have been carried out at the plant, however the ASSET team
found that the training of the operators and maintenance personnel could be improved and the failure of the electrical, control and instrumentation
systems is occurring too frequently.  More recently a large team of experts under Agency auspices visited the Smolensk nuclear power plant Nr. 3 and
had useful discussions with their Russian counterparts.
<P><B>Nuclear dumping in the sea</B>
<P>The issue of nuclear waste dumping in the Arctic Seas by the former Soviet Union has attracted much international public attention and the
Agency seeks to help establish the facts.  A project has been launched which seeks to evaluate the possible health and environmental effects of the
dumping.  Secondly the Agency is directly involved in the Norwegian-Russian exploratory visits to the Barents and Kara Seas through the participation
of staff of the Monaco Laboratory.  More information has still to be obtained before a reliable assessment of the potential impact of the dumping can be
made, but it is hoped that the work can be completed and reported to the London Convention within three years.
<P><B>Let me sum up:</B>
<OL>
<LI>	The environmental problems which are facing us have gone from local to becoming regional and global and now threaten to have a
serious impact on the global climate.  The wastes from our energy use are an important part of the problem, in particular the CO2, SO2 and NOx from
fossil fuels.
<P>
<LI>Many nuclear techniques are of direct help to avoid environmental damage and to use natural resources more efficiently.  We must
make more efforts to demystify nuclear energy to the public and explain that we can use it and are using it to the benefit of the world.
<LI>We must explain in particular that nuclear power, used safely, gives us great amounts of energy without causing acid rains or global
warming.  The limited volumes of waste which it produces can be altogether isolated from the biosphere.
<LI>We must further show in practice that the nuclear waste can be safely handled and clean up where it has been imprudently handled,
especially in the military sphere.
<LI>	We must show, through coming years of good nuclear operations around the whole world, that nuclear power is one of the safest
ways of generating energy.
<LI>	Lastly through nuclear disarmament and successful non-proliferation we must ensure that nuclear energy becomes an exclusively
peaceful power.
</OL><HR>
