<TITLE>Statement by IAEA Director General Hans Blix at the First Arab Conference on the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Statement by IAEA Director General Hans Blix at the First Arab Conference on the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>First Arab Conference on the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Tripoli, Libya</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>2 February 1992</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
<B> INTRODUCTION</B>
<P>To many people the words "atomic" or "nuclear" evoke mainly fear.  They think of bombs and Chernobyl.  It is certainly important for us to be aware of the risks of some uses of the atom, because they do exist.  But this should not lead us to overlook, for instance, that radiation is a principal way of treating cancer.  Nor should we forget that over 16% of the world's electricity supply comes from nuclear power - compared with 17% for hydro power.  Nuclear energy can be used for good and bad.  It can be used prudently or carelessly.  Used for peaceful purposes and prudently nuclear energy has tremendous benefits to offer mankind.
<P>In 1957 the IAEA began its work with the twin tasks of promoting the peaceful uses of nuclear energy and of verifying that such use was exclusively peaceful.  This remains the core of the Agency's work.  However, the volume of work has increased much since 1957.  Let me give you some figures.
<P>We should all be aware that budget and manpower increases do not necessarily mean that useful work is done.  It depends on what you do with the money and the people!  However, the IAEA is an international organization with a reputation for using both its money and its personnel well, and I think the figures which I will give you therefore do say something about expansion of useful work by the IAEA.
<P>In its first full year of work, l958, there were 81 professional staff in the secretariat.  In 1992, there are 721.  In 1958, the budget was just under $4 million.  For 1992, the  budget is approximately $200 million.  From outside the budget some $43 million are available for technical co-operation.  Membership today stands at 112 States, and will soon be 116 when the three Baltic States and Yemen ratify the Statute.  The Russian Federation will continue the membership, rights and obligations of the USSR and we expect States of the Commonwealth of Independent States to join.
<P>The IAEA does not operate any nuclear power plants.  Nor does it licence such plants.  Nor does it run any cancer radiation wards.  What, then, does it do?
<P>The Agency is an instrument through which the member governments co-operate in the nuclear field.  The co-operation takes four main forms:
<P>The first is the exchange of information and experience.  There are, for instance, over 200 international expert meetings a year.  Experience is also shared through the dissemination of a vast number of specialist publications and through the operation of the 
International Nuclear Information System (INIS), a comprehensive database which is an electronic bibliography for nuclear science and technology.
<P>	A second - more advanced - form of co-operation lies in the joint international elaboration of norms in various nuclear matters, e.g. recommendations, standards, guidelines or, indeed, binding conventions.
<P>The third form of co-operation is the collective effort to try to obtain assurance, through the safeguards system, that nuclear material and installations in civil programmes are not diverted from peaceful to military uses and that all material subject to safeguards are declared and safeguarded.
<P>The fourth form of co-operation is using the Agency as a mechanism for services to Member States.  The transfer of technology from the industrialized to developing countries through technical assistance and co-operation is such a service.  There are many services organized to strengthen nuclear safety and radiation protection.  You might also consider the safeguards system a service.  The outside, independent and impartial verification of the peaceful character of nuclear activities in States is a service to Member States to have it demonstrated with a credibility that self-inspection can never give, that activities on their territories are exclusively peaceful.  Trade in nuclear material and equipment would hardly be possible without safeguards.
<OL>
<LI><B>	TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER: NUCLEAR ENERGY AND DEVELOPING WORLD </B>
	I shall begin to talk about the Agency's role in the transfer of technology to developing countries.
<P>	What role does nuclear energy have for developing countries?  It is very clear in today's world that "appropriate" technology is much more than tractors and sewing machines.  Where advanced   including nuclear   technology can be used economically and competently for development, it should be used.
<UL>
<LI>(a)	Agriculture
<P>	In the field of agriculture, where we operate a joint programme with the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), nuclear techniques are in fact already making a substantial impact.  Let me touch here on some of the key uses in the agricultural field.
<P>Fertilizers.  Nitrogen fertilizers are used widely to increase agricultural production.  If they are used excessively or inappropriately, however, many fertilizers harm the environment and lead to pollution of water supplies.  A nuclear technique, which uses a stable nitrogen isotope as a tracer, can help us to determine the best form, timing, and 
placement of fertilizers and thereby to avoid waste and reduce pollution.  Other isotopes are used to detect, measure, and track fertilizer supplied nutrients in soil and plants, to determine the availability of soil moisture, and to study the natural process of nitrogen fixation by certain plants.  Thereby you can considerably reduce fertilizer costs, and at the same time increase plant protein.
<P>	Sustainable agricultural production requires an adequate supply of water in soils.   Nuclear techniques help irrigation specialists and others to choose the best option to increase or improve the way water resources are used.  Results of co ordinated research programmes where neutron moisture gauges are used extensively show that traditional irrigation methods can be improved to cut total water use by 40%.  Saved resources can thus be spent to irrigate additional areas.
<P>Plant breeding and genetics.  The radiation of seeds, provoking mutants, can be used to develop new strains of important food crops.  Sometimes these techniques are used in combination with other biotechnology.   These techniques have yielded new varieties of many different crop species, such as rice, wheat, and soy bean.  They may have a better resistance to disease, be of a higher product quality, or have a higher yield.  Worldwide, more than l500 mutant cultivars of crop plants and ornamental plants have been released to growers in the past 30 years.  Eight percent of agricultural land in China, for example, is planted with mutants of rice, wheat, corn, and cotton.  In Asia as a whole, over 600 plant varieties derived from seeds or plant tissues exposed to ionizing radiation are now growing on millions of hectares of land.
<P>The Agency provides assistance to Member States in the proper application of mutation breeding techniques in highly diversifed plant breeding programmes.  Research contracts and agreements focus on the advancement of mutation breeding technology particularly to improve root and tuber crops, oil seed crops, and cereals, and to improve resistance to disease.  Plant breeders from 46 countries at a recent meeting assessed the economic benefit of mutant crop cultivars as running into billions of dollars.
<P>Animal production and health.  Sensitive techniques based on the use of radioactive "tracers" are used to improve animal production and health,  e.g. in studies of the productivity of sheep and goats in both Africa and Asia.  Similar methods are used to determine whether animals are infected with disease causing agents.
<P>To make some of the modern nuclear-based techniques easier to use in the field, the Agency produces standardized kits and distributes them worldwide.  For example, under the Pan African Rinderpest Campaign, kits are sent regularly to 17 African countries so that veterinarians can monitor accurately the progress of their vaccination programmes.
<P>	Insect and Pest Control.  Radiation can be used to sexually sterilize insects.  When insects that are mass reared and sterilized in laboratories are released in the wild population, the female mates of sterilized males will not produce offspring.  This method, called the Sterile Insect Technique (SIT), has been used successfully to control or eradicate dangerous insects and pests which account for substantial losses in food supplies and animal production.  The technique has been further developed at the IAEA's Laboratories.
<P>The technique has been used in the past to successfully eradicate the Mediterranean fruit fly in Mexico and against various species of tsetse fly in Nigeria.
<P>	I am happy to report a further success for the technique in eradicating the New World Screwworm Fly here in Libya over a ten month period.  The fly, first detected in Libya in 1988, infested more than 12,000 animals here in 1990.  It could have spread elsewhere in 
Africa and the Mediterranean Basin, with devastating consequences for livestock and wild animals.  However, following the release of over 1,300 million sterile male flies only 6 cases were recorded in Libya in the whole of 1991.  Monitoring work has continued since release of the sterile flies ended in October last year, and if no further evidence is found, the Libyan Government should be able to declare the country officially free of the pest by June of this year.  The organization and equipment which has been set up for the screwworm and so successfully operated here in Libya, could perhaps be used now to tackle the Mediterranean Fruit Fly.
<P>	This is an excellent example of a collaborative effort, in which Libya, the FAO, the IAEA, the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) and the UN Development Programme (UNDP) combined their efforts.  Support also came from the Swedish International Development Authority, the Austrian Government, in addition to a number of other donors.  Later on you will hear more about nuclear applications in 
agriculture from Dr. Sigurbjoernsson, Director of our Joint Division with FAO and on the screwworm programme from Dr. Lindquist, Director of the screwworm field programme here in Libya who, in fact, is on loan from the IAEA to the eradication campaign.
<P><LI>(b)	Medicine<P>An area which is just as important as agriculture in terms of nuclear applications is the medical field.  A wide spectrum of techniques is available.  To take an example, chemical compounds "labelled" with short lived radioactive isotopes are especially useful for diagnostic purposes.  These compounds are "watched" as they travel through the human organs which are being studied to assess how well they are functioning.  
<P>	Radiation biology and radiotherapy.  In many countries, doctors use disposable sterilized prepacked medical supplies, such as hydodermic syringes and needles, that are thrown away after only one clinical use.  To improve quality control of sterility, the Agency has developed a code of practice for the radiation sterilization of disposable medical supplies.  The Egyptian Government with the assistance of UNDP and the Agency has installed irradiation facilities to sterilize medical supplies and preserve food using irradiation.  At the present time the Agency is assisting Syria to set up a pilot scale irradiation facility for radiation sterilization purposes.
<P>A variety of radiation techniques for cancer treatment has been devised especially for use in developing countries, where hospital resources are often limited.  One particularly successful technique is for the treatment of cervical cancer, which is common in many 
developing countries.  The Agency and WHO together with the Government of Italy, are supporting the use of this technique in Egypt where it is saving hundreds of lives each year.
<P>	Radiation dosimetry.  As many as one out of every three cancer patients in industrialized countries may receive radiation treatments.  The dose of radiation each patient receives must be precise.  Accurate dosimetry   the measurement of radiation doses 
  is vitally important.  The IAEA and many institutes in Member States have established a network of Secondary Standard Dosimetry Laboratories (SSDLs) to expand the number of laboratories that can maintain accurate standard measurement instruments.  With the assistance of the Agency an SSDL has been set up in Egypt and Algeria and one is at present under construction in Libya.  National laboratories participating in this network can determine the accuracy of their own instruments and check instruments used in the field.  For countries wihtout an operational SSDL, the IAEA's dosimetry laboratory at Seibersdorf in Austria provides calibration services upon request.
<P>	Industrial applications.   Many applications of radiation and radioisotopes are now well established in industry.  They include non destructive testing, control systems and radioactive tracers, analytical techniques and quality control.
<P>Radiotracer applications in chemical, oil, steel and cement industries have offered great economic benefits and have provided solutions to problems which could not be solved by other techniques.
<P>The most important "industrial" application of nuclear energy - nuclear power to generate electricity - is a subject to which I will revert in a moment.
</UL>
<LI><B>	IAEA REGIONAL PROGRAMMES   AFRA</B>
<P>Over the years, the IAEA and its members have found it practical to promote co operative nuclear research, development and training projects through regional institutions.  We have had very positive results from the Regional Co operation Agreement (RCA) in Asia 
and its younger counterpart   ARCAL   in Latin America.  The latest is the African Regional Co operation Agreement related to nuclear science and technology, known as AFRA.  Thirteen countries have so far acceded to it. 
<P>Regional activities can allow resources to be used more efficiently: experts can advise counterparts in several countries during the same assignment, equipment can be purchased more economically for several laboratories, and training can be organized regionally at lower cost and in the mother tongue of the participants.
<P>The AFRA programme is based on the concept of collaboration among participating African countries.  As activities increase in that region co ordination and co operation amongst countries and institutions in it should continue to improve.
In regional projects emphasis is placed on the development priorities of the Member States in the region and on contributing to their institution building.  Both are crucial in the African region where many of the countries have limited resources.
<P>	The AFRA programme has prudently concentrated at the outset on a limited number of areas.
<P>These include:<P>  Waste management, to provide training for scientists and technicians.  With Agency assistance Egypt has established a facility for the storage or treatment of liquid and solid low and medium level radioactive wastes.  This is a subject of high priority for Algeria, Egypt and Libya.
<P>Food preservation by radiation processing, in which Algeria, Egypt, Libya and Nigeria are active.
<P>Nuclear instrumentation: to maintain and repair nuclear instruments and to establish a capability to design and manufacture simple instruments.  Here, Algeria, Egypt, Madagascar, Nigeria and Tunisia are co-operating.
<P><UL>
<LI>-		Non destructive testing techniques, to improve quality control and safety through standardized, regionally harmonized certification schemes, involving Algeria, Egypt, Libya and Tunisia.
<P>	Other projects are under consideration such as one to determine the areas with Mediterranean fruit fly infestation in Algeria, Libya, Morocco and Tunisia as a basis for future programmes using the sterile insect technique.
<P>	Another effort of particular interest to developing countries, which was initiated with the active involvement of Libya, concerns the assessment of the costs of potable water production by various sizes of nuclear desalination plants at selected promising sites and to compare the costs of desalination by nuclear and other means.  Additionally, several North African countries, including Libya, have submitted a request to the Agency for assistance in carrying out a feasibility study on nuclear desalination at selected sites in this region.  It was decided to proceed simultaneously with a general assessment of nuclear desalination costs and the feasibility study.
<P>	Radiation Protection.  As nuclear techniques are used more widely, a condition for acceptance is effective protection against any injury or damage.  This is why the Agency places great emphasis on radiation protection.
<P>The number of major radiation sources in medicine, agriculture and industry - cobalt, caesium, etc. - continues to grow.  Although the overall safety record is good, it is essential to ensure that users and regulatory authorities continue to be able to meet their responsibilities, notably in the area of management of spent sources.  Radiation accidents involving loss of life or causing extensive exposures and damages have occurred in the last years in Goiania in Brazil, in Morocco, in El Salvador, in Spain (Saragossa) and in France.
<P>The IAEA has launched a new project, of particular interest to developing countries, to improve the safe management of spent sources of radiation used in medicine, industry, and other fields.  Such sources include cobalt 60 (commonly used in radiotherapy units and 
industrial irradiators) iridium 192 (used in industrial radiography and medical care), caesium 137 (used in agricultural moisture and density gauges, medical care, and radiography), and radium, once widely distributed in developing and industrialized countries for medical and other applications but now largely replaced by other sources.  Worldwide, more than half a million sealed radiation sources are estimated to be in commercial use.
<P>The project is particularly directed towards assisting developing countries, where needs are considered most urgent.  The estimated number of spent radiation sources in developing countries is about 30,000, most of which are radium sources.  Under the project's action plan, which covers a period of 5 years, international experts will convene training courses and conduct field missions to assist authorities in identifying, collecting, conditioning, and properly storing spent radiation sources.  Also planned is assistance to countries interested in establishing interim storage facilities on a national or regional basis.  Before concluding my comments on the transfer of nuclear technology to developing countries through the IAEA, I should like to stress that we could handle a much larger volume of Technical Co-operation Projects if more funds were available.  For instance, in the 1992 TC Programme, projects positively assessed and representing a total value of       $14 million, have not been included because of lack of funds.
</UL>
<LI><B>NUCLEAR POWER</B>
<P>I turn now to the subject of nuclear power.  We live in an energy hungry world, where appetite for electricity in particular is growing.  Increase in the world population, urbanization and the demand for a higher standard of living provide the basis for the greater 
demand for electricity.  Over the past 15 years energy use more than doubled in developing 
nations and electricity demand went up by almost 200%.  This electricity demand is projected to grow at an annual rate of nearly 6 percent into the next century whereas the world's total consumption of electricity will be growing at a rate of about 3 percent.
<P>
</OL>
The World Energy Council reports that worldwide consumption of energy will increase by 50 to 75 percent by the year 2020, even with vigorous efforts for more efficient uses of energy.  The question is:  where will this energy come from?
<P>The answer is that there will be a mix, as there is today, of fossil fuels coal, oil, gas   plus hydro power and nuclear, with renewables such as solar, wind power and biomass becoming significant only well into the next century.  China plans to double its coal burning capacity in this next decade, and in India it is supposed to treble, although both countries do have a nuclear component as well.
<P>The problem with burning fossil fuels is the effect they are reported to have on the world's atmosphere and climate   the greenhouse effect and, regionally, in the form of acidification.
<P>Nuclear power has the advantage of giving rise to no harmful emissions in normal operation.   This means nuclear power helps us to avoid CO2 and NOx and SO2 emissions.  According to our calculation, if the electricity currently produced by nuclear power plants 
worldwide were produced instead by burning coal, a further 8 percent or l.6 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide would be added to the world's atmosphere.
<P>The Japanese Government has announced two new programmes on energy policy   one is "Targets for Supply of Alternative Energy Sources to Oil" and the other is an "Action Programme to Arrest Global Warming."  The Japanese plans include targets for use of alternative energy sources for oil including nuclear power.  Those targets state that the supply of nuclear power will increase 2.5 times between 1989 and 2010 with a target of 30.8% of electricity coming from nuclear by then.  The Action Programme to reduce greenhouse effect causing gases states that Japan will stabilize carbon dioxide emissions per capita after 2000 at the same levels as 1990 on condition that the industrialized countries of the world make joint efforts to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.  It is difficult to see how such efforts can be achieved without the contribution that nuclear can make.
<P>It is clear that we can hope to reduce or contain CO2 emissions only through international action and it is generally understood that at least one of these actions will have to involve limiting the burning of fossil fuels.  Such a limitation will raise formidable economic and political problems.  Developing countries are not likely to accept limitation of their economic development plans to help solve a problem which has been caused mostly by 
the industrialized world.  It may also reasonably be argued that the technically more 
advanced countries have a political duty to employ nuclear power as the technically more demanding solution.
<P>	I do not claim that expanded use of nuclear power alone is the answer to the greenhouse problem.  I do believe, however, that it must be part of the answer.
<P>Among the objections to nuclear power that are frequently voiced, three are particularly common:  the issues of safety, waste and proliferation.  Let me address all three.<P><B>Safety.</B><BR>
  No one will deny that operating nuclear power requires adequate safety everywhere in the world.  Some have suggested that there should be binding international safety rules and inspection of their implementation.  Although governments are not at present ready to confer a supervisory role on any international body in the field of nuclear safety, they may accept some binding rules relating to safety.  The Agency is currently exploring the possibility of drafting a global safety convention, to which a series of specific protocols on specific safety issues, e.g. transport of nuclear material, etc. could be attached.
<P>Already in the 1970s an international consensus on safety standards and practices was worked out within the IAEA, the so called NUSS programme, with five Codes of Practice for nuclear power plant safety.  Member States have used these extensively in the elaboration of national regulations.  To take an important example, China, with its emerging nuclear power programme, has adopted the NUSS standards as the basis for its national regulatory requirements.
<P>Standards and regulation are not enough to ensure nuclear safety.  Equal attention must be paid to operational safety in the some 430 nuclear power plants which are now 
operating in the world and the 100 or so plants which will soon be put into operation.  To 
assist its Member States in this regard, the Agency is offering several services which are being increasingly used.
<P>Most important are the so called Operational Safety Review Teams (OSARTs) are sent to nuclear power plants in response to a request.  The teams are composed of experts from both the Agency and Member States. Over a period of several weeks they thoroughly review plant operations management and procedures.
<P>What about the future nuclear power plants which are supposed to be safer and more tolerant of human errors than the ones belonging to the current generation?
<P>Actually even today's most common types of nuclear power reactors are designed to tolerate a great deal of human error.  Their safety systems have much built in redundancy and they rely on decades of proven technology and engineering.  In the TMI accident, the containment worked as the final barrier in spite of several operator errors which caused a melt of about 50% of the core.  The accident at Chernobyl occurred because of deficiencies in the design and because several safety systems had in fact been switched off.
<P>The industry now seems ready to present advanced versions of the currently most common reactor types, with standardized and simpler design, more "passive" safety features and often smaller sizes.  This could make them attractive for the industrialized countries 
seeking to meet the current lower rate of increase in electricity demand.  They might also 
be interesting for some developing countries.  The emergence of these new reactors should not and does not preclude R & D work on radically new types of power reactors.  From the Agency's side, we are seeking to promote renewed co operation on this subject between governments and industry, also internationally.
<P><B>Nuclear waste management.</B>
<P>  Nuclear waste is another issue of key importance for public acceptance of nuclear power.  Experts have been convinced for a number of years that the concepts and technologies which already exist for waste disposal guarantee the safety of present and future generations.  However, the public concern, often caused by nuclear opposition groups, remains in many countries.  A sustained effort to disseminate factual information is needed.  However, the actual construction of repositories for waste and installations for interim disposal of spent fuel would be the most tangible way to demonstrate our ability to handle this issue.  Such construction will gradually come in more and more countries.
<P>Within the IAEA a programme   called RADWASS   will provide a structured series of international consensus documents on radioactive waste management safety.  It may be particularly valuable for developing States wishing to establish waste management programmes.
<P>Transboundary movement of radioactive waste.  Recently an expert code was adopted by consensus within the IAEA on the international transboundary movement of radioactive waste.  This code was a response to reports of illicit transfer and dumping of hazardous 
wastes, notably in African countries.  Although no case of illicit dumping of nuclear waste had been found, the Agency's Member States have drafted a code which establishes basic principles for the transfer of radioactive wastes.  It affirms the sovereign right of every State to prohibit the movement of radioactive waste into, from or through its territory.  It further requires that transboundary movements of radioactive waste should only take place in 
accordance with internationally accepted safety standards, and with the prior notification and consent of the sending, receiving and transit States and in accordance with their respective laws and regulations.
<UL>
<LI>4.<B>	SAFEGUARDS: PREVENTING DIVERSION OF NUCLEAR MATERIAL</B>
<P>	A third public concern about nuclear power is the risk that its use may facilitate a proliferation of nuclear weapons.  Although none of the five declared nuclear-weapon States came to nuclear weapons via the development of civil nuclear power, the risk of a misuse of such programmes exists.  The Non-Proliferation Treaty and some other treaties enable States to make binding pledges not to use peaceful installations to develop weapons.  To be credible such pledges require verification of the nuclear activities.  
<P>The task of verifying that nuclear material in civil inventories and programmes remains peaceful and are not diverted to military applications has now been a central function of the IAEA for a quarter of a century.  This was the world's first experience of international on-site inspection.  Of late, it has taken on even greater importance as a result of several factors.
<P><UL>
	<LI>First, the more the nuclear arsenals of nuclear-weapon States may become reduced, the more important it becomes that no further States acquire and develop nuclear weapons capacity.<P>
<LI>Secondly, the tendency is toward more universal support for non-proliferation.  Both China and France are preparing to sign the Non Proliferation Treaty.  South Africa has already adhered to the treaty and accepted inspections by the IAEA.  Late last year Argentina and Brazil accepted a comprehensive safeguards agreement.  A similar step was just taken by the DPRK.  The NPT has already 140 States parties.  I see universality of adherence to the non-proliferation regime as a realistic and desirable ambition for 1995 when the NPT comes up for extension.  The regime must then be reliable.<P>	The discovery of a major clandestine uranium enrichment programme in Iraq, an NPT country with full-scope safeguards, has led to calls for more vigorous checks and inspection to ensure that all countries that have adhered to the NPT and have accepted to place all nuclear installations under IAEA safeguards actually live up to their obligations.
<P>	To give confidence that there is no clandestine development of nuclear weapons anywhere, the IAEA verification system must be strengthened.
</UL>
<P>What sort of steps do we have in mind?  The Agency needs to receive information from a variety of sources and not be dependent exclusively on the declarations of an inspected State.  We cannot look for possibly undeclared material or activities unless 
we have some information about them.  However, all information must be very carefully evaluated.  If there were reasons to believe that undeclared nuclear material or facilities existed, the State concerned would be asked for explanations.  Should such explanations be 
deemed inadequate, the possibility of a special inspection would come to the fore.  Should the State refuse to receive such inspection, the Board of Governors might transmit the question to the Security Council.
<P>Some have asked whether the IAEA's inspections in Iraq will serve as a model for strengthened safeguards.  The answer is no.  The role which the IAEA has been called upon to play in Iraq by the Security Council under Resolution 687 goes far beyond what will be acceptable to States under safeguards.  It is clear, however, that safeguards must be improved as regards their ability to give confidence about the absence of non-declared nuclear facilities.
<P>To a State which respects a pledge given under the NPT or other treaty not to develop or acquire nuclear weapons the strengthening of safeguards should be welcomed.  There is no question of encroachment of sovereignty.  These activities take place on the basis of agreements freely made.  The verification which occurs will result in a stronger - more credible - assurance about the peaceful nature of its nuclear programme.  Indeed, it would seem to me that if allegations were made about the existence of clandestine nuclear activities or installations in a country, that country would be well advised spontaneously to ask the 
<P>IAEA to visit the location and report on it.  IAEA verification should be able to detect violations of NPT and safeguards agreements, but they should also be able to clear a country of unfounded allegations or suspicions.
I shall not go into many other measures that are now discussed in order to strengthen the effectiveness of safeguards and thereby the confidence they can offer that a country accepting full-scope safeguards actually respects its non-proliferation pledge.
<P>	I should mention, however, that the IAEA currently has some 200 inspectors and a safeguards budget of some $60 million.  With this we check nuclear material at well over 900 installations worldwide.
<P>The strengthening of safeguards is not the only thing that can be done to reduce the risk of proliferation of nuclear weapons.  Supplier States may have to show more rigour and vigilance in the control of experts of nuclear sensitive items and materials.
<P>An even more important factor is détente - global and regional.  Perceived threats to a country's security may constitute an inducement to acquire or approach nuclear weapons capacity.  The geographic areas of continuing proliferation concern are, of course, the Indian sub continent and the Middle East.  It might not be unrealistic to hope that if global nuclear disarmament accelerates and the regional political climate improves, India and Pakistan will at some point be able to come to an arrangement similar to that arrived at recently by Argentina and Brazil whereby mutual, bilateral nuclear openness is practiced and supplemented by international inspections.
</UL>
As regards the Middle East, it can only be hoped that a peaceful settlement will result from the conference that has started.  The question of weapons of mass destruction, including nuclear weapons, is on the agenda, and might be solved within the context of a broad peaceful settlement.  All the States in the region are on record as supporting a nuclear-
weapon-free zone.  No doubt the question of verification will be central for confidence within such a zone.  I have been asked by the General Conference of the IAEA to explore with 
countries in the region what kind of safeguards would be required and I am doing so through contacts in capitals.  Let me only add on this point that confidence between countries about 
non-proliferation can gradually grow not only from effective verification but also from active co-operation in the nuclear sphere, e.g. through technical or scientific projects.  I wish you well in your efforts at this conference to develop active regional co-operation.<HR>
</DOC>
