<TITLE>Statement by IAEA Director General Hans Blix on the occasion of the 25th Anniversary of the Tlatelolco Treaty</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Statement by IAEA Director General Hans Blix on the occasion of the 25th Anniversary of the Tlatelolco Treaty</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>25th Anniversary of the Tlatelolco Treaty</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Mexico City, Mexico</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>14 February 1992</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
I appreciate the invitation to participate in this 25th anniversary of the Tlatelolco Treaty for the prohibition of nuclear weapons in Latin America and I should like to begin by congratulating the Latin-American States to the creation and possession of this important instrument.  May I turn in particular to Mexico which has played such a crucial role as initiator and guardian of the Treaty.  And let me pay homage to that indefatigable and persistent crusader for disarmament who earned the respect of the world for Mexico's and his own efforts, Alfonso Garcia Robles.  His passing away was a great loss for all of us.
<P>Many people think only of bombs and of Chernobyl when "nuclear" is mentioned.  Both are indeed realities which we must tackle.  But in our preoccupation with these problems, we must not forget that nuclear energy is used for enormous benefit to mankind and that its potential for further use is great.
<P>We must not forget that nuclear techniques are of central and growing importance in medicine.  The use of radioisotopes is of great value in diagnostic work and the use of radiation is still a principal method of treating many forms of cancer.
<P>We must not forget that nuclear techniques are helping us to achieve better crops and to protect them.  Nuclear agriculture is an important branch.  New strains of seeds are provoked by radiation and some are found that are more resistant to drought or salt or cold.
<P>Nor should we forget that nuclear power gives the world some 17% of its electricity -only one percent less than all the hydro power in the world.  We must not ignore the Chernobyl accident, but consistently strengthen nuclear safety - phase out or modify reactors that are not up to high standards, design new, safer, easier to operate plants.  But we must also not ignore that nuclear power is the only economically viable alternative to fossil fuels -coal, oil and gas - when we need additional large-scale generation of electricity.  Hydro power is already exploited fully in large areas of the world and renewable sources like wind power and solar power do not yield the quantities we look for.  Within foreseeable time nuclear power is the main alternative, if we wish to avoid increasing our use of the fossil fuels which all give rise to carbon dioxide and thereby contribute to the risk of global warming.  I am not suggesting that nuclear power is the solution to the global warming or acid rain.  But it is unrealistic to believe that we can tackle these problems without the use of nuclear power.
<P>Some people oppose the use of nuclear power for fear that a further reliance on nuclear techniques will lead to weapons production.  We should remember, however, that the weapons techniques can be developed also without power stations.  No one of recognized nuclear-weapon States began with nuclear power.  They began with weapons.  Indeed, even if all the some 430 nuclear power plants in the world were closed, it would not make weapons development impossible.
<P>The road we must go is rather to create such conditions that countries do not feel any security need for nuclear weapons.  Mutuality is of importance.  A country can renounce nuclear weapons if potential adversaries also renounce them and effective verification gives confidence that no cheating occurs.  This is really the basis and rationale of nuclear-weapon-free zones.  It is easier to abstain from these weapons if you do it together with others in the same region.  It is also easier if the five nuclear-weapon States reduce their arsenals through nuclear disarmament and if they stop testing new weapons.
<P>The Tlatelolco Treaty was the first to establish a nuclear-weapon-free zone in a large inhabited area of the world.  The Non-Proliferation Treaty with its world-wide scope came second.  There is no competition between these treaties.  Most Latin American States are parties to both.  The fundamental aim served by both is to ensure that nuclear weapons do not spread and that disarmament, especially nuclear disarmament, be promoted.
<P>As we seek the full accomplishment of that aim in the next five to ten years, the example set by Latin-American States in concluding a treaty that responded to their particular requirements and conditions is important.  It may well be that some other areas, too, may best be made secure against nuclear weapons by regional arrangements.  States in the South Pacific have concluded the Rarotonga Treaty and recently the Republic of Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea have issued a joint declaration for a Non-Nuclear Korean Peninsula, supplementing their adherence to the NPT.  A zone free of weapons of mass destruction is an important point on the agenda of the Middle East.
<P>	Today we have reasons both for optimism and for vigilance.<BR>
<P>The increasing optimism is justified by the fact that there remain only a handful of States with significant nuclear know-how outside the treaties which together form a non-proliferation regime and it is justified by the fact that the largest retainers of nuclear weapons - the United States and Russia - are embarking on significant reductions of their nuclear arsenals.  The nightmarish armaments race should be turned into a disarmament race.  It is not unrealistic, in my view, to aim at a universalization of binding non-proliferation commitments and drastic nuclear disarmament by 1995.
<P>The increasing vigilance is prompted by our recent experience that a State which had legally and voluntarily committed itself to non-proliferation could embark on a weapons programme without being detected.  The very essence of non-proliferation commitments and their verification is that neighbours, regions and the world shall be able to rely upon them with confidence and without risking surprises that may be catastrophic from the viewpoint of security.  If it is not possible to reduce to zero the risk that clandestine and impermissible nuclear activities could take place without detection, it is possible to considerably reduce the risk.
<P>Firstly, a universalization of binding non-proliferation commitments should, in itself, help to reduce the risk of violations.  So long as any States remain outside the non-proliferation regime and the nuclear-weapon States have not decisively embarked upon nuclear disarmament, the regime could still be subject to some strain.
<P>Secondly, the system through which we verify that States comply with their non-proliferation commitments under the various treaties - the safeguards system - can and must be strengthened.  For the vast number of States which rely in their security policies upon non-proliferation pledges of neighbours and other States, it is not enough to feel certain that there is no diversion of nuclear material for weapons purposes from declared facilities.  They want to feel sure that - whether declared or not - no nuclear materials will be devoted to weapons.  Where there exist reasonable doubts in this regard, such doubts call for explanations and - if these are not sufficient - inspection.  In my view we are not here concerned with any inroads on State sovereignty.  Of course, inspectors are given the right to visit countries and nuclear facilities or suspected nuclear facilities.  However, acceptance of the system is a voluntary act, made by States because they find it is in their interest.  Through this system of independent outside inspection their non-proliferation stance achieves a credibility that no self-inspection could offer.
<P>It is now 25 years ago that the Tlatelolco Treaty was concluded.  It has been in force for a great many countries in this hemisphere and it has contributed to the detente between Latin American States.  After the conclusion by Argentina and Brazil of the agreement at Guadalajara last year on a joint accountancy and control system and the safeguards agreement between the Brazilian-Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Material (ABACC), Argentina, Brazil and the IAEA, it is not unreasonable to expect that the Tlatelolco Treaty will soon be joined by all parties required for it to enter into force for all.  The world is eagerly looking forward to this event.  I note in this context the Foz de Iguacu Declaration on Common Policy between Argentina and Brazil and the undertakings of the two States "to adopt, after the safeguards agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency is concluded, pertinent measures leading to the full entry into force for both countries of the Treaty including actions at updating and improving its text."  Entry into force of the treaty should encourage and spur us to new efforts at disarmament and demilitarization.
<P>It is for the parties to the Treaty to examine what improvements may be appropriate in the Tlatelolco Treaty and to decide whether such improvements require formal amendments.
<P>	We need to build on our experience.  Twenty five years ago many thought nuclear explosions might have important peaceful uses.  Experience has told us that such explosions for peaceful purposes are not a practical need and we cannot moreover distinguish them from weapons testing.  Experience has also told us that inspection has not impeded national nuclear development, nor resulted in the revelation of commercial secrets - which some feared 25 years ago.  Experience has rather told us that commitment to non-proliferation and credible verification to it is a precondition for full participation in nuclear trade.  Suppliers want to feel sure that they don't contribute to weapons development.
<P>Verification and inspection still evoke mixed feelings in some.  I think it is time we recognize that verification is a service to all who respect their obligations.  They have nothing to fear from it - only to gain.  And should some State try secretly to disregard its commitment it is vitally important for all others that it be detected at an early stage.  This is a lesson which we have learnt in the past year.
<P>On the part of the IAEA I should like to conclude by expressing support for the efforts to make the Tlatelolco Treaty a live force in a disarming world and by assuring you that the IAEA remains at the service of Latin American States and of all other States to provide with the co-operation of the States comprehensive objective verification of non-proliferation commitments and thereby contribute to confidence, detente and a full use of the peaceful potential of nuclear energy for the benefit of their people.<HR>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B39-31</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA059-000320-B036-8</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://nesihp01.iaea.or.at:80/worldatom/inforesource/dgspeeches/dgsp1992n15.html 193.81.60.210 19970114201425 text/html 34491
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Tue, 14 Jan 1997 20:14:27 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<TITLE>Seminar on Energy, Economics, Environment and Nuclear Power</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Seminar on Energy, Economics, Environment and Nuclear Power</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by Hans Blix, IAEA Director General</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Cairo, Egypt</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>3 March 1992</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
The world around us generously generates front page events, such as the break-up of the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia, nuclear disarmament, a conference on peace in the Middle East.  What I am going to talk about this morning may seem to be less breath-taking stuff Ä the environment, energy and economics Ä but these items are of decisive importance for the climate in which our grandchildren will live, the standard they will enjoy and the security they will feel.  Governments and the public have therefore reason to pay serious attention to them.
<P>	Energy is a vital condition for development.  Our standard of living depends on it.  It is no wonder that the world is greedy for it.  There is a clear relationship between the level of economic development and energy consumption.  The average North American uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent per year and the average Chinese uses 590 kg, the average Indian makes do with 280 kg of oil equivalent and here in Egypt, the average per capita consumption is 550 kg oil equivalent per year.
<P>The OECD countries with one sixth of the world's population now use almost one half of the world's primary energy, while the developing countries with three quarters of the world population use less than one third of its primary energy.  The appetite for electricity, in particular, is growing.  Increase in world population, urbanization and the demand for a higher standard of living all drive this greater demand for electricity.  Over the past 15 years, total energy use increased by more than 100% in developing countries, but electricity demand went up by almost 200%.  This demand for electricity by developing countries is projected to grow at an annual rate of nearly 6% into the next century, while the world's total consumption of electricity is expected to grow at a rate of about 3%.
<P>It is hard to overstate the importance of electricity to the standard of living and the quality of life in a country.  A friend of mine told me that his 105 year old father thought the most important change he had experienced in the world during his long life was the introduction of electricity.  We sometimes hear voices urging a return to lifestyles of minimal reliance on energy, including electricity.  The reality is that electricity transports energy to our doorsteps and houses, that ample lighting prolongs our days and makes our streets light at night, that electric pumps bring water to fields and houses, that refrigerators and deep freezers keep our food fresh and reduces spoilage, television allows us to meet the whole world at home.
<P>The services which electricity provide may be taken for granted in industrialized countries but they are anxiously sought by the developing nations of the world.  In these countries the words of the famous Indian nuclear physicist, Homi Bhabha "No energy is more expensive than no energy" are well understood.
<P>An example:  China has the ambition to ensure that each household has a refrigerator.  But to fulfil this desire for a basic improvement in the quality of life, China will have to expend enormous amounts of energy.  Even with refrigerators of modest size and of the most current and efficient model available, they will need a base load capacity of some 20 000 MWe or 20 large nuclear power reactors.
<P>A major driving force behind the appetite for energy, apart from development, is the explosive growth in the world's population.  At the birth of Christ there were some 350 million people on the Earth.  In 1900 there were 1 billion; in 1990 there were more than 5 billion and in the year 2000 there will be well over 6 billion.  Thus, in the last ten years of this century we expect to increase about as much as we did in the one thousand nine hundred years following the birth of Christ! (or from the birth of humanity to the year 1900).
<P>Is it not possible to stop the world's appetite for energy by conservation?  Energy saving is, indeed, of the greatest importance, but even with vigorous efforts for more efficient use of energy, world-wide consumption of energy can be expected to increase by 50 to 75 percent by the year 2020 according to the World Energy Council.
<P>We must ask ourselves:  "Where will this energy come from?"  And, confronted with evidence that already the present level of consumption of energy has brought severe environmental damage world wide, we must understand that there is tremendous tension locally, regionally and globally between the demands for more energy, notably electricity, and the demands for the protection of life, health and the environment.  We face a dilemma.
<P>We must also realize that one cannot change energy systems overnight.  In the foreseeable future there will be an energy mix, as there is today.  Fossil fuels Ä coal, oil gas Ä that now cover a little under 90% of the world's total energy use Ä are certainly not going to be phased out.  Nor is hydro nor nuclear power.
<P>All of these sources will continue to be used, but the proportions in which they come into play have relevance from an economic as well as from an environmental point of view.  The practical questions will rather be whether old coal fired electricity plants are to be replaced by new fossil-fuelled plants or by nuclear?  Or conversely, will old nuclear power plants be replaced by fossil fuelled plants?  In industrialized countries little hydro potential remains to be exploited.  Commercial, new and renewable sources of energy, e.g. biomass, solar and wind power now give less than 0.5% of the world's energy and experts believe they may provide some 3 5% by the year 2010.  This leaves us in reality, for the foreseeable future, with the choice between coal, oil and gas on the one hand and nuclear power on the other.
<P>Looked at from a global standpoint it is reasonable to suggest that the least developed countries should be enabled to use the least demanding technologies, which are the fossil based ones and that the advanced countries should make greater use of the more demanding nuclear technology.  In reality both industrially advanced States and some of the more technologically advanced developing countries are at present planning to use both more gas, coal and nuclear.  Mexico, that is now operating one nuclear power reactor and is scheduled to take another into operation in two years, is also building six coal fired plants to cover its growing needs for electricity.  China Ä while it is at present building a few nuclear plants Ä is also planning to double its coal use by the year 2000.  And India, which has a number of nuclear plants, is planning to treble its use of coal by the same year.  The coal consumption of China and India together would then be greater than the coal consumption of all the advanced industrialized States lumped together.
<P>These are the realities.  The global demand for energy will increase significantly in the future.  However, this demand is now standing face to face with fear about the environmental consequences of even present levels and patterns of energy use.
<P><B>Environmental Concerns</B><P>Twenty years after the first UN Conference on the Environment in Stockholm, we are now becoming painfully aware that environmental problems have not diminished.  On the contrary, they have escalated from the local to the regional level and now pose some threats to the entire planet.  Here in Cairo you are well acquainted with air pollution but it is only part of a much greater problem.  The emissions of SO2 and NOx caused by the burning of coal and oil have led in Europe and North America to the problems of acid rain, dying forests and decaying cities.  To these problems we must now add the global threat of the greenhouse effect which is linked to a great extent to the world's use of fossil fuels.  As you know, the "greenhouse effect" Ä or global warming Ä is the increase in the temperature of the world's atmosphere which is expected to follow from the current level of emissions of some gases of which carbon dioxide is the most important.
<P>Certain gases released into the world's atmosphere Ä primarily chlorofluoro-carbons (CFCs), methane and carbon dioxide (CO2) Ä trap the heat in the atmosphere.  It is calculated that the increases in these gases are gradually leading to a higher temperature in the world's atmosphere Ä with consequent climate changes.  More research can be expected to give us greater certainty about the threat, but many scientists are convinced that we have already experienced a minor warming and that further warming is inevitable.  The question seems only to be whether, through determined action, we are able to slow this development and stabilize it.  The governments of the world are at present jointly focussing upon this issue but so far no world-wide agreement has been reached on world-wide CO2 reductions.
<P>On the other hand the chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) which are used in modern refrigerators and in foam plastic production are to be phased out because, apart from being a source of greenhouse gases, they also are destructive to the world's ozone layer and it is this characteristic which has led to an early agreement.  Methane gas gets into the atmosphere from animals, rice paddies and leaks during the production of natural gas.  It is not easy to reduce these emissions.  Then there remains carbon dioxide (CO2), which results from the burning of all fossil fuels and all organic material, including wood.  There is no economically viable way in which CO2 emissions can be avoided in such combustion.  All fossil fuel burning Ä in cars and other machines, in heating and in electricity generation Ä is thought to contribute about 50% of the greenhouse effect.  The current burning of rain forests is deemed to add some further 10 20%.  The different fossil fuels do not, however, contribute CO2 in equal measure.  Counted per unit of energy generated, the burning of gas yields about half as much CO2 as does coal.  The amount of CO2 produced by burning oil lies between those of coal and gas.
<P>If the current global levels of burning of fossil fuels are too high for the health of our planet, it is easy to see that increased levels are even more dangerous.<P><B>Energy Planning</B><P>We must accept the fact that all energy sources have some impact upon life, health and the environment.  We must also face the reality that all sources will be needed and that the real question before us will not be the inclusion or exclusion of some energy options but rather their optimal mix, national and internationally.
<P>Traditionally, energy planning took only the economic aspect into consideration.  The cheapest energy was the best energy.  After the oil embargo a number of countries began to consider energy independence as a significant factor.  And today it is evident that we must take into account, not only the costs of generating and distributing energy, but also the costs in terms of life, health and environmental damage.   A gradual warming of the earth's atmosphere through a continuous increase in the carbon dioxide level caused by an accelerated use of fossil fuels may be a price we don't want our grandchildren to pay.
<P>It is important to recognize that the discussion of the merits and demerits of an energy option become meaningful only when this option is compared with its alternatives.
<P>Currently, about 63% of the world's electricity is generated by the burning of coal, oil and gas.  The technology is not very complicated.  From the point of view of economic cost, generation by coal is about equal with nuclear in many places.  From the viewpoint of safety, all three fossil fuels are accepted by the public, although the number of casualties is high in accidents related to coal mining, offshore drilling and gas transportation.  Oil is a much more expensive fuel for electricity production than coal.  The price of gas used to be linked to that of oil, but we have seen recently how it has instead been linked to the price of coal, at least for electricity generation.  This makes gas attractive.                         
<P>There has been a decided trend in the past few years to make greater use of natural gas in producing electricity.  This has less consequences in the form of acid rain and dying forests.  As the burning of gas results in half as much CO2 as does coal per energy unit, there is a net advantage in replacing coal by gas in terms of the greenhouse effect.  Where gas is burned for additional energy generation, there will, of course, be additional CO2 Ä though less than if coal had been used to generate that additional electricity.
<P>Looked at from the viewpoint of the world's resources, one might regret the burning of finite oil and gas resources, which could have more valuable uses.  Coal is more plentiful Ä but also more problematic from the viewpoint of CO2 emissions.  Other pollutants from coal Ä SO2 and NOx Ä can be removed Ä at a cost.  In the IAEA we are even promoting a method of using electron beams on the flue gases of coal plants to transform the gases into fertilizer!<P><B>Conservation</B><P>If you ask green movements about the energy-environment dilemma you are likely to get the answer that it can be solved by conservation and a greater use of renewable energy sources.  The concept of conservation covers both a more discriminating and more efficient use of energy.  The difference between the two ways of saving energy is easily seen when we consider that we can save petrol by driving less or by using a more fuel efficient engine.  The latter form of saving is easily accepted Ä though it may be expensive if it requires a new car ...  To limit reliance on energy Ä to drive less Ä is more difficult.  It is very difficult to calculate how much energy we can save.  The quantities are significant, but no serious energy experts believe that one can achieve more than a partial off setting of the increasing demand for energy.  Certainly current energy plans in the world do not point to a reduced use of fossil fuels.
<P><B>Renewable Sources of Energy</B><P>	The most important renewable and non CO2 producing source of electricity is hydro power.  At present, it generates some 20% of the world's electricity.  In the industrialized world, most hydro potential has already been exploited, but in some developing countries, notably Africa, significant resources remain and will undoubtedly be used, where it is economic and where the environmental consequences are not too severe.  The Assuan dam is an example of a huge electricity producing hydro power installation which has also had very severe environmental consequences.  In China, a giant hydro-electric project on the Yangtse river will now be launched.  It is to yield enormous quantities of electricity, but will also, apparently, require the resettlement of large numbers of people.
<P>There is much talk about the use of biomass in the industrialized countries.  Rapidly growing trees, harvesting, burning and the planting of new
trees would be a fuel cycle without any net contribution of CO2.  However, the economics of this source have not yet been established and so far it
has not really been relied upon on a large scale anywhere.  In many developing countries, biomass in the form of non commercial fuel wood and
animal dung is a dominant fuel.  With growing population, the reliance on this source has become much too heavy in many places, with deforestation
and desertification as a result.  In such areas, a more efficient use of fire wood, replantation and greater use of other fuels is desirable.  As far as we
can see today, a greater global reliance on biomass is not likely to become a very significant method of substituting for fossil fuels.
<P>Solar power is making a substantial contribution in isolated locations and on a small scale and heating of water by solar energy is practical
and economic in many places Ä not least in this part of the world.  However, solar cells for large scale economic electricity production are still deemed
to be far away.
<P>Windmills have a long tradition, but despite considerable experimentation and promotion, wind power has not become economic, nor does it
yield the large quantities of energy we need.  More about that in a moment.
<P>Taken together solar power, wind power, biomass and other commercial, new and  renewable sources yield today less than 0.5% of the
world's energy.  Most of it is actually geothermal Ä e.g. in the United States, Iceland, Italy and New Zealand.
<P>What I said a moment ago, that the realistic energy choice boils down to one between fossil fuels and nuclear power, is clearly demonstrated
by experience in Europe.  Let me give you some examples.  Denmark, that rejects nuclear power, is often cited as a country with an ambitious wind
power programme, but not more than 2% of Danish electricity originates in wind power, while the capacity of coal generated power stations has been
allowed to expand fast and covers some 95% of the Danish electricity generation.  In Belgium, industry's request to build another nuclear plant a few
years ago was rejected by the government.  The alternative proved to be gas.  And gas on a large scale would also have been the replacement for
nuclear in my own country, Sweden, if a phasing out had started in the middle of the nineties as originally intended.  For Finland the choice at the
present moment seems to be nuclear or coal.
<P>How does nuclear power compare with other sources of electricity from the four key standpoints of environment, economy, security and
safety?<BR>
<B>Environment and Nuclear Power</B>
<P>Nuclear power - which provides about 17% of the world's electricity - has the great advantage of giving rise to no harmful emissions in normal
operation.  This means that the use of nuclear power helps us to avoid CO2 and NOx and SO2 emissions.  According to our calculation, if the
electricity currently generated by nuclear power plants worldwide were produced instead by burning coal, a further 8 percent or 1.6 billion tonnes of
carbon dioxide would be added to the world's atmosphere.
<P>The Japanese Government has announced two new programmes on energy policy Ä one is "Targets for Supply of Alternative Energy Sources
to Oil" and the other is an "Action Programme to Arrest Global Warming."  The Japanese plans include targets for use of alternative energy sources
for oil, including nuclear power.  According to those targets, the supply of nuclear power is to increase 2.5 times between 1989 and 2010 with a target
of 30.8% of electricity coming from nuclear power in 2010.  The Action Programme to reduce gases which cause the greenhouse effect aims at
stabilizing Japan's carbon dioxide emissions per capita after 2000 at the levels which prevailed in 1990 Ä on condition that the industrialized countries
of the world make joint efforts to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.  It is difficult to see how such aims can be achieved without increasing reliance on
nuclear power.
<P>I am not suggesting that increased use of nuclear power alone can stabilize CO2 emissions in Japan as in other industrial countries, but I do
maintain that it must be part of the solution.
<P>In terms of economics, as I said a moment ago, there is today not much difference between nuclear power and coal generated electricity.
Assumptions regarding discount rates, the number of years of use and the upfront investment for construction have a heavy influence on cost
calculations.  In the United States and the United Kingdom the high costs calculated for nuclear power is one main reason for the absence of new
nuclear power projects.  However, in other countries privately owned utilities wish to build more nuclear power plants and it may be assumed that they
expect to make a profit.  In Asia, countries pushing ahead with nuclear include Japan, the Republic of Korea, China and Taiwan (China).  A special
economic problem with nuclear power is that the upfront investment costs are very heavy.  This is undoubtedly a drawback for developing countries.
The lower fuel costs, which make for economy, are only enjoyed later.
<P>In the long term, I think nuclear power will present significant economic advantages.  The potential for reducing the production costs of nuclear
power is still large, for instance through standardization of construction and serial fabrication of main components.  On the other hand, the coal burning
techniques are probably reaching the limit of industrial improvements, and modifications imposed for environmental reasons may add to the production
costs.  To take an example, clean air legislation in the United States imposed such stringent filtering conditions on old high sulphur coal plants, that a
number of them will be forced to close.<P>
<B>Security</B>
<P>There are several kinds of security to discuss in relation to energy.  One is security of supply.  Perhaps coal offers the greatest security of
supply, there being many different suppliers and an ample supply available.  To be at the end of a gas pipeline offers much greater supply risks.  As to
oil, a nervous world was reminded during the Gulf crisis that both price and availability depend much on the political conditions in a rather small
number of supplier countries.
<P>The risk of supply that exists for nuclear power hardly relates to uranium which is in ample supply for many different regions and countries,
like Australia, Canada, Namibia, Niger, China, CIS.  The number of States able to supply enrichment services was for a long time very limited.  This is
less true today.  The energy density of uranium is also such that a utility can store fuel for several years' use and, thereby, acquire very substantial
energy independence   even without an indigenous supply of uranium and enrichment services.  A 1000 MW(e) nuclear plant consumes about 80Kg of
uranium per day.  A coal fired plant of the same capacity uses about 7000 tons of coal per day   i.e. about five train loads.  Thus where the electricity
generating plants cannot be located at the coal fields, the use of coal for electricity generation requires a well functioning and vast transport network.
To take an example, the rail-roads of China are burdened by coal transports.
<P>We can also speak of security of operation, in the sense of reliability.  Available statistics do not point to more frequent or longer stoppages in
nuclear plants than in fossil fuelled plants, though one might get such an impression from news reports that are inclined to report all nuclear stoppages
and ignore those in coal  or oil fired plants.
<P>Another security aspect relates to physical protection of plants.  One cannot completely rule out the risk that terrorists could try to occupy a
nuclear plant, although fortunately it has not happened so far.  If they were not experts the chances are that their actions would only achieve automatic
shut downs.  It must be recognized, however, that modern society is vulnerable to many other risks from terrorists.  None can be ignored.
<P>Reference is sometimes made to the risk that nuclear power plants present in time of war.  It cannot be ignored or denied, but if we think of
war, it seems more justified to look first at the risk of tens of thousands of nuclear warheads that still remain in the world.  In the region of the Persian
Gulf nuclear reactors have been bombed three times.  Twice there was no nuclear fuel present:  when Israel bombed a big research reactor in Iraq in
1981 and when Iraq fired rockets at Iranian power reactors under construction during the Iraq Iran war.  Only the American action during the recent
UN authorized operation against Iraq involved the bombing of two small research reactors containing nuclear fuel.  Fortunately, as IAEA inspection
has found, the fuel was not damaged and no radiation hazard arose.
<P>The bombing of coal mines is not likely to pose a great war hazard, but as we all know the burning of oil wells can cause grave damage, and
attacks on gas cisterns or big hydro dams may have devastating consequences.
<P>It is often alleged that nuclear power increases the risk of a spread of nuclear weapons to other countries.  As is well known, President
Kennedy surmised in the 1960s about a world with over twenty nuclear weapon States.  This fear has simply not materialized.  However, the risk of
proliferation cannot be ignored   least of all these days.
<P>It cannot be excluded that a State could try to make use of a nuclear power programme to hide a weapons programme.  However, not even
the dismantling of all peaceful nuclear power in the world would be a guarantee against development of a nuclear weapon by a State which was
determined to have one.  The nuclear genie has been out of the bottle for a long while.  The risk that some country develops a nuclear weapon
capacity exists regardless of whether it has civilian nuclear power.  All the five recognized nuclear weapon States developed weapons first   nuclear
power second.  And Israel, which many believe to have developed nuclear weapons, does not have any nuclear power.  Nor was Iraq building any
nuclear power plants.
<P>The non proliferation regime, verified by IAEA safeguards, is not a police power that can stop nuclear activities in a State.  But States which
pledge themselves not to acquire nuclear weapons and promise to hold all their nuclear material, present or future, available for inspection, open
themselves for considerable control.  A misuse of the verified programmes could not be physically stopped by inspectors but it would be reported.  It is
not only the verification of nuclear non proliferation but the verification of all arms control that will be limited to observation and reporting.
<P>States allow themselves to be inspected by international inspectors, because they want to demonstrate to neighbours and to the world at large
that they are using nuclear energy only for peaceful purposes.  Inspection is not an encroachment on sovereignty.  It is rather a service requested by
and rendered to the inspected State.  To be credible and have the confidence-building effect that is desired by the inspected State, the inspection
must be sufficiently thorough and frequent.
<P>What is the risk that international inspectors will not discover violations of nuclear non proliferation pledges?  It is simply not feasible to
organize a control system under which inspectors systematically comb through every nook and corner, every cave and cellar of whole countries.  The
present system is based upon States declaring nuclear material that they import, produce and possess and it is supplemented by declarations of other
States exporting nuclear material.  This system does not create a guarantee against a State secretly mining its own uranium and itself secretly
enriching it.  In today's world with many satellites and much intelligence around, evidence is likely to become available of such clandestine
programmes.  Uranium mining is mostly visible and enrichment and reprocessing plants are also likely to be seen from above.  Such observations, if
made known to the IAEA, may trigger proposals for special inspections of possibly non declared nuclear material.  The risk of non-detection is not
great but the case of Iraq shows that it is not zero.  With greater alertness and more effective export controls it should be possible to make it minimal.
Let us also note that a universal commitment to non-proliferation and nuclear disarmament coupled with effective verification will reduce the security
interest that any State may feel for acquiring a nuclear weapons capacity.  A well verified nuclear-weapon-free zone for the Middle East as a part of a
peace settlement is thus an important aim to pursue.
<P>Let me sum up:  the risk of proliferation would not go away even by a total elimination of all civilian nuclear power in the world.  It has to be
tackled by a combination of political means, export controls and inspection.<P>
<B>Safety</B>
<P>My last points relate to the safe operation of nuclear power plants and the safe disposal of nuclear wastes.
<P>A Symposium in Finland last May on Electricity and Environment which compared risks of different energy sources through the whole cycle,
from mining to waste disposal, found that virtually all sources have some degree of risk.  Nuclear and renewables were found to be in the low end of
the risk spectrum, whilst coal and oil were found on the high.  This conclusion is certainly encouraging for nuclear power and squares with our
experience that Chernobyl is the only large radiation releasing accident in a civilian nuclear power plant despite the experience of some 6000
operation years of civilian reactors.  However, we face a special problem in that the public, which seems to tolerate the risk that people may drown in
hydro dam catastrophes, die in explosions in coal mines, on oil platforms or at gas cisterns and pipes, may be less tolerant about the risk that
anyone's health is affected by the exposure to radiation   whether in the short term or the long term.
<P>We can only respond to this public attitude in two ways.  First, by factual information about the risks of nuclear power use and waste disposal
and by comparing these risks with those that will be taken if fossil fuels are the alternative.  Second, by strengthening the safety of nuclear power so
that no accidents occur in which significant radiation is released.  This, of course, is what is being done   even without any public concern.  Safety is
never static   whether in automobiles, aeroplanes or nuclear power plants.  Nuclear power is safer today in most countries than it was before the
Chernobyl accident and it will be safer tomorrow.  Some technical modifications have been made on many existing plants and the next generation of
plants which will be ready for ordering within a few years will be improved compared to the present generation.
<P>Responsibility for nuclear power safety rests with national authorities.  The IAEA is no supranational regulatory body with powers to order a
State to modify plants or to close them.  Yet, we know that an accident anywhere has a heavy psychological fall out everywhere.  It is against this
background that much interest is now focussed on how the international community can better influence nuclear power safety in individual countries.
<P>The IAEA does not have a right to inspect the safety of any nuclear power reactor as it has a right, in most non nuclear weapon States, to
inspect and verify that the reactors are not used for weapons production.  The Agency does, however, offer Member States safety reviews of various
kinds through international expertise.  These services are increasingly used and the expert advice offered is normally accepted and acted upon.  But
we  cannot order action.  If serious deficiencies are found, we must tell the responsible government about it and, if need be, seek to organize
assistance.<P>
<B>Nuclear Waste</B>
<P>Let me conclude by some comments on nuclear waste.  It is a fact that the public is concerned about this issue in many countries.  It is also a
fact that nuclear experts are convinced that there are no scientific or technological breakthroughs needed for a waste disposal that is safe even for
very, very long time periods.  The technological solutions favoured all around the world are the same, namely to leave spent nuclear fuel at surface
level to cool and lose in radioactivity for some 30 60 years and thereafter to isolate it from the biosphere by several barriers and place it in deep stable
geological formations.
<P>It is puzzling that the confidence of the experts is not conveyed to the general public.  Much more information is evidently needed.  My own
country, Sweden, may be an exception.  A Gallup poll not long ago indicated that a majority of people in Sweden would accept a high level nuclear
waste disposal site in their own community, if that community were judged to be the most suitable location.
<P>The point is often made that we are dealing with waste that remains hazardous for many thousands of years.  This is true, but the quantities
are so limited that they can be isolated.  This is not the case with the larger quantities of toxic waste that result from the burning of coal.  By 1987 the
high level nuclear waste arising annually from all the world's nuclear power stations amounted to about 6000 tons in the form of spent fuel.  If the
amount of electricity that these nuclear plants generated had instead come from electricity generating coal plants, alone the toxic heavy metals
released    mercury, arsenic, vanadium, etc.   would have amounted to some 100 000 tonnes.  These toxic wastes do not have a half life like
radioactive wastes.  They remain toxic forever and they remain at the surface of the earth.
<P>I submit to you that the world would look very different if other industries adopted concepts for their waste disposal that are as safe as the
civilian nuclear industries have   rightly   been obliged to work out.  It is not the nuclear waste of the civilian nuclear industry that causes acid rains,
dead forests and lakes, smog and corrosion in our cities and a possible greenhouse effect.  The wastes of uranium are put back in the crust of the
earth from where the uranium came.  The coal, oil and gas is also fetched from the crust of the earth, but as the final disposal site for their wastes we
historically have choosen the atmosphere and the surface of the earth.  The quantities are so great that we can hardly do otherwise.  But it is puzzling
that this overwhelming problem is tolerated, while the limited problem of civilian nuclear power waste disposal appears unbearable to many.
<P>Perhaps the increasing awareness of the greenhouse effect will convince the public that the risks connected with an expanding use of nuclear
power, although not zero, are more tolerable than the risks of an excessive use of fossil fuels.
<HR>
</DOC>
