<TITLE>Nuclear Power in Perspective Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Nuclear Power in Perspective Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Nuclear Power in Perspective </H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Elsinore, Denmark</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>31 August 1992</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
In a speech to the Rio Conference on "Environment and Development" a few months ago, I observed that nuclear power, which gives rise to practically no emissions, could be of significant help in providing electricity economically without releasing CO2 to the atmosphere and thereby adding to the risk of global warming.  Only one other speaker appears to have mentioned nuclear power in this context, and he warned against any reliance on this "discredited technology".  Some will probably see this paucity of pronouncements as evidence that nuclear power is becoming obsolescent.  They may see confirmation of their view in the fact that there is relatively little nuclear power plant construction practically everywhere except in the Far East and India.
<P>I submit, however, that conclusions about the demise of nuclear power are premature.  The vast majority of today's governments either favour the use of nuclear power or insist on keeping the option open.  A very small number Ä less than half a dozen Ä are declared opponents of nuclear power.  Further, there is an increasing awareness among governments that nuclear power can help resolve the dilemma of the need for more energy, notably electricity, and the need to restrain carbon dioxide emissions.  Both the Paris and the Houston summit meetings of seven industrialized States expressly pointed to nuclear power as a means of restraining greenhouse gas emissions.  Indeed, calculations show that if today's 415 or so nuclear power plants were closed and that if the electricity generated by them were instead generated by coal-fired plants, global carbon dioxide emissions would increase by some 7%.  A drastic expansion of nuclear power in the world would be a very significant factor, even though it alone would not eliminate the risk of global warming.  Indeed, apart from vigorous efforts to conserve energy, increased reliance on nuclear power is one of the few significant measures we can take that could restrain CO2 emissions in the next few decades.
<P>	Why then did the Rio Conference not talk about nuclear power?  The answers are simple.  The Conference adopted its conclusions by consensus and there is no consensus among governments about the use of nuclear power.  Oil-producing States Ä although not opposed to nuclear power Ä are averse to stressing the CO2 problems of fossil fuels and explicitly endorsing the merits of nuclear power.
<P>To assess the future role of nuclear power, it is not sufficient only to examine the declared current positions of governments.  It is necessary to look at nuclear power from a number of perspectives.
<P>The cost of energy Ä which alone used to be the decisive factor Ä certainly still remains very important, but the environmental perspective, the safety perspective, the military/security perspective and, related to that, the energy independence perspective are also of great importance today.
<P>I shall discuss the nuclear option from these various perspectives, but I shall begin with the premise for all these questions:  the need for more energy.
<P>No one denies that life styles could be developed in many industrialized States which used less neon light, fewer television sets and electric tooth brushes, or whatever consumes energy.  While such things may be obvious, the fact remains that large groups of people even in highly developed States are looking, not unreasonably, for a less burdensome existence through laundry machines, dish washers, vacuum cleaners and refrigerators Ä all demanding more electricity.  Especially the lives of women and their emancipation into the labour market are facilitated by all these electricity-consuming conveniences.  Moreover, energy and electricity consumption varies a great deal between different industrialized countries.  There is every reason to expect that those with a relatively low level will seek to raise it.
<P>Even more obvious is that developing countries will seek to use more energy.  The average North American uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent per year;  the average Chinese uses 590 kg, and the average Indian makes do with 280 kg of oil equivalent per year.  Developing countries, with three fourths of the world's population, use less than one third of the primary energy.  If these countries are to develop, they will certainly need more energy.  Population growth will only increase this demand.  The World Energy Council has estimated that global energy consumption can be expected to increase by 50-75% by the year 2020.  These figures assume vigorous efforts to conserve energy.
<P>There can be little doubt that the long-term trend is for greater use of energy, in particular electricity, which is a convenient, flexible form Ä as useful to large industries as to small households, as important in driving pumps for irrigation in developing countries as in driving public transport.  If we were to reduce oil-based transport by cars, trucks, buses and airplanes this would, of course require a switch to electric trains, tubes, trolley-buses and Ä eventually Ä electric cars.
<P>The prospect of greater future need for energy, especially electricity, is not inconsistent with the experience of many industrialized countries, which overestimated growth in their energy demand and invested accordingly, and which still have a relatively comfortable energy and electricity balance.  As this comfortable situation gradually disappears, governments and industry will be obliged to plan for additional energy/electricity supply and decide whether to maintain or modify their current energy mix.  Is the number of coal-fuelled plants to stagnate or fall, and the number of gas-fuelled plants and nuclear plants to grow?  Or are decommissioned nuclear plants to be replaced by coal- or gas-fuelled ones?  It is understandable at a time when the public is averse to any new power scheme Ä be it fossil- or uranium-fuelled, or hydropowered Ä that there may be an inclination to postpone the choice as long as possible.  Although more can be squeezed out of existing investments through better planning of demand, connection of grids and prolongation of the life of existing plants, the days when decisions have to be made will come.
<P>Power-starved developing countries, a few industrialized Western States Ä like Finland Ä and the economically booming Far East can no longer put off these decisions.
<P>The question of cost remains crucial, but is not the only factor.  Oil is not expected to be economically attractive as a fuel for electricity generation.  In contrast, gas is now being used increasingly, and its attraction seems to lie in its current cost advantage over oil and its environmental advantage over coal.  However, a question mark hangs over its future costs.  Where gas has to be imported, dependence on one supplier may also appear undesirable.  Coal remains a competitive fuel for electricity generation and supplies are ample.  For countries like China and Australia, with abundant coal supplies of their own, this option has evident economic attractions.  As concern grows about damaging emissions from the combustion of coal, there are increasing calls for technical systems to prevent pollution.  This will raise the cost of the coal option Ä as the Danish experience shows.  Even so, concern will remain about the environmental impact of CO2 emissions, for which no economically viable prevention system is likely to emerge.
<P>Nuclear power will remain costly in the construction phase and this characteristic and the fact that it is technologically very demanding will make it less attractive to capital-weak developing countries.  The world's ample uranium resources and their geographical spread are likely to make this fuel attractively priced and easily available, even with a much larger number of nuclear power plants around.  As nuclear power is a relatively young technology, moreover, it may be expected that many cost-saving devices and designs are yet to come which will reduce the cost of construction and more than offset the costs incurred for additional safety devices.  It can also be assumed that the regulatory process Ä which in some cases has led to prolonged and costly construction times Ä will be streamlined.  In the calculation of the cost of nuclear-generated electricity, it is already normal practice to include the costs of responsible waste disposal and decommissioning.  This is not Ä as is the case with coal Ä a sum to be added.
<P>In conclusion, therefore, it can be said that some important question marks hang over the future costs of gas- and coal-fuelled electricity generation, while the outlook for the cost of nuclear-generated electricity may well be positive.  In hydropower, the costs clearly depend on the location.  Hydro will remain an attractive source wherever its costs or environmental consequences are not exorbitant.  As for renewable sources of energy, considerable and interesting efforts are being made, not least regarding wind power here in Denmark.  These efforts, too, need to be viewed in perspective.  About 2% of Denmark's electricity is wind-generated.  Practically all the rest is coal-generated.  In the whole world, less than 0.5% of electricity is generated by renewable sources Ä other than hydropower.  Most of it, in fact, is geothermal.  Although these renewable sources may well become more important than they are today, they have a variety of limitations and are not expected to become competitive in the next few decades, except in particular locations and situations.  Even in a longer perspective, they are not expected to provide more than 3 to 5% of the world's energy (International Energy Agency, World Energy Council).
<P>I have already referred to the increasingly important environmental perspective.  Fortunately, techniques are available Ä at a cost Ä to avoid SO2 and NOx pollution from coal-fuelled power plants, and I understand that these techniques are increasingly being used in Denmark.  Great concern nevertheless remains as regards all fossil and other organic fuels because of the carbon dioxide they release during combustion.  Per energy unit, coal releases twice as much as gas, and oil lies somewhere between these values.  Although questions remain in the calculation of the greenhouse effect, the great majority of scientists dealing with this topic believe that a reduction of emissions of greenhouse gases is needed.
<P>To work out an acceptable international response to this need is a formidable political task.  Indeed, the matter is already controversial.  It did not prove possible to attain agreement at the Rio Conference on the proposed target of a return to the 1990 CO2 emission levels by 2005, as was proposed by many governments, including the European Community.  Even such a target, however, is regarded as wholly insufficient by experts.  This subject may become a major international problem already during the present decade.  Developing countries may quite reasonably say that the excessive emissions of greenhouse gases, including CO2, are mainly the doings of the industrialized countries and that it is the responsibility of those countries to use their resources to pull the world out of the mess into which they have dragged it.  Developing countries might suggest an international allocation of licenses for greenhouse gas emissions on the basis of population figures, and offer protection of forests provided resources and assistance are given.  Agreement may be elusive.
<P>What we can see already today is that pressure will build up in the industrialized countries for the restraint and reduction of emissions, particularly of CO2.  Although power plants are only a part of this problem and a part that does not change overnight, it is hard to avoid the conclusion that concern over global warming Ä apart from stimulating energy efficiency and renewable energy development Ä will favour greater reliance on CO2-free nuclear power and hydropower.  And it will work against fossil fuels.
<P>Of course, the public's major concerns about nuclear power also relate to the environment:  the concern that waste disposal and power plant accidents will lead to radioactive contamination.  
<P>Before I address these two important issues, let me make a comment on contamination due to the military use of nuclear power.  To the public, it evidently makes no difference if the sea or the land is contaminated through military or civilian activities.  However, practically everywhere the standards of safety applied in the military sphere are not open to public scrutiny and control.  It is evident that severe radioactive contamination has occurred in several places, especially in the former Soviet Union and in the United States, as a result of military activities.  More and more information is becoming available and it is clear that the clean-up bill will be large.  The problems are not strictly limited to the territories of nuclear-weapon States.  There are several known cases of sunken nuclear submarines, and a Russian-Norwegian investigation of Russian dumping of radioactive equipment in the Kara Sea Ä with participation from the IAEA Ä is now underway.
<P>The handling of waste from civilian nuclear activities is subject to national regulations.  In many developing countries, the regulation and control of radioactive waste from, say, medical activities are unsatisfactory and it is a priority activity for the IAEA technical assistance programme to help remedy these shortcomings.  The handling of high level radioactive waste from nuclear power activities raises a different type of problem.  The responsibility remains a national one but it is understandable that waste which will remain radioactive for many thousands of years will interest people, regardless of frontiers.  It is legitimate for the international community to be concerned about hazardous material that is put back in the crust of the earth.  This concern has not yet found any response through internationally agreed and binding standards for waste disposal or registers of disposal installations or obligatory reporting.  What guidelines are being developed internationally are no more than recommendations.  In addition, there are international reviews on a voluntary basis.  We are familiar with the term "an international nuclear safety regime", relating to the operation of nuclear power plants.  In my view, such a regime should extend to cover waste disposal also.
<P>There are grounds for optimism about our ability to dispose of high level waste in a safe manner.  The nervousness of the public in this regard is not shared by scientists and experts, who are fully confident about the techniques already at our disposal.  It is a bit paradoxical that the public opinion Ä which is so concerned about nuclear waste disposal Ä is often the very factor that prevents such disposal by opposing the use of any site that is found suitable.
<P>To be a bit provocative, one might say that high level waste is the greatest asset of the nuclear power industry Ä because it is so small in volume that it can be isolated and disposed of in its entirety.  There are in principle two methods of handling hazardous waste:  one is to dilute it until it becomes harmless, the other is to concentrate it and isolate it from the biosphere.  The wastes from fossil fuels have become so voluminous that isolation is impossible in practice.  The surface of the earth and the atmosphere are the final disposal sites, and we are now realizing that the volumes we emit are too large for the dilution method.  We must remove SO2 and NOx.  CO2 remains a big problem.  Some comparative data on volumes are illuminating.  By 1991 the spent fuel arising annually from all the world's nuclear power stations amounted to about 10,000 tonnes.  If the electricity that those plants generated had instead come from coal-fired plants, the residual toxic heavy metals alone found in the ashes after the burning of the coal Ä mercury, arsenic, vanadium, etc. Ä would have been in the range of 100,000 tonnes.  They don't have a half-life like radioactive wastes.  They remain toxic forever, and they remain on the surface of the earth.
<P>The timescale of nuclear waste disposal is long, but the technique is manageable.  Although the costs are high, they form a very small part of the cost of nuclear electricity, and in many countries they are included in the price for electricity, and are hardly noticed by the consumer.  The major problem today appears rather to be one of communication with the public and creation of confidence.  As more disposal installations are built and are seen to function well, this confidence should grow.  The Swedish and Finnish pioneering installations are a welcome and important step in this direction.
<P>I would now like to consider nuclear power from the safety perspective.  It is unquestionably here that the major objections exist in public opinion in many countries.  Lethal, invisible radiation is something scary and the explosions in Hiroshima and Nagasaki and the catastrophe at Chernobyl are concrete evidence of the effects of uncontrolled radiation.  Many people are so horrified by any risk of uncontrolled radiation that they wish to stop nuclear power altogether.
<P>It does not seem to help much to compare the risks of operating nuclear power plants with the risks we run in making use of other activities that raise our standard of living.  The World Health Organization has estimated that worldwide the use of pesticides cause the loss of some 15,000 human lives and more than a million cases of poisoning each year!  We must assume that these casualties are tolerated by the public because of the vital importance of pesticides for agriculture today.  The same attitude is not taken towards nuclear power.  A symposium in Helsinki in May 1991 on Electricity and the Environment, which compared the risks of different energy sources through the whole cycle from mining to waste disposal, found nuclear and renewables in normal operation to be at the low end of the risk spectrum, while coal and oil were found to be at the high end.  The risk of large accidents was found to be greatest with hydropower, where many dam failures have taken a heavy toll of lives.  These conclusions square with our daily experience of nuclear power and with the fact that Chernobyl is the only large radiation-releasing accident in a civilian nuclear power plant despite the experience of some 6000 years of civilian reactor operation.
<P>We must be aware, however, that the public, which seems to tolerate the risk that people may drown in hydro dam catastrophes, die in explosions in coal mines, or on oil platforms, or at gas cisterns and pipes, is less tolerant about the risk of anyone's health being affected by exposure to radiation Ä whether in the short or the long term.
<P>We can only respond to public attitudes in two ways.  First, by providing factual information about the risks of nuclear power use and waste disposal, and by comparing these risks with those of fossil fuels if these are the alternative.  Secondly, by strengthening the safety of nuclear power so that no accidents occur in which significant amounts of radiation are released.  This, of course, is what is being done Ä even without any public concern.  Safety is never static Ä whether in automobiles, airplanes or nuclear power plants.  Nuclear power is safer today in most countries than it was before the Chernobyl accident and it will be still safer tomorrow.  During a visit I made to North Korea last May, I was told that after the Chernobyl accident they had made several modifications in the nuclear power plants which they are building Ä although their type of reactor is different from the Chernobyl type.
<P>Let me make some comments on what can be done and what is being done to further reduce the risk of accidents.  There is, of course, the
technical evolution which will result in future reactors which draw on past experience.  There will also be more revolutionary designs available in the
years to come.  There is also backfitting, e.g., with filtered containment venting systems in existing plants.  Especially in several of the Soviet-designed
plants, back-fitting is necessary.  I shall come back to this point in a moment, but I should like to stress first the importance of the emergence of an
international nuclear safety regime.  Responsibility for nuclear power safety Ä as for nuclear waste Ä rests with national authorities.  The IAEA is no
supranational regulatory body that has been given powers to order a State to modify plants or to close them.  Yet, as experience from the Three Mile
Island and Chernobyl accidents shows, any big accident affects the acceptability of nuclear power the world over.  Thus, for example, there is strong
interest in Japan that the rest of the world should operate nuclear power plants safely and there is an interest in the whole world that Japan should
operate its many reactors safely.  Also, countries have a special interest that their neighbours handle their nuclear power plants prudently and safely.
Increasingly, special neighbour agreements are being concluded Ä as in the Nordic countries Ä to respond to the legitimate interests of neighbours.
<P>It seems to me that we are in a stage of transition as regards international nuclear safety norms.  We have a long period behind us during
which national authorities have exchanged their experience and even codified good practices as recommendations.  Little was done, however, to
verify whether the recommendations were actually followed by every State using nuclear power.  While everybody recognizes that such verification
must be achieved chiefly through a joint international instrument, there is reluctance among national authorities even to establish rules about periodic
international visits by safety experts, and there is a valid argument that no action should be taken that might remove responsibility from national
authorities.
<P>A sharp increase in the number of international visits to nuclear installations occurred after the Chernobyl accident, when the phrase "an
accident anywhere is an accident everywhere" was coined.  Within the IAEA, the International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group, a committee of very
prominent nuclear safety experts from the national sphere, was set us to help give guidance on safety standards to the nuclear community and to the
IAEA.  Furthermore, a number of international expert services Ä Operational Safety Review Teams, Radiation Protection Advisory Teams Ä were
made available to Member States, mostly at some cost to them.  In parallel, the World Association of Nuclear Operators began its work with the aim of
ensuring, through direct contacts between nuclear plant operators around the world, that all of them partake of the best experience and Ä if they do not
make the best use of it Ä are at least subject to peer pressure.
<P>All of this Ä and I have only offered a few examples Ä can be seen as measures through which international interest in respect for good
nuclear safety standards is manifested.  The question that is now increasingly being raised is whether international interest requires that some norms
in the form of recommendations be transformed into legally binding rules and that periodic visits by international safety expert teams become a
commitment.  An affirmative answer is given to the first question in the current work on a nuclear safety convention, containing basic rules that are to
be legally binding on the parties.  From what we have seen so far, the rules are of a very basic character.  But they may develop further.  The second
question has not yet been answered in the affirmative.  The present system of services against payment has the merit that visits will not be requested
as a matter of bureaucratic routine, but only if they are really felt to be useful.  A drawback is that there is no guarantee that those installations which
really need an infusion of international advice will receive visits.
<P>What is the status of this advice?  In my view it is enough for the advice to remain "advice" to national regulatory authorities, thus
strengthening their hands, but not replacing them.  Competent and impartial international expert advice is not easily ignored.
<P>How do these considerations square with current activities aimed at strengthening nuclear safety in Soviet-designed nuclear power plants?
Certainly the strong international interest, manifested inter alia at the July summit in Munich and in the establishment among many industrialized
States of mechanisms for providing assistance, shows that the world at large cannot afford for nuclear safety to have severe deficiencies anywhere.
The approach to the East could have been tidier;  more effective use might have been made of the expertise and capacities of Russia;  more use
could have been made of the IAEA Ä as was done in respect of the inquiry into the VVER 440/230 type of reactor, the oldest Soviet-designed nuclear
power plant.  It is easy to be wise after the event.  Right now, the most important thing is to intensify and improve the organization of these efforts, in
which Nordic countries are playing an important and constructive role.  In my view it would be desirable for the diagnosis of deficiencies to be made Ä
systematically Ä by truly international teams of experts in co-operation with designers and other groups in the countries which have the reactors.  It
should thereafter be for the governments and authorities of those countries to decide on the remedies they will undertake and to negotiate with
lenders, donors and suppliers on conditions.  The final phase, the verification of the adequacy of remedies undertaken, should, again, be
internationally and impartially organized.
<P>Partly for reasons of speed, the initial phase of the process of assistance and co-operation has had considerable bilateral components.
<P>It is evident that Russia and other countries in the former East Bloc will continue to rely on nuclear power.  In 1990, the nuclear share of
electricity production was 51% in Hungary, 36% in Bulgaria, 28% in Czechoslovakia, 12% in the Russian Federation, 25% in Ukraine, 45% in
Lithuania, and 10% in Kazakhstan.  Governments may shut down some of the reactors, but many will continue to operate with a gradual
implementation of high-priority safety improvements.  As these countries emerge from their Communist isolation, we should welcome them in joining
other countries to establish the international nuclear safety which both they and the rest of the world need.
<P>I should like to end by looking at another aspect of safety:  prevention of the further spread of nuclear weapons.  An argument sometimes
advanced against the use of nuclear power is that it may contribute to the spread of nuclear weapons.  We have not so far seen any country advance
from a civilian nuclear programme to a military one.  The order has always been the opposite.  Nevertheless, it is true that a capacity to enrich uranium
can be used to make low-enriched nuclear fuel as well as high-enriched uranium for bombs.  And spent fuel from a research or a power reactor may,
after reprocessing, yield weapons-grade plutonium.  For a more peaceful world, we must seek both nuclear disarmament and assurances against the
production of fissionable material for bomb use.  For both we need inspection and verification.  The major instruments for achieving these ends are
agreements on nuclear disarmament Ä of which there are now dramatically important ones Ä and agreements on non-proliferation, of which the most
important are the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) and the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons in Latin America
(Tlatelolco Treaty).  The IAEA is providing verification as regards the treaties against proliferation, and it could provide verification also of the peaceful
uses or storage of fissionable material which is recovered for civilian use after the dismantling of weapons.  There will be considerable quantities of
such materials, and it is important that all of it is continuously accounted for.
<P>There has been much concern in the past year about the risk of the spread of nuclear material and know-how as a result of the break-up of
the Soviet Union.  After IAEA inspections in Iraq under Security Council Resolution 687, there has also been concern about the risk of some
developing countries acquiring nuclear weapons.
<P>One cannot ignore the danger that the disappearance of tight military and police controls in the former Soviet Union increases the risk of
material Ä even weapons Ä and experts "trickling" into the hands of potential proliferators.  Media have been full of reports Ä not least about the mystic
substance "red mercury".  Such inquiries as the IAEA has been able to make through contacts with authorities in the relevant cases so far, however,
have shown no ominous events.  Many crooks from the East and elsewhere are circulating, claiming to be able to sell bomb-grade material.  On
investigation, gram or milligram quantities of plutonium are sometimes found.  Natural, depleted or low-enriched uranium in small quantities has also
been found.  From the viewpoint of radiation protection, this traffic is disquieting.  From the viewpoint of non-proliferation, it is a warning signal Ä so far,
fortunately, not more.
<P>More worrisome is the case of Iraq, a country which had committed itself, by adhering to the NPT, not to make nuclear weapons and which
was found to have built large installations for the enrichment of uranium and to have made preparations for the making of nuclear bombs Ä all secretly
and escaping detection by IAEA safeguards control as well as foreign intelligence.  Are there more such cases, we are bound to ask, and how
effective is IAEA verification?
<P>Verification by the IAEA Ä or anybody else Ä must necessarily be based in the first place upon the declarations of the country accepting
inspection.  It is not unimportant that large known and declared nuclear installations and large quantities of declared nuclear material are checked and
shown not to have been diverted.  The techniques used Ä although there are some difficulties in large bulk handling facilities Ä are well developed.
The major problems are not in this area.
<P>The lesson of Iraq is rather that more must be done to increase the risk of discovery of secret, non-declared activity.  It is not practical or
possible to send in inspectors to roam the whole territory of States, searching in every nook and cranny for secret nuclear installations.  Inspectors
must have information about where they should look.  In the case of Iraq, this information came from defectors and satellites.  In the future, the IAEA
will make use of many sources of information apart from the declarations of inspected States:  from exporters, from the media, and from Member
States.  The risk that a secret programme will go undetected will probably not be reduced to zero, but it can be much lower than it was when the Iraqi
programme successfully escaped discovery.  Should a country deny IAEA inspectors access, the Security Council is also now ready to exercise
pressure.  It may be hoped that the existence of strengthened verification and Security Council determination will deter any State so inclined from
attempting to cheat.
<P>We must not lose sight, however, of the fact that basic assurances against proliferation lie in the political field.  Disarmament among nuclear-
weapon States and détente regionally and globally are disincentives to proliferation.  Universalization of non-proliferation pledges also strengthens
reliability.  It is easier for a State to commit itself if its neighbour does.
<P>I think there are reasons to be optimistic about non-proliferation.  In the past year, South Africa, Argentina and Brazil have committed
themselves to non-proliferation and are opening up for inspection.  So is North Korea.  There remain, essentially, India, Pakistan, Israel and Algeria
which have not made legally binding international non-proliferation commitments.  The solution of these cases requires détente and tailor-made
arrangements.  The outlook is not without hope, and there is certainly the possibility that in 1995 the Non-Proliferation Treaty will be prolonged
indefinitely.
<P>Let me conclude:  Mankind has bitten into the apple of nuclear knowledge, and the experience cannot be undone.  We can only try to tame
our use of this knowledge and exploit it to our advantage.  Enormous efforts have gone into and are going into achieving this Ä not least by the Nordic
States and by the IAEA, in which the Nordic States play such an important and constructive role.  May I end by expressing the appreciation of the
IAEA for the firm support of the Nordic States and the confidence that it will continue and help the world make safe use of the atom.  In particular, I find
it natural and desirable that the Nordic States make efforts and devote economic resources to co-operation with Russia, Ukraine and the Baltic States,
and with the IAEA and the new international project to strengthen nuclear safety in these countries.<HR>
</DOC>
