<TITLE>Energy, Economics, Environment and Nuclear Power</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Energy, Economics, Environment and Nuclear Power</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix Hong Kong Seminar on Nuclear Energy</B>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Hong Kong</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>21 May 1992</H4>
<P><HR>Let me begin by saying that the International Atomic Energy Agency is pleased to organize this seminar with the assistance of the Hong Kong Government and the Hong Kong Nuclear Investment Company.
<P><B>East Asia and nuclear energy</B>
<P>East Asia is an economically booming region of the world.  Industries are sprouting from the ground and the standard of living is rapidly rising.  All this requires energy, not least electricity, and among the sources used to generate electricity is an increasing number of nuclear power plants - in Japan, Korea, China and Taiwan (China).  Interest in nuclear power is also rising in Indonesia and in the Philippines, where a plant has been ready for several years but has not yet been brought into operation.
<P><B>Role of media</B>
<P>It is easy for media to exploit the scare and concern many people feel about nuclear matters, and to make headlines out of small matters.  This happens only too often.  But media also have the ambition of responsibly serving society by straight news and by providing balanced judgements.  For this media people need some knowledge and understanding of the functioning, possibilities and problems of nuclear power.  This seminar is organized as a contribution to this end.
<P><B>What is the IAEA?</B>
<P>In the IAEA we are sometimes asked:  are you in the pockets of the nuclear industry?  The answer is that the IAEA is in the pocket of governments - 115 of them.  It is an intergovernmental organization in the United Nations family, like the World Health Organization or the International Civil Aviation Organization.  We have some 2000 employees.  The budget - of some 200 million dollar/year - is paid by the Member Governments.  Not all these Member Governments favour the use of nuclear power - but the vast majority does.  However, whether they favour or are sceptical about nuclear power, they wish the Agency to provide on-site inspection of nuclear non-proliferation commitments, and to help strengthen safety in nuclear power operations and in the disposal of nuclear waste.  They also want the Agency to contribute factual information for the public debate.  This is what we shall try to do here.  I shall try to give you an overview.  Others will give you more thorough descriptions of various subjects.
<P><B>Burning issue for the IAEA - non-proliferation</B>
<P>The IAEA is active in some of the burning problems of our days:  inspection and neutralization of the nuclear weapons capacity of Iraq, verification of the peaceful nature of the nuclear activities in most non-nuclear-weapon countries in the world.  You may be interested to know that I have just visited the DPRK which has recently ratified an agreement with the IAEA to submit all its nuclear material for Agency inspection.  An Agency inspection team will soon go to the DPRK to inspect the declared nuclear installations and material.  I went to the DPRK to familiarize myself with the nuclear programme of the country and to have discussions at the political level.
<P><B>Let me say one further word about the case of Iraq.</B>
<P>The discovery of the clandestine development of nuclear weapons in Iraq, a party to the Non-Proliferation Treaty, must lead to greater vigilance, but it should not cause us to ignore the fact that the international community has been rather successful in preventing the spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.  Instead of the dozens of nuclear weapons States, which President Kennedy feared would emerge, there are still only five declared ones, plus a few which are thought to be capable of assembling weapons in a short time, if they don't have them now. These have reduced in number, as have the number of nuclear weapons stockpiled in the US and the former USSR.  Over the past year, Argentina and Brazil have bound themselves to non-proliferation and are opening up all their nuclear installations for IAEA inspection.  South Africa, having adhered to the Non-Proliferation Treaty, is doing the same.  The DPRK has now ratified an agreement with the IAEA providing for comprehensive safeguards verification.  With China and France joining the Non-Proliferation Treaty, all declared nuclear-weapon States are now parties to that Treaty.  All this is positive and we hope that the States of the former Soviet Union will, likewise, join the NPT as non-nuclear-weapon States.  Russia, of course, will remain a nuclear-weapon State.
<P>Another burning issue for the IAEA:  CO2 emissions and global warming<BR>
	The Agency is also engaged in examining the relations between energy use and the effect of global warming.  In two weeks' time the World Conference on Environment and Development will open in Rio de Janeiro in Brazil.  The risk of "global warming" - of an increase in the temperature of the world's atmosphere - will be uppermost in the minds of the delegates of this conference.  Although there are many unknowns and uncertainties attached to this problem, it is clear that the increasing volumes of certain gases, notably carbon dioxide, in the atmosphere contribute to the effect.  Attention is therefore focussed on how to restrain the emission of carbon dioxide, the largest part of which comes from the burning of coal, oil and gas.  Energy generation, conservation and substitutes for fossil fuels are at the centre of attention.  One might have thought that there would be much discussion about nuclear power, which gives vast amounts of energy without emitting any carbon dioxide or, for that matter, any sulphur dioxide (SO2) or nitrogen oxides (NOx) which are linked to acid rains.  However, I predict nuclear power will not be mentioned by many in Rio.  Why?  Because the conference acts by consensus and recommending an expanded use of nuclear power to avoid an alternative burning of fossil fuels would not have a consensus.  Nor would any recommendation opposing nuclear power have a consensus - or even a broad support.  The conference may advocate conservation and the use of environmentally "benign" energy sources - which each country can interpret as it likes.  Perhaps it will succeed in setting a target for the restraints in CO2 emissions.  Ambitious targets will hardly be attainable only through conservation and the use of renewable sources of energy.  A greater use of nuclear energy would be of significance.  A figure will illustrate.  If today's some 430 nuclear power plants were closed and the electricity which they generate were instead to be generated in coal-fired plants, the carbon dioxide emissions into the atmosphere would increase by 7 percent.  It shows that already at present nuclear power is relevant in the discussion of global warming.
<P><B>Expanded use of energy and electricity</B>
<P>Now let me turn to our need for energy and electricity.  There is a clear relationship between the level of economic development and energy consumption.  The average North American uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent per year, the average Chinese uses 590 kg and the average Indian makes do with 280 kg of oil equivalent.  Almost one half of the world's primary energy is used by one sixth of the world's population in the OECD countries.  The developing countries with three fourths of the world's population use less than one third of its primary energy.
<P>The increase in the demand for electricity is conspicuous.  Over the past 15 years, total energy use increased by more than 100% in developing countries, but electricity use was double that.  Moreover, developing countries' demand for electricity is projected to grow at an annual rate of nearly 6%, into the next century.  We sometimes hear voices urging a return to lifestyles of minimal reliance on energy, including electricity.  A prudent and efficient use of energy must certainly be promoted but we cannot ignore the reality that electricity transports energy to our doorsteps and houses, that ample lighting prolongs our days and makes our streets light at night, that electric pumps bring water to fields and houses, that refrigerators and deep freezers keep our food fresh and reduces spoilage, television allows us to meet the whole world at home.
<P>The services which electricity provide may be taken for granted in industrialized countries but they are anxiously sought by the developing nations of the world.  In these countries the words of the famous Indian nuclear physicist, Homi Bhabha "No energy is more expensive than no energy" are well understood.
<P>An example:  China has the ambition to ensure that each household has a refrigerator - a basic improvement in the quality of life.  But it requires a good deal of energy.  Even with refrigerators of modest size and ofthe most current and efficient model available, a  base load capacity of some 20 000 MEe or 20 large nuclear power reactors will be needed.  It is not enough to plug in the refrigerator.  The electricity must be generated somewhere.
<P>One major driving forcebehind the appetite for energy, apart from development, is the explosive growth in the world's population.  At the birth of Christ there were some 350 million people of the Earth.  In 1900 there were 1.5 billion; in 1990 there were more than 5 billion and in the year 2000 there will be well over 6 billion.  Thus, in the last ten years of this century we expect to increase about as much as we did in the one thousand nine hundred years from the birth of Christ to the year 1900.
<P>With such population increase and demand for development, world wide consumption of energy is expected to increase by 50 to 75 percent by the year 2020 according to the World Energy Council.
<P>We must ask ourselves:  "Where will this energy come from?"  And, confronted with evidence that already the present level of consumption of energy has brought severe environmental damage world wide, we must understand that there is tremendous tension locally, regionally and globally between the demands for more energy and the demands for the protection of life, health and the environment.
<P><B>Environment and energy</B>
<P>Twenty years ago the first UN Conference on the Environment in Stockholm, called the world's attention to environmental degradation.  Today we are becoming painfully aware that environmental problems have not diminished, but escalated from local to regional pollution and now pose some threats to the entire planet.  The emissions of SO2 and NOx caused by the burning of coal and oil have led to the problems of acid rain, dying forests and decaying cities.  To these problems we must now add the threat of global warming which is linked to a great extent to the world's use of fossil fuels.
<P>It is calculated that certain gases released into the world's atmosphere - primarily chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), methane and carbon dioxide (CO2)   trap the heat in the atmosphere and this gradually leads to a higher temperature in the world's atmosphere   with consequent climate changes.  More research can be expected to give us greater certainty about the threat, but many scientists are convinced that we have already experienced a minor warming and that further warming is inevitable.  The question seems only to be whether, through determined action, we are able to slow this development and stabilize it.
<P>Carbon dioxide results from the burning of all fossil and all organic material, including wood.  There is no economically viable way in which CO2 emissions can be avoided in such combustion.  All fuel burning   in cars and other machines, in heating and in electricity generation   is thought to contribute about 50% of the greenhouse effect.  The current burning of rain forests is deemed to add some further 10 20%.  The different fossil fuels do not, however, contribute CO2 in equal measure.  Counted per unit of energy generated, the burning of gas yields about half as much CO2 as does coal.  The amount of CO2 produced by burning oil lies between those of coal and gas.
<P>We cannot change energy systems overnight.  In the foreseeable future there will be an energy mix, as there is today.  Fossil fuels   coal, oil gas   that now cover a little under 90% of the world's total energy use   are certainly not going to be phased out.  Nor is hydro - nor nuclear power.  But it does matter what share is given to the different energies in the mix.
<P>Looked at from a global standpoint it is reasonable to suggest that the least developed countries should be enabled to use the less demanding technologies, which are the fossil based ones and that the advanced countries should make greater use of the more demanding nuclear technology.  In reality we find that both industrially advanced States and some of the more technologically advanced developing countries are at present planning to use both more gas, coal and nuclear.  Mexico, that is now operating one nuclear power reactor and is scheduled to take another into operation in two years, is also building six coal fired plants to cover its growing needs for electricity.  China   while it is at present building a few nuclear plants   is also planning to double its coal use by the year 2000.  And India, which as a number of nuclear plants, is planning to treble its use of coal by the same year.  The coal consumption of China and India together would then be greater than the coal consumption of all the advanced industrialized States lumped together.  This will not reduce CO2 emissions.
<P><B>Energy planning</B>
	<P>Traditionally, energy planning took only the economic aspect into consideration.  The cheapest energy was the best energy.  After the oil embargo a number of countries, e.g. Japan and France, began to consider energy independence as a significant factor.  And today it is evident that we must take into account, not only the costs of generating and distributing energy, but also the costs in terms of life, health and environmental damage.  Environmental price tags must be put on different sources to allow us to compare.  It is important to recognize that the discussion of the merits and demerits of an energy option become meaningful only when this option is compared with its alternatives.
<P>Currently, about 63% of the world's electricity is generated by the burning of coal, oil and gas.  The technology is not very complicated.  From the point of view of economic cost, generation by coal is about equal with nuclear in many places.  From the viewpoint of safety, all three fossil fuels are accepted by the public, although the number of casualties is high in accidents related to coal mining, offshore drilling and gas transportation.  Oil is a much more expensive fuel for electricity production than coal. The price of gas used to be linked to that of oil, but we have seen recently how it has instead been linked to the price of coal, at least for electricity generation.  This makes gas economically attractive at present and there has been a decided trend in the past few years to make greater use of natural gas for electricity generation.  As the burning of gas results in half as much CO2 as does coal per energy unit, there is a net advantage in replacing coal by gas in terms of the greenhouse effect - if leakages of methane can be kept low.  Where gas is burned for additional energy generation, there will, of course, be additional CO2   though less than if coal had been used to generate that additional electricity.
<P><B>Conservation</B>
<P>Some people argue that the question about energy environment can be solved by conservation and a greater use of renewable energy sources.  The concept of conservation covers both a more descriminating and more efficient use of energy.  The difference between the two ways of saving energy is easily seen when we consider that we can save petrol by driving less or by using a more fuel efficient engine.  The latter form of saving is easily accepted   though it may be expensive if it requires a new car...  To limit reliance on energy   to drive less   is more difficult.  It is difficult to calculate how much energy we can save.  The quantities are significant, but no serious energy experts believe that one can achieve more than a partial off setting of the increasing demand for energy.  Certainly current energy plans in the world do not point to a reduced use of energy.
<P><B>Renewable Sources of Energy</B>
<P>The most important renewable and non CO2 producing source of electricity is hydro power.  At present, it generates some 20% of the world's electricity.  In the industrialized world, most hydro potential has already been exploited, but in some developing countries, notably Africa, significant resources remain.  In China, a giant hydro electric project on the Yangstse river will now be launched.  It is to yield enormous quantities of electricity, but will also, apparently, require the resettlement of large numbers of people.
<P>There is much talk about the use of biomass in the industrialized countries.  Rapidly growing trees, harvesting, burning and the planting of new trees would be a fuel cycle without any net contribution of CO2.  However, the economics of this source have not yet been established and so far it has not really been relied upon on a large scale anywhere.
<P>Solar power is making a substantial contribution in isolated locations and on a small scale and heating of water by solar energy is practical and economic in many places    not least in this part of the world.  However, solar cells for large scale economic  electricity production are still deemed to be far away.
<P>Windmills have a long tradition, but despite considerable experimentation and promotion, wind power has not become economic, nor does it yield the large quantities of energy we need.
<P>Taken together solar power, wind power, biomass and other commerical, new and renewable sources yield today less than 0.5% of the world's energy.  Most of it is actually geothermal   e.g. in the United States, Iceland and New Zealand.
<P>How does nuclear power compare with other sources of electricity from the standpoints of environment, economy, security and safety?
<P><B>Environment and Nuclear Power</B>
<P>Nuclear power   which provides about 17% of the world's electricity   has the great advantage of giving rise to no harmful emissions in normal operation.  This means that the use of nuclear power helps us to avoid CO2 and NOx and SO2 emissions.
<P>I am not suggesting that increased use of nuclear power alone can stabilize CO2 emissions, but I am certain that it must be part of the solution - if there is to be a solution.
<P>We come to the issue of security.  It is often alleged that nuclear power increases the risk of a spread of nuclear weapons.  It cannot be excluded that a State could try to make use of a nuclear power programme to hide a weapons programme.  However, stopping civilian 
nuclear power would be no guarantee against development of nuclear weapons.  Rather we must seek to create such political and security conditions that nuclear weapons do not appear desirable to any State.  In this regard the world has come a long way - though admittedly not yet all the way.  The ambition should be a drastic reduction in the nuclear arsenals of the five nuclear weapon States and acceptance of non-proliferation by other States by 1995.  This, I think, is not an unrealistic target.
<P>IAEA safeguards control is not a police power that can stop nuclear activities in a State.  But States which pledge themselves not to acquire nuclear weapons and promise to hold all their nuclear material, present or future, available for inspection, open themselves for considerable control.
<P>What is the risk that international inspection will not discover violations of nuclear non proliferations pledges?  It is simply not feasible to organize a control system under which inspectors systematically comb through every nook and corner of whole countries.  The present system is based upon States declaring nuclear material that they import, produce and possess and it is supplemented by declarations of other States exporting nuclear material.  This system does not create a guarantee against a State secretly mining its own uranium and itself secretly enriching it.  However, in today's world with many satellites and other information around, evidence is likely to become available of such clandestine programmes.  Uranium mining is mostly visible and enrichment and reprocessing plants are also likely to be seen from above.  Such observations, if made known to the IAEA, may trigger proposals for special inspections of possibly non declared nuclear material.  The risk of non detection is not great but the case of Iraq shows that it is not zero.  With greater alertness and more effective export controls it should be possible to make it minimal.
<P><B>Safety</B>
<P>My last points, but not the least ones, relate to the safe operation of nuclear power plants and the safe disposal of nuclear wastes.
<P>A Symposium in Finland in May 1991 on Electricity and Environment which compared risks of different energy sources through the whole cycle, from mining to waste disposal, found not surprisingly that all sources of electricity have some degree of risk.  
Nuclear and renewables were found in normal operation to be in the low end of the risk spectrum, whilst coal and oil were found on the high.  The risk for large accidents was found to be greatest in hydro power, where many dam bursts have taken heavy tolls of lives.  These conclusions square with our daily experience of nuclear power and with the fact that Chernobyl is the only large radiation releasing accident  in a civilian nuclear power plant despite the experience of some 6000 operation years of civilian reactors.  However, we must be aware that the public, which seems to tolerate the risk that people may drown in hydro dam catastrophes, die in explosions in coal mines, or oil platforms or at gas cisterns and pipes, is less tolerant about the risk that anyone's health is affected by the exposure to radiation   whether in the short term or the long term.  As individuals we are neither realistic nor logical in our attitudes to risk.  Let me cite an example.  The World Health Organization has estimated that worldwide the use of pesticides cause some 15 000 human lives and more than a million cases of poisoning each year!  We must assume that these casualties are ignored and tolerated by the public because of the great economic importance of pesticides.  We don't reason the same way about nuclear power although its casualties are few and it provides the world with about 17% of its electricity.  It is true that radioactive contamination may have rather long-lasting effects.  But the use of pesticides sometimes leads to mercury pollution which requires that lakes be black-listed for fishing.
<P>We can only respond to the public attitudes in two ways.  First, by factual information about the risks of nuclear power use and waste disposal and by comparing these risks with those that will be taken if fossil fuels are the alternative.  Second, by strengthening the safety of nuclear power so that no accidents occur in which significant radiation is released.  This, of course, is what is being done   even without any public concern.  Safety is never static   whether in automobiles, aeroplanes or nuclear power plants.  Nuclear power is safer today in most countries than it was before the Chernobyl accident and it will be safer tomorrow.  Some technical modifications have been made on many existing plants and the next generation of plants which will be ready for ordering within a few years will be improved compared to the present generation.
<P>Responsibility for nuclear power safety rests with national authorities.  The IAEA is no supranational regulatory body with powers to order a State to modify plants or to close them.  The Agency does, however, offer Member States safety reviews of various kinds through international expertise and these services are increasingly used and the expert advice offered is normally accepted and acted upon.  Discussions how the international community can better influence nuclear power safety in individual countries have also started and work has begun on an international convention on nuclear safety containing rules that would be binding on the parties.  There is also a considerable amount of activities under way to help strengthen nuclear power safety in ex-Soviet Union and in Eastern Europe.
<P><B>Nuclear Waste</B>
<P>Let me conclude by some comments on nuclear waste.  Nuclear experts are convinced that there are no scientific or technological breakthroughs needed for a waste disposal that is safe even for very, very long time periods.  The technological solutions favoured all around the world for highly radioactive waste are the same, namely to leave spent nuclear fuel at surface level to cool and lose in radioactivity for some 30 60 years and thereafter to isolate it from the biosphere by several barriers and place it in deep stable geological formations.
<P>This confidence of the experts is not yet conveyed to the general public.  The point is often made that we are dealing with waste that remains hazardous for many thousands of years.  This is true, but the quantities are so limited that they can be isolated. This is not the case with the larger quantities of toxic waste that result from the burning of coal.  By 1987 the high level nuclear waste arising annually from all the world's nuclear power stations amounted to about 6000 tons in the form of spent fuel.  If the amount of electricity that these plants generated had instead come from electricity generating coal plants, alone the toxic heavy metals released   mercury, arsenic, vanadium, etc.   would have amounted so some 100 000 tonnes.  These toxic wastes do not have a half life like radioactive wastes.  They remain toxic forever and they remain at the surface of the earth.  The wastes of uranium are put back in the crust of the earth from where the uranium came.  As the final disposal site for the wastes of coal, oil and gas we have chosen the atmosphere and the surface of the earth.  The quantities are so great that we can hardly do otherwise.  But it is puzzling that this overwhelming problem is tolerated, while the limited problem of civilian nuclear power waste disposal appears unbearable to many.  Perhaps the increasing awareness of the greenhouse effect will convince the public that the risks connected with an expanding us of nuclear power, although not zero, are more tolerable than the risks of an excessive use of fossil fuels.<HR>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B39-35</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA059-000320-B036-131</DOCOLDNO>
