<TITLE>Nuclear Energy and the Environment</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Nuclear Energy and the Environment</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix at the International Conference on the 50th Anniversary of the Fermi Reactor and on Peaceful Applications of Nuclear Energy</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Liege, Belgium</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>14 October 1992</H4>
<P><HR>Mr. Chairman, Rector of the University of Liège,
<P>	Before I present my prepared comments I should like to tell you how pleased I am to be in this historic city of Liège.  I should like to pay tribute to the Association des Ingénieurs de Liège, to the European Nuclear Society and to the University of Liège as principal sponsors of this European celebration of the first controlled nuclear chain reaction achieved by Enrico Fermi in Chicago in 1942.
<P>Some people wish that this experiment had never succeeded.  However, the apples which we pluck from the tree of knowledge remain plucked.  They cannot be put back.  We can only try to use them for good and not for bad.  That is up to us!
<P>Only a few years ago I felt the evolution was going in the wrong direction.  The lethal nuclear bomb arsenals were growing and the building of peaceful nuclear power plants was stagnating.  Today, at least the arsenals are shrinking and I am convinced the peaceful uses of nuclear energy will increase.  To me the environmental merits of nuclear power, compared to other energy sources, have always been their major attraction - far outweighing the risks it poses.  And I am glad to be invited to talk about this issue at the outset although a separate session is devoted to it.
<P>The world in which Enrico Fermi so brilliantly succeeded in bringing about the first controlled nuclear fission was a world of lethal conflict among great powers and the destructive force of the atom was demonstrated early.  For nearly fifty years thereafter the many thousands of bombs based on nuclear fission - and fusion - have constituted a sword of Damocles threatening the survival of humanity.  But during those fifty years a nuclear power industry has also grown up generating some 17% of the world's electricity and thousands of nuclear applications are used to promote our health and livelihood.
<P>Today the risk of major conflagrations is rapidly receding.  Production of weapons grade uranium and plutonium is being phased out and thousands of nuclear weapons in the US and Russia are being deactivated and will be dismantled.  In the world of ideological detente and accelerated nuclear disarmament, a complete ban on the testing of nuclear weapons and a drastic reduction in the nuclear weapon arsenals of the five permanent members of the Security Council are not just dreams but distinct possibilities.  While the risk of spread of nuclear weapons to further States is by no means eliminated - as we have seen recently in the case of Iraq - Argentina's and Brazil's decisions to fully open their nuclear programmes for IAEA inspection, South Africa's adherence to the Non-Proliferation Treaty and acceptance by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea of IAEA inspection are important and very encouraging steps.  So are the declarations by new States, like the Ukraine, Belarus and Kazakhstan that they will join the NPT.  The task laid upon the IAEA of inspecting a growing number of nuclear installations will become even more important to give assurance that these installations are used only for peaceful purposes.  Other speakers will address this issue which remains a central one for the IAEA.
<P>In this world of decreasing global military threats, other threats and major problems have to be faced.  Among them are many armed conflicts between ethnic groups, the protection of minorities and human rights, development and a better management of the economy of the world and - not least - the protection of the global environment.  It is this last issue which I shall address, focussing on the significance of nuclear power and nuclear techniques for development and for the environment.
<P>Let me begin by saying that although our ancestors were perfectly capable of destroying their own environment - e.g. through excessive logging for shipbuilding leading to deforestation - they were fewer than we are and their technical tools were not so numerous and so powerful as those which we possess.
<P>The importance for the environment of population growth can hardly be overestimated.  It is calculated that at the time of the birth of Christ there were about 350 million people on the earth; in 1900 there were 1.5 billion; in 1990 there were about 5 billion and in the year 2000 we expect to be about 6 billion.  Thus in the last 10 years of this century it is expected that the world's population will increase almost as much as it did from the time of Christ to the year 1900.  As there are no virgin continents left, erosion, desertification and other environmental problems will drive people to emigrate to areas already well populated - with the risk of conflict.  The demand for reasonable standards of living by an ever increasing number of people is already placing terrible strains on global resources of soil and fresh water.  In my view none of the central problems of the next century - and certainly not the environmental ones - can be tackled with the hope of success, unless we vigorously address the issue of population growth.
<P>Environmental destruction and dangers have evolved from the local to the regional and now the global level.  The awareness of this is increasing rapidly.  No international conference has seen so many Heads of State and government as that on Environment and Development held in Rio de Janeiro in Brazil last June.  And nearly 10,000 media representatives helped to heighten global consciousness about the threats to our environment.
<P>Some people want to place the blame for environmental dangers and destruction on modern science and technology, e.g. on new compounds invented by the chemists, or nuclear techniques developed by physicists and engineers.  It is undeniable that many compounds designed - for instance - to help us increase agricultural production have proved to have dangerous effects, and it is true that many techniques, including nuclear power, give rise to problems and risks and yield not only benefits.  It is important that resources are devoted to non-chemical means of increasing food production and to sources other than nuclear power to increase energy production.  But it is naive and futile to turn our backs on chemistry or nuclear physics.  It is in large measure science and technology that we have to thank for our standard of living in the industrialized countries and it is to science and technology that we must turn to solve our problems - including those created by science and technology themselves.
<P>Some people want the world to close the nuclear chapter.  It would be most unwise, however, to disregard techniques that help to restore our health, increase food production and produce clean energy at competitive costs.  We would do better to analyse the cost benefits of nuclear techniques and compare them with alternatives.
<P>There are today many nuclear techniques directly serving environmental protection and effective resource utilization.  In agriculture, new strains of seeds are created through mutations induced by irradiation, strains that may be more pest-resistant or drought-resistant or have other desirable features.  Cotton crops in Pakistan and rice crops in Indonesia, to take two examples, have increased enormously thanks to the use of mutants.  Through the use of radioisotopes many difficult and important measurements can be performed which help identify water resources or paths of pollution, or measure the uptake of fertilizer in plants.  In Libya the FAO and the IAEA helped, through a nuclear technique, to eradicate an infestation of the New World screwworm, a pest which kills cattle as well as wild animals.  The technique consisted in releasing millions of insects which had been rendered sterile by irradiation.  They mated with fertile insects and no offspring resulted.  The insect population was eradicated in less than one year from the beginning of the campaign.  Only tiny quantities of insecticide had been used for treating wounds infested with the parasite.  The benefit cost ratio of this successful campaign was calculated to be 50 to 1.
<P>In industry, nuclear techniques offer unique ways of making exact measurements which saves raw materials and other resources.  A nuclear technique is even being tested to reduce pollutants arising from the burning of coal.  Flue gases from the coal burning are mixed with ammonia and subjected to electron beams from an accelerator.  The result is that most of the SO2 and NOx is removed from the emissions and a substance that can be used as fertilizer is obtained (ammonium nitrate and sulfate).
<P>I need hardly remind you of the many uses of nuclear techniques in modern medicine, not only to combat cancer where they remain a principal method of treatment, but to achieve many new forms of diagnostic imaging.
<P>Few people perhaps are ready to turn their backs on nuclear techniques such as these.  Indeed, relatively few are probably aware of the wide range of nuclear techniques which serve us in today's world.  The brunt of the opposition is directed against the use of nuclear power and it is based on the view that the costs of this source of energy are unacceptable in terms of risks to life, health and the environment.  We must, of course, analyse what these risks are.  We must also ask what risks are acceptable to society, and what risks we would be taking by relying on possible alternative means of energy generation, or by refraining from producing more energy.  And we must ask, lastly, to what extent risks connected with nuclear power can be further reduced.
<P>The question of what level of risk is acceptable to society in various activities - how safe is safe enough? - is not technical but political.  Governments answer it, influenced by political movements, parties and the media.  Technical data and facts, while not irrelevant to this process, are only a small part of the input.  Nor is there a single answer to the question.  The answers vary from country to country.  They may depend on local circumstances and they vary greatly from one human activity to another.
<P>Our attitudes to risk may, indeed, seem puzzling and inconsistent.  One of the everyday risks to life in modern society is the use of automobiles.  Statistics published a few days ago put the number of killed or injured annually per 10 000 cars at 203 in Belgium, highest in Europe, and 59 in Denmark, lowest in Europe.  Public opinion and governments in these countries, as in others, tolerate these risks, presumably because they are deemed to be outweighed by the benefits.  In both cases the risks can certainly be lowered - at some cost.  Another example:  a publication by the WHO (1990) on the "Public Health Impact of Pesticides used in Agriculture" estimates the global number of annual unintentional deaths caused by pesticide poisoning in 1985 at 20 000 and the total number of unintentional non-fatal poisonings caused by pesticides in 1985 at 1 million!  Presumably these high numbers of casualties are "accepted" by governments and public opinion because of the vital importance of pesticides to food production.  The Bhopal accident - with about 2500 dead - was much publicized but no one suggested a moratorium on the production of pesticides.
<P>While the continued use of automobiles and pesticides and continued coal mining are not questioned by any strong body of public opinion, despite the heavy toll of lives these activities take, the reliance on nuclear power is questioned and in several European States there are formal or informal moratoria on the construction of new plants.  There can be no doubt that this opinion has been influenced by the nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island - where there were hardly any radioactive releases into the environment - and at Chernobyl, where there were vast releases.  It has no doubt been influenced also by the fear that toxic radioactive wastes would leak now or in the future from their disposal sites.
<P>No one can ignore the health and environmental impacts of the Chernobyl accident or the irresponsible handling of radioactive wastes that has occurred in the military sectors in the US and former USSR.  It is interesting, however, to see the conclusions of a Senior Expert Symposium on Electricity and the Environment which took place in Helsinki in 1991 and which was organized by a large number of international organizations, including IAEA.  Comparing the health and environmental impacts of different electricity-generating systems and considering the impacts of the systems from beginning to end - e.g. from fuel extraction to waste disposal - the Symposium concluded - with some reservations due to incompleteness of data - that "under routine operation conditions, nuclear power and renewable systems tend to be in the lower spectrum of health risk and ... energy systems based on coal and oil are in the higher spectrum of health risk"; and that
"human health risks from severe accidents from nuclear, oil and natural gas are of the same order of magnitude and two orders of magnitude smaller than those from the hydroelectric option."
<P>The second conclusion may appear surprising until one looks at the number of hydro dams which have burst over the years drowning many thousands of people.  These dispassionate conclusions of an expert symposium deserve to be cited as they contrast with commonly held perceptions.
<P>It is often claimed that we can do without nuclear energy and its risks, either through energy savings or through greater reliance on renewable sources of energy.  Although both accelerated conservation and the development of solar power and other renewable sources are desirable, neither is credibly predicted to be alternatives to nuclear power.  The 15th Congress of the World Energy Council held in Madrid last month stated that "we cannot do without any of the sources of supply which presently exist, since renewable energy and new technologies will not be able to replace fossil fuel or nuclear".
<P>It is evident that developing countries in particular will seek to use much more energy than they do today.  The average North American now uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent per year; the average Chinese uses 590 kg and the average Indian makes do with 280 kg of oil equivalent per year.  It is not surprising that China is at present planning to double its use of coal by the year 2000.  The World Energy Council has estimated that global energy consumption can be expected to increase by 50-75% by the year 2020 - even assuming vigorous efforts to save energy.  And the same institution puts the contribution of renewable sources of energy at around 3% by that time.
<P>If fears about a global warming effect from the so-called greenhouse gases, notably CO2, are confirmed to be justified, we will face a dilemma:  how to reconcile the predicted greater use of energy with the need to restrain CO2 emissions - which are linked to the burning of all fossil fuel.  Nuclear power is of great importance in this situation, firstly as it is used primarily to generate electricity which is the fastest growing form of energy use, secondly because nuclear power plants do not emit any CO2 or other substances which would have an impact on global climate.
<P>It has been suggested that nuclear power, which today is responsible for about 5% of the world's energy and 17% of its electricity - a little less than hydro's 20% of electricity -is too small a source to be of any importance to global CO2 emissions.  No one has contended that nuclear power, alone, can be the answer to the threat of global warming, but it has been calculated that if today's 400 or so nuclear power plants were closed and the electricity generated by them were instead generated by coal-fired plants, total global CO2 emissions would increase by some 7%.
<P>Thus it does matter to global CO2 emissions if obsolescent coal plants are replaced by nuclear plants or if obsolescent nuclear plants are replaced by coal plants.  The relevance of nuclear power to CO2 emissions can also be seen from a comparison between the UK and France.  In the UK, where about 70% of electricity comes from coal combustion, average CO2 emission per kWh was 0.78 kg.  In France, where more than 70% of the electricity comes from nuclear power, the CO2 emissions per kWh are about one tenth of the British value (0.086 kg).
<P>At the present time when a fairly large sector of public opinion in many industrialized countries is still sceptical about a wider use of nuclear power, it is understandable if governments, aware of the need to limit CO2 emissions, either postpone decisions on power generation or opt for gas, which does contribute to CO2 but generates about half as much CO2 per energy unit as does coal.
<P>There is no doubt, however, that the awareness is increasing among governments that, although the problem of global warming cannot be answered by nuclear power alone, it can also not be answered without reliance on nuclear power.  Both the Paris and Houston summits of seven industrialized States pointed to nuclear power as a means of restraining greenhouse gas emissions.
<P>Even the Club of Rome seems - lately and reluctantly - to have come to the conclusion, in the face of the risk of global warming, that the use of nuclear power is necessary.  Coal and oil, it is said, are "probably more dangerous to society because of the carbon dioxide they produce ..." and "There are, therefore, strong arguments for keeping the nuclear option open".
<P>At the level of the United Nations, e.g. at the Rio Conference, no such conclusion would have been possible.  Certainly, a vast majority of the world's governments either favour the use or expanded use of nuclear power or, at least, the retention of the option, and only a handful of governments are opposed.  Nevertheless conclusions at the UN level are mostly by consensus and there is clearly no consensus on the matter between governments.  At Rio a Framework Convention on Climate Change was concluded.  It failed to include the proposal that CO2 emissions by 2005 should have returned to the levels of 1990, but it did set as an ultimate objective the stabilization of greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere at a level that would prevent dangerous interference with the climate system.  The Conference and Convention refrained to tell us how this was to be achieved.  The real discussions on CO2 emissions and energy sources - including the merits of nuclear power -therefore lie before us in years to come.  My own conclusion is that the industrially advanced States will have to consider a continued, indeed, expanded use of nuclear power in order to enable many developing countries to expand their use of less demanding fossil fuel-based technologies.  I believe we must also develop nuclear power plants which are easier to operate for eventual use by the more advanced developing countries.
<P>Returning to the two principal points which underlie most of the scepticism about nuclear power - waste disposal and operational safety - one might conclude that in the environmental context, nuclear wastes are, in fact, the greatest asset of nuclear power.  They do not contribute to acid rain or global warming and they are so limited in volume that they can be disposed of and isolated in their entirety.
<P>Some figures and comparisons may be helpful.  A coal-fired plant of 1000 MW(e) will require about 7000 tons of coal per day - i.e. about five train loads.  A nuclear plant of the same electric capacity will use some 80 kilograms of uranium per day.  Even with excellent flue gas cleaning equipment the coal plant will annually emit some 9000 tons of SO2, 4500 tons of NOx, some 400 tons of various heavy metals and no less than 6.5 million tons of CO2.  The nuclear plant will produce 30 tons of highly radioactive waste per year.
<P>The methods which have been worked out for the disposal of the limited amounts of nuclear waste are designed to ensure isolation for tens of thousands of years.  They would seem vastly less risky than our current free release of most of the waste resulting from the burning of fossil fuels.  It would seem desirable, however, that the international consensus on responsible management, transport and disposal of nuclear wastes should be laid down in standards for both civilian and military wastes accepted and respected by all.  Such standards are, in fact, being worked out within the IAEA.
<P>With regard to operational safety it is understood by the nuclear power industry that the level world wide must be so high that accidents with significant releases will not occur.  This realization is leading to an intensification of international co-operation regarding nuclear safety.  The safety weaknesses identified in design and operation of nuclear power plants in the former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe are leading the countries of these regions to work together with other industrialized States to back-fit and upgrade plants or gradually to phase out plants which are not deemed able to attain an internationally acceptable level of safety.  Moreover, much more use is being made of international peer reviews in the nuclear safety field - both between operators and between regulators.  To existing non-binding standards regarding nuclear safety there will soon be added a convention containing safety fundamentals, which will become legally binding upon States adhering to it.
<P>The ambition is that through measures such as these, an international nuclear safety culture will emerge whose positive impact will be reflected in an excellent global operating record for nuclear power plants.  Such results, if attained over a period of time, I think will convince the public that the expanded use of nuclear power, which may be indispensable, is also fully acceptable.<HR>
</DOC>
