<TITLE>Coping with Nuclear Danger in a Post-Cold War World</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Coping with Nuclear Danger in a Post-Cold War World</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix on the IAEA's Safeguards and Verification Role to the Council on Foreign Relations</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>New York, NY, USA</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>20 October 1992</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
I am pleased to have the opportunity to speak on a subject which is central to the work of the International Atomic Energy Agency - the efforts to prevent the spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.  Some experts tell us that nuclear proliferation is the greatest military risk we face in the world today.  I shall describe these risks and responses, as I see them.  I should like to begin, however, by noting that there are several factors in the post-cold-war world which favour non-proliferation and which have already led to important positive results.
<P>The primary factor in the attitude of States to nuclear weapons is their perceived security interests.  Global and regional tensions and nuclear arms races are incentives to acquire such weapons; detente globally and regionally and nuclear disarmament are disincentives.  In the present global detente, with the major military powers helping to settle regional conflicts rather than competing in them, and with accelerating nuclear disarmament between the United States and Russia, the general climate is positive and there are good reasons to set our non-proliferation ambitions high.  In my view we should aim, firstly, at an unlimited extension of the NPT at the conference which will take place in 1995; secondly, we should seek to obtain non- proliferation commitments from all States except the five declared nuclear-weapon States - if possible by the same date.  Today, agreement on a final date for nuclear weapons testing does not seem totally excluded and an agreement on a cut-off of the production of enriched uranium and plutonium for weapons purposes should not be too difficult, considering that the disposal of fissionable material for dismantled weapons is already a problem.  Agreements on these two matters would be highly significant in the non-proliferation issue.
<P>Let me now point to some specific recent non-proliferation gains.  With Argentina and Brazil having declared themselves committed to non-proliferation and Cuba apparently ready to join the Tlatelolco Treaty, there are good prospects that this Treaty may enter into force for all parties next year.  Latin America would become a nuclear-weapon-free zone.
<P>South Africa, dismantling apartheid and no longer feeling under a potential military pressure from the outside world, has ratified the NPT and is opening its nuclear installations to IAEA inspection.  Thereby the efforts of African States to make their continent a nuclear-weapon-free zone take on more realism.
<P>The States in the Middle East have long expressed a consensus support for the concept of a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the region and still do so.  At the recent General Conference of the IAEA I was instructed to consult with these States about comprehensive verification in the region and to work out a model safeguards agreement.  A nuclear-weapon-free zone is unlikely to be established except in the context of a negotiated peace settlement.  Today the chances for such a settlement are greater than ever before.  Agreement on a zone comprising all relevant States would not only be desirable per se.  Without it there could be reluctance among Arab States, now parties to the NPT, to support an unlimited extension of the Treaty in 1995.
<P>The security perspectives on the Indian sub-continent, where neither State is legally committed to non-proliferation, and in the Korean peninsula, where both States are so committed, are unclear.  A positive factor here as elsewhere in the post-cold-war world is that the declared nuclear-weapon States, which are also permanent members of the Security Council, co-operate in favour of non-proliferation.
<P>If there are reasons to be pleased that some of the old non-proliferation problems have been solved and that there might be gleams of hope in others, we also have to register some new problems.
<P>One question which has often been asked in the past year is whether the break-up of the Soviet bloc and the break-down of the firm communist state structures have increased the risks of nuclear weapons, material, know-how or scientists and engineers trickling out to would-be proliferating countries.  It would, indeed, seem plausible that a loosening of government controls and administrative order, coupled with desperate living conditions and increased criminality, could lead to proliferating acts.  Judging by media reports one would even think that there is a flourishing black market in plutonium and enriched uranium.  However, all news items which the IAEA has been able to follow up with governmental authorities have proved - so far - to be uninteresting from the viewpoint of proliferation.  Similar conclusions were reported by Mr. Gates of the CIA early this year.  Gram quantities of plutonium have been sold and the illegal transactions raise concern from the viewpoint of radiation protection, but not from the standpoint of proliferation.  We have also not seen any evidence so far of scientists or engineers emigrating from the Soviet bloc.  There is, however, no reason for complacency.  The best remedy is political and social stabilization in the former Soviet Union.
<P>An acute proliferation problem would arise if Ukraine, Belarus or Kazakhstan decided to try individually to control strategic nuclear weapons which remain on their territory.  I have no knowledge about current negotiations between these States and Russia and the United States.  I can only tell you that the IAEA is discussing with authorities in these States how to set up accounting and control systems for their peaceful nuclear installations to enable them to accept safeguards verification by the Agency once they have ratified the NPT as non-nuclear-weapon States.
<P>I turn now to the risk that the case of Iraq has demonstrated, namely that some developing countries are reaching a technological level where they can produce enriched uranium and plutonium and design weapons.  When the NPT was concluded the fears were about countries like Germany, Switzerland and Sweden.  Later the fears were about a few technologically advanced developing countries, like Argentina and Brazil.  Today the concern is rather about countries like Algeria, Iran and North Korea.  Of these three only Algeria is not a party to the NPT.  What is the risk of another Iraq?  And what can be done about it?
<P>Iraq was a highly militarized society with well-trained scientific and technical cadres and a government able and willing to spend vast resources on the nuclear sector and motivated to do so by perceived strategic interests.  The conditions were unusual - but not unique.
<P>The means by which the world can discourage nuclear weapons development in technologically advancing developing States are largely the same as for advanced States.  The most important means lie in the political-security field:  regional detente, security guarantees, absence of military threats.  A peaceful settlement in the Middle East and the establishment of a nuclear-weapon-free zone, comprising Iran, Iraq, Israel, Algeria, Libya and other States would be the most important measure.  Another barrier against nuclear proliferation lies in export restrictions on nuclear material and sensitive equipment.  After Iraq agreement has been reached among a number of States on a tightening of such restrictions.
<P>A third means of influence lies in economic favours for non-proliferation status and threat of action against proliferation - as declared by the summit-level meeting of the Security Council early this year.
<P>The safeguards inspectors of the IAEA are not nuclear police that stop proliferation by the use of force but the reports of the inspectors may trigger action by governments in the diplomatic, economic, political or military field.  It is the awareness of this that lends authority to the inspections.  However, the potential reactions of the outside world are only a deterrent to proliferation if the risk of detection is high.  Before the events in Iraq the membership of the IAEA asked the Agency primarily to verify that there was no diversion of nuclear material from declared nuclear programmes.  The safeguards system was well developed to do this.  After the events in Iraq the demand not surprisingly has been that the safeguards system should also verify that there exist no clandestine, undeclared nuclear installations.  This is harder to do.
<P>In the case of Iraq the Security Council asked the IAEA to map the nuclear capacity of Iraq through inspections, to destroy or otherwise neutralize Iraq's capacity to make weapons and weapons-useable material and to organize long-term monitoring.  The corresponding tasks regarding chemical and biological weapons and missiles were given to a Special Commission, to be nominated by the Secretary-General.  The Commission was also to assist and co-operate with the IAEA and - on the basis of information given to it - to designate sites and installations for the IAEA to inspect.
<P>Through the highly intrusive inspections which the IAEA has performed in Iraq on sites designated by the Special Commission, the nuclear enrichment and weaponization programme was uncovered.  The question has inevitably arisen:  Why did you not perform inspections of such thoroughness before?  Why did you only visit the nuclear facilities which Iraq declared?  Why did you give advance notice about inspections instead of performing surprise visits?  Why did you let Iraq reject inspectors proposed by you?
<P>Following on these questions, suggestions are made by some that for the future inspections might be more effective if directed from some organ under the Security Council -a permanent commission on the pattern of the Special Commission for Iraq, but with a mandate to look after all countries and all weapons of mass destruction, and with easy access to the Security Council and to national intelligence sources.
<P>It is clear that lessons must be drawn from the case of Iraq.  As I shall explain lessons are drawn.  It is also to be welcomed that the Security Council is ready to tackle cases of proliferation which may constitute threats to international peace and security.  It is not equally clear - at least not to me - that there would be any advantage in or need for a bureaucratic filter between the IAEA which is continuously responsible for the inspections all over the world and the Council which, if need be, supports the inspections and which may act on any violation reported by the IAEA.
<P>Let me now address some of the questions raised about inspections in the wake of the revelations in Iraq.  The first point to consider is the basis of information upon which inspections take place.  Inspectors cannot roam whole countries in blind search of nuclear installations.  They must have information on where they may reasonably look.  Under the IAEA safeguards inspection system the inspected State has a duty to declare all relevant material and all relevant installations.  It is certainly important that these be subject to inspection, that the large quantities of declared plutonium and enriched uranium be checked and accounted for.  But what about the possible undeclared material and installations?  In the case of Iraq information about them came from defectors and satellite pictures.  Such information was given by national governments to the Special Commission, which used it to designate sites for inspection by the IAEA - in the case of nuclear-related sites.  Such information was not available to the Agency before Iraq.  Under the safeguards system as it was designed before the events in Iraq, the Agency would get some information that did not originate in the inspected State itself, notably about nuclear material exported to that State.  In order to reduce the loss of commercial industrial secrets NPT-type safeguards were designed to focus on the nuclear material.  It is true that without such material you cannot make a weapon, but it is also true that a completely indigenous and undeclared production of nuclear material could go undetected.  This is what happened in Iraq as regards the enriched uranium emerging from the EMIS method.
<P>Post Iraq the IAEA has sought drastically to broaden its information basis.  It urges Member States to supply it with information about the export and import of sensitive equipment.  Had such information existed in the case of Iraq, suspicions and grounds for questions might have arisen.  Post Iraq the Agency also scans media for possible clues about undeclared material or installations.  Lastly, it asks Member States to provide any relevant information they may have, including information obtained through satellite photography.  There is, of course, a lot of disinformation circulating and even more poor or erroneous information.  Therefore, the assessment of all the information must be critical.  The Agency should not overlook material or installations which should have been declared but it should also not strike false alarms.  With the expanded information basis that is now being created the risk should be much reduced that sites calling for inspection are not identified.
<P>If access to information about sites is the first requirement for successful inspection, access to the sites is the second.  In the case of Iraq there is a right to "unimpeded" access under the Security Council resolution and an exchange of letters between the Secretary-General and Iraq.  This has meant the right to go anywhere, anytime, to look for anything relevant to that resolution.  No need for visas and no right for Iraq to reject inspectors.  It has allowed surprise inspections, visits to prisons, ministries, military sites and the search for documents.
<P>The inspection rights in Iraq contrast sharply with the rights which the IAEA used to be accorded under safeguards agreements.  It should be recalled, however, that the arrangements in Iraq were accepted by a defeated government in conjunction with a cease-fire.  The inspection rights laid down in the newly negotiated convention on chemical weapons are probably more indicative of how far States are willing to go.  It will be found that visas can still be required and that inspector designations rejected.  However, some progress has been made compared to inspection arrangements under safeguards agreements.  This should be allowed to rub off on the nuclear inspection system.
<P>A special question relates to the speed with which an inspection can be sent.  In the case of Iraq, surprise was very important to success in a few cases where the targets were mobile, namely documents and nuclear equipment on trucks.  These, however, are not typical objects of inspection.  The normal object would be reactors, enrichment or reprocessing plants and similar installations.  They do not move overnight.  A bomb-quantity of plutonium or enriched uranium, on the other hand, is so small in volume that it could be moved within hours, defeating the most ambitious surprise inspection.  It must be remembered that the inspectors work on the territory controlled by a government.  That government is physically capable of obstructing or impeding the inspection if it so chooses.
<P>The IAEA is now affirming a right which exists in safeguards agreements to perform so-called "special inspections" when the Agency has reason to believe that something that should have been declared has not been declared.  Such inspections will certainly not take place overnight if the recipient country is reluctant to receive them.  However, if access were resisted by the country and the matter were brought to the Board of Governors of the IAEA, the Board could submit the case without delay to the Security Council under the relationship agreement between the IAEA and the United Nations.  In any situation the Council could evidently also address an issue of apparent proliferation on its own and call on a State to accept Agency inspection.
<P>I have spoken in some detail about inspections, because it is a central function of the IAEA.  We have a department of some 600 people dealing with it, consuming about one-third of our budget of some $60 million.  Yet, there are many questions I have not answered.  I hope, however, that I have given you some ideas both on the nuclear proliferation dangers and the means of meeting them - including inspection.<HR>
</DOC>
