<TITLE>Lessons of Iraq</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Lessons of Iraq</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>European Strategy Group and Aspen Strategy Group Conference on Proliferation in the 1990s Address by IAEA Director General Hans Blix</H4>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Rome, Italy</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>28 October 1992</H4>
<HR>
<OL>
<LI>	I am pleased to address the question of "proliferation in the 1990s".  When I saw the title I asked myself if there was a pessimistic assumption in it.  My remarks will be the same as if I had addressed the issue "non-proliferation in the 1990s".
<P>Before I focus on Iraq and IAEA inspections, some broader and more fundamental questions may be appropriate.
<LI>To understand how we can best counter proliferation, we must identify what factors are incentives to it and disincentives.  The primary factor, most will agree, is perceived security interests.  Global and regional tensions and nuclear arms races are incentives, detente globally and regionally and nuclear disarmament are disincentives.
<LI>In the present global detente, with the major military powers helping to settle regional conflicts rather than competing in them, and with accelerating nuclear disarmament between the United States and Russia, the general climate is positive.  South Africa's adherence to the NPT and Argentina's and Brazil's movement toward acceptance of the Tlatelolco Treaty have several reasons, but the general climate, I think, is one.
<LI>	In my view, it is not naive to aim ambitiously now at<BR>
 <OL>
<LI>(a)	An unlimited extension of the NPT in 1995;
<LI>(b)	The universalization of non-proliferation commitments from all but the declared nuclear-weapon States.
</OL>
       Two agreements in the disarmament sphere would be helpful to these aims for the NPT and, indeed, be valuable in themselves:<P>
       <OL>
	<LI>(a)	An agreement on a final date for all nuclear weapons testing;
	<LI>(b)	A cut-off of the production of enriched uranium and plutonium for weapons purposes.
        </OL><P>
<LI>I am not claiming that a final date on testing is a sine qua non for an unlimited NPT extension, but I am convinced that it would be the right signal for the 1990s and that continued testing of "better" weapons would send the world the wrong signal.
<LI>	Even more important for an unlimited extension of NPT than a final date for testing may be agreement on a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the Middle East.  Arab States now bound by NPT may not wish to bind themselves for an unlimited time, unless all States in the region - including Israel - did the same.  Paragraph 14 of Security Council resolution 687 on Iraq does state that the resolution's provisions on the mapping and neutralization of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction represent steps toward the goal of establishing in the Middle East a zone free of all weapons of mass destruction.  Maybe so, but agreement on a zone is likely to be reached only in the context of a peace settlement in the region.
<LI>	It seems clear, especially after Iraq, that a simple acceptance of NPT and NPT-type safeguards by all States in a region stretching from Iran to Algeria would be insufficient both for Israel and for the other States in that region.  The NPT does not explicitly prohibit the construction or possession of enrichment and reprocessing plants, nor the possession of highly enriched uranium or plutonium, so long as it is all declared and placed under safeguards.  It is hard to believe that this would be acceptable in the Middle East.  It is also hard to believe that NPT-type IAEA safeguards would satisfy the parties in this region.  Without going so far as the inspection rights in Iraq, safeguards verification in a nuclear-weapon-free zone in an extended Middle East would have to be much sharper and more intrusive than those under NPT, probably including both international and bilateral elements.
<P>A peace settlement and a closely verified nuclear-weapon-free zone embracing all States in an extended Middle East would remove mutual incentives which now exist to acquire nuclear weapons capacity.  It would cover a number of the countries against which suspicions are now directed from various quarters.
<LI>	As in the Middle East, non-proliferation on the Indian sub-continent probably requires a tailor-made agreement and presupposes regional detente and some steps toward global nuclear disarmament.  The bilateral agreement between North and South Korea also points to the need in that region for special rules that go beyond the NPT.
<LI>	I have now pointed to positive - and difficult - political action that would result in credible non-proliferation assurances regarding the countries which are most frequently mentioned as real or potential risks:  Algeria, Libya, Syria, Iraq, Iran and the Koreas, in addition to Israel, India and Pakistan which are assumed to have the ability to make nuclear weapons.  Considering how few these States are, it is not unreasonable to look for tailor-made approaches.
<LI>	However, it is also necessary to consider general measures impeding proliferation especially if we take a pessimistic view of our ability to remove certain perceived security interests as incentives to acquire a nuclear weapons capacity.
<LI>	Restrictions on the export of sensitive technology generally make proliferation more difficult.  A tightening of international rules has been agreed upon as a lesson of Iraq and more States appear willing to join this effort.  A good deal of items were, indeed, imported by Iraq through a wide and clandestine procurement network which has not been declared.  We must be aware, however, that a country with a high degree of self-reliance will not be much affected by export restrictions.
<LI>	The break-up of the Soviet State and the break-down of rigid Communist structures are often cited as causing a risk of illegal and uncontrolled export, of the trickling of nuclear weapons or material or equipment or technology or scientists or engineers to potential proliferators.  This is a plausible risk and it calls for alertness.  The best remedy, surely, is stabilization of the countries of the former Soviet Union.  Fortunately we have not so far seen any real export of weapons or weapons-grade material, but lots of scams.  Enriched uranium, so far, has turned out to be depleted uranium, natural uranium or low-enriched uranium fuel.  Plutonium has turned out to be gram quantities.  But there is no cause for complacency.
<LI>	Carrots and sticks, held by the outside world, play some role as incentives and disincentives.  The Security Council waved the stick in its summit statement of January this year.  The carrots are a major reason for many developing countries to formally commit themselves to non-proliferation.  But they don't work where perceived security interests point in the opposite direction, as in Pakistan.
<LI>	Safeguards verification cannot physically stop proliferation attempts.  The inspectors are not policemen with executive power.  They are observers who report and their reports may trigger action by governments, perhaps collectively decided by the Security Council.  Lax verification may invite cheating by a State inclined to acquire nuclear weapons despite a non-proliferation commitment.  Effective verification may constitute a deterrence.  Of course a State could renounce its NPT commitment and its safeguards obligations, but predictable reactions to such renunciation might deter from such conduct.  No State has done it so far.
<LI>	After the disclosure of Iraq's clandestine nuclear programme, the IAEA has been both praised for its inspections there and criticized for failing to have identified the programme before the war.  The questions asked are how could Iraq escape being found out by Agency inspectors, and are there more Iraqs?  Are we in a new era in which a number of developing countries are reaching a technological level enabling them to go for nuclear weapons?
<P>In my view, the current discussion focusses a bit too much on how the inspections are carried out and a bit too little on the information on which they are based.  It has been suggested, inter alia, that inspection would become much more effective if placed directly under the Security Council, as in the case of Iraq.  Short notice or no notice, aggressive snap inspections are described as an ideal by some contrasting with the IAEA's advance notice visits to declared installations under NPT safeguards.  The Agency has been described as sleepy or soft - or worse - by outside critics, mostly in the US.  Not so, however, by governments.  They have commended the Agency and its Action Team for Iraq.
<LI>	In a couple of cases, short notice inspections were highly successful and significant in Iraq, namely, against mobile targets:  nuclear equipment on trucks and documents.  However, it must be borne in mind that objects of nuclear inspection are normally highly sedentary:  research reactors, enrichment or reprocessing plants.  They do not move away overnight, or even in a week.  It must also be recognized that a country in which inspection is to take place is not like a flat that is raided by police.  A country is controlled by its own police and military.  They are physically actually capable of stopping international inspectors if they have their government's order to do so.  They did stop Mr. Kay, leading an IAEA team, from entering the truck park and they did prevent a UNSCOM team for several days from entering the Ministry of Agriculture.  Meanwhile mobile objects, like documents, can be removed.
<P>How co-operative an inspected regime may be will depend on the one hand on how embarrassed it would be by revelations that would result and what punishment it may risk for resisting inspection.  It is not self-evident that trade embargoes or punitive air strikes will be inflicted automatically for lack of co-operation.
<P>In Iraq the inspectors have had very extensive rights of access, granted by Iraq as a part of the cease-fire settlement.  This has been helpful - even though Iraq has not always respected the rights.  In other cases, the inspectors' rights will probably be less far-reaching.  The chemical convention probably shows what balance is acceptable today to States between the interest of rights of inspection and the interest of undisturbed State integrity.  This balance differs in some respects favourably from the balance struck in the 25 year-old safeguards system.  However, under the chemical convention, visas can still be required and designated inspectors can still be rejected.  Where the chemical convention is more favourable to inspection than safeguards, it should, if possible, be emulated by the IAEA.
<LI>	Now to the question of information.  It must be recognized that inspectors cannot roam foreign territories in blind search of clandestine installations.  They must have information about where to go.  Under the IAEA NPT safeguards system, the inspected State is obliged to declare all nuclear material and the installations in which it is produced or otherwise found.  This system was designed primarily with the industrialized advanced open democratic States in mind.  And it is not a matter of indifference that the large quantities of enriched uranium and plutonium in these States are declared and checked.  Limitations on the rights of inspection were set, however, in order to reduce the risk of revelation of commercial or technological secrets.  These limitations are hardly crippling, but they are unhelpful.  More important is the difficulty of getting information about possible clandestine installations.  If the State itself does not declare them, how will the Agency know?
	In no case has any Member State come to the Agency during my eleven years there to tell us that at such and such a geographic point there is an installation that should be inspected.  It is true that Iraqi procurement of maraging steel, end caps of centrifuges and krytrons was described in some newspapers.  In the absence of detailed data and knowledge about locations, however, there was a poor basis for requesting a special inspection, if this had been considered - which it was not, or if it had been suggested by any Member - which it was not.
<LI>	The situation regarding information is better today than before the war in Iraq. 
<P>Firstly, we expect Member States to inform us about export and import of certain equipment Ä in addition to nuclear material.  Although the risk of smuggling remains, much information can be expected through this new recommendation.
<P>Secondly, we scan media for information.  It is somewhat dismaying to see how much of the information turns out, upon checking, to be erroneous, but in the future as in the past, there could be some needles in a haystack, where much of the material consists of misunderstandings, perhaps disinformation or and certainly sensationalism.  Many of the stories published seem to have been too good for the publishers to check...
<P>Thirdly, we ask Member States to provide us with information they may obtain, whether through satellites or otherwise.  The satellites, in particular, are an obvious powerful source Ä but they only see what they are directed to.  The Argentine enrichment plant in Pilcanyo appears not to have been seen before the Argentine Government itself declared it.  And a research reactor in Algeria appears to have been under construction for a good number of years before it was reported in the US press.  In Iraq, information from defectors and satellite photography appear, however, to have been key elements in identifying sites for inspection.  This is an important lesson.
<LI>	I have mentioned the Security Council.  The Council does not have any satellite and cannot tell us where to go, but it can back up inspectors in their right to access to sites to be inspected.  This lesson of Iraq is not lost for the future.  There is no difficulty in liaison between the IAEA and the Council and the Secretary-General.
<LI>	I should mention one more novel feature, namely, the invitations to the Agency by some states to visit any site or installation, regardless of whether it is declared and regardless of whether the Agency has reason to believe that the site has something that should have been declared but was not.  Such invitations have been offered so far by Iran, Libya, South Africa and the DPRK, to cite the offers in the order they were made.  Such visits may have great advantages:  they may enable the Agency to ask to see something without it being implied that the State had been negligent in its duty to declare the site.  The information available may be too vague or uncertain for us to request a special inspection.  The invitation may also enable a country to clear itself of any allegation that a particular site or installation is clandestine and should have been declared.<HR>
</DOC>
<DOC>
