<TITLE>Statement of IAEA Director General on the occasion of International Women's Day Celebration</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Statement of IAEA Director General on the occasion of International Women's Day Celebration</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER> International Women's Day Celebration</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Vienna, Austria</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>9 March 1992</H4>
<P><HR>Seventeen years ago, the United Nations launched the Decade for Women. At that time the Board of Governors of the IAEA adopted a Resolution requesting the Director General to give "... special consideration to the appointment of qualified women to policy making and other professional posts on the staff of the Secretariat." Since then, a number of steps have been taken resulting in an increase of some 60% in the number of professional women on the staff of the Agency. However, in spite of this considerable improvement, we are still far from the 30% target for women professionals and   I am sorry to say   we are still a male dominated organization with one of the highest proportion of professional men, about 86%.
<P>The reason for this is simple. We are dealing with very technical programmes for which mostly nuclear engineers or nuclear scientists are required. In these particular fields despite Marie Curie and Lise Meitner   the number of trained women worldwide is still rather limited. Although we have made special pleas to Govemments to ensure that qualified professional women be given every opportunity to apply for our announced vacancies on an "equitable basis with men", the number of women's applications received is still very disappointing. For instance, for scientific/engineering posts, only 29 out of 671 applications received last year   or 4%   were from women whereas for administrative or other posts the percentage is 17%, which is also low.
<P>In the Safeguards Inspectorate, however, a field where a few years ago supervlsors were hesitant to recommend the employment of women because of the physical strain involved and where some Governments, too, were reluctant to accept women inspectors, we have been able through a training programme to increase their number considerably. We now have 18 women inspectors, or assistant inspectors, who side by side with men are performing physically and technically difficult inspection tasks in nuclear facilities all over the world.
<P>Women professionals contribute to the Agency's work in an exemplary manner and so do the many other women in other categories of employment who are equally contributing to the success of our organization. In total they are more than 900 and I would like to THANK every one of them. Without their intelligence, knowledge, wisdom and dedication it would be impossible to accomplish what we do.<HR>
</DOC>
