<TITLE>Peaceful Nuclear Development</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Peaceful Nuclear Development</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by Hans Blix at the <BR>Nairobi Seminar on Nuclear Law</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Nairobi, Kenya</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>6 March 1991</H4>
<HR>
<P>
<H3>Sustainable development</H3>
<P>The World Commission on Environment and Development defined "sustainable development" as "development which meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs."  I agree with this basic thought.  We must not ruin the resource base off which future generations will also need to live.  Nor should we leave chemical or other wastes that could bring disaster for them.  These principles are easy to articulate but less easy to put into practice.  We are often groping in the dark.  For instance, we do not always know what the long term effects may be of using certain new chemical compounds.  A little later I shall tell you that in my view the peaceful nuclear industry is able and willing to take very safe care of its wastes.
<P>Before I address the positive role that nuclear applications play to bring about sustainable development, I want to make a few points that seem to me fundamental in this context.
<P>The first relates to the size of the world's population.  At the time of the birth of Christ there were   it has been calculated   some 300 400 million people on the earth.  In l900, there were l.5 billion, we have now passed 5 billion and by the year 2000 we shall be 6 billion.  Thus, in the ten years between 1990 and 2000, we expect to increase almost as much as we did in the preceding 2000 years!  If the world's population were to double in the next 40 to 60 years, it is hard to see how desertification, deforestation, climate change and urban decay could be arrested.  In my view, any strategy for sustainable development pre supposes population restraint.
<P>Second, the most important areas in which sustainable development must be sought are, of course, food production, availability of water and energy generation.  To achieve it requires efforts by all countries and it is of mutual interest that the North provides financial assistance and facilitates a transfer of technology to the countries of the South.
<P>Third, the new climate of East West relations, which we hope will remain, holds out the prospect of a much more ambitious international co operation and calls for greater and better use of international organizations, including the IAEA.
<P>A lessening of tensions and a reduction of military arsenals among industrial and developing countries alike would release very substantial resources.  Large parts of these resources will no doubt be used for domestic purposes.  However, it will be important to insist that significantly increased resources be devoted to assistance to poor countries and to the protection of the environment.
<P>A world in which half of humanity lives in misery and a minority enjoys an ever improving standard is not a stable world.  The wall between East and West has fallen.  It cannot be followed by a wall between the North and the South.  Development from poverty is a global issue   not only for humanitarian but also for political reasons.
<P>Transfer of technology and know how is vitally important for development, and nuclear techniques are of great use   also to Africa, where our Agency has a substantial technical co operation programme.
<P>Let me give you a few examples of such nuclear applications.
<H3>Food and agriculture</H3>
In agriculture, for instance, radioisotopes and radiation help us:
<P>To optimize fertilizer and water use and improve biological nitrogen fixation.  Inter alia this provides higher protein content in plants;
<P>Radiation induced mutations help us to breed high performance, well adapted and disease resistant crop varieties;
<P>Using insects that have been radiation sterilized or genetically altered helps us to eradicate or control insect pests;
<P>Reproductive performance, nutrition, and health of animals is improved by nuclear methods.
<P>Water is the most important limiting factor for crop production in many areas of the world.  The efficient use of water in irrigation systems requires continuous monitoring of the moisture content of soil.  Moisture gauges using neutron techniques are ideal instruments for this purpose.  Through these methods, traditional irrigation methods are being improved and in some cases up to 40 percent of the water can be saved.
<P>Radioisotopes have proved to be ideal tools for studying the behaviour, breakdown, and residues of agrochemicals in soil, water, plants, animals and their products.  Through the use of isotopes it has been possible to devise safer ways to apply agrochemicals and formulations which are effective and environmentally benign in controlling pests and promoting growth.
<P>For centuries, mankind has tried to improve the quantity and quality of crops.  Natural evolution of plants results from spontaneous mutation and selection of the fittest mutants.  By radiation treatment the rate of mutation occurrence can be multiplied, thereby accelerating evolution and the selection of superior crops.
<P>The number of mutant induced crop varieties now exceeds 1500 worldwide with billions of dollars added to farmers' incomes annually.  One striking example is a cotton mutant developed in Pakistan in the early Eighties which helped to double the country's output.  And China has had such remarkable success in improving its rice crops through mutations that about one tenth of its total acreage is now mutant derived.
<P>In Africa, nuclear methods are helping to fight two devastating diseases   rinderpest and trypano somiasis   thereby increasing food production and incomes for small farmers.
<P>Controlling or eradicating insects can be achieved without the use of chemicals through the sterile insect technique (SIT).  In this approach, insects are produced in large rearing plants, sexually sterilized using gamma radiation, and released into the native insect population.  When the sterile insects mate with the wild insects, no offspring are produced.  This approach is not only environmentally sound, frequently it is the only practical means of insect eradication.
<P>The first successful use of the SIT related to the New World screwworm, a devastating pest of livestock and wild life, on the island of CuraÜao in 1954.  Later the screwworm   which can also attack humans   was eradicated from the USA and then Mexico.  In 1989, however, the New World Screwworm was reported in Libya and the SIT is now being applied there to try to stop this new introduction.
<P>The SIT has also been used against tsetse flies which, as you know, have prevented settlement and development of large areas of Africa.  One species of tsetse flies has been eradicated from parts of Nigeria and three species from parts of Burkina Faso using the SIT.
<P>Much more food would be available to people if harvested food were better preserved and protected against contamination and pests.  Preservation methods have evolved from sun drying to salting, smoking, canning, freezing, heating, and the addition of chemicals.  The latest addition to this list is the exposure of foods to carefully controlled amounts of ionizing radiation.
<P>All the research and testing have been made that is needed for a safe use of this method and all the necessary rules and regulations to irradiate certain foods have been adopted by the WHO and the FAO, but there is still public reluctance in many places over the acceptance of such foods.  This, we believe, will fade in due course.  In future food irradiation will certainly be of considerable use, not least to the developing countries.  It is potentially of great use and is at present really the only a viable method to eliminate health risks in some food.  It is particularly useful to disinfest stored products such as grain, beans, spices, fruit, and dried fish.
<P>Human health applications of nuclear techniques are doubtless well known to you.  One of particular interest to Africa is brachytherapy, which has become the method of choice for treatment of cancer of the cervix.  It is both relatively cheap and effective.  One of the first big projects of this kind in a developing country was organized in Egypt.  Trainees from various African countries have now learned this technique and introduced brachytherapy to the hospitals in their home countries.
<P>A final area of application I might mention is hydrology.  The problems where isotopes play an important role here include testing ground water for:
<P>Origin;<BR>Age;<BR>Distribution;<BR>
Water quality;<BR>Occurrence and recharge mechanisms; and<BR>Interconnections between groundwater bodies.
<P>They also permit testing surface water with regard to 
<P>Dynamics of lakes and reservoirs;<BR>Leakage through dams;<BR>Seepage to subways;<BR>
River discharge measurements; and<BR>Sedimentation rate.
<P>In the future, we may use nuclear generated heat to desalinate sea water.  This is a project which the IAEA is currently developing, and in which Libya and some other North African countries are showing special interest.
<H3>Nuclear power</H3>
I turn now to nuclear power.  There are today some 430 commercial nuclear power plants in operation.  Nuclear power provides about 5 percent of the world's energy and 16 percent of its electricity.  As I mentioned, some industrialized countries with scant energy reserves of their own have opted for nuclear as offering a measure of energy independence.
<P>There is another, and increasingly important reason for using the nuclear option and reducing our dependence on fossil fuels like coal, oil and gas.  That is the negative effects that their burning has on our planet's atmosphere:  acid rains and greenhouse effect.
<P>The use of coal and oil at current levels, and without abatement of sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxide, has led to severe damage to the environment and the atmosphere.
<P>While solutions exist for reducing these two emissions, albeit at substantial cost, we cannot see any for the carbon dioxide emissions that stem from the burning of all fossil fuels, most in coal, least in gas.  CO2 is considered to be responsible for 50 percent of the so called greenhouse effect.
<P>How are we to reduce CO2 emissions?  There is no viable way of neutralizing or removing the CO2.  Only less burning of the dominant part of the world's energy   fossil fuels   will reduce CO2 emissions.
<P>Most so called environmentalists feel conservation   meaning both a more efficient use of energy and less reliance on energy   and renewable sources of energy are the best answer.
<P>Everybody is for conservation and we need to pursue it vigorously everywhere because significant savings can be made.  However, we need to be realistic about what conservation is likely to achieve.  The World Energy Council calculates an increase of 50 75% in energy demand by 2020   even with vigorous energy conservation.  As to renewable sources of energy   solar power, wind power, geothermal power, etc.   the same Council calculates that they could give some 3% of the world's energy by 2020.  Today they yield less than 0.3%, most of which is geothermal.  I am not, of course, here including hydro.
<P>Nuclear energy has the advantage of releasing no C02, SO2 or NOx.
<P>If the scientific warnings remain firm that we need to reduce global CO2 emissions drastically to avoid a severe climate change, I predict we are in for an agonizing public debate in the l990s on how to achieve this.  Who will reduce CO2 emissions how much   and how?
<P>I do not suggest that nuclear power is the answer.  I am not even sure there is an answer.  But I would note that, if today's some 430 nuclear power stations were switched off, and were replaced by coal burning plants, global carbon dioxide emissions would rise annually by about nine percent.  This, I submit, is not an insignificant amount.
<P>A doubling of nuclear power would not remove the threat of global warming, but it would certainly alleviate the problem.  At a time when the scientists tell us that drastic targets are needed to stabilize or reduce the level of CO2, I submit it would not be responsible to brush the nuclear option aside.
<P>My own belief is that, even with conservation, more renewable energy sources and more nuclear power, the greenhouse effect will still be very difficult to bring under control.
<P>This is not just a problem for the industrialized world:  the burning of coal in the developing nations is set to rise substantially over the next ten years. Countries such as China and India plan to double or even treble their coal burning capacity to try to keep pace with their energy needs.  This would not reduce CO2.
 <P>Today, only a minority of developing countries can look to nuclear power as part of a solution to their urgent energy needs.  This advanced and demanding technology requires adequate local infrastructures, industrial support, trained personnel and much capital.  In a decade or two, conditions may have changed in a number of developing countries and there will in all likelihood also be new types of nuclear power reactors that are smaller, simpler to maintain and operate than the current types.  For their future energy needs, developing countries, especially those poor in hydropower and fossil fuels, have a great stake in the development of this new nuclear power technology   as well as of solar power and other techniques.  They also have a strong interest in the advanced countries' making use of advanced energy technologies so as to reduce the pressure on, and prices of, oil and gas resources.
<P><H3>Nuclear waste</H3>
<P>I should say a word about nuclear waste.  It is a common view that the disposal of radioactive waste is an unsolved problem.  The only sense in which this is true is that no disposal facilities for high level waste   as distinct from low and intermediate waste   have yet been built.  But this is not due to an inability to isolate such waste from the biosphere.  This is done through the construction of deep, multi barrier facilities in stable geological areas.  Nor is it due to any lack of international criteria on how to set about it.  It is due rather to two simple facts.  First, it is desirable to delay ultimate storage of high level waste   or unprocessed spent fuel   for 30 to 50 years to allow it to lose much of its heat and radioactivity before packaging and depositing it.  Secondly, there is the political problem of                                       
public acceptance of possible sites.  It is connected with our will, not to our ability.  It is sometimes stressed that nuclear waste may retain radioactivity for many thousands of years and that it is irresponsible vis à vis future generations to produce such waste.  The first answer is that it is possible safely to isolate the waste for these long periods.  The second point to make is that alternative fossil fuels   coal and oil   give rise to some waste products that remain hazardous forever.  And they are not isolated!
<P><H3>Nuclear law</H3>
<P>May I conclude by some comments on nuclear law.  Nuclear law is a newcomer in the national and international legal systems.  It is new because the object it regulates   the various uses of nuclear energy   is new.  It is rapidly growing, and it is important that all countries have lawyers who are familiar with it.  The purpose of this training course is precisely to boost knowledge of nuclear law in Africa.
<P>Almost every branch of law nowadays has a domestic part and an international part and these parts communicate a great deal.
<P>It is easily understandable that rules regarding the international transport of nuclear material need to be international.  
<P>It might be thought, on the other hand, that how a country regulates the safety and use of radioactive sources, say, in hospitals, would be exclusively a matter of domestic law.  Yet, we find strong tendencies to develop and use international standards as models.  This has great advantages.  World wide                                       
experience can be pooled and expertise can be available for the elaboration of guidelines or rules.  Standardization of rules worldwide gives confidence and facilitates operation.
<P>	Unlike aeroplanes that fly around the world, nuclear power plants sit firmly on the ground and again one might think that national rules and
measures would be enough.  However, we find that a large number of rules and measures are still needed at the international level.  Accidents must
be prevented everywhere, and the only way in which States can exercise influence outside their own borders is through joint international rules and
measures.  Reducing the transboundary impact of accidents   if any should occur   requires international preparedness.  Aspects of this international
regulation of nuclear energy, is what I shall discuss in the remainder of my address.
<P>The IAEA is the central instrument   but not the only instrument   through which States create an international framework within which nuclear
energy is used.  The working methods vary from simple international exchanges of views through meetings or publications to the working out of joint
recommendations or binding norms, the provision of services upon request and the conducting of obligatory inspections.
<H3>Safeguards</H3>
The safeguards system of the IAEA has existed for over 25 years.  Its purpose is to create confidence that civil nuclear installations and
nuclear material are only used for peaceful purposes.  States supplying nuclear technology, hardware or fuel want to be sure that there is no military
use of what they export.  Mere assurances do not suffice.  They require that inspection takes place.  Such inspection need by no means be seen by
the recipient State as an imposition.  This State may well, itself, have a strong interest to demonstrate to its own public opinion, to neighbouring States,
to the State from which it imports nuclear material and to the world at large, that it is using nuclear energy exclusively for peaceful purposes.
Inspection through an impartial international organization will give much greater confidence than any self inspection could do.  This, in simple terms, is
the background of the safeguards system.
<P>The IAEA's safeguards system at present employs some 200 inspectors who travel all around the world to inspect nuclear installations and
material.  Some 95% of all nuclear installations outside nuclear weapon States are inspected and the annual cost of the system is some US$ 60
million.
<P>During the seventies, the Agency safeguards system underwent a major transformation in character and scope.  The change was the result of
the "non proliferation regime";  that is, the set of treaties, legal norms and voluntary undertakings which were developed to deal with the peaceful uses
of nuclear energy and to prevent nuclear weapons proliferation.
<P>Let me mention the l967 Treaty for the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons in Latin America (the Tlatelolco Treaty), the l968 Treaty on the Non
Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (the NPT) and, more recently, the South Pacific Nuclear Weapon Free Zone Treaty (the Rarotonga Treaty).  All
these treaties require the application of safeguards by the Agency to all peaceful present and future nuclear activities in a State.  Thus, for the 137
non nuclear weapon States Party to the NPT, for the 23 States for which the Treaty of Tlatelolco is in force, all of which are also Parties to the NPT,
and for the nine Parties to the Rarotonga Treaty, IAEA safeguards have become obligatory in character and comprehensive in scope.  In some States
not parties to these treaties, there are installations not subject to safeguards.  This is   until now   the case of Argentina and Brazil, Israel, South Africa,
India and Pakistan.  However, South Africa recently opened talks with us on a comprehensive safeguards agreement, and Argentina and Brazil are
doing the same.
<P>By last year, the Agency safeguards system, including agreements concluded pursuant to treaty obligations and voluntary undertakings,
encompassed l72 safeguards agreements with l0l States and was applied to 922 facilities and locations throughout the world.
<P>The safeguards system is not an international nuclear police.  The inspectors cannot stop diversion of nuclear material.  Only report it.  The
same will be true, however, of inspection of disarmament measures.  The verification is a confidence building measure, not a policing.  This does not
mean, however, that inspection is without teeth.  Discovery of diversion would have serious consequences.  There would be a report to the Agency's
Board of Governors that would report further to the Security Council of the United Nations.  Even before such procedures take place, reactions would
probably have occured.  Indeed, even poor co operation by a State in safeguards may raise suspicions and lead to political and economic reactions.
<H3>Nuclear safety</H3>
Responsibility for the safe use of nuclear energy rests with the State within whose territory or under whose jurisdiction or control the nuclear
activity takes place.  States enact legislation that is designed to prohibit any activity making use of nuclear energy or radioactive materials without a
license, specify the safety norms to be observed in all such activities, provide for inspections to be made to ascertain whether there is compliance with
the requirements of the legislation and prescribe penalties for failure to observe the requirements of the Act.  A nuclear regulatory authority,
independent of the executive government, is usually charged with the implementation of this legislation and it is this authority, together with the plant
owner, which has to lead the efforts to achieve the excellence in safety which is imperative.
<P>The national regulatory structure in the area of safety is complemented by an international structure that consists of norm setting and service
mechanisms.  In addition there is a vast amount of exchange of experience.  Nuclear institutions learn from each other how best to maintain safety.
<P>Under its Statute the IAEA is empowered to establish or adopt standards of safety for the protection of health and the minimization of danger
to life and property.  The standards are not obligatory for Member States except in relation to Agency projects in a Member State.  Agency standards
are general in content but provide enough guidance to be used by national authorities, sometimes directly but more often with some additions of detail.
<P>The Agency's basic standards for radiation protection constitute one example.  They are the authoritative international translation of principles
and recommendations of the International Commission for Radiation Protection into practical standards and they have found very wide use.
<P>The Agency has developed many other safety standards.  Some examples may be given.
<P>The Agency's Regulations for the Safe Transport of Radioactive Material have been adopted as requirements for the transport of such
material by the competent international bodies for transport.  They are kept up to date and some l0 million packages are transported each year in
accordance with these regulations.
<P>Standards for the protection of nuclear material in domestic use, storage and transport against theft, have also been developed by the
Agency.  As a result of a revision made last year, these guidelines now also deal with the protection of nuclear facilities against sabotage.
<P>The Board of Governors of the IAEA has adopted a Code of Practice on the International Transboundary Movement of Radioactive Waste.
The Code prescribes that the movement of such waste should take place only when authorized by all States involved   that is "with the prior
notification and consent of the sending, receiving and transit States".  A further requirement is that all States involved should have the administrative
and technical capacity and the regulatory structure needed to fulfil their respective responsibilities.  The Code was worked out by an IAEA expert
working group
after complaints by African countries that toxic and nuclear waste was being dumped in the territories of developing countries.  While chemical waste
has been dumped, no case has, in fact, been identified of illicit transfer of radioactive waste.  Nevertheless, the existence of a code is important as a
preventive measure and to assure the public that the nuclear community is acting in a responsible manner.
<P>In addition to the recommendatory safety standards, there are a number of legally binding international conventions, concluded within the
framework of the IAEA and regulating various aspects of nuclear safety.
<P>The l979 Convention on Physical Protection establishes binding standards for the protection of nuclear material in international transport.  The
Convention, although legally binding, is narrower in scope than the Guidelines I mentioned earlier.  It does not deal with the protection of nuclear
facilities against sabotage.  An international conference is, however, to be convened in l992 to review the implementation and adequacy of the
Convention.
<P>The 1986 Convention on Early Notification of a Nuclear Accident was adopted after the Chernobyl accident and seeks to assure through a
notification procedure that any nuclear accident with possible transboundary effects be instantly brought to the attention of all so that they can take
protective measures.  The Convention does not formally cover military nuclear activities.  However, all nuclear weapon States have made a voluntary
commitment to apply the provisions to any accident involving releases not formally covered by the Convention.  To other States it obviously does not
matter if radioactive fall out is from peaceful or military sources.
 <P>The Chernobyl accident resulted in some radioactive fall out in large areas of Europe.  States established very different levels of radioactivity
above which foodstuffs would not be permitted on the market, so called intervention levels.  There could be differences of l00 times and more in levels
set by neighbouring States.  Needless to say this caused some confusion and undermined people's confidence in authorities.  Two years later the
Codex Alimentarius Commission of the FAO and WHO, using the IAEA's expertise and advice, agreed on contamination levels below which there
should be no concern for foodstuffs in international trade.  This is an example of a useful effort of standardization.
<P>The l986 Emergency Assistance Convention, likewise adopted after the Chernobyl accident, establishes an international framework to
facilitate prompt provision of assistance in the event of a nuclear accident or a radiological emergency.  States have undertaken to co operate in case
of a nuclear accident or radiological emergency in order to minimize its consequences and protect life, property and the environment.  The Emergency
Assistance Convention was invoked by Brazil in the radiological accident in Goiania in September l987.
<P>To fulfil its functions under the Convention on Early Notification and the Convention on Emergency Assistance, the IAEA has established an
emergency response system that is designed to ensure prompt communciation of information and co ordination of action.  We have tested the system
together with governments several times.
 <P>The mitigation of the consequences of an accident through prompt and adequate compensation is an important component of the regime for
the safe utilization of nuclear energy.  Today there exist two international conventions that regulate liability for nuclear damage.  The Vienna
Convention on Civil Liability for Nuclear Damage concluded under the auspices of the IAEA and the Paris Convention on Third Party Liability in the
Field of Nuclear Energy which was concluded in l960 within the framework of the OECD.
<P>The Chernobyl accident has made it clear that the existing liability system is not adequate to ensure equitable and rapid compensation,
particularly in the event of large scale damage.  This is because of its limited territorial application, its narrow definition of damage and the low level of
guaranteed compensation under it.
<P>New attention has therefore been devoted to the question of nuclear liability and over the last four years some progress has been made.  In
l988 a Joint Protocol linking the Vienna and Paris Conventions was concluded to expand the scope of their application.  Parties to the Vienna
Convention have also made a formal request for the revision of that Convention.  A revision conference will be convened to that purpose after the
necessary preparatory work has been completed.  As you know, work is also being carried out on the feasibility of establishing an additional system of
State liability to provide for interstate settlement of claims.
<H3>Conclusion</H3>
Summing up, society's regulation of the use of nuclear energy is a combination of national and international rules.  These have changed over
the years and may be expected to change in the future.
<P>The Agency has a central role in this process.  It collects and disseminates objective data and facts.  It provides a forum for discussion   and
for co ordination between States   also between international organizations such as CMEA, CEC and OECD.  It further offers a framework within which
standards and regulations are developed and expert services are provided.  The results that have been achieved by and through the Agency are
significant.  Safety is improving.  Technical solutions to waste disposal issues have been developed.  Radiation is better understood.  The non
proliferation regime has been gradually strengthened.  The key to this success,
of course, has been the extensive co operation among Agency Member States.
<P>There is now a mix of legally and non legally binding standards and rules.  However, some standards that were recently non binding have
today been transformed into binding commitments.  The new conventions in the area of Physical Protection, Notification and Emergency Assistance
are examples.  The fact that many regulations are still non binding should not be a matter for concern.  Many States have accepted such standards as
a basis for their national legislation.  The focus need not be on the formal character of the rule, but rather on the degree of compliance.
<P>Our societies must set the framework within which they accept that nuclear energy is used.  That framework must include guarantees that
peaceful nuclear installations are not misused for military purposes and verification that creates confidence.  It must include a combination of national
and international rules, arrangements and services to help ensure that nuclear installations are used safely all over the world and that the safety is
continuously strengthened.  The same high standards are required the world over regarding the management, transport and disposal of waste.
<P>I hope I have showed to you that we have come a long way to meet these conditions, that there is still work to be done and that the IAEA is a
useful instrument for the States of the world to create a solid, social framework for the use of nuclear energy.<HR>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B39-48</DOCNO>
