<TITLE>The revival of the nuclear power option</TITLE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The revival of the nuclear power option </H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by Hans Blix at the <BR>Neuntes Deutsches Atomrechts-Symposium</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Munich, Federal Republic of Germany</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>24 June 1991</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>
Let me tell you at the outset that I believe there will be a revival of the nuclear power option in the course of this decade.  The global demand for energy is going to increase despite ambitious and necessary efforts to generate and use energy more efficiently.  Commercial renewable sources of energy like solar power, wind power and biomass, will remain too expensive to be made use of for large scale contributions to our energy needs.  The real choice to meet substantial energy needs in an economically acceptable way in the next decade is between fossil fuels and nuclear power.  Both will continue to be used, but the mix may be modified.  Neither can be used at zero risk to life, health and the environment, but all the fossil fuels present the disadvantage of adding to the CO2 emissions into the atmosphere.  If the world concludes that these emissions must be reduced and at the same time demands more energy, there is at present no other CO2 free way than increasing nuclear power and   in some developing countries   hydropower.  The widespread uneasiness about nuclear power in the public will be met in two ways:  by continuous improvements in the safety, reliability and performance of nuclear power and by more information.  In my view, only another nuclear accident involving a large release of radioactivity will block this evolution.  Further international measures are necessary to ensure that nuclear safety is at a high level in all countries.
<P>Lawyers are an important group, accustomed to dispassionately
weighing arguments and evidence.  Not only their professional assistance but also their consideration of and judgement in the energy questions is desirable.
<P>Everybody will not share my conclusion about the future of nuclear power. I shall now develop my thoughts in greater detail and begin with a description of the current global situation of nuclear power which offers a very heterogeneous picture. In some countries the construction of nuclear power plants is stopped by public referenda.  This is true of Austria, Italy and Switzerland.  In others orders for new plants are politically out of the question for the time being without any referenda, e.g. the United Kingdom, Belgium, Spain.  In a number of countries where for various reasons opposition was not heard earlier, it is now articulate, e.g. the Soviet Union and Japan.  Active programmes for the expansion of nuclear power continue in the booming Far East:  South Korea, Japan and China and in India.  In Europe, France continues to construct nuclear power plants   though at a slower pace.  In the United Kingdom a pro nuclear government has placed further construction decisions on ice for a few years.
<P>More interesting, but more difficult, is to identify tendencies for the next few years.  The US government explicitly favours more nuclear power and is slowly trying to create an institutional climate in which the next generation of nuclear power plants can be ordered.  The Canadian government is similarly clearly favouring more nuclear power and is facing a public opinion that is relatively positive.  The Dutch government is still analyzing the conditions for a possible resumption of the nuclear power option.  The Finnish government is perhaps the one in Europe that is most actively considering                                       
further nuclear plants.  My own country, Sweden, is an interesting case.  A referendum in 1980 decided after the Three Mile Island accident that the country was to have the 12 reactors planned and no more.  When these had reached the end of their economic life   which Parliament decided would be in 2010   other sources of energy, preferably renewable indigenous ones, like biomass, would hopefully have been phased in.  After the Chernobyl accident the government decided that the phase out of nuclear power should start with the closure of two reactors in the middle of the nineties.  After much agony this plan was dropped by agreement between the government and two major opposition parties by the end of last year.  It is fair to say that this turnabout was caused by fears that more expensive alternative and CO2 
emitting gas generation of electricity would result in difficulties for Swedish industry and employment and by limited confidence in energy sources like biomass, solar and wind power.
<P>The case of Sweden may be instructive.  It would be wrong to say that the Swedish public has come to positively embrace nuclear power.  There would not today be a majority for the construction of additional plants.  But even to begin phasing out a nuclear programme that gives the country nearly half of its electricity, was also not acceptable.  It is tempting to conclude that a fully grown nuclear programme does not easily die, while fledgling ones can be knocked out   as the cases of Austria and Italy show.  Less is at stake economically in these cases.  It is increasingly realized in Sweden and elsewhere that renewable sources of energy and conservation are not going to offset the substantial needs of electricity that would arise from a phase out of nuclear power.  It is also understood that the realistic alternative sources for electricity generation will be found in fossil fuels, gas and coal.  These alternatives are not very attractive to a public increasingly concerned with CO2 emissions and global warming.
<P>The apparent inconsistency in the present mind of the public   no nuclear phase out, but also no new phase in   is not hard to understand.  Doubts about nuclear power come from concern about the safe operation of nuclear plants and the safe disposal of nuclear waste.  Doubts about the fossil fuels come from fears about increasing CO2 emissions and   in the case of gas and oil   energy independence and cost.  Doubts about commercial renewable sources of energy come from the fact that despite the enthusiastic support they have from some and a good deal of government subsidies, they still cover less than 0.5% of the world's energy   if hydropower is not counted.  The doubts about offsetting new power demand by conservation stems from the experience that electricity consumption is continuously going up despite increases in efficiency.
<P>It is a sad reality that the state of the public mind makes it very difficult for democratic governments in most countries to shape energy policies.  To emerge from this paralysis we need to make efforts of two kinds.  First, to further enlighten the public through facts and discussion.  Second, to further reduce the risk of nuclear accidents and to demonstrate that safe waste disposal installations can be built.
<P>In the International Atomic Energy Agency both pro nuclear and anti nuclear member governments support the Agency seeking and disseminating factual information and analysis and making efforts to strengthen safety.  Current examples of such activities are a recent expert symposium arranged in Helsinki by the Agency and ten other international organizations comparing the impacts upon life, health and the environment of different ways of generating electricity.  Another example is the large inquiry which we organized   again                                       
together with several other organizations, including the WHO and the CEC   about the radiological consequences of the Chernobyl accident for the population living in the most affected States.  A third example is an international project examining safety problems in the oldest type of 440MW(e) Soviet designed pressurized water reactors.
<P>Let me now turn to discuss in greater detail some facts that are relevant to my thesis that the nuclear power option needs to be revived.
<P>The global need for more energy in general and electricity in particular.
<P>A major driving force, of course, is the population development.  At the time of the birth of Christ there were some 350 million people on the Earth.  In 1900 we were 1.5 billion; in 1990 we were 5 billion and in the year 2000 we shall be over 6 billion.  Thus in the last ten years of this century we expect to increase about as much as in the 1900 years following the birth of Christ.  No environmental problems, I fear, can be meaningfully tackled without the world jointly addressing the population problem.  But even a very slowly growing world population will need more energy and we must not forget that the majority of the world's population live in countries where much more energy will be demanded, at least if there is to be development.  Taking electricity use as an example, I might mention that Bangladesh uses less than 100 kWh/capita and year, while Italy uses about 3500, France and Germany some 7000 and Norway some 25 000.  But for prohibitive pricing policies or rationing, demand for and use of more electricity will increase globally and nationally.  On this practically all expert assessments agree.
<P>Many switches to electricity from fossil fuels in end use are desirable because they may save primary energy, but also because they help to avoid pollution.  We have reasons to wish more electricity powered transport   trains, trams, tubes and trolley buses.  As a European I would wish to see the new Europe tied closer together by fast electric trains from East to West and North to South.  To lift us up to 10 000 metres in order to transport us even moderate distances is a method wasteful of energy and generous in emissions.  Cars, indeed, give us a dimension of freedom that is precious, but we should wish a speedy development of the electric car to avoid the automobile emissions that now add to local, regional and global environmental problems.
<P>If it is clear that more energy, particularly electricity, will be needed,
the question is how this energy will be generated.  The answer is most certainly that there will have to be a mix   as there is now.  Fossil fuels that now cover a little under 90% of the world's energy use are not going to be phased out.  Nor is hydro or nuclear power.  But are ageing coal  and oil fuelled electricity generating plants in industrially advanced countries to be replaced by new fossil fuelled plants   or by nuclear?  Or   conversely   are old nuclear power plants to be replaced by fossil fuelled plants?  In industrialized countries little hydro potential remains to be exploited and the commercial renewable sources of energy   e.g. biomass, solar and wind power   which now give less than 0.5% of the world's energy, mostly geothermal,
are not believed by experts to be able to offer more than 3 5% by 2010.  This leaves us in reality with the choice between fossil fuels and nuclear power for the foreseeable future.
<P>It is reasonable to suggest that the least developed countries should be enabled to use the least demanding technologies viz. the fossil based ones.  Indeed, we know that even some technologically advanced developing countries are planning to increase their use of coal.  China is to double its coal use by the year 2000 and India is planning to treble its use of coal by the same time.  The coal consumption of these two countries together would be greater than the consumption of all OECD States together.  There is no doubt that from the viewpoint of CO2 emissions and the risk of a greenhouse effect, an increased use of fossil based energy in developing countries would make an expanded use of nuclear power desirable in technologically advanced countries.  A speedy development of simpler and safer nuclear power reactors would be highly desirable to generate electricity especially for the fast growing cities in the poor countries.  It is expected that by the year 2000 there will be more than 15 cities with more than 10 million inhabitants in devloping countries.
<P>What I said a moment ago that the realistic energy choice boils down to one between fossil fuels and nuclear power is demonstrated by experiences in Europe.  Let me give you some examples.  Denmark, that rejects nuclear power, is often cited as a country with an ambitious wind power programme, but only a percent or two of the Danish electricity originates in wind power, while the capacity of coal generated power stations has been allowed to expand fast and covers some 95% of the Danish electricity generation.  In Austria a nuclear power station of 725 MW(e) was mothballed after a referendum.  A 725 MW(e) coal generated plant was built instead.  In Belgium the request of industry to build another nuclear plant a few years ago was rejected by the government.  The alternative proved to be gas.  And gas on a large scale would also have been the replacement for Swedish nuclear power, if a phasing out would have started in the middle of the nineties.  For Finland the choice at the present moment seems to be nuclear or coal.
<P>What is there to say about this choice from the viewpoints of economy, security, environment and safety?
<P>In terms of economics, there is today not much difference between nuclear power and coal generated electricity.  But in the long term nuclear power should present significant advantages.  The potential for reducing the production costs of nuclear power is still large.  Standardization of construction, serial fabrication of main components, improved efficiency of load following systems are examples.  On the other hand, the coal burning techniques appear to reach the limit of industrial improvements and modifications imposed for environmental reasons could add to the production costs.
<P>Assumptions regarding discount rates, number of years for construction have a heavy influence on cost calculations.  Since privately owned utilities in several countries wish to build more nuclear power plants and it may be assumed that they do not wish to lose money, they must be expecting that they can generate electricity by nuclear power at a profit.  It is expected that at current prices gas is going to look attractive for electricity generation in several countries.  Since the environmental impact of the burning of gas is much less than the impact of burning of coal, gas will very likely be chosen in places where resistance to nuclear power is strong.  In the longer term and with greater consumption a question mark would attach to the price of gas, while the price of uranium can be expected to remain low even with a much increased number of reactors.
<P>There are several kinds of security to discuss in relation to energy.  One is security of supply.  Perhaps coal offers the greatest security of supply, there being many different suppliers and an ample supply available.  To be at the end of a gas pipeline offers much greater supply risks.  As to oil, a nervous world was reminded during the Gulf crisis that both price and availability depend too much on the political conditions in a volatile part of the world.
<P>The risk of supply that exists for nuclear power hardly relates to uranium which is in ample supply from many different regions and countries, like Australia, Canada, Namibia, Niger, China, USSR.  The number of States able to supply enrichment services was for a long time very limited.  This is no longer true.  The energy density of uranium is also such that a utility can store fuel for several years' use and, thereby, acquire very substantial energy independence   even without an indigenous supply of uranium and enrichment services.  A 1000 MW(e) nuclear plant consumes about 80 kg of uranium per day. A coal fired plant of the same capacity uses about 7000 tons of coal per day   i.e. about five train loads.  It goes without saying that the coal plant is dependent upon a well functioning vast transport apparatus.
<P>We can also speak of security of operation, in the sense of reliability.  Available statistics do not point to more frequent or longer stoppages in nuclear plants than in fossil fuelled plants, though one might get such an impression from media that are inclined to report all nuclear stoppages and ignore those in coal  or oil fired plants.
<P>Another security aspect relates to physical protection of plants.  Opponents of nuclear power used to maintain that nuclear power required so much police protection that it was incompatible with democracy.  However, democracy seems to survive in many countries with nuclear power.  It is somewhat of a paradox that it is precisely those who pretend they worry about the democracy, that are likely to try to stop nuclear activities which have been properly authorized by the democratic society.
<P>One cannot completely rule out the risk that terrorists could try to occupy a nuclear plant, although fortunately it has not happened so far.  If they were not experts the chances are that their actions would only achieve automatic stoppages.  It must be recognized, however, that modern society is vulnerable to many other risks from terrorists.  None can be ignored, but I shall refrain from offering a check list.
<P>Reference is sometimes made to the risk that nuclear power plants present in time of war.  It cannot be ignored or denied, but if we think of war, it seems more justified to look first at the risk of some 60 000 nuclear warheads.  In the region of the Persian Gulf nuclear reactors have been bombed three times.  Twice there was no nuclear fuel present:  when Israel bombed a big research reactor in Iraq in 1981 and when Iraq sent rockets on Iranian power reactors under construction during the Iraq Iran war.  Only the American action during the recent UN operation against Iraq involved the bombing of two smaller research reactors containing nuclear fuel.  Fortunately, as IAEA inspection has found, the fuel was not damaged and no radiation hazard arose.
<P>The bombing of coal mines is not likely to pose a great war hazard, but as we all know the burning of oil wells can cause grave damage, and attacks on gas cisterns or big hydro dams may have devastating consequences.
<P>Perhaps it should also be recalled that one major reason why the Middle East is such an explosive region is that it holds a large part of the world's oil reserves.  Violence and wars are linked to oil resources, not to the well spread uranium resources of the world.
<P>It is often alleged that nuclear power increases the risk of a spread of nuclear weapons to further countries.  As is well known President Kennedy prophesized about a world with dozens of nuclear weapon States.  This fear has not materialized, but the risk of proliferation cannot be ignored   least of all these days.
<P>I shall make some comments on Iraq in a moment, but I would like first to note that the risk of some country developing a nuclear weapon capacity exists regardless of whether it has civilian nuclear power.  All the five recognized nuclear weapon States developed weapons first   nuclear power second.  And Israel, which many believe have developed nuclear weapons, does not have any nuclear power.
<P>It cannot be completely excluded that a State could try to make use of a nuclear power programme to hide a weapons programme.  However, not even the dismantling of all peaceful nuclear power in the world would be a guarantee against development of a nuclear weapon by a State which was determined to have one.  The nuclear genie has been out of the bottle for a long while.
<P>The non proliferation regime, verified by IAEA safeguards, is not a police
power that can stop nuclear activities in a State.  But States which pledge themselves not to acquire nuclear weapons and promise to hold all their nuclear material, present or future, available for inspection, open themselves for considerable control.  A misuse of the verified programmes could not be physically stopped by inspectors but would be reported.  The Security Council and individual States would react to such reports by different means.  In the case of Iraq the suspicion of a clandestine weapons programme led the United States to bomb nuclear installations in Iraq during the UN sanctioned action.<HR>
</DOC>
<DOC>
