<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE>STATEMENT BY THE DIRECTOR GENERAL TO THE INFORMAL MEETING OF MEMBER STATES</TITLE>
<BODY>
<H3 ALIGN =CENTER>STATEMENT BY THE DIRECTOR GENERAL TO THE INFORMAL MEETING OF MEMBER STATES
ON PROGRAMME AND BUDGET FOR 1991- 92 </H3>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Vienna,Austria</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>19 February 1990</H4>
<P> 
<HR>    
<P>
In my statement to the Board a year ago, I indicated that the work on
formulating the 1991- 92 programme and budget would take place in three stages:
<P><UL>
<LI>(i)  Assessment of trends in the nuclear field and an outline of the proposed programme   July 1989;
<LI>(ii)  Preparation of the revised outline of the programme and initial budget estimates    October 1989;
<LI>(iii)  Preparation of the detailed programme and a draft budget January 1990;
</UL>
<P>With some delays the above information was distributed to Missions, and that related to the first two stages was the subject of active consultations. We are now in the middle of consultations on the detailed programme and budget, of which today's meeting is an important element.  The documentation distributed in the second and third stages also contained information on changes introduced in the content of the programme and budget in response to
the .
<P>The documentation made available to you so far contains ample information both on general aspects of the programme   for example, changes in comparison with 1989 - 90 and the identification of problems and their priority ranking as well as a detailed list of tasks planned for implementation during 1991 - 92.  Detailed budget figures for both 1991 and 1992 have also been provided.  There seems to be no need for me to go into details on the programme and budget today.  As on previous occasions we are ready to provide you with any explanations or additional information requested either in the course of this meeting or later.
<P>I would like to make some general observations concerning the budget. The initial budget estimates made in October last year indicated that our needs exceeded the 1990 level by US $6.4 million, which is 4.1% in real terms.  This growth was mainly the result of growing needs in the area of "Safeguards" and '"Direction and Support"", which were explained both in the documents distributed and at the briefing meetings.  Almost no further budget growth was planned for 1992.  Being aware of potential reservations that many countries might have regarding such growth in the budget, in my paper of 7 November 1989 I put forward the idea of seeking voluntary contributions which would be earmarked for specific activities or equipment and which would reduce the level of Regular Budget funds needed.  Specific activities that could be financed from such voluntary contributions were suggested in the paper of 7 November.  In the responses received from groups of Member States no specific offer of voluntary contributions was made.  Rather" I was given to understand that the overall level of the Regular Budget in real terms for 1991 should remain at the 1990 level.
In my Note of 2 February 1990 I explained the reasons for my concern in this connection.  As it was not possible to achieve zero real growth in the budget for 1991 by introducing economy measures, cuts in the substance of the programme were necessary.  I considered it important, for the sake of transparency in the programme budget process, to explain which activities had been reduced as a result of budget reductions.  These are shown in Annex B to my Note.  It should be pointed out that a substantial part of these reductions was achieved through the proposed postponement to 1992 of part of actions originally planned for 1991.
<P>In the light of the information on how the 1991 budget was reduced practically to the zero growth level, Member States may wish to revert to the idea of providing the Agency with some additional resources either through voluntary contributions or by agreeing that, by rearranging the time scale of certain activities, the higher budget increase now planned for 1992 would be effected partly in 1991.
<P>One final point, Mr. Chairman.  In the paper outlining the safeguards programme distributed with my Note of 31 July 1989, information was provided on a number of options for expanding the level of safeguards in nuclear weapon States.  The option with the smallest budget implications would be to receive and to store in the safeguards data base information on the status of and changes in nuclear material in all peaceful nuclear facilities in nuclear weapon States.  The annual cost of so doing would be US $l50,000.
<P>In the absence of comments by governments urging this action we have however, refrained from adding even this amount to the Budget.<HR>
</BODY>
