<HTML>
<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE>STATEMENT AT THE WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM </TITLE>
<BODY>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>STATEMENT AT THE WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM </H3>
<H4 ALIGN =CENTER>Hans Blix<BR>
Director General<BR>
International Atomic Energy Agency</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Davos,Switzerland</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>5 February 1990</H4>
<P><HR>Last summer the participants in the Paris summit declared:<BR>
"We recognize that nuclear power [also] plays an important role in limiting the output of greenhouse gases".
<P>A few months later many environment ministers met in the Netherlands to discuss climate change. Although they could not reach agreement on a specific target for reductions in C02 emissions, they urged energy conservation and the promotion of renewable sources of energy as means of restraining CO2 emissions. Only one of the participating ministers mentioned nuclear power. He warned against any use of it.
<P>I relate this to illustrate how negative or mute most of the present leaders in the field of environment are in the question of use of nuclear power   even though they are desperately looking for energy systems that reduce CO2 emissions.
<P>And yet, the reality is that 17% of the world's electricity is generated by nuclear power today without adding any CO2 to our atmosphere. If this electricity had been generated instead by the burning of coal, about 1800 M.t. of CO2 would have been added to the 20,000 M.t. that already go into the atmosphere from the burning of fossil fuels. An increase of 9%.
 I am not going to suggest to you that an expanded use of nuclear power is a panacea for global warming, nor that it is without some problems, but I do submit that if we are serious about limiting CO2 emissions, we cannot afford to do without an expanded use of nuclear power in the world's energy mix.
<P>Conservation and greater energy efficiency can help us over time to avoid a good deal of CO2 but such measures are not likely to do more than partly offset increased demand. Indeed, according to the World Energy Conference the world's primary energy consumption is likely to increase by 50 75% between 1985 and 2020. Actual trends are clearly towards the use of more fossil fuels. Not long ago Belgium opted for a gas fuelled power plant rather than a nuclear one. Sweden seems intent to phase in gas and phase out nuclear. China, even though aiming for a 40% improvement in efficiency of energy use during the 1990s, plans to double its coal production between 1985 and 2000. India plans to treble its coal use over the same period. All this will increase CO2 emissions   not reduce them. Who could reproach China and India? The current per capita CO2 emission is 2 tons per year in China and 0.9 tons in India. This compares, for instance, with 12.3 tons in the US and 10.5 tons in the FRG. Suggestions that energy hungry developing countries like China and India should freeze their CO2 emissions at current low levels are hardly realistic. Stepped up technological and economic assistance to them to promote nuclear expansion, energy efficiency and the use of renewables could limit the increase in their use of fossil fuels, but they will most certainly and not unreasonably insist that the greatest emitters of CO2, the industrialized countries, reduce their CO2 emissions.<BR>
 Renewable sources   solar, wind, commercial biomass and geothermal power   today provide less than 0.3% of the OECD countries' energy. According to Mrs. Steeg, the head of the International Energy Agency, these sources might give a maximum of 5% of the OECD countries' energy in 2010. The World Energy Conference suggests an even lower figure: 3% for the whole world by 2020.
<P>Suggesting that we can reduce the world's CO2 emissions by conservation, energy efficiency and a greater use of renewables alone is in my view trying to take us to the greenhouse through the dreamhouse!
<P>Nuclear power, as I said, is already helping us to avoid significant volumes of CO2 emissions and a strong expansion could help us to avoid even more. We have the industrial capacity for it. An annual start up of between 40 and 60 new nuclear power plants as from 2001 would be possible. If we did, nuclear power would cover some 25% of the electricity consumption we expect by 2010, avoiding 17 20% of the CO2 emissions which would have resulted from an alternative reliance on coal. The supply of uranium is no problem for a nuclear power expansion of this dimension   even without recourse to breeder
reactors.
<P>What are the objections to nuclear power? I shall start with the issue of waste.
<P>Disposal of radioactive waste is sometimes spoken of as if it were an unsolved technical problem. This is not so. There are no insuperable scientific or technological problems in the commonly accepted multi barrier
 concepts for disposal deep underground. The problems which do exist are of a different kind, namely those of public acceptance of disposal sites. It is somewhat like the siting of airports. Most people want to fly but no one wants an airport in his neighbourhood.
<P>I turn now to the question of safety . No energy generation is without some risk and being without energy has also some negative consequences. The risks of using nuclear power are not zero but they must be compared to the risks which we run in using other methods of generating the desired energy. The number of dead from Chernobyl   31   must be compared with casualty figures from coal mines, oil platforms, gas explosions and hydrodam bursts. The size of the exclusion zone around Chernobyl should be compared with forests that are severely damaged or destroyed as a result of acid rain. The additional risk of cancer cases from Chernobyl fallout can also be compared with similar risks from other industrial activities, including energy generation. Perhaps such comparisons can also help us to somewhat demystify nuclear energy!
<P>This being said, we need also to further strengthen the safety of operating nuclear power plants so that no plants are trailing behind in safety. International co operation to achieve this is underway. I should add that the new nuclear power plants that are coming on the market in the 90s and beyond will be simpler to operate and the aim will be to give them such safety features that no evacuation plans will have to be drawn up.
 One final point. Nuclear opponents often claim that nuclear power increases the risk that more countries will acquire nuclear weapons. In reality the risk of proliferation exists whether or not we expand nuclear power, and it would not disappear even if we were to close all the world's power reactors. It deserves to be known, however, that the IAEA inspects and verifies the exclusively peaceful use of 95% of all nuclear installations outside nuclear weapon States. In the present hopeful climate for disarmament one might even dare to hope that we shall one day safeguard all nuclear installations outside nuclear weapon States.<HR>
 </BODY>
 </HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B39-57</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA059-000320-B038-3</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://nesihp01.iaea.or.at:80/worldatom/inforesource/dgspeeches/dgsp1990n04.html 193.81.60.210 19970114203120 text/html 30577
