</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE> Nuclear Safety, Environment and Non Proliferation</TITLE>
<BODY>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Nuclear Safety, Environment and Non Proliferation</H3>  
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Hans Blix<BR>Director General<BR>Intemational Atomic Energy Agency</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN =CENTER>Die Osterreichische Gesellschaft<BR>fur Aussenpolitik und Internationale Beziehungen<BR>
(Austrian Society for Foreign Affairs and International Relations)<BR>und
Die Osterreichische Liga fur die Vereinte Nationen<BR>(Austrian League for the United Nations)<BR>
Vienna, Austria</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Thursday, 8 March 1990</H4>     
<P><HR>
<P>
The subjects of this presentation are all very much in the public mind. First: the safety of nuclear power installations is now being discussed intensely in Eastern Europe and measures to strengthen safety can be expected. Second: there is a great worry that enormous CO2 emissions which result from the burning of fossil fuels contribute a major part of the so called greenhouse effect. Third: in August this year, the third review conference of the Non Proliferation Treaty, or NPT, will start in Geneva, and in 1995 a conference will decide whether the Treaty is to be prolonged for one or more fixed periods or indefinitely.
<P>There are important links between these three topics. Energy generation through nuclear power has great advantages from the environmental point of view as it does not give rise to any S02, NOx or CO2 and thus does not contribute to acid rains, dying forests or the greenhouse effect. This assumes, however, that the level of nuclear safety is high. An accident of the Chernobyl type, as we know, has severe health and environmental impacts. A wider transfer of nuclear technology to generate power without severe environmental consequences also requires that full guarantees exist against proliferation.
<P>The premise which I start from, namely that there is a need for more energy, is not universally accepted, and I must discuss the objections to it. Environmentalist constituencies the world over try to persuade us that we can meet the threat of global warming simply by using less fossil fuels    conservation  and by using more renewable sources of energy. While it is not hard to accept the tenet that the least polluting energy source is the one you don't use, one must examine the social cost attached to scarcity of energy and one must also realistically examine how much energy we can save.
<P>Energy is the lifeblood of our societies. An enormous increase in the use of oil, coal, gas and hydropower has been a major means of raising the standard of living in a few countries to unprecedented levels. There is a clear relationship between the level
 of economic development and energy consumption. The average North American uses 7200 kg of oil equivalent per year and the average Chinese uses 590 kg, and the average Indian has to make do with 280 kg of oil equivalent (of commercial energy). Even after the oil shocks, the OECD countries with one sixth of the world's population consume almost one half of the world's primary energy. Not surprisingly, the developing countries are trying to expand their energy generation as fast as they can    chiefly with fossil fuels. But industrialized countries, too, are expanding their energy use, especially their electricity use. For Austria, for instance, an increase of 25% in electricity use is forecast between 1987 and 2000.
<P>We are not without experience of what energy conservation can achieve. After the oil price shocks a more efficient use of energy allowed continued economic growth in industrialized countries without increased use of primary energy. The use of electricity increased, however. There undoubtedly still remains considerable potential for energy saving. To take but one example, future cars will certainly get more kilometers per liter of petrol than the present generation. Getting the car owners to drive fewer kilometers is a much more difficult proposition. The World Energy Conference, which met last September in Montreal, fully recognized the importance of energy conservation, but it warned at the same time that    I quote   "few subjects have been or are the object of as much wishful thinking".
<P>It may be predicted that    despite conservation efforts and barring some dramatic developments including drastic actions by governments  the global demand for more energy, particularly electricity, will increase in the future. The World Energy Conference last September published a scenario which suggests a global energy consumption 50 to 75% higher in 2020 than today  even with strong energy conservation measures.
<P>Let me turn now to the scope for an expanded use of renewable energy sources as a means of avoiding CO2 emissions. If you except hydro power, these sources now contribute about 0.1% of the global energy supply  and a major part of that is geothermal energy. As to solar power, there have been promising developments in photovoltaic cells. They are of use in satellites, isolated locations e.g., in the mountains, and in watches, calculators, etc., where cost is not so important. Solar cells are still not viable for large scale electricity generation. I might mention that to provide the same amount of electric energy as a 1000 MW(e) power station, some 90 square kilometers would need to be covered by solar cells.
<P>There exists long experience with wind generators. In California alone, there are some 15,000 wind generators now in operation. It would take at least 13,000 wind generators of 200 kW capacity each to provide the same electric energy as a 1000 MW(e) thermal power station (with 80% load factor). The surface area needed would be of the order of 100 square kilometers. Wind power can hardly be expected to become viable for large scale electricity generation.
<P>Much work is needed to reduce the costs of solar and wind generators if they are ever to become generally economically competitive. Mrs. Helga Steeg, Director General of the International Energy Agency in Paris, recently stated that "the contribution of renewable energies, besides hydro power, in most of the IEA countries [i.e. most of the Western industrialized countries] for the year 2010 can be estimated to be a
 maximum of SO2. The World Energy Conference was even more pessimistic: it suggested 3% by 2020. This does not negate the fact that these energy forms can be very important in specific regions or situations. Nor do present modest results suggest that research and development funds should be withheld for these energy sources. But they do suggest that it would be irresponsible to count on major global contributions from energy systems that have so far not turned out to be viable on a large scale. To suggest that they can replace fossil fired plants to any major extent during the next decades is as unrealistic today as it was when similar forecasts were being made ten years ago.
<P>My conclusion is that, although there may be a significant potential for saving both primary energy and electricity, especially in high consumption countries, this will not be enough to offset the increasing global energy demand which we can expect in the near and intermediate future. We will also not be able to meet this demand with renewable energy sources alone. The reality is that fossil fuels, nuclear power and    where available  hydropower are the sources we can turn to.
<P>As I mentioned, however, a further expanded use of fossil fuels raises the problem of CO2 emissions. While the SO2 and NOx emissions from fossil fuels are linked to local and regional environmental problems of acidification and Waldsterben, the greenhouse gases, including CO2, confront us with the global environmental problem of a warming atmosphere. Already in 1988, a conference in Toronto with scientists and politicians recommended a reduction by 20% in CO2 emissions by 2005. While there has since been much talk about a convention against climate change, there are so far no international commitments to reductions in CO2 emissions. The outlook is rather for increased emission.
<P>It is calculated that 50% of the greenhouse effect is caused by CO2, about 15% by CFCs and 20% by methane. The CFCs are being phased out as they are also thought to be destructive of the ozone layer. Methane reductions are hard to achieve.
<P>The additions to the atmospheric content of CO2 come mainly from our use of fossil fuels. The present emissions from these sources are some 20,000 million tons per year. An estimated additional 5,000 million tons per year come from the destruction of tropical rain forests.
<P>Since there is no economically viable way in which CO2 can be eliminated in the combustion of fossil fuels, any action to reduce CO2 emissions would have to involve limitations on the use of fossil fuels or a shift between them. The burning of oil produces less CO2 than coal per unit of heat generated. Natural gas is even more advantageous from this point of view.
<P>Afforestation would certainly be beneficial, and should be pushed with vigour. However, we must be aware that its effects would be slow and it would necessarily involve vast surface areas. Just to compensate for the present rate of deforestation in the world, it would be necessary to replant an area of the order of half of France every year.
<P>It is clear that we can hope to reduce or contain global CO2 emissions only through international action and that at least one of these actions will have to involve limiting
 the burning of fossil fuels. Such a limitation will raise formidable political problems and severely tax the solidarity of States.
<P>A switch from coal or oil to natural gas is helpful as the CO2 ernissions from the combustion of natural gas are much lower per thermal unit produced than from coal or from oil. It is likely that natural gas will be increasingly relied on for some decades to come in several countries. It does not produce any SO2, but apart from the CO2, it does produce NOx. Greater use of natural gas would meet some environmental concerns, and for some time it is likely to be available in large quantities in a number of areas. One can, of course, query whether it is rational to burn up what is also a clean and valuable industrial raw material, but that consideration may not weigh very heavily when the demand for energy becomes pressing.
<P>What about the use of nuclear power? Can it be of significance in the world's efforts to limit CO2 emissions? Some facts may be of interest: In 1988, which is the last year for which we have complete statistics, nuclear power worldwide produced 1800 TWh of electric energy. If that had instead been produced by coal fired power plants, which would have been the economically competitive alternative, it would have meant a 9% increase in the CO2 emissions resulting from the worldwide burning of fossil fuels (or 1800 Mt CO2).
<P>Some twenty five percent of the world's total CO2 emissions come from electricity generating stations. In the United Kingdom, where only 20% of the electricity comes from nuclear stations, the average CO2 emission per kWh produced was 0.78 kg. In France, where nuclear plants generate 70% of the electricity, the corresponding figure was 0.09 kg. In Sweden, with electricity generated almost exclusively by hydro or nuclear plants, the average kWh gave rise to only 0.03 kg of CO2. This gives a perspective not only on what can be achieved, but also on the potential problems in negotiating a convention to reduce CO2 emissions worldwide.
<P>The industrial capacity to build more nuclear power plants exists. An annual start up of between 40 and 60 new nuclear power plants as from 2001 would be possible. If we did this, nuclear power would cover some 25% of the electricity consumption we expect by 2010, avoiding 17 20% of the CO2 emissions which would have resulted from an alternative reliance on coal. The supply of uranium is no problem for a nuclear power expansion of this dimension  even without recourse to breeder reactors.
<P>I submit to you that the sooner we face up to the reality, the better the chances are for energy policies to meet the threat of global warming. An international convention committing the world's governments to maximum energy conservation, reforestation and an expanded use of renewable sources of energy is desirable, but is not enough. The world will not only need to keep the nuclear power capacity which exists, but also to considerably expand it. That this will actually happen is by no means a foregone conclusion, however. It requires above all that no accidents with significant radioactive releases occur. It may also require a gradual demystification of nuclear energy. It probably also requires that nuclear weapons lose some of their prominence.
<P>Nuclear power today provides some 17% of the world's electricity and 5% of its primary energy. This is just a few percent less than hydroelectric power. The importance
 of nuclear power is, however, very different in different countries. France is the world leader with 70% of its electricity coming from nuclear power, which means in practice that oil has been fully replaced by nuclear power for electricity generation in France. Through its large nuclear power capacity, France now generates more electricity than it needs itself, and exports electricity valued at more than $1 billion per year to its neighbours. Belgium gets 65% of its electricity from nuclear plants, South Korea 50%, and Sweden 45%. There are now 11 countries which get more than 30% of their electric energy from nuclear power. Of the Eastern European countries, Hungary at present has the highest fraction of nuclear generated electricity    49%.
<P>There is at present considerable doubt about the future of nuclear power, even among the big users of it. In Sweden, the phasing out of nuclear power by 2010 has been decided upon by Parliament. In Italy even the existing nuclear plants are no longer in use following a referendum. Switzerland, the Federal Republic of Germany, Belgium and the Netherlands have a de facto moratorium on new plants. Several countries like Austria, Denmark and Ireland have renounced nuclear power entirely, even though they need more electricity generating capacity. In the USA, no plant has been ordered since the middle of the 1970s and no new orders are expected for several years, despite the fact that there is a need for new generating capacity. In the UK, the recent decision about privatization appears to make nuclear power uneconomic through the very special conditions imposed. Against these trends, I may mention that nuclear programmes continue to grow in a few countries, notably France, Japan and Eastern Europe.
<P>The Chernobyl accident had a serious effect on public opinion everywhere, above all in the Soviet Union itself and the countries of Eastern Europe. The Soviet Union closed two nuclear plants in Armenia after the earthquake there. It also stopped construction on several plants, and abandoned plans to use a number of sites for nuclear plants. Although a considerable antinuclear opinion is now visible and audible in the USSR, as in most industrialized countries, the Soviet Government still plans to expand its nuclear power plant capacity. There are nuclear power plants in operation or under construction in almost every one of the East European countries, but here, too, opposition grows with glasnost. Two older plants have recently been shut down in the GDR. Environmentalist opinion seems to be somewhat divided in East Europe between the traditional categorical green rejection of nuclear power and the opinion that the alternative use of coal is worse.
<P>The main arguments against nuclear power are well known. They relate to safety, waste and non proliferation. Let me first discuss safety. The TMI and especially the Chernobyl accident raised interest in creating some international guarantees of nuclear power safety. There have been demands for the adoption of binding international safety rules and inspection of their implementation. However, the reactions to these demands have shown that governments are not at present ready to subject their nuclear installations to binding international rules on safety or to obligatory international safety inspections. The international safety regime that is developing so far is more subtle. It offers models for national safety regulations and international missions of assistance, support and advice to plant operators and regulators.
<P>Already in the early 1970s, the IAEA served as an instrument for building an international consensus on safety standards and practices. The Agency's basic standards
 for radiation protection have been used in many countries around the world as the basis for national protection standards. As the Agency looks for scientific guidance in these matters to the International Commission for Radiological Protection, we are now carefully following the probable conclusions of the Commission to the effect that dose limits for workers in nuclear facilities should be set even stricter than they are now. We also note the recent statistical study in England which seems to couple leukemia in some children in Sellafield to radiation doses incurred by their fathers. A first reaction is that for the ten cases concerned, the doses were fairly high and at a level which would be rare in the industry today. It is also difficult to explain why a similar occurrence of leukemia has not been found among the children whose fathers incurred radiation doses from the Hiroshima bomb. This, I think, is all that I can say on the subject at the present time. The Nuclear Safety Standards Programme -- the so called NUSS programme -- produced five Codes of Practice covering the essential safety aspects of governmental organization, siting, design, operation and quality assurance. The Codes were supplemented by 56 Safety Guides recommending how these safety requirements could be implemented. We recently revised the Codes to reflect current thinking and experience gained in accident prevention and management.
<P>Member States have used the Codes extensively to elaborate national regulations. To take an important example, China, with its emerging nuclear power programme, has adopted the NUSS standards as the basis for its national regulatory requirements. Several Member States have directly adopted the Code for quality assurance.
<P>While standards and regulations are indispensable to ensure nuclear safety, equal attention must be paid to operational safety in the some 430 nuclear power plants which are now operating in the world and the 100 or so plants which will soon be put into operation. To assist its Member States in this regard, the Agency is offering several services which are being increasingly used.
<P>Firstly, Operational Safety Review Teams (OSARTs) are sent to a nuclear power plant in response to requests. The teams are composed of experts from both the Agency and Member States and their reviews are certainly not cosmetic. Over a period of several weeks they thoroughly review plant operations management and procedures. Since Chernobyl the reports of most of the some 30 OSARTs which the Agency has performed have been published by the authority which requested the OSART, in order to inform the public. Industrialized countries pay the full cost of such visits; developing countries pay all local expenses.
<P>Secondly, the Agency offers expert teams (ASSETs) to help a nuclear plant operator assess safety significant events and define the real root causes.
<P>The changes which have been taking place with such breathtaking pace in Eastern European countries have also brought with them a new openness as regards the safety of the nuclear power plants operating there. A group of safety experts in the CMEA (Comecon) countries have expressed reservations about the safety of the early 440 MW(e) PWR plants. Four such plants are operating in the Soviet Union, four in the German Democratic Republic, four in Bulgaria and two in the CSSR at Bohunice. Backfitting of safety related equipment has been recommended. This position has been supported in general terms by a report issued by safety experts from the Federal
 Republic of Germany after a review of the four PWR units of early design at Greifswald in the German Democratic Republic. An ASSET mission which the IAEA sent to Greifswald last month to examine past accidents and incidents in the plant recommended several improvements in the operational safety procedures of the plant.
<P>There is now a very rapid increase in the demand for Agency safety support services from the Eastern European countries In the Soviet Union we have undertaken safety reviews at the Ignalina, Rovno and the future Gorki plants, and we are now starting a review of the radiation protection measures taken or planned in the Ukraine and Byelorussia after the Chernobyl accident. The situation in Byelorussia has received a great deal of attention recently and I hope that the review we are undertaking will be as authoritative and enlightening as the inquiry which the Agency made about the technical causes of the accident.
<P>Czechoslovakia has requested an Operational Safety Review mission to the Dukovany plant and a pre operational safety review of Temelin. We have carried out an Operational Safety Review mission to the Paks plant in Hungary and a pre operational review in Poland. Those reviews which have been carried out have generally found good competence in the staff, but many recommendations for improvements have been made. Reviews have so far mostly had regard to operational safety. Future requests may also relate to the safety aspects of plant design.
<P>So much for international action related to safety at existing nuclear power plants. What about the future plants which are supposed to be safer and more tolerant of human errors than the ones which were subject to accidents at TMI and Chernobyl?
<P>I must preface my remarks about future reactors with the comment that today's nuclear power reactors are designed to tolerate a great deal of human error. Their safety systems have much built in redundancy. Moreover, they rely on decades of proven technology and engineering practices reflecting the high standards and strict regulations of the nuclear industry. In the TMI accident, the containment worked in spite of several operator errors. The accident at Chernobyl occurred because several safety systems had in fact been deliberately switched off. A strengthened safety system which has been introduced for that reactor type now makes it harder to do so.
<P>The industry now seems ready to present advanced versions of the currently most common reactor types, with standardized and simpler design, more "passive" safety features and often smaller sizes. Through lower total capital costs these reactors could help to improve the management of investment risks. Such features might also make them interesting for some developing countries.
<P>I do not propose to discuss the question of nuclear waste at length. Contrary to common belief, there is no lack of technical ability to construct facilities in which the waste will be safely stored for thousands of years. The difficulties are rather that public and political organs are unwilling to consent to the use of any possible sites. Dr. Herbert Kouts, chairman of the IAEA's International Nuclear Safety Advisory Group, summed up the situation when he said, I quote, "The 'unsolved' problem of radioactive waste is more political than technical and will require more guts than brains to solve,,. Interna
 tional criteria for the safe disposal of high level wastes were approved in September lastyear by the IAEA's Board of Governors.
<P>The argument sometimes heard that this generation is enjoying the benefits of nuclear power and leaving the burden of waste disposal to our children is not valid. In a good number of countries, the current users of nuclear generated electricity are actually paying for future waste disposal and decommissioning of plants by a special fee built into the cost of each kilowatthour.
<P>One reason why the non military nuclear industry has been able to isolate all its waste is the exceptionally small volume of that waste. Let me give you a comparison of the wastes of a 1000 MW(e) nuclear plant and a 1000 MW(e) coal plant: The coal fired plant will require 7000 tons of coal per day,    i.e., about five train loads. The nuclear plant will use some 80 kilograms of uranium per day. Even with the best flue gas cleaning equipment, the coal plant will annually emit some 900 tons of SO2, 4500 tons of NOx, 6.5 million tons of CO2 and some 400 tons of various heavy metals as wastes. The nuclear plant will produce 30 tons of highly radioactive waste per year.
<P>Let me turn now to the issue of non proliferation. Unlike, for instance, the dissemination of chemical technology, the transfer of nuclear power technology has been based from the beginning on schemes for international co operation with built in checks and controls against the risk of proliferation of nuclear weapons. The Atoms for Peace programme which led to the creation of the International Atomic Energy Agency within the UN system was based on the philosophy that technology, material and equipment would be made available against commitments that they would only be used for peaceful purposes. The verification that these cornrnitments are upheld is now being provided through the IAEA safeguards system, the first international on site inspection system; it now costs about US $60 million per year and has some 200 inspectors regularly visiting some 60 countries. Some 95% of all fissionable material outside nuclear weapon States is under safeguards control. The fears which were common 25 years ago that many States would acquire nuclear weapons have not materialized. The risk of proliferation exists, but I think we can confidently state that the development of civilian nuclear power does not significantly contribute to it. None of the present nuclear weapon States began with nuclear power. The weapons came first. Indeed, the only industry which is subjected to international controls on its exclusively peaceful use is the nuclear power industry in non nuclear weapons States.
<P>Nevertheless, concern exists about the intentions of some countries which have not joined the NPT or allowed the Latin American Tlatelolco Treaty to take effect. The future actions of these countries can be expected to be mainly influenced by their perception of their own security situation. If we are going into a period of drastic disarmament, including nuclear disarmament, a period in which military power gradually comes to play a smaller role at least in relations between great powers, then nuclear weapons may also come to look less meaningful to countries which have not yet completely renounced the option. Continued international detente in the next few years, including some settlement in the Middle East, could lead to universal adherence to non proliferation by non nuclear weapons States. This certainly is an objective to work for.<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
