<HTML>
<HEAD></HEAD>
<TITLE>International Women's Day</TITLE>
</BODY>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>International Women's Day</H3>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Address by<BR>Hans Blix<BR>Director General,<BR>International Atomic Energy Agency</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Vienna International Centre</H4>
<P><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Thursday, 8 March 1990</H4>
<P><HR>
<P>First, I would like to thank the UNIDO Forum of Women Professionals and the Group on Equal Rights for Women at the VIC for having invited me to join you in celebrating today the International Women's Day. I also would like to wish success to the Thirty fourth Session of the Commission on Status of Women' whose important work will come to a close tomorrow.
<P>In 1975, the United Nations launched the Decade for Women. At that time' the Board of Governors of the IAEA adopted a Resolution requesting the Director General to give "... special consideration to the appointment of qualified women to policy making and other professional posts on the staff of the Secretariat". Since then, a number of steps have been taken, resulting in an increase of 60% since 1981 in the number of professional women on the staff of the Agency. However, in spite of this considerable improvement' we are still   I am sorry to say  among the organizations with the highest proportion of men: 88% of our professional staff!
<P>The reason for this low representation of women in the IAEA is simple: We are dealing with very technical programmes in which mostly nuclear engineers or nuclear scientists are required and it seems that in these particular fields the number of trained
 and experienced women worldwide is rather limited. When circulating vacancy notices to our Member States, we draw their attention to the very low proportion of women on our professional staff. We further urge them to ensure that qualified women be given every opportunity to apply to these posts on an "equitable basis with men". In spite of this, the number of applications we receive from women is still disappointing. In 1989' only 11.4% of all applications received in respect of vacant professional posts were from women. For "technical" positions, the percentage for that year was even less, namely 4.5% of all applications.
<P>In the safeguards inspectorate, however, a field where a few years ago some supervisors were hesitant to recommend the employment of women because of the physical strain in inspection tours' and where some Governments' too, were reluctant to accept women inspectors, we have been able through a training programme to increase their number considerably. We now have 11 women inspectors who, side by side with men, are performing physically and technically difficult inspection tasks in nuclear facilities all over the world.
<P>The IAEA is still "globally" far from the 30% target for women professionals' but in some sectors, mainly "administrative", women are relatively well represented' i.e.: in Budget and Finance 52% of the professionals are women, in Personnel 33%' in Technical Assistance Implementation 35%, and in the Library 70%.
<P>The relatively small number of professional women responding to our vacancy announcements, of course, places some constraint on our efforts to increase the number of women in the Professional and higher categories. I can assure you, however, that we try to improve the situation. One step recently taken    in conformity with Common System practice    is to allow the employment of spouses under certain conditions. In this era of both spouses working professionally, this step might in come
 cases enable both spouses to work for the organization. However, to encourage women to go into technical professions, both Governments and international organizations should ensure that women be given equal access to education at all levels and in all fields. l can tell you that in the lAEA particular attention is paid to the applications of women candidates for fellowships and training courses under our Technical Co operation Programme. In fact, in 1989, 22% of the participants in our training courses were women, and 21% of all fellowships were awarded to women. It is also our intention to involve more women in Technical Co operation Projects and promotional activities.
<P>Improvements in the representation of women among the Professional staff should be at all levels. An increase in the number of women at the senior and policy making levels would be most desirable. Some  but slow   progress is made in this respect: the number of P 5 posts held by women has increased from 1 in 1981 to 6 today. I am also glad to tell you that, for the first time since the establishment of the Agency' a women was recently appointed Division Director, namely for the Division of Scientific and Technical Information, which includes a total of 177 staff members.
<P>Let me end by saying that to cope with the exciting challenges of the 90s, international organizations need the broadest possible recruitment base to get the best possible staff. Half of humanity is women. The full use of their intelligence' knowledge' wisdom and energy is needed to shape a better world and many more of them are needed in international organizations' including traditionally male dominated ones like the IAEA.<P><HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
