<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Seminar on Food Irradiation to Control Food Losses and
Foodborne Diseases, and Facilitate Food Trade
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>ECA/FAO/IAEA/IIR/ITC/WHO</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>Regional Seminar on Food Irradiation to Control Food
Losses and Foodborne Diseases, and Facilitate Food Trade</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Rabat, Morocco
<BR>
26 February - 1 March 1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Background Information</B>
<P>
Irradiation of food has the same objectives as other food
processing methods - the reduction of losses due to spoilage
and deterioration and control of the microbes and other
organisms that cause foodborne diseases.  Food irradiation
employs ionizing radiation from gamma ray sources, such as
cobalt-60, and from machines, such as x-ray generators and
electron accelerators.  Based on decades of research and
unprecedented number of studies, the technology is
increasingly accepted as safe and effective in controlling
insects and other pests responsible for post-harvest losses;
in meeting quarantine requirements; in reducing levels of
foodborne pathogens and parasites; and in prolonging the
shelf-life of fresh produce and other foods.  Food irradiation
can contribute significantly to food preservation and safety
and the facilitation of trade, but legislation permitting its
use is essential for the commercialization of the process. 
Furthermore, as it is the case with other food preservation
method such as thermal processing, many applications of food
preservation through irradiation require that the irradiation
process be integrated with other processes, particularly
refrigeration, to attain its full potential.
<P>
The safety and effectiveness of food irradiation have been
established through the positive recommendations of the Joint
FAO/IAEA/WHO Expert Committee on the Wholesomeness of
Irradiated Foods in 1980 and the subsequent adoption of the
Codex General Standard for Irradiated Foods and its associated
Code of Practice by the Codex Alimentarius in 1983.

<P>
Following the adoption of the Codex General Standard for
Irradiated Foods, thirty eight countries have approved
irradiation for the treatment of one or more food items,
including countries in the Africa and Near East Regions.  In
1984, an International Consultative Group on Food Irradiation
(ICGFI) was established to evaluate global developments,
provide a focal point of advice and furnish information on
food irradiation.  Currently, ICGFI has 43 member countries and
meets periodically under the aegis of FAO, IAEA and WHO.  A
number of policy guidelines and recommendations with regard to
control and trade aspects of food irradiation, food hygiene,
quarantine treatment and public information have been
developed and documents and materials issued by ICGFI.  In
1988, food irradiation was reviewed and endorsed by the
International Conference on the Acceptance, Control and Trade
in Irradiated Food, jointly convened by FAO, IAEA WHO and
ITC-UNCTAD/GATT in Geneva.
<P>
Positive regulations on food irradiation in 38 countries and
increasing commercial application in some 30 countries,
indicate growing interest and confidence in this technology. 
The Agreements on the Application of Sanitary and
Phytosanitary Measures and Technical Barriers to Trade,
adopted during the GATT Uruguay Round, could facilitate wider
trade in food (including irradiated food) in the near future. 
Thus, significant international trade in irradiated food
products could be expected.  Similarly, actions taken or being
taken by countries in Africa and the Near East are likely to
increase trade (domestic, intra-regional and international) in
irradiated food products.
<P>
Considering that many applications of food irradiation such as
reduction of pathogenic and spoilage microorganisms and
inactivation of parasites in meats, poultry, fish and
seafoods, and insect disinfestation of fresh fruits and
vegetables that remain perishable after irradiation, it is
important to ensure that the benefits attained through the
food irradiation process are not lost post-irradiation. 
Consequently, it is often necessary to integrate food
irradiation, as a process, into the overall system of food
handling and preservation which includes packaging, storage,
transportation and, most especially, refrigeration.  Thus,
successful implementation of food irradiation must be
accompanied by the development of appropriate, complementary
infrastructure.
<P>
Given the unique potential of food irradiation technology in
overcoming such food safety problems as parasites and
pathogens, as well as its potential technological and
commercial advantages in controlling insect pests especially
as a replacement of methylbromide fumigation which is being
phased out globally, and prolonging shelf-life of fresh
produce and other foods, it would seem desirable for countries
in the Africa and Near East Regions to introduce appropriate
regulations in preparation for an increase in the application
of food irradiation and in trade in irradiated food products. 
Furthermore, it would be desirable to take steps to ensure
that the introduction of such regulatory control of food
irradiation be done in a consistent manner leading to uniform
regulations which reflect internationally acceptable control
measures.
<P>
This seminar represented a combined effort of the United
Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), Joint FAO/IAEA
Division of Nuclear Techniques in Food and Agriculture,
International Institute for Refrigeration (IIR), International
Trade Centre (ITC), the World Health Organization (WHO) and
FAO Near East Regional Office in introducing food irradiation
technology to reduce postharvest fool losses and foodborne
diseases, to consider a harmonized regulations in this field,
and to facilitate trade in certain food commodities within and
from the African continent and the Near East Region.
<P>
<B><LI>Objectives</B>
<P>
The objectives of the seminar were:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a)  to discuss technical issues related to implementation
of irradiation to control food losses and foodborne diseases;
<P>
<DD>(b)  to review the role of food irradiation as a
substitute to fumigation of fresh and dried foods in trade;
<P>
<DD>(c)  to discuss the integration of food irradiation
processing into the food production and handling system, and
the need to develop support or complementary infrastructure to
enable commercial application of food irradiation; and
<P>
<DD>(d)  to review the current situation concerning enactment
and enforcement of regulations on food irradiation in Africa
and the Near East, and technical issues facing national
regulatory control authorities (including those involved in
food regulation, control and safety, and plant protection and
quarantine) in introducing and implementing regulations based
on the principles of the Codex Standard on Irradiated Foods
and the recommendations of ICGFI.
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
Back to listing of <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/index.html">IAEA Meetings in 1996</A>
