<HEAD>
<TITLE>
International Seminar on Enhancement of Research Reactor
Utilization
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>International Seminar on Enhancement of Research Reactor
Utilization</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Bhabha Atomic Research Centre
<BR>
Bombay, India
<BR>
11 - 15 March 1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
The establishment of a nuclear research reactor and
multi-disciplinary research facilities around it can be regarded
as a precursor to the introduction and development of nuclear
technology in the country.  Such a research reactor centre is
expecte to make important contribution to research,
technology, education, training and other national interests. 
This perception was the main reason for the establishment of a
large number of reactors during the 1960s and 1970s.  Many of
these continue to operate even today although some have been
shutdown and decommissioned.  Accoring to the IAEA Research
Reactor Database, there are 288 research reactors that are
currently operational in 57 countries.  This includes 88
reactors in 39 developing countries.
<P>
A research reactor centre is generally a major component of
science and technology infrastructure and, in the case of
developing countries, it is a place for high level research,
training and education and facilities which are usually not
available elsewhere in the country.  It serve to generate and
disseminate knowledge and skills which cover widely diverse
scientific fields such as physics, chemistry, life sciences,
materials and advanced technologies.  They also play an
important role by meeting national demands in th fields of
medicine, agriculture and industry.  The resulting social
benefits go far beyond what may be seen mere cost analyses.
<P>
Since most of the reactors were established several years ago,
their continued operation critically depends on their ability
to meet current scientific demands.  To undertake new
technical programmes, efficient operation and effective
utilisation of these reactors is, therefore, of prime
importance.
<P>
The seminar represented one of the various activities of the
Agency aimed at enhancing the operation and utilisation of
research reactors.
<P>
<B><LI>Purpose of the Seminar</B>
<P>
In view of the continuing role or research reactors in
achieving national goals, the problems concerning their
under-utilisation must be duly addressed.  Efforts should be
made to enhance utilisation by resolving various problems.  To
this end, the seminar provided a forum for the research
reactor operation personnel and users to exchange information
and discuss current perspectives; highlighted the role of
research reactors in promoting basic and applied research and
in providing various services; and presented views and
discussed future initiatives concerning improved utilisation,
more effective use of human and financial resources, and co-
operative efforts.
<P>
<B><LI>List of Topics</B>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>The seminar comprised a number of technical sessions:
<P>
<DD><I>Operation and management of research reactors
<P>
<DD>Refurbishment
<P>
<DD>Engineering research and development programmes
<P>
<DD>Production of radioisotopes
<P>
<DD>Industrial irradiations
<P>
<DD>Neutron activation analysis
<P>
<DD>Neutron beam research
<P>
<DD>Neutron beam applications
<P>
<DD>Panel discussion
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
Back to listing of <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/index.html">IAEA Meetings in 1996</A>
