<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Symposium on Low Level Waste Disposal Facilities
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>International Symposium on Experience in the Planning and
Operation of Low Level Waste Disposal Facilities</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Vienna, Austria
<BR>
17 - 21  June  1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
Low level radioactive wastes (LLW) exist in most Member States.
They arise from nuclear fuel cycle activities and also as a
result of the use of radionuclides in medicine, research and
industry. In some countries LLW disposal facilities have been in
operation for many years and so a considerable base of experience
in operation exists. A few repositories have reached the end of
their operational lives and have been closed and so a limited
amount of experience now exists of the closure and post-closure
phase. On the other hand, in some countries efforts are still
being made to site and license the first repositories of this
type. The IAEA considers that it could be beneficial for experts
in countries with operating or closed LLW repositories to share
their experiences by means of an international Symposium on the
subject. The Symposium will also be of interest to experts from
countries planning to build LLW disposal facilities. It will
provide an opportunity for them to share their experiences and
gain valuable information on the subject.
<P>
The objective of the Symposium was to review and summarize
experiences in planning and operating LLW disposal facilities.
<P>
<B><LI>List of Topics</B>
<P>
The following list of topics was covered at the Symposium:
<P>
<DL>
<DT>(I) Organizational Issues
<P>
<DD>national system
<DD>regulatory framework
<DD>planning
<DD>licensing
<DD>identification of inventory
<DD>decision making process (e.g., public acceptance)
<P>
<DT>(II) Siting
<P>
<DD>siting criteria
<DD>siting approach (including socio-economic considerations)
<DD>site investigation and evaluation
<P>
<DT>(III)     Design
<P>
<DD>design criteria
<DD>design approach
<DD>performance of engineered barrier
<DD>design of repository
<P>
<DT>(IV) Construction 
<P>
<DT>(V)     Operation
<P>
<DD>commissioning
<DD>waste acceptance
<DD>waste emplacement
<DD>control of operation
<DD>monitoring
<P>
<DT>(VI) Closure
<P>
<DD>closure criteria
<DD>closure approach
<DD>capping system and performance
<P>
<DT>(VII)     Post-closure Approaches
<P>
<DD>institutional control issue
<DD>monitoring and corrective action
<DD>long term record keeping 
<P>
<DT>(VIII)    Safety Assessment
<P>
<DD>safety assessment methodology
<DD>use of safety assessment
<DD>case studies 
<DD>example of assessment
<P>
<DT>(IX) Quality Assurance
<P>
<DT>(XI) R&D, International Co-operation Regional Repository, and
Confidence Building
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
Back to listing of <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/index.html">IAEA Meetings in 1996</A>
