<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Seminar on Nuclear Techniques for the Detection and Management of
Cancer
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>Seminar on Nuclear Techniques for the Detection and
Management of Cancer</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Colombo,
Sri Lanka
<BR>
12 - 16 August 1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
The applicability of nuclear techniques to the primary detection
and, more widely, the follow up of cancer after treatment has
been a high interest area of the Nuclear Medicine Section of the
Agency. Since arranging the first seminar on this topic, in
Vienna, in 1989, three co-ordinated research programmes have been
organized on the topics of radioimmunoscintigraphy (RIS) for
colon cancer, alpha feto protein  (AFP) measurement by
radioimmunoassay in liver cancer, and the determination of the
biological sensitivity of breast cancer by measuring steroid
receptors, EGFR, and pS<SUB>2</SUB> antigen. A CRP on tumour
markers as relevant to prostate cancer is being organized for
1996. A series of training courses, two at regional and one at
interregional level, have served to transfer the necessary
technology to developing countries in addition to which numerous
individual TC projects are operative in the field of RIS and
tumour marker assays.
<P>         
RIS has been found to be a non-invasive diagnostic technique
which also appears to have been advantageous over alternative
imaging modalities in several cases. The increasing availability
of monoclonal antibodies specific to tumour associated antigens
combined with developments that have enabled these to be labeled
with <SUP>99</SUP>Tcm as an alternative to <SUP>131</SUP>I or
<SUP>111</SUP>In have increased their applicability in nuclear
medicine departments in developing countries. The value of
determining serum concentrations of tumour associated antigens
(tumour markers) by radioimmunoassay for primary diagnosis,
screening programmes, and the follow up of cancer patients is
also well recognised and  numerous RIA laboratories in developing
countries have been successfully utilising these  methods for
many years. 
<P>         
<B><LI>List of topics</B>
<P>         
The purpose of the seminar was to upgrade knowledge on basic and
applied aspects of radioimmunoscintigraphy and tumour markers
assays,as used for the detection and follow up of cancer, as a
diagnostic tool which could directly influence patient management
decisions. Invited review papers by international
experts focused on recent advances and possibilities in developing
countries in the fields of radioimmunoscintigraphy and tumour
marker assays. Bone marrow scintigraphy and RIS as applied to non
malignant disorders  also received some attention.
<P>
Papers and presentations covered methodological and
clinical aspects on the following main topics.
<P>
<DL>
<DD>        
- RIS in cancers of the colon, liver, ovary, head and neck,
brain, stomach, etc.
<DD>- Bone marrow imaging
<DD>- RIS in non malignant disorders
<DD>- Tumour markers assays
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
Back to listing of <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/index.html">IAEA Meetings in 1996</A>
