<html>
<head>
   <title>16th IAEA Fusion Energy Conference
</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/3.0b3Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>


<center><p><b>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</b> </p></center>

<center><p>
<hr NOSHADE SIZE=1></p></center>

<h3 align=center>16th IAEA Fusion Energy Conference</h3>

<center><p><b>(formerly called the International Conference on Plasma Physics
and Controlled Nuclear Fusion Research)</b> </p></center>

<center><p><b><i>Montreal, Canada 
<br>7 - 11 October 1996</i></b> </p></center>

<center><p>
<hr width="100%" ></p></center>

<center><p><i>For further information on the Conference, see the <a href="http://ccfm.ireq.ca/congres/p2en.html">Web
page</a> prepared by CCFM-Centre canadien de fusion magnetique</i></p></center>

<center><p>
<hr width="100%" ><b>INFORMATION SHEET</b> </p></center>

<ol>
<li><b>Introduction</b> </li>

<p>Recognizing the prominent role that energy plays in the world and the
expectation that controlled fusion will provide an effectively inexhaustible
energy source, the International Atomic Energy Agency encourages the exchange
between nations of scientific and technical information on fusion research.
The results from large experimental devices now in operation and under
construction, the advances in the understanding of plasma physics, and
the engineering design consideration of fusion experimental devices may
lead to the demonstration of &quot;scientific breakeven&quot; soon. </p>

<p>Previous conferences in this series were held in Salzburg (1961), Culham
(1965), Novosibirsk (1968), Madison (1971), Tokyo (1974), Berchtesgaden
(1976), Innsbruck (1978), Brussels (1980), Baltimore (1982), London (1984),
Kyoto (1986), Nice (1988), Washington (1990), Wurzburg (1992) and Seville
(1994). </p>

<li><b>List of topics</b> </li>

<ol TYPE=A>
<li>Tokamak Experiments </li>

<li>Inertial Confinement Fusion </li>

<li>Non-Tokamak Confinement Systems (Helical Systems, Open Confinement
Systems, Reversed Field Pinches, etc.) </li>

<li>Magnetic Confinement Theory and Modeling </li>

<li>Plasma Heating and Current Drive </li>

<li>ITER Engineering Design Activities </li>

<li>Fusion Technology and Reactor Concepts </li>

<li>Economic, Safety and Environmental Aspects of Fusion </li>
</ol>

<p>This time the conference has been shortened from six days to five and
this requires adjustment of the format. In order to reduce overlap that
has occurred in the past, papers whose main aim is to review research programmes
or to overview results presented elsewhere in the conference are not desirable.
Because of the progression of the field towards a more technological phase,
papers on fusion technology are encouraged. </p>

<p>Papers dealing with diagnostics, fundamental processes, etc. will be
considered if clearly relevant to fusion problems. </p>

<p>A scientific programme committee with a representative international
membership will be responsible for the selection of papers, the arrangements
of conference sessions and the overall scientific content of the conference.
</p>

<p>In the event that an excessive number of papers describing significant
new research is submitted, some of the accepted papers may be selected
by the programme committee for presentation in summarized form by rapporteurs.
</p>

<p>Poster sessions will be included in this conference. Papers selected
for poster presentation will be published in the proceedings. </p>

</DL>
</OL>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
