<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Symposium on Reviewing the Safety of Existing Nuclear Power
Plants
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY
<P>
in co-operation with the
<P>
NUCLEAR ENERGY AGENCY OF THE ORGANIZATION FOR ECONOMIC
CO-OPERATION AND DEVELOPMENT IN EUROPE</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>International Symposium on Reviewing the Safety of Existing
Nuclear Power Plants</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Vienna,Austria
<BR>
8 - 11 October 1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Purpose</B>
<P>     
The purpose of the symposium was to exchange experience and
lessons learned in safety reviews and experience feedback systems
for existing NPPs. These are means for identifying safety
improvements; for the verification of plant safety, including
decisions on the acceptability of the safety level and continued
plant operation; and for licensing. It was intended through this
symposium to make available to all those involved in maintaining
the safety of NPPs (i.e., to plant owners/operators, regulators,
designers, technical support organizations and manufacturers)
information on effective methods, practices and criteria for
safety reviews and experience feedback systems.
<P>
<B><LI>Background</B>
<P>         
Several types of safety review are used to ensure the safety of
existing nuclear power plans. <I>Routine reviews</I> of NPP
operation
(including ongoing reviews of significant events, hardware and
procedural modifications, operating experience, plant management
and personnel competence) and <I>special reviews</I> following
accidents
are the primary means for safety verification and ongoing safety
improvements. <I>Periodic safety reviews</I> (PSRs) have been
initiated
in recent years to deal with cumulative effects of NPP ageing,
modifications and operating experience; with changes in safety
standards; and with advances in technology and in scientific
knowledge and analytical techniques. (IAEA issued in 1994 a
Safety Guide on PSRs.)
<P>         
PSRs, which are undertaken every 10 years, make use of results of
routine and special safety reviews and of other relevant studies,
including a plant-specific PSA, if available. These reviews are
complementary and together provide the means for ensuring safety 
throughout plant service life. In addition, <I>safety reviews of
NPPs built to earlier standards</I> have been performed to
determine
which design and operational modifications are needed to improve
the safety of these plants. The symposium will be a forum for the
exchange of experience with all of the above safety reviews and
with the related issue of the basis for judging the
<I>acceptability
of continued plant operation.</I>
<P>
<I>Operational experience feedback</I> (OEF) is a means by which
experience and lessons learned are exchanged on a range of
activities, from NPP design, through operation, to
decommissioning. It can be used to indicate whether the design
safety intent of plants is realized in operation and as a
pro-active technique to assist in reducing risks. The     
effectiveness of OEF depends on identifying the most useful data
to be collected; on appropriate balance in coverage between
events which have led to incidents or accidents, and those which
are safety related deviations/findings (detected for example
through testing, maintenance and safety reviews); on
comprehensiveness of data analysis; and on disseminating
information that meets the needs of users.
<P>         
The means for the management of data is crucial to the success of
safety reviews and  experience feedback systems. The
multidimensional nature of the data (textual, numerical and
graphical) in safety reviews and feedback systems should be
accommodated by the use of object and relational <I>database
management systems.</I>
<P>
<B><LI>List of topics</B>
<P>       
In the context of the above purpose and background of the
symposium, papers should address one or more of the following
topics (a) to (h). For each of these topics, suggested subtopics
are also presented.
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) <I>Periodic safety reviews of operational NPPs</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- scope of the review (safety factors/areas covered)
<DD>- safety standards, methods and practices used
<DD>- review process and related roles of NPP owner/operator and
regulator
<DD>- utilization of results of routine and special safety
reviews, of reviews of NPPs built to earlier standards, and of
PSA
<DD>- results of the PSR and safety benefits achieved
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(b) <I>Routine safety reviews of operational NPPs</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- routine inspections
<DD>- investigation and analysis of significant events
<DD>- reviews of proposed changes
<DD>- reports required by an operating license
<DD>- safety performance indicators
<DD>- annual plant safety assessments (self and regulatory
assessments)
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(c) <I>Special safety reviews following NPP accidents</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- in-depth accident analysis, including possible alternative
<DD>- accident scenarios
<DD>- lessons learned
<DD>- implementation of corrective measures
<DD>- implications for safety standards and the design of future
plants
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(d) <I>Safety reviews of NPPs built to earlier standards</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Safety criteria used
<DD>- methods used
<DD>- results (e.g. recommended corrective actions)
<DD>- implementation of results (e.g. backfitting programme)
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(e) <I>Basis for acceptability of continued NPP operation</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- relevant national policy
<DD>- significance of safety deficiencies and time required to
implement
<DD>- corrective actions
<DD>- remaining period of operation
<DD>- cost-benefit considerations
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(f) <I>Feedback and analysis of NPP operational
experience</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- reporting, documentation, screening, analysis
<DD>- corrective action selection, implementation, and evaluation
of actual benefits
<DD>- dissemination and exchange of information
<DD>- voluntary and mandatory elements of the feedback process
<DD>- future trends
</DL>
<P>
<DD>(g) <I>Information databases in support of safety reviews and
feedback system</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- databases in operation or under development
<DD>- software for managing data
<DD>- approaches to integrating databases and knowledge systems
</DL>
</OL>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
</DL>
<P>
