<HEAD>
<TITLE>
International Seminar on the Use of Isotope Techniques in Marine
Environmental
Studies
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>International Seminar on the Use of Isotope Techniques in
Marine
Environmental Studies</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Athens, Greece
<BR>
11 - 22 November 1996</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
In recent years, isotope techniques have largely contributed to
the progress
of marine environmental studies. Research in these fields is
directed
towards a better understanding of fundamental oceanographic
processes and
phenomena, the protection and management of the marine
environment including
adequate use of marine resources, and the reconstruction of past,
and the
prediction of future global change. The tracers used include
stable
isotopes, natural radionuclides, especially those of the U/Th
decay series,
and nuclides of anthropogenic origin.
<P>         
In many Member States, especially in developing countries, there
is a
growing need for such environmental studies, for instance in
connection with
the protection of their coastal/shelf regions and estuaries from
land-based
pollution, eutrophication and other types of anthropogenic impact
on their
marine and aquatic ecosystems.
<P>         
<B><LI>List of topics</B>
<P>         
The scope of the Seminar included a critical review of the
applications of
isotope techniques to environmental studies in marine, aquatic
and associated
hydrological studies. The meeting focused on:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>* The oceanography of closed or partially closed seas, e.g.
Mediterranean,
Baltic, Black, and Caspian Seas.
<P>         
<DD>* Applications of isotope techniques to environmental studies
of marine
and large aquatic systems. The following topics will be
discussed:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- sources, distributions and inventories of isotopes in
marine and aquatic
systems;
<P>
<DD>- water balance and dynamics of closed or partly closed seas;
fingerprinting of contaminant origins using isotopic signals;
<P>
<DD>- water transport, particle transport, scavenging processes,
residence
times;
<P>
<DD>- water-sediment interaction, resuspension, sediment
dynamics,
sedimentation rates;
<P>
<DD>- biogeochemical processes, radiological aspects;
<P>
<DD>- organic and inorganic pollution;
<P>
<DD>- reconstruction of environmental changes;
<P>
<DD>- palaeoclimatology .
</DL>
<P>
<DD>* Hydrodynamic modelling, dispersion studies, river inputs.
<P>         
<DD>* Storage, evaluation and interpretation of environmental
data.
<P>         
<DD>* Ongoing international programmes related to the Agency's
marine
environmental programme.
<P>         
<DD>* Discussions on current marine environmental and aquatic
studies in
Member States, as presented by the participants.
<P>         
<DD>* New developments in isotope techniques.
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
Back to listing of <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/index.html">IAEA Meetings in 1996</A>
