<HEAD>
<TITLE>
FAO/IAEA International Symposium on Diagnosis and Control of Livestock Diseases using Nuclear and Related Techniques "Towards Disease Control in the 21st Century"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY
<BR>
FOOD AND AGRICULTURE ORGANIZATION OF THE UNITED NATIONS</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<H3>FAO/IAEA International Symposium on Diagnosis and Control of Livestock Diseases using Nuclear and Related Techniques "Towards Disease Control in the 21<SUP>st</SUP> Century"</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Vienna, Austria
<BR>
7 - 11 April 1997</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
The Symposium will be organized by the Animal Production and Health Section of the Joint FAO/IAEA Division of Nuclear Techniques in Food and Agriculture. The main thrust in supporting disease control by the Agency has been the development and utilization of kits for the measurement of antibodies and antigens based on ELISA (a technique which was accepted as being analogous to RIA). The symposium will cover the areas of serology, molecular biological approaches, epidemiology and socio/economics. All are relevant to the consideration of disease control. These topics will be reviewed by invited speakers and their impact on developing countries and feasibility of transfer assessed. The proceedings will be essential reading to scientists and administrators involved in using and choosing appropriate technologies to control disease in developing countries.
<P>
<B><LI>List of Topics</B>
<P>
<OL TYPE="I">
<LI><I>Overview of technology impact on developing countries</I>
<BR> technologies applicable to disease 
<BR>
diagnosis links with research and applied research feasible vs unfeasible technologies 
<BR>
technology transfer and problems
<P>
<LI>Serology 
<BR>
<I>ELISA overview</I> 
<BR>
summary of achievements of ELISA 
<BR>
reagent developments 
<BR>
sensitivity/specificity uses and abuses. 
<BR>
ELISA-rinderpest 
<BR>
ELISA-brucellosis 
<BR>
ELISA-trypanosomosis 
<BR>
ELISA-foot-and-mouth disease 
<BR>
Other forms of assays
<BR>
Biosensors
<BR>
Pen side tests
<BR>
Monoclonal antibodies
<P>
<LI><I>Molecular biological approaches</I>
<BR>
general overview 
<BR>
PCR overview 
<BR>
diagnostic applications PCR 
<BR>
molecular biological techniques paper-foot-and-mouth disease 
<BR>
molecular biological techniques paper-rinderpest 
<BR>
molecular biological techniques paper-CBPP kits, problems and solutions 
<BR>
vaccines
<P>
<LI><I>Epidemiological aspects</I>
<BR>
overview
<BR>
sampling strategies-monitoring control programmes
<BR>
EQA/QC 
<BR>
example of QA monitoring 
<BR>
training/tech transfer 
<BR>
information networks 
<BR>
information technologies (telos) 
<BR>
GIS 
<BR>
mathematical modelling 
<BR>
climatic change 
<BR>
satellites etc
<P>
<LI><I>Economic/social factors</I>
<BR>
 overview
<BR>
sustainability 
<BR>
cost/benefit approaches 
<BR>
future of livestock trade 
<BR>
summary implications for disease programmes 
<BR>
conclusions and recommendations
</OL>
<P>
<B><LI>Participation</B>
<P>
All persons wishing to participate in the meeting are requested to complete a Participation Form and send it as soon as possible to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs or national atomic energy authority) for subsequent transmission to the IAEA. A participant will be accepted only if the Participation Form is transmitted through the government of a Member State of the International Atomic Energy Agency or by an organization invited to participate.
<P>
Participants whose designations have been received by the IAEA will be notified directly two to three months before the meeting.
<P>
<B><LI> Expenditures</B>
<P>
As a general rule, the IAEA does not pay the cost of attendance, i. e. travel and living expenses, of participants. However, limited funds are available to help meet the cost of attendance of selected specialists mainly from <I>developing countries with low economic resources</I>. Generally, not more than one grant will be awarded to any one country.
<P>
If governments wish to apply for a grant on behalf of one of their specialists, they should address specific requests to the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency to this effect. Governments should ensure that applications for grants:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) be submitted by <B>20 November 1996</B>
<P>
<DD>(b) be accompanied by a duly completed and signed Grant Application Form.
</DL>
<P>
Applications which do not comply with the conditions mentioned under (a) and (b) cannot be considered.
<P>
The grants awarded will be in the form of lump sums usually covering only part of the cost of attendance.
<P>
No registration fee is charged to participants.
<P>
<B><LI>Invited Papers</B>
<P>
Selected specialists from developing and developed countries are being invited to present papers.
<P>
All papers must present <I>original</I> work; they should <I>not</I> have been published elsewhere.
<P>
A completed <I>Form for Submission of a Paper</I> (Form "B") together with four copies (including the master copy with original figures + diskette) of the full text of the paper, preceded by an abstract of 300 words maximum, must be sent direct to the IAEA by
<B>25 February 1997</B> for editorial purposes.
<P>
In addition, two copies of an extended synopis of 800 words (i.e. two A4 format pages of single spaced typing or the equivalent, including any tables or diagrams and a few pertinent references) should be attached. The synopsis will be reproduced in unedited form in the Book of Extended Synopses and should therefore be submitted as camera-ready copy. The general style and presentation should be as in the attached sample.
<P>
Both the paper and the extended synopsis (on paper and on diskette) should be sent to the IAEA by <B>25 February 1997</B>.
<P>
<B><LI>Poster presentations</B>
<P>
Poster presentations are welcomed in any of the topics outlined. Authors whose poster has been accepted for poster presentation will receive instructions for the preparation of the poster, both as regards presentation and the subsequent form of publication.
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a)	A completed <I>Form for Submission of a Poster</I> (Form "P"). together with the
Participation Form (Form "A") and four copies of an <I>extended synopsis</I> of <B>500</B> words in English to the competent official authority for transmission to the IAEA to reach
it by <B>20 November 1996</B> (see section 12 below).
<P>
The synopsis should give enough information on the contents of the proposed poster to enable the selection committee to evaluate it. Introductory and general matters should not be included. The synopsis - if accepted - will be reproduced in unedited form in the Book of Extended Synopses; therefore, the original must be submitted as camera-ready copy. The general style and presentation should be as in the attached sample.
<P>
<DD>(b) 	If changes or corrections of an extended synopsis become necessary, a revised version may be sent to the IAEA by <B>25 February 1997</B> for inclusion in the book of extended synopses;
</DL>
<P>
<I>Further details concerning poster presentation at the meeting will be sent to all authors in due course.</I>
<P>
<B><LI>Proceedings</B>
<P>
The proceedings of the meeting will be published by the International Atomic Energy Agency as soon as possible after the meeting. They will include all invited papers presented printed in full, together with abstracts, in English. In addition they will include extended synopses of poster presentations. With a view to speeding up publication of the proceedings and reducing its costs, the length of the papers will be limited.
<P>
Participants who order copies of the proceedings in advance during the meeting will be entitled to a 50% discount.
<P>
<B><LI>Working language</B>
<P>
The working language of the meeting will be English. All communications, synopses, abstracts and papers must be sent to the Agency in English.
<P>
<B><LI>Distribution of documents</B>
<P>
A preliminary programme of the Symposium will be sent to the participants before
the meeting.
<P>
The final programme book of extended synopses in the original language and preprints, to the extent available, will be distributed on registration.
<P>
<B><LI>Accommodation</B>
<P>
Detailed information on accommodation and other items will be sent direct to all designated participants well in advance of the meeting.
<P>
<B><LI>Secretariat</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The address of the Secretariat is:
<P>
International Atomic Energy Agency
<BR> 
IAEA-D3-SM-348
<BR>
