<HEAD>
<TITLE>Symposium on Desalination of Seawater with Nuclear Energy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<H3>Symposium on Desalination of Seawater with Nuclear Energy </H3>
<P>
<B><I>Taejon, Republic of Korea
<BR>
26 - 30 May 1997</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Introduction</B>
<P>
Worldwide availability of potable water substantially exceeds the amount of water consumed. However, water resources are not evenly distributed. About three quarters of the world's population lack an adequate supply of safe potable water and some Member States are confronting acute water shortages. There has been a significant increase in the installation of seawater desalination facilities over the past decades, and there are many regions and countries which are expected to expand their desalination capacity.
<P>
The various incentives which in the past have led to the deployment of nuclear energy for electric power generation are now also applicable to the choice of nuclear energy as the source for seawater desalination plants. The reasons include: economic competitiveness in areas which lack inexpensive fossil fuel resources: energy supply diversification, conservation of limited fossil fuel resources: and promotion of technological development and environmental protection through the elimination of emissions causing acid rain and climate changes originating from the burning of fossil fuels.
<P>
As early as the 1960s the IAEA surveyed the feasibility of using nuclear energy for seawater desalination and held an international symposium in 1968. Since that time, no forum has been made available for discussions and information exchange on the subject. In 1989, renewed interest in utilizing nuclear energy for seawater desalination, indicated by several Member States, led to a resolution at the IAEA's General Conference, requesting the Agency to proceed with studies to assess the technical and economic potential of nuclear reactors for seawater desalination in the light of experience gained in recent years. This interest is confirmed each year, when the General Conference requests the Agency to include activities on nuclear desalination in its programme.
<P>
The IAEA has performed several feasibility studies regarding the use of nuclear energy for seawater desalination, with the participation and support of several Member States. In addition to the IAEA's studies, several bilateral and national activities on nuclear desalination are also in progress.
<P>
Considering the ongoing programmes, as well as the growing interest in nuclear desalination worldwide, the IAEA recognizes a need to provide, with the co-operation of other international organizations, a forum for the review of the state-of-the-art technological experience, design and development of nuclear desalination systems, and of prospects for nuclear desalination.
<P>
The Symposium will be beneficial to technical, financial and regulatory decision makers and governmental people associated with this subject.
<P>
<B><LI>List of topics</B>
<P>
The Symposium covers nuclear desalination systems, with emphasis on their near term application. The Symposium will consist of contributed technical papers on nuclear desalination systems, and invited papers.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Session I.</I> Overview
<DD>[invited papers]
</DL>
<P>
The first session will summarize global potable water needs, present an update on state-of-the-art desalination system technologies, and inform on relevant activities of selected international organizations.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Session II.</I> National Programmes and Activities
<DD>[invited and contributed papers]
</DL>
<P>
Session II will present the status of ongoing and planned national programmes and activities.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Session III.</I> Technical Aspects
<DD>[invited and contributed papers]
</DL>
<P>
Session III will concentrate on specific technical aspects. Papers may cover topics on the design and safety of nuclear reactors for desalination, desalination technologies, and integration of nuclear and desalination systems.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Session IV.</I> Experience in Desalination using Nuclear, Fossil and Other Energy Sources
<DD>[invited and contributed papers]
</DL>
<P>
Session IV will focus on discussions of experience in operation, maintenance, impact on the environment, water production costs and cost comparisons of desalination plants.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Session V.</I> Opportunities for Desalination Systems using Nuclear Energy
<DD>[invited and contributed papers]
</DL>
<P>
Session V will be devoted to discussions on future opportunities for desalination systems using nuclear energy. Papers may be contributed on such topics as:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Expected market for desalination systems using nuclear energy
<DD>- Demand for desalination systems using nuclear energy
<DD>- Potential users' positions and considerations
<DD>- Economic and financial aspects
<DD>- Issues related to technology transfer
</DL>
<P>
<I>Panels</I>
<P>
Two expert panels will be held to stimulate discussion and provide incentives for desalination systems using nuclear energy.
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Panel I: The Challenges of International Co-operation 
<DD>- Panel II: Why are There Not More Desalination Plants Using Nuclear Energy?
</DL>
<P>
<I>Poster and Exhibition Sessions</I>
<P>
In a parallel session, participants will be offered the opportunity to present relevant papers and exhibitions of their various nuclear desalination plant designs (mature and conceptual) according to the scope of the Symposium.
<P>
<I>Technical Tours</I>
<P>
Two technical tours are planned. Tour A will give participants an opportunity to visit the Korea Atomic Energy Research Institute and its facilities for one day. Tour B planned for two days is to visit a nuclear power plant site and industrial site(s).
<P>
<B><LI>Participation</B>
<P>
About 150 participants from Member States with own nuclear desalination activities or interest in future deployment of nuclear desalination are expected to attend, as well as interested international organizations.
<P>
All persons wishing to participate in the meeting are requested to complete a Participation Form and send it as soon as possible to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs or national atomic energy authority) for subsequent transmission to the IAEA. A participant will be accepted only if the Participation Form is transmitted through the government of a Member State of the International Atomic Energy Agency or by an organization invited to participate.
<P>
Participants whose designations have been received by the IAEA will be notified directly two to three months before the meeting.
<P>
<B><LI>Expenditures</B>
<P>
As a general rule, the IAEA does not pay the cost of attendance, i.e. travel and living expenses, of participants. However, limited funds are available to help meet the cost of attendance of selected specialists mainly from <I>developing countries with low economic resources</I>. Generally, not more than one grant will be awarded to any one country.
<P>
If governments wish to apply for a grant on behalf of one of their specialists, they should address specific requests to the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency to this effect. Governments should ensure that applications for grants:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) be submitted by <B>25 November 1996</B>:
<P>
<DD>(b) be accompanied by a duly completed and signed Grant Application Form.
</DL>
<P>
Applications which do not comply with the conditions mentioned under (a) and (b) cannot be considered.
<P>
The grants awarded will be in the form of lump sums usually covering part of the cost of attendance.
<P>
The costs for the organization of the meeting are borne by the IAEA and the Host Government. No registration fee is charged to participants.
<P>
<B><LI>Papers/Posters</B>
<P>
All papers and posters - apart from invited review papers - must present <I>original</I> work; they should <I>not</I> have been published or presented elsewhere.
<P>
A completed <I>Form for Submission of a Paper</I> (Form "B"), together with the Participation Form (Form "A") and six copies of an <I>extended synopsis</I>. of 800 words (i.e. two A4 format pages of single spaced typing or the equivalent, including any tables or diagrams and a few pertinent references) must be sent to the competent official authority for transmission to the IAEA to reach it by <B>25 October 1996</B> (see section 11 below).
<P>
The synopsis should give enough information on the contents of the proposed paper or poster to enable the selection committee to evaluate it. Introductory and general matters should not be included. The synopsis - if accepted - will be reproduced in unedited form in the Book of Extended Synopses; therefore, the original must be submitted as camera-ready copy. The general style and presentation should be as in the attached sample.
<P>
<B>Authors should indicate on the form whether the synopses is submitted for oral presentation or for poster presentation.</B>
<P>

Authors will be informed whether their papers have been accepted for presentation at a regular session on the basis of the extended synopses by the end of December 1996. <I>The Agency however reserves the right to refuse</I> the presentation or publication of any paper that does not meet the expectations based on the information given in the extended synopsis.
<P>
<B>Further details concerning the written and oral presentation at the meeting will be sent to all authors in due course.</B>
<P>
<B><LI>Proceedings</B>
<P>
The proceedings of the meeting will be published by the International Atomic Energy Agency as soon as possible after the meeting. They will include all papers presented, together with abstracts. In addition they will include extended synopses of poster presentations. With a view to speeding up publication of the proceedings and reducing its costs, the length of the papers will be strictly limited.
<P>
<B><LI>Working languages</B>
<P>
The working language of the meeting will be English. All communications including extended synopses and full texts should be made in English. No interpretation will be provided.
<P>
<B><LI>Distribution of documents</B>
<P>
A preliminary programme of the Symposium will be sent to the participants before the meeting.
<P>
The final programme, the book of extended synopses and preprints, to the extent available, will be distributed on registration.
<P>
<B><LI>Accommodation</B>
<P>
Detailed information on accommodation and other items will be sent direct to all designated participants well in advance of the meeting. The cost will be approximately from US$ 40 to US$ 100. 
<P>
<B><LI>Secretariat</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
