<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Symposium on Nuclear Fuel Cycle and Reactor Strategy:  Adjusting to New Realities</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY
<BR>
<SMALL>in co-operation with EUROPEAN COMMISSION
<BR>
NUCLEAR ENERGY AGENCY of the OECD
<BR>
THE URANIUM INSTITUTE</SMALL></B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<H3>Symposium on Nuclear Fuel Cycle and Reactor Strategy:  Adjusting to New Realities</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Vienna, Austria
<BR>
2 - 6 June  1997</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Purpose</B>
<P>
The purpose of the symposium is:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- 	To prepare for decision-makers (including nuclear-weapon States in relation
to excess weapons material) and the public, a scientific assessment of the
different fuel cycle and reactor strategies with particular reference to the
production, use and disposal of plutonium;
<P>
<DD>- To examine the policy options and explore the scope for international
common understanding on these options;
<P>
<DD>- 	To enhance the transparency of the management and disposition of
plutonium;
<P>
<DD>- 	To examine the scope for future international collaboration in matters relating
to the production, storage, use and disposal of plutonium.
</DL>
<P>
<B><LI>Background</B>
<P>
The nuclear community faces new realities which were not foreseen two decades ago. Nuclear power generation has grown at a far slower rate than expected. Second, there has been limited interest in fast reactors and delay in their commercialization where they are being developed. Third, the adoption of a closed nuclear fuel cycle, where chosen, is only partially achieved through the burning of mixed oxide fuels. These new realities have resulted in the accumulation of plutonium in civilian programmes. In addition, as a result of the end of the cold war, there may soon be a large amount of plutonium from dismantled warheads.
<P>
The production, storage and use of plutonium are the subject of international concerns but there is no common international understanding on what policies should be adopted. The 1995 Review and Extension Conference of the Parties to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons called for "greater transparency on matters relating to the management of Pu (and HEU) for civil purposes, including stock levels and their relationship to national nuclear fuel cycles". Also, the Conference urged "continued international examination of policy options concerning the management and use of stocks of Pu. This consideration could include, inter alia, arrangement for the deposit with IAEA, as envisaged in Article XII.A of its Statute, of Pu (and HEU) as an additional precaution against diversion of materials to nuclear weapons or other explosive devices as well as the possibility of regional fuel cycle centres".
<P>
It is, therefore, timely and important to provide an international forum to examine the policy options and explore the international common understanding, based on sound scientific assessment.
<P>
<B><LI>List of topics</B>
<P>
In the context of the above purpose the following six topics will be covered at the Symposium. These topics will be discussed at six sessions and Key Issue Papers prepared by Working Groups are to be presented (see 4). For each of the topics, subtopics are also listed.
<P>
<DL>
<DD><B>(a) Present Status and Immediate Prospects of Plutonium Management</B>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>State of technology and developments expected up to about 2015
	<P>
<LI>Plutonium quantities and balance (plutonium in spent fuel, separated
plutonium, weapons surplus plutonium)
<P>
<LI>Plutonium recycle
	<P>
<LI>Direct disposal of plutonium
	<P>
<LI>Storage of plutonium.
</UL>
<P>
The state of the technology and rationale for the different options in the short term will be assessed.
<P>
<DD><B>(b) Global Energy Outlook</B>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Existing scenarios (a. 2015, b. 2050 beyond) with be reviewed with a view to
identifying key factors which may determine nuclear development, for
example world population growth, world demand for energy, possible
availability and costs of different energy sources, progress with reduction of
greenhouse gas emissions
<P>
<LI>Possible availability and costs of uranium
<P>
<LI>Likely contribution of nuclear energy and factors that may limit it
<P>
<LI>Plutonium usage if any
</UL>
<P>
<DD><B>(c) 	Fuel Cycle and Reactor Strategies</B> (long term up to 2050)
<P>
<UL>
The options will be reviewed under the following classification:
<P>
<LI>Once through cycle (implications for treatment of surplus weapons plutonium
should be identified)
<P>
<LI>Thermal recycling
	<P>
<LI>Fast Reactors
	<P>
<LI>For each of the options the economic and technical rationale, the possibilities
of further development of existing systems, the constraints imposed by
licensing requirements and possible techniques for decreasing hazards in the
different stages of the fuel cycle will be assessed
</OL>
<P>
<DD><B>(d) 	Safety, Health and Environmental Implications of the Different Fuel Cycle
Options</B>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Different disposition options with respect to occupational exposure, public exposure,
environmental impact, safety and accidental risks
<P>
<LI>	All phases of the fuel cycle short term and long term
<P>
<LI>Topics of special interest like transportation, hazards of plutonium, long-lived
radionuclides, toxicity reduction for geological disposal and health effects of
techniques for decreasing hazards in the different stages of the fuel cycle
</UL>
<P>
<DD><B>(e) Non-Proliferation and Safeguards Aspects</B>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>	Existing non-proliferation requirements which any fuel cycle must satisfy including,
amongst others safeguards (including IAEA Programme for Strengthening the
Effectiveness and Improving the Efficiency of the Safeguards System [93+2]
Programme), physical protection, export controls, agreements on management of
surplus weapons material.
<P>
<LI>New requirements that may emerge from new non-proliferation initiatives like
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), Fissile Material Cut-Off Convention, NPT
Review Process and others
<P>
<LI>Are there any fuel cycle options that create special difficulties in meeting these
requirements?
<P>
<LI>Special questions concerning e.g. managing surplus weapons material or expansion
of international trade in fuel cycle services
</UL>
<P>
<DD><B>(f) International Co-operation</B>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Is the existing international framework sufficient for
<P>
<DL>
<DD>-	the economic and orderly development of the world's nuclear energy
systems?
<P>
<DD>- 	the safe and secure operation of the fuel cycle in any one country?
<P>
<DD>- international co-operation in research and development?
<P>
<DD>- international co-operation in industrial activities?
</DL>
<P>
<LI>Can new forms of co-operation be foreseen which would make it easier to 
implement any of the fuel cycle options in a safe, secure and responsible way?
<P>
<LI>Other forms of international co-operation which would affect the fuel cycle, 
e.g. regional institutions and an international plutonium management regime and/or
storage
<P>
<LI>Appropriate role of IAEA in any of  these?
</UL>
</DL>
<P>
<B><LI>Format of the Symposium</B>
<P>
<DL>
<DD><I>Six Key Issue Papers</I> will provide an overview and an international common understanding, if any, of the topics mentioned above. They are prepared by Working Groups composed of renowned international specialists and will be printed and distributed in advance of the symposium. The Key Issue Papers will be presented at each session.
<P>
<DD><I>Invited Papers</I> will provide more detailed information on selected topics or will present personal views of outstanding members of the international nuclear community. Copies of the Invited Papers will be distributed during the Symposium.
<P>
<DD><I>Contributed Papers</I> should present new information on the topics of the symposium. The Contributed Papers will be evaluated and selected by a Selection Committee. A few papers may be selected for oral presentation, others will be selected for presentation at a poster session.
<P>
<DD><I>A Panel discussion</I> is planned for the final day of the symposium to discuss major aspects of plutonium disposition and related matters.
</DL>
<P>
<B><LI>Participation</B>
<P>
All persons wishing to participate in the symposium are requested to complete a Participation and send it as soon as possible to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs or national atomic energy authority) for subsequent transmission to the IAEA Secretariat. A participant will be accepted only if the Participation Form is transmitted through the government of a Member State of the sponsoring organizations or by an organization invited to participate.
<P>
Participants whose designations have been received by the Secretariat will be notified directly two to three months before the meeting.
<P>
No registration fee is charged to participants
<P>
<B><LI>Expenditure</B>
<P>
As a general rule, the IAEA does not pay the cost of attendance, i.e. travel and living expenses, of participants. However, limited funds are available to help meet the cost of attendance of selected specialists whose papers were selected for presentation by the Selection Committee mainly from <I>developing countries with low economic resources</I>. Generally, not more than one grant will be awarded to any one country.
<P>
If governments wish to apply for a grant on behalf of one of their specialists, they should address specific requests to the Director General of the international Atomic Energy Agency to this effect. Governments should ensure that applications for grants:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) be submitted by <B>31 December 1996</B>;
<P>
<DD>(b) be accompanied by a duly completed and signed Grant Application Form.
</DL>
<P>
Applications which do not comply with the conditions mentioned under 7.(a) and 7.(b) cannot be considered.
<P>
The grants awarded will be in the form of lump sums usually covering part of the cost of attendance.
<P>
<B><LI>Papers and Poster Presentation</B>
<P>
The Contributed Papers must present <I>original</I> work; they should <I>not</I> have been published elsewhere.
<P>
<I>Deadlines for submission</I>
<P>
A complete <I>Form for Submission of a Paper</I> (Form "B"), together with the Participation Form (Form "A") and six copies of an <I>extended synopsis</I> of up to 800 words (i.e. two A4 format pages of single spaced typing or the equivalent, including any tables or diagrams and a few pertinent references) must be sent to the competent official authority for transmission to the Secretariat to reach it by <B>31 December 1996</B> (see section 11. below).
<P>
The synopsis should give enough information on the contents of the proposed paper to enable the Selection Committee to evaluate it. Introductory and general matters should not be included. The synopsis - if accepted - will be reproduced in unedited form; therefore, the original must be submitted as camera-ready copy. The general style and presentation should be as in the attached sample.
<P>
<I>Authors are urged to strictly observe the above deadline as otherwise distribution of copies of their papers cannot be guaranteed.</I>
<P>
Authors will be informed whether their papers have been accepted for either oral or poster presentation on the basis of the extended synopses. The Agency however reserves the right to refuse the presentation or publication of any paper that does not meet the expectations based on the information given in the extended synopsis. Further details concerning the written or oral presentation at the meeting will be sent to all authors in due course.
<P>
<B><LI>Documentation</B>
<P>
The six Key Issue Papers will be published by the International Atomic Energy Agency before the meeting and mailed to the participants. The Invited Papers and the synopses of the Contributed Papers will be copied and distributed during the meeting. A preliminary programme of the symposium will be sent to participants before the meeting. The final programme will be available upon registration.
<P>
<B><LI>Working language</B>
<P>
The working language of the meeting will be English.
<P>
<B><LI>Accommodation</B>
<P>
Detailed information on accommodation and other items will be sent direct to all designated participants well in advance of the meeting.
<P>
<B<LI>Secretariat</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

The address of the Secretariat is: 
<P>
International Atomic Energy Agency 
<BR>
IAEA-SM-346 
<BR>
Vienna International Centre 
<BR>
Wagramerstrasse 5 
<BR>
P.O. Box 100 
<BR>
A-1400 Vienna 
<BR>
Austria
<P>
	Telephone No.:	+43-1-2060(0) plus extension
<BR>
	Telex No.:	+43-1-12645
<BR>
	Telefax No.:	+43-1-20607
</BLOCKQUOTE>

The Scientific Secretaries of the Symposium are Mr. N. Oi (telephone extension 22766) and Mr. P. Jelinek (telephone extension 22770) Division of Nuclear Power and the Fuel Cycle. Meeting organization is provided by Ms. E. Fritz, Conference Service Section, Division of External Relations (telephone extension 21314, e-mail address: fritz@adpo01.iaea.or.at).
<P>
<B><LI>Channels of communication</B>
<P>
The Participation Form and the Form for the Submission of a Paper, together with six copies of each synopsis, and, if applicable, the Grant Application Form, should be sent to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs, national atomic energy authority) for transmission to the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency). Subsequent correspondence on scientific matters should be sent to the Scientific Secretaries and correspondence on administrative matters to the IAEA Conference Service Section.
</OL>
<P>
