<HEAD>
<TITLE>Symposium on Upgrading the Fire Safety of Operating Nuclear Power Plants</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER>
<B>INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY</B>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<H3>Symposium on Upgrading the Fire Safety of Operating Nuclear Power Plants</H3>
<P>
<B><I>Vienna, Austria
<BR>
17 - 21 November  1997</I></B>
<P>
<B>INFORMATION SHEET</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<OL>
<B><LI>Objectives of the Symposium</B>
<P>
The purpose of the Symposium is to exchange experience and lessons learned in fire safety assessment and backfitting for nuclear power plants in operation, especially those built to earlier standards. The Symposium will focus on various fire safety reviews and audits as a means of identifying deficiencies as well as on the process implementing appropriate safety improvements, whereby effective methods, practices and criteria applied in the fire safety assessment and upgrading will be addressed. The Symposium is intended to provide assistance to all those involved in maintaining the fire safety of NPPs (i.e. plant owners/operators, regulators, designers, technical support organizations and manufacturers).
<P>
<B><LI>Background</B>
<P>
Lessons learned from experience in nuclear power plant operation indicate that fires in NPPs pose a real threat to nuclear safety and that their significance extends far beyond the scope of a conventional fire hazard.
<P>
Considerable progress in design and regulatory requirements for fire safety, in fire protection technology and in related analytical techniques has been made in the past two decades. Substantial efforts have been undertaken worldwide to implement these advances in the interest of improving fire safety both at new nuclear power plants and at those in operation.
<P>
Particular attention is being given to those nuclear power plants that were designed and constructed to earlier fire protection standards. The unique requirements on fire safety of NPPs were not clearly recognized before the Browns Ferry incident in 1975. Although the general principles of fire protection were commonly acknowledged, such rules as the physical separation of redundant safe shutdown equipment or the application of fire retardant cable insulation were not strictly followed in the process of design and construction. There are plants in which the fire safety has not been sufficiently taken into consideration in the design and operation of the plants. A systematic examination of the fire safety of these plants is needed in order to identify the existing deficiencies and to implement appropriate corrective measures.
<P>
To assist in these efforts, the IAEA has initiated a project devoted to fire safety. The project, which commenced in 1993, concentrated mainly on the development of guidelines for examining, item by item, the adequacy of overall fire safety arrangements for a plant. During the period 1993-94 the project's tasks focused on the development of a Safety Guide on "Fire Safety during Operation of Nuclear Power Plants". This Safety Guide formulates specific requirements addressed at the plant management and regulatory organizations with regard to the fire safety of nuclear power plants in operation and recommends means to effectively implement such requirements. In the course of preparing this Guide, several Safety Practice documents developed to assist in its implementation. They address the inspection of various elements of fire protection programmes at NPPs including hardware, organization and management and fire hazard analyses. Two Safety Practice documents on the preparation of fire safety analyses (deterministic and probabilistic) are under development.
<P>
It has been recognized that the expertise of a systematic independent assessment of fire safety of a NPP may not always be available to a number of Member States with operating NPPs. In order to assist in enhancing fire safety, the IAEA has already started to offer a number of services to Member States such as fire safety review missions of varying scope.
<P>
This topical Symposium is intended to provide further assistance in enhancing fire safety of the operating nuclear power plants designed and constructed to earlier standards. The Symposium will be a forum for the exchange of practical experience in the systematic assessment of fire safety at NPPs and in the backfitting process.
<P>
<B><LI>Topics of the Symposium</B>
<P>
It is intended that the Symposium should cover all elements of the upgrading process, namely: the identification of fire safety related deficiencies, the search for the most appropriate corrective measures, and the implementation of selected engineering or organizational solutions.
<P>
Various types of reviews of fire safety and audits of plant fire protection programmes will be addressed as an effective means of identifying fire safety deficiencies. Routine reviews, periodic reviews and post-incident reviews are to be mentioned in this context. Fire safety is one of the important areas covered by special safety reviews of NPPs built to earlier standards. A systematic fire hazard analysis and recently, also risk based fire safety assessment studies provide relevant input for these reviews. Currently, work is being carried out within the IAEA project on Fire Safety to provide assistance in the preparation of such studies. Their role in the identification of fire safety deficiencies will be one of the topics of the Symposium.
<P>
The systematic assessment of fire related incidents is another source of information on the fire safety of the plant. Lessons learned from fire may lead to the identification of plant deficiencies that are difficult to discover by routine or periodic fire safety inspections. Fire incident reporting and assessment, exchange of information and related databases are the important topics covered by the Symposium. These topics are also addressed in the current activities of the IAEA project on Fire Safety.
<P>
The basis for the acceptability of fire safety upgrading measures is an important element in the selection of the most appropriate corrective measures and their justification. The regulatory approach to fire safety backfitting will therefore be addressed at the Symposium. The role of the performance based regulatory approach is considered as one of the Symposium topics.
<P>
Finally, the Symposium is expected to provide information on the lessons learned from the implementation phase.
<P>
In the context of the above objectives and background of the Symposium, papers should address one or more of the following topics. For each of these topics, suggested subtopics are also listed.
<P>
<DL>
<DT><I>(a) Fire safety reviews of operational plants</I>
<P>
<DD>- methods and criteria, 
<DD>- scope of the reviews, 
<DD>- the use of the risk-based fire safety assessment, 
<DD>- deficiencies identified (statistics and examples).
<P>
<DT><I>(b) A Analysis of fire related incidents</I>
<P>
<DD>- reporting of fire incidents,
<DD>- related databases,
<DD>- dissemination and exchange of information,
<DD>- root cause analysis,
<DD>- lessons learned from fire incidents,
<DD>- data for risk-based fire safety assessment.
<P>
<DT><I>(c) Selection of corrective measures, basis for acceptability</I>
<P>
<DD>- relevant national policy,
<DD>- performance based versus prescriptive regulatory approach,
<DD>- the role and use of risk-based methods,
<DD>- cost benefit considerations.
<P>
<DT><I>(d) Implementation of the corrective measures</I>
<P>
<DD>- practical examples, 
<DD>- lessons learned.
</DL>
<P>
<B><LI>Format the Symposium</B>
<P>
Contributed papers should present information on the experience gained and lessons learned from fire safety reviews of operational plants and their backfitting. The papers should address one or more of the topics covered by the Symposium. In addition to contributed papers invited papers will be prepared to provide a summary of experience on some of the topics.
<P>
<B><LI>Participation</B>
<P>
All persons wishing to participate in the meeting are requested to complete a Participation Form and send it as soon as possible to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs or national atomic energy authority) for subsequent transmission to the Secretariat. A participant will be accepted only if the Participation Form is transmitted through the government of a Member State of the International Atomic Energy Agency or by an organization invited to participate.
<P>
Participants whose designations have been received by the IAEA will be notified directly two to three months before the meeting.
<P>
<B><LI>Expenditures</B>
<P>
As a general rule, the IAEA does not pay the cost of attendance, i.e. travel and living expenses, of participants. However, limited funds are available to help meet the cost of attendance of selected specialists mainly from <I>developing countries with low economic resources</I>. Generally, not more than one grant will be awarded to any one country.
<P>
If governments wish to apply for a grant on behalf of one of their specialist, they should address specific request to the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency to this effect. Governments should ensure that applications for grants:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) be submitted by <B>6 June 1997</B>;
<P>
<DD>(b) be accompanied by a duly completed and signed Grant Application Form.
</DL>
<P>
Applicants which do not comply with the conditions mentioned under (a) and (b) cannot be considered.
<P>
The grants awarded will be in the form of lump sums usually covering part of the costs of attendance.
<P>
No registration fee is charged to participants.
<P>
<B><LI>Papers/Posters</B>
<P>
All papers and posters - apart from invited review papers - must present <I>original</I> work; they should <I>not</I> have been published elsewhere.
<P>
<I>Deadlines for submission</I>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>(a) 	A completed <I>Form for Submission of a Paper/Poster</I> (Form "B"), together with the Participation Form (Form "A") and six copies of an extended synopsis of up to 800
words (i.e. two A4 format pages of single spaced typing or the equivalent, including
any tables or diagrams and a few pertinent references) must be sent to the competent
official authority for transmission to the Secretariat to reach it by <B>5 May 1997</B>.
<P>
The synopsis should give enough information on the contents of the proposed paper or poster to enable the selection committee to evaluate it. Introductory and general matters should not be included. The synopsis - if accepted - will be reproduced in unedited form in the Book of Extended Synopses; therefore, the original must be submitted as camera-ready copy. The general style and presentation should be as in the attached sample.
</DL>
<P>
<B>Authors should indicate on the form whether the synopses is submitted for oral presentation or for poster presentation.</B>
<P>
Authors will be informed whether their papers/posters have been accepted for presentation at a regular session on the basis of the extended synopses. The Agency however reserves the right to refuse the presentation or publication of any paper that does not meet the expectations based on the information given in the extended synopsis.
<P>
<I>Further details concerning the written and oral presentation at the meeting will be sent to all authors in due course. </I>
<P>
<B><LI>Proceedings</B>
<P>
The proceedings of the meeting will be published by the International Atomic Energy Agency as soon as possible after the meeting. They will include all papers presented, printed in full in the language of submission, together with abstracts in the original language and in English. In addition they will include extended synopses (300 word abstracts) of poster presentations. With a view to speeding up publication of the proceedings and reducing its costs, the length of the papers will be strictly limited.
<P>
<B><LI>Working languages</B>
<P>
Working languages of the meeting will be English and Russian.
<P>
<B><LI>Distribution of documents</B>
<P>
A preliminary programme of the Symposium will be sent to the participants before the meeting.
<P>
The final programme, the book of extended synopses in the original language and preprints, to the extent available, will be distributed on registration.
<P>
<B><LI>Accomodation</B>
<P>
Detailed information on accommodation and other items will be sent direct to all designated participants well in advance of the meeting.
<P>
<B><LI>Secretariat</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The address of the Secretariat is:
<P>
International Atomic Energy Agency
<BR>
IAEA-SM-345
<BR>
Vienna International Centre
<BR>
Wagramerstrasse 5
<BR>
P.O. Box 100
<BR>
A- 1400 Vienna
<BR>
Austria
<P>
	Telephone No.:	+43-1-2060 plus extension (or plus 0)
<BR>
	Telex No.:	+43-1-12645
<BR>
	Telefax No.:	+43-1-20607
	<BR>
e-mail:	Official.Mail@iaea.org

</BLOCKQUOTE>
The Scientific Secretary of the Symposium is Mr. M.J. Kulig (telephone extension 22007) Division of Nuclear Installation Safety. Meeting organization is provided by Ms. E. Piller, Conference Service Section, Division of External Relations (telephone extension 21315 or 21311).
<P>
<B><LI>Channels of communication</B>
<P>
The Participation Form and the Form for the Submission of a Paper/Poster, together with six copies of each synopsis, and, <I>if applicable</I>, the Grant Application Form, should be sent to the competent official authority (Ministry of Foreign Affairs, national atomic energy authority) for transmission to the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency.
<P>
Subsequent correspondence on scientific matters should be sent to the Scientific Secretaries and correspondence on administrative matters to the IAEA Conference Service Section.
</OL>
