<HEAD>
<TITLE>Regional Training Course on Radioimmunoscintigraphy for the Detection and Management of Cancer</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>Regional Training Course on Radioimmunoscintigraphy for the Detection and Management of Cancer</H3>
<P>
<SMALL><B>Departmento de Medicina Nuclear, Instituto Nacional de Oncolog&iacute;a y Radiobiolog&iacute;a (INOR)
<BR>
Havana, Cuba
<BR>
7 - 18 April 1997</B></SMALL>

</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Deadline for nominations:</B> 31 December 1996
<P>
<LI><B>Organizers:</B>International Atomic Energy Agency in co-operation with the Government of the
		Republic of Cuba through the Instituto Nacional de Oncolog&iacute;a y Radiobiolog&iacute;a
<P>
<LI><B>Language:</B>	The language of instruction will be Spanish and English.
<P>
<LI><B>Participation:</B>	The training course is open to 20 participants from IAEA Member States in the Latin
		America region.
<P>
<LI><B>Purpose and nature of  the course:</B>	The essential objective of the course is to introduce radioimmunoscintigraphy
		(RIS) methods using <SUP>99</SUP>Tc<SUP>m</SUP> labelled specific monoclonal antibodies for the
	detection and management of common malignant tumours such as those of the colon,
		stomach, ovary, head and neck, as well as bone marrow scintigraphy. The technique,
		which targets labelled monoclonal antibodies against tumour associated antigens is a
		convenient and non invasive method for the detection of some primary cancers as well
		as local recurrences and metastases. The course will introduce participants to the RIS
		technique, including labelling of monoclonals with <SUP>99</SUP>Tc<SUP>m</SUP>, clinical interpretation of
		results and the ways in which these would influence patient management.
<P>
		The teaching will be entrusted to international experts and IAEA staff. The main topics
		to be covered, by means of lectures, practical classes and discussion sessions include:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Production and biological properties of murine, chimeric, humanized, biospecific
sad genetically engineered monoclonal antibodies;
<P>
<DD>- Pre-clinical evaluation of Mabs;
<P>
<DD>- Radiolabelling techniques and quality control;
<P>
<DD>-	Scintigraphic techniques, QC of the gamma camera, Planar and SPECT imaging,
image processing, documentation,
<P>
<DD>- Possible complications of administration of murine monoclonal antibodies;
<P>
<DD>- Current techniques for the treatment of tumours.
</DL>
<P>
<LI><B>Participants' qualifications:	</B>The course will be open to nuclear medical physicians with strong clinical orientation
		and familiar with organ imaging procedures using planar and also (though not
		necessarily) SPECT imaging. Some experience in in whether with with <SUP>99</SUP>Tc<SUP>m</SUP> or other
		labels desirable. As the course will be held at a "train-the-trainers" level, senior
		medical academics from nuclear medicine departments are invited to apply. However,
		other nuclear medicine professionals (physicists, radiochemists, senior technologists)
		with strong clinical orientation would also be considered.
	<P>
As some lectures will be delivered in English, good knowledge of this language is also required.
<P>
<LI><B>Language certificate:</B>	In the case of countries in which Spanish is not an official or customary language,
		nominations must be accompanied by a <I>separate</I> certificate of the candidate's
		proficiency in Spanish. This certificate must be issued by a language school or cultural
		institution, or an embassy of a country in which the language of the course is spoken.
<P>
<LI><B>Application procedure:</B>	Nominations should be submitted in duplicate on the standard IAEA application forms
		for training courses. Completed forms should be endorsed by and returned through the
		of official channels established (Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the National Atomic Energy
		Authority, or the office of the United Nations Development Programme). They must
		be received by the International Atomic Energy Agency, P.O. Box 100, A-1400 Vienna,
		Austria, not later than <B>31 December 1996</B>. Nominations received after that date or
		applications which have not been routed through one of the aforementioned channels
		cannot be considered.
<P>
		Advance nominations by fax or telex are welcomed. The fax/telex should contain the
		following basic information about the candidate: name, age, academic qualifications,
		present position including exact nature of duties carried out, mailing address including
		phone/fax/telex numbers, to enable the IAEA to make a preliminary evaluation of the
		candidates.
<P>
<LI><B>Administrative and financial arrangements:</B>	Nominating governments will in due course be informed of the names of the selected 	candidates and at that time will be given full details of the procedures to be followed 	with regard to administrative and financial matters.
	<P>
During their attendance at the course, participants will receive from the IAEA a stipend
	sufficient to cover the cost of their accommodation, food and incidentals. The IAEA
	will also pay the full cost of their air travel, economy class, from their home countries
	to Havana and return to their home countries.
<P>
	The organizers of the course do not accept liability for the payment of any costs or
	compensation that my arise from damage to or loss of personal property, or from
	illness, injury, disability or death of a participant while he/she is travelling to and from
	or attending the course, and it is clearly understood that each Government, in
	nominating participants, undertakes responsibility for such coverage. Governments
	would be well advised to take out insurance against these risks.
</UL>
<P>
