<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>IAEA/FAO Interregional Training Course on Advance in Technologies for Induced Mutations in Crops</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>IAEA/FAO Interregional Training Course on Advance in Technologies for Induced Mutations in Crops</H3>
<P>
<SMALL><B>IAEA Laboratories, Seibersdorf (near Vienna), Austria
<BR>
20 May - 27 June 1997</B></SMALL>

</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Deadline for nominations:</B> 28 February 1997
<P>
<LI><B>Organizers:</B> The Training Course is organized by the International Atomic Energy Agency and
		the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
<P>
<LI><B>Language:</B>	The language of instruction will be English.

<P>
<LI><B>Participation:</B>	The Training Course is open to 25 candidates from IAEA Member States in all
		geographical regions. Preference will be given to qualified candidates from
		developing countries.
<P>
<LI><B>Purpose of the course:	</B>The objective of this training course is to train plant breeders in the application of
		mutation techniques using biotechnological tools for the improvement of crops. A
		general coverage will be given of all relevant techniques and crop types.
		Furthermore, training will be provided to use the rapid development in molecular
		techniques to facilitate characterization of generated variation and their wider
		application in breeding programmes.
<P>
<LI><B>Participants' qualifications:</B>	Participants in this course should be active plant breeders from universities, national
		agricultural research institutes and institutions responsible for nuclear applications.
		At least three years of professional experience is desirable.
		As the course will be conducted in English, the participants should have no difficulty
		in following lectures and expressing themselves in this language.
<P>
<LI><B>Nature of the course:</B>	
<DL>
<DD>A. Description of course activities:
<P>
The course will deal with general aspects of application of nuclear techniques for induced mutations to improve seed and vegetatively propagated crops, selection and characterization of mutants of various crops with the use of DNA technology and the detection and screening techniques of induced mutants in <I>in vitro</I> and <I>in vivo</I> systems.
<P>
<DD>B. Syllabus and time planning:
<P>
<I>1st and 2nd week:</I> Characteristics of mutagens. Dosimetry, radiation protection and safe handling of mutagens. Initiation of <I>in vivo</I> mutation induction experiments.
<P>
	<I>3rd and 4th week:</I> Mutation techniques in seed propagated crops.
		Evaluation of mutation induction experiments carried out in the first two weeks.
		Lectures and exercises on biotechnology and in vitro techniques.
<P>
<I>5th and 6th week:</I> Mutation techniques in vegetatively propagated crops. Lectures
		and practical training in molecular techniques. Exercises, literature studies and
		excursions to plant breeding institutes. Interpretation of results carried out during
		the course.
<P>

	Special emphasis will be given to the design of projects on mutation techniques to
		meet the breeding objectives in the participant's home institute. Discussions based
		on presentations given by the participants after consultation with technical staff and lecturers.
</DL>
<P>
<LI><B>Application procedure:</B>	Nominations may be submitted on the standard IAEA application forms for training
		courses. Completed forms should be endorsed by and returned through the official
		channels established (the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Ministry of Agriculture,
		the National Atomic Energy Authority, or the Office of the United Nations
		Development Programme). They must be received by the International Atomic
		Energy Agency, P.O. Box 100, A-1400 Vienna, Austria, not later than <B>28 February
		1997</B> . Nominations received after that date or applications which have not been
		routed through one of the aforementioned channels <I>cannot be considered</I>.
		Advance nominations by facsimile (43-1-20607), telex (1-12645) or E-mail
		Official.Mail@iaea.org are welcomed. The facsimile, telex or E-mail should
		contain the following basic information about the candidate: name, age, sex,
		academic qualifications, present position including exact nature of duties carried out,
		proficiency in English and full working address (including telex, facsimile and
		telephone numbers).
<P>
<LI><B>Language certificate:</B> 	In the case of countries in which English is not an official or customary language,
		nominations must be accompanied by a <I>separate</I> certificate of the candidate's
		proficiency in English. This certificate must be issued by a language school, a
		cultural institution or an embassy of a country in which the language of the course
		is spoken.
	<P>
<LI>
<B>Administrative and financial arrangements:	</B> Nominating Governments will be informed in due course of the names of the
		candidates who have been selected and will at that time be given full details of the
		procedure to be followed with regard to administrative and financial matters.
		<P>
During their attendance at the course, participants from developing countries eligible
		to receive technical assistance, will be provided by the IAEA with a stipend
		sufficient to cover accommodation, food and incidental expenses. The IAEA will
		also bear the full cost of their round-trip air ticket, economy class, from their home
		countries to Vienna and return. Shipment of accumulated course materials to the
		participant's home countries is not the responsibility of the IAEA.
		<P>
The organizers of the course do not accept liability for the payment of any cost or
		compensation that may arise from damage to or loss of personal property, or from
		illness, injury, disability or death of a participant while he/she is travelling to and
		from or attending the course, and it is clearly understood that each Government, in
		nominating participants, undertakes responsibility for such coverage. Governments
		would be well advised to take out insurance against these risks.
</UL>
<P>
