<HEAD>
<TITLE>Regional Training Course on Decontamination and Decommissioning of Research Reactors and Other Small Nuclear Facilities</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>Regional Training Course on Decontamination and Decommissioning of Research Reactors and Other Small Nuclear Facilities</H3>
<P>
<SMALL><B>Bucharest, Romania
<BR>
9 - 20 June 1997</B></SMALL>

</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Deadline for nominations:</B> 1 March 1997 (advance nominations by fax are welcomed)
<P>
<LI><B>Organizers:</B>International Atomic Energy Agency in co-operation with the 	Government of Romania through the National Agency for Atomic
		Energy of the Ministry of Research and Technology and the Institute
		for Physics and Nuclear Engineering.
<P>
<LI><B>Language:</B>	The language of instruction will be English and Russian (Simultaneous
		interpretation will be provided.)
<P>
<LI><B>Participation:</B>	The training course is open to 25 participants from IAEA Member
		States in the Europe region. Preference will be given to candidates
		from countries which are recipients of IAEA technical co-operation.
<P>
<LI><B>Target countries:</B>	The training course will focus on the needs of developing countries
		having research reactors already shutdown or facing retirement and
		considering decommissioning in the near future. This will also include
		small nuclear facilities typically associated with research reactors such
		as radiochemical laboratories, waste treatment and decontamination and
		storage facilities. Invited countries should ideally propose two
		candidates, one from the operators', the other from the regulators' side.
<P>
<LI><B>Purpose of the course:</B>	This training course is designed to provide information and to impart
		lessons learned from past experiences in decommissioning to
		developing Member States. In this manner, elements learned at this
		training course will assist decision making, planning and implementation
		associated with the decommissioning of research reactors and research
		facilities. This is especially true of those facilities undergoing
		decommissioning because of their ageing condition or because they are
		facing shutdown in the near term. Moreover, it is the main objective of
		this training course to demonstrate the need for early and complete
		project planning to achieve safe and cost-effective decommissioning of
		nuclear installations.

	<P>
<LI><B>Participants' qualifications:</B>	The course is designed for managers or engineers responsible for planning and implementing decommissioning programmes of research 	reactors. The course should be also useful for those involved in the
		nuclear regulatory framework, when reviewing decommissioning plans,
		inspecting decommissioning activities and confirming satisfactory
		completion of decommissioning. Participants must be fluent in English
		or Russian, and should have a university degree in science or
		engineering and ideally a minimum of three years relevant experience in
		the field of decommissioning, waste management and/or radiation
		protection techniques.
<P>
<LI><B>Nature of the course:	</B>The course covers <I>inter alia</I> decommissioning planning, including the
		selection of a strategy and the development of a decommissioning plan,
		decontamination and dismantling technologies, waste management
		aspects, and decommissioning cost estimating and financing. Besides
		the technological aspects, the course includes regulatory, safety and
		radiation protection issues of decommissioning, as well as an overview
		of national programmes in decommissioning and recommended
		international practices. Although spent fuel management is an
		important pre-requisite to the safe and timely implementation of the
		overall decommissioning process, it will not be explicitly discussed in
		the course. The course will include technical lectures by experts
		followed by discussion periods to allow an exchange of information,
		discuss and seek solutions to practical national problems. Lecturers will
		come from Member States with well developed decommissioning
		programmes as well as from the IAEA. In addition to course lectures,
		technical visits and relevant video films are also planned. A short
		survey of the national decommissioning experience is expected to be
		presented by the participants for discussion. A syllabus of the course is
		attached.
<P>
<LI><B>Application procedure:</B>	Nominations may be submitted on the standard IAEA application form
		for training courses. Completed forms should be endorsed by and
		returned through the official channels established (the Ministry of
		Foreign Affairs, the National Atomic Energy Authority, or the Office of
		the United Nations Development Programme). They must be received
		by the International Atomic Energy Agency, P.O. Box 100, A-1400
		Vienna, Austria, not later than <B>1 March 1997</B>. Nominations received
		after that date or applications which have not been routed through one
		of the aforementioned channels cannot be considered.
<P>
		Advance nominations by facsimile (43-1-20607) or telex (1-12645) are
		welcomed. The facsimile/telex should contain the following basic
		information about the candidate: name, age, academic qualifications,
		present position including exact nature of duties carried out, proficiency
		in English or Russian, and full working address (including
		telephone/facsimile/telex numbers).
<P>
<LI><B>Language certificate:</B>	In the case of countries in which English or Russian are not an official
		or customary language, nominations must be accompanied by a <I>separate</I>
		certificate of the candidate's proficiency in English or Russian. This
		certificate must be issued by a language school, a cultural institution or
		an embassy of a country in which the language of the course is spoken.
	<P>
<LI><B>Administrative and financial arrangements:	</B>Nominating Governments will be informed in due course of the names
		of the candidates who have been selected and will at that time be given
		full details of the procedures to be followed with regard to
		administrative and financial matters.
<P>
		During their attendance at the course, participants from developing
		countries eligible to receive technical assistance will receive from the
		IAEA a stipend sufficient to cover the cost of their accommodation,
		food and incidental expenses. The IAEA will also bear the full cost of
		their round-trip air ticket, economy class, from their home countries to
		Bucharest and return. Shipment of accumulated course materials to the
		participants' home countries is not the responsibility of the IAEA.
	<P>
	The organizers of the course do not accept liability for the payment of
		any cost or compensation that may arise from damage to or loss of
		personal property, or from illness, injury, disability or death of a
		participant while he/she is travelling to and from or attending the
		course, and it is clearly understood that each Government, in
		nominating participants, undertakes responsibility for such coverage.
		Governments would be well advised to take out insurance against these
		risks.
</UL>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<CENTER>
<B>Syllabus</B>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<CENTER>
<B>Regional Training Course on Decontamination and Decommissioning of Research Reactors and Other Small Nuclear Facilities</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><B>Part A</B>
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 1</I>	Introduction and general information (5 hours)
<P>
<DD>1.1	Course opening, overview of the course, introduction of participants
<P>
<DD>1.2	Role of the IAEA in decommissioning of nuclear facilities, including
	technical co-operation activities
<P>
<DT><I>	Module 2</I>	International perspective (4.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>2.1	 Guidance in safety and radiation protection criteria in
decommissioning
<P>
<DD>2.2 	Guidance in safety and radiation protection criteria in
		waste management
<P>
<DD>	2.3Clearance levels. National policies and international recommendations
<P>
<DT><I>	Module 3</I>	Responsibilities and functions of parties (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>3.1	Licensee
<P>
<DD>3.2	Regulatory body
<P>
<DD>3.3	Other involved parties
<P>
<DT><I>	Module 4</I>	Decommissioning planning (9 hours)
<P>
<DD>4.1	Facility characterization (4.5 hours)
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Physical status
<DD>- Radioactive inventory
<DD>- Hazardous materials
<DD>- Radiation and contamination levels
</DL>
<P>
<DD>4.2	Assessment of alternative strategies (3 hours)
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Conceptual design alternatives
<DD>- Risk assessment for various strategies
<DD>- Feasibility studies
</DL>
<P>
<DD>4.3	Preliminary/detailed planning (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Sequencing of activities
<DD>- Identification of essential services/systems
<DD>- Procedures for corrective/remedial action
</DL>
<P>
<DT><I>Module 5</I> 	Decommissioning waste management (4.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>5.1	Assessment of amounts and characteristics of decommissioning waste
<P>
<DD>5.2	Procedures for conditioning, packaging, storage, transport and
	disposal
<P>
<DD>5.3	Compliance with radioactive waste management standards
<P>
<DD>5.4	Recycling/reuse of decommissioning materials / waste
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 6</I>	Decontamination (3 hours)
<P>
<DD>6.1	Need for and extent of decontamination
<P>
<DD>6.2	Decontamination techniques
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- Chemical processes
<DD>- Mechanical processes
<DD>- Electropolishing
<DD>- Other
</DL>
<P>
<DD>6.3	Selection of optimal decontamination technique
<P>
<DD>6.4	Planning and execution of a decontamination campaign
<P>
<DT><I>	Module 7</I>	Dismantling (4.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>7.1	Metal cutting techniques
<P>
<DD>7.2	Concrete removal
<P>
<DD>7.3	Intact removal of large components
<P>
<DD>7.4	Remotely-controlled operations
<P>
<DD>7.5	Selection of optimal technique
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 8</I>	Costs (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>8.1	Elements of decommissioning costs
<P>
<DD>8.2	Cost estimating guidelines
<P>
<DD>8.3	Financing approaches
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 9</I>	Long-term integrity of structures and systems (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DT><I>	Module 10</I> 	Safety and radiation protection aspects (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>10.1	Unexpected occurrences
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- safety assessment prevention
<DD>- mitigation
</DL>
<P>
<DD>10.2	Radiation protection of the workforce
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- radiation monitoring
<DD>- protective features
<DD>- occupational exposures
</DL>
<P>
<DD>10.3	Public exposures and other environmental impacts during
	decommissioning
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 11</I>	Decommissioning management (3 hours)
<P>
<DD>11.1 Organization and staffing
<P>
<DD>11.2	Training
<P>
<DD>11.3	Quality assurance/quality control
<P>
<DD>11.4	Record-keeping and reporting
<P>
<DD>11.5	Security
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 12</I> 	Completion of decommissioning (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DD>12.1	Post-decommissioning surveys to verify compliance with release 	criteria
<P>
<DD>	12.2	Licence termination
<P>
<DT><I>Module 13	</I> Decommissioning of nuclear laboratories and other facilities supporting research reactors (1.5 hours)
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 14</I>	Decommissioning experience (4.5 hours)
<P>
<DT>	<I>Module 15	</I> Working sessions and group discussion including review of national
	programmes (4 hours)
<P>
<DT>
<B>	Part B	Technical visit (4  hours)</B>
<P>
Technical visit to a research reactor for which decommissioning is planned, and ancillary facilities including waste treatment, conditioning and storage facilities.
</DL>
<P>
