<HEAD>
<TITLE>Post-graduate Regional Training Course on Radiation Protection and Nuclear Safety</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Arial, Helvetica">
<A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/index.html">Meetings Calendar</A>  | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/1996meet/">1996 Meetings</A> |  <A HREF="1997meet/index.html">1997 Meetings</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/training/training.html">Training Courses</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/november.pdf">Meetings Schedule</A> | <A HREF="/worldatom/thisweek/preview/general.html">General Information</A>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>Post-graduate Regional Training Course on Radiation Protection and Nuclear Safety</H3>
<P>
<SMALL><B>Buenos Aires, Argentina
<BR>
1 April - 15 August 1997 (Module I: Radiation Protection)
<BR>
18 August - 24 October 1997 (Module II: Nuclear Safety)</B></SMALL>

</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Deadline for nominations:</B> 15 January 1997.
<P>
<LI><B>Organizers:</B>	International Atomic Energy Agency in co-operation
		with the Government of the Republic of Argentina
		through the Ente Nacional Regulador Nuclear, the
		Ministerio de Salud y Acci&oacute;n Social, and the
		Universidad de Buenos Aires.
<P>
<LI><B>Language:</B>	Spanish.
<P>
<LI><B>Participation:</B> The training course of open to 30 participants. Of the 30 places, 15 will be taken by Argentine nationals
	while the remaining 15 will be offered by the IAEA to
	candidates designated by it. Member States of the
		Latin America and the Caribbean region.
		For Module II (Nuclear Safety) only candidates from
		Member States where nuclear reactors (power or
		research) are in operation or in the planning stage
		will be considered.
<P>
<LI><B>Purpose of the course:</B>	The purpose of the Module on Radiation Protection is
		to meet the educational and initial training
		requirements of graduate level staff or earmarked 
for
		positions in radiation protection including health
		physics. The target audience i. young professionals
		needing to acquire a sound basis in radiation
		protection and knowledge of related nuclear safety
		fundamentals in order to become, in the course of
		time, leaders and trainee in the protection of the
		health and safety of workers and the public from the
		hazards due to exposure to ionizing radiation.
		The purpose of the Module on Nuclear Safety is to
		provide basic knowledge on safety on nuclear 
reactors,
		including system analysis for staff with regulatory
		functions such as licensing and inspection of 
nuclear
		facilities as well as for staff operating the
		facilities.

<P>
<LI><B>Participants' qualifications:</B> Candidates should have a formal education to a level

		equivalent to a university degree in the physical
		and/or biological sciences or engineering and 
should
		have been selected to work, the future, in the 
field
		of radiation protection in their country. Only
		candidates with a proficiency in verbal and written
		Spanish are eligible to be considered for 
selection.
		Participants will be expected to prepare a written
		summary of the approximate number and types of
		radiation sources in use in their country, and a 
brief
		description of the National Programme for radiation
		protection control.
<P>
<LI><B>Nature of the course:</B>	The course will consist of lectures, study, 
discussion
		and work sessions, laboratory and field exercises, 
and
		examinations. It will be designed to provide both
		theoretical and practical training in the 
fundamental
		physical, biological and mathematical basis of
		international recommendations on radiation 
protection
		standards and their implementation. The focus of 
the
		practical work will be on the technical and
		administrative framework that is necessary for
		regulatory and operational controls designed to
		protect the health and safety of workers and the
		public from hazards that may be caused by exposure 
to
		sources of ionizing radiation commonly used in
		industry, medicine, agriculture and research. A
		syllabus of the subjects that will be addressed is
		attached.
<P>
<LI><B>Application procedures:</B>	Nominations should be submitted on the standard 
IAEA
		application forms for training courses. Completed
		forms should be endorsed by and returned through 
the
		official channels (Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the
		national Atomic Energy Authority, or the Office of 
the
		United Nations Development Programme). Applications
		must be received by the International Atomic Energy
		Agency, P.O. Box 100, A-1400, Vienna, Austria, not
		later than <B>15 January 1997</B>. Nominations received
		after that date or not routed through one of the
		aforementioned channels, cannot be considered.
		Advance nominations by fax or telex are welcomed. 
The
		fax/telex should contain the following basic
		information about the candidate: name, age, 
academic
		qualifications, present position including exact
		nature of duties carried out, proficiency in 
Spanish,
		mailing address including phone/fax/telex numbers.
<P>
<LI><B>Administrative and financial arrangements:</B> Nominating Governments will be informed in due course of the names of the candidate" who have been selected and will at that time be given full details of the procedure to be followed with regard to administrative and financial matters.
<P>
During their attendance at the course, the 15 participants sponsored by the IAEA will receive a monthly allowance adequate to cover their coats of lodging and maintenance. The IAEA will also pay the full cost of their air travel, economy class, from their home countries to Buenos Aires and return. Nominating Governments must be prepared to defray the coat of shipment of accumulated course materials to the participants' home countries.
<P>
Neither the Argentine authorities nor the IAEA accept any responsibility for solving problems associated with participants' lodging or with their stay in Argentine; however, all possible assistance will be given to them to resolve any difficulties that may arise.
<P>
The organizers of the course do not accept liability for the payment of any cost or compensation that may arise from damage to or loss of personal property, or from illness, injury, disability or death of a participant while he/she is travelling to and from or attending the course, and it is clearly understood that each Government, in nominating participants, undertakes responsibility for such coverage. Governments would be well advised to take out insurance against these risks.
</OL>
<P>
