<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
INDUSTRIAL APPLICATIONS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Industrial Applications
</H2>
<P>
<H3>
RADIATION PROCESSING
</H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>
Applications of Isotopes and Radiation in
Conservation of the Environment
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium, Karlsruhe, 9-13 March 1992. The
objective was to review present knowledge of the applications of
radiation, radioisotopes and nuclear methods of analysis in the
monitoring and control of environmental pollution and in reducing
emissions of environmentally toxic substances. Isotopes and
radiation have many characteristics which uniquely contribute to
the better understanding of environmental processes, as well as
directly protect the environment from the impact of toxic
substances. These kinds of applications form the focus of this
volume.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Overviews of some main areas of application of
nuclear
techniques; Flue gas purification; Radiation processing of liquid
and solid wastes; Industrial applications; Radiotracer studies;
Major analytical techniques and new approaches in environmental
monitoring and research; Nuclear analytical techniques and their
applications: 1. Atmospheric studies; 2. Studies of solid wastes,
sediments and soils; 3. Hydrochemical and miscellaneous
studies; Panel: Current problems and future trends in the use of
isotopes and radiation for conservation of the environment.
<P>
STI/PUB/904 (699 pp., 221 figures; 1992)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-000492-X
<BR>
Price: 1900 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
High Dose Dosimetry
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium, Vienna, 8-12 October 1984. Radiation
dosimetry provides reliable quality control of radiation
processes and is the basis for regulatory acceptance of
irradiation products. This symposium, the first of its kind, was
therefore designed to be of particular interest to scientists
developing dosimetry and dose assurance techniques for both
research and applied industry. The papers presented at the
meeting discussed the expectations of industry, the problems
facing dosimetry, the concern of industrialists and their
activities, thoughts and hopes for the future.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> General aspects; Dosimetry techniques and
systems;
Dose
standardization and calibration, physical aspects.
<P>
STI/PUB/671 (449 pp., 248 figures; 1985)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-010085-6
<BR>
Price: 1060 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
High Dose Dosimetry for Radiation Processing
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium, the second in its field, Vienna, 5-9
November 1990. Reliable dosimetry is a key parameter for
quality assurance of radiation processing and irradiated
products. The standardization of dosimetry provides a basis for
the regulatory approval of irradiated products and for
international clearance for free trade. Papers presented at the
meeting discussed the development of new techniques, the
improvement of reference and routine dosimetry systems and the
quality control and assurance of dosimetry presenting an
authoritative account of the status of high dose dosimetry
throughout the world in 1990.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> General aspects; Development of dosimetry
techniques;
Reference dosimetry and review of dosimetry techniques; Quality
control and assurance of dosimetry.
<P>
STI/PUB/846 (513 pp., 217 figures; 1991)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-010291-3
<BR>
Price: 1380 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>

High Dose Measurements in Industrial
Radiation Processing
<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 205</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of an Advisory Group meeting, Vienna, 25-29 September
1978. The publication reproduces in full all scientific working
papers presented at the meeting, gives a review of the results of
a comprehensive intercomparison and concludes with the
recommendations of the panel members.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> 1. Introduction; 2. The IAEA high-dose
standardization and intercomparison programme; 3. Working papers;
4. A
review of the results of the comprehensive intercomparison 1978;
5. Recommendations.
<P>
STI/DOC/10/205 (239 pp., 139 figures; 1981)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-010581-0
<BR>
Price: 500 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
<A NAME=6>Industrial Application of Radioisotopes and Radiation
Technology
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I></A>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a conference, Grenoble, France, 28 September to 2
October 1981. Applications of nuclear techniques, in particular
radioisotope and radiation technology, were reviewed with
emphasis on the role of these technologies in energy saving, in
conserving and exploring for resources and in protecting the
environment. Promising new applications of radiation technology
included radiation treatment of sewage sludge for municipal water
and exhaust gases, while advanced applications in areas such as
the polymer industry, the manufacture of disposable medical
supplies and the production and preservation of food were
described. The value of the application of nuclear techniques in
the exploration of resources such as coal, uranium, natural gas
and petroleum was emphasized. Nucleonic control systems were
reported to be an increasingly important technique for industrial
process control purposes.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Use of nuclear technology in exploration,
processing
and the recycling of resources; Industrial radiation processing;
Nuclear technology for environmental conservation; Radiation
technology for bioengineering; Use of nuclear technology for
industrial process and quality control; Equipment facilities and
services; Technology transfer to developing countries; Economic  

             
benefits of nuclear technology.
<P>
STI/PUB/598 (595 pp., 190 figures; 1982)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-060082-4
<BR>
Price: 1180 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<HR>
<P>
