<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 216</I>
</B>
<P>
This report is essentially a companion document to Safety Series
No. 53, Shallow Ground Disposal of Radioactive Wastes: A
Guidebook,
published by the IAEA in 1981.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> 1. Introduction; 2. Scope; 3. Waste and disposal
concepts; 4. Shallow ground disposal objectives and siting
considerations; 5. Overview of investigations for site selection;
6. Earth science investigative needs; 7. Techniques for earth
science investigations; 8. Safety analysis; 9. Other studies;
References; Bibliography; Glossary.
<P>
STI/DOC/10/216 (89 pp., 3 figures; 1982)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-125382-6
<BR>
Price: 260 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
Site Investigations, Design, Construction, Operation, Shutdown
and
Surveillance of Repositories for Low and Intermediate Level
Radioactive Wastes in Rock Cavities
<BR>
<I>Safety Series No. 62</I>
</B>
<P>
This document is a follow-up report to IAEA Safety Series No. 59,
Disposal of Low and Intermediate Level Solid Radioactive Wastes
in
Rock Cavities -- A Guidebook, which reviewed and gave general
guidelines on the subject. The present publication is more
technical in its approach.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Introduction; Scope; Basic considerations;
Safety
assessments; Site investigations; Design, construction and
commissioning; Repository operation; Shutdown of the repository;
Surveillance of repositories.
<P>
STI/PUB/659 (92 pp., 8 figures; 1984)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-123284-5
<BR>
Price: 300 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
Siting, Design and Construction of Underground Repositories for
Radioactive Wastes
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium, Hannover, Germany, 3-7 March 1986.
The
purpose was to review advances made in the area of siting, design
and construction of underground repositories for radioactive
wastes
and to consider developments of future importance. Forty-nine
papers were presented, covering general approaches and regulatory
aspects, disposal in shallow ground and rock cavities, disposal
in
deep geological formations and safety assessments.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Keynote address: Are we ready to construct and
operate an underground repository? General approaches and
regulatory aspects; Disposal in shallow ground and rock cavities;
Disposal in deep formations: Investigations on sites; Disposal in
deep formations: Repository designs; Safety assessment; Pane I:
Performance and safety assessments and their interactions with
field investigations of deep geological repositories; Overview of
symposium.
<P>
STI/PUB/715 (727 pp., 217 figures; 1986)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-020286-1
<BR>
Price: 1780 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
Techniques for Site Investigations for Underground Disposal of
Radioactive Wastes
<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 256</I>
</B>
<P>
The techniques described in the present report can be applied in
site investigations for either shallow or deep repositories. The
report is addressed to technical authorities responsible for or
involved in planning, approving, executing and reviewing national
waste disposal programmes. It may also help administrative
authorities in this field to select appropriate techniques that
are
technically feasible and economically advantageous for obtaining,
under specific conditions, the majority of the required
information
at minimum cost.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Introduction; Scope; Initial investigations at
the
surface; Borehole drilling and characterization; Measurement of
hydrogeological parameters; Determination of geochemical
parameters; Measurement of parameters for engineering feasibility
studies; Bibliography.
<P>
STI/DOC/10/256 (62 pp.; 1985)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-125785-6
<BR>
Price: 210 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
Underground Disposal of Radioactive Wastes: Basic Guidance
<BR>
<I>Safety Series No. 54</I>
</B>
<P>
The present publication is part of the IAEA programme on the
disposal of radioactive waste into geological formations and
gives
background guidance on the wide variety of potential waste types
and forms, and on the differing technical and environmental
aspects
of the disposal options. 
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Introduction; Scope; Basic objectives and
principles of radioactive waste disposal; Types and conditioning
of
radioactive waste; Underground disposal options; Technical
considerations in selecting a waste disposal option; Major stages
in the implementation of a waste disposal option; Glossary of
terms
used.
