<P>
<B> 
Reactivity Accidents
<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 354</I>
</B>
<P>
(See under <A HREF=npp.html#71>Nuclear Power Plants</A>.)
<P>
<B>
Risks and Benefits of Energy Systems
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium organized in co-operation with UNEP
and WHO, J&uuml;lich, Germany, 9-13 April 1984. The role of
energy in the economy and in society, the risks and impacts of
energy production, cost effective measures to reduce risks and
national energy strategies in response to global constraints were
discussed. Decisions on energy systems have to be based on an
assessment of many different aspects regarding their risks and
benefits. Many case studies were presented and it was shown that
it is of the utmost importance to list all the assumptions made
and to discuss the uncertainties and limitations of the analysis.
Comparison of risks of energy systems lead to a definite rank
ordering per unit of energy produced, but risks are only one
aspect in defining an appropriate energy mix. In order to allow
for efficient risk management it is important to apply cost
effectiveness techniques to various options for reducing risks.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I>  Energy, economy and society; Panel 1: Energy
and societal goals; Risks and impacts of energy systems; Risk
management; Panel 2: Risk management; Low probability/high
consequence risks; National energy strategies in response to
global constraints; Panel 3: Risks, benefits and decisions.
<P>
STI/PUB/668 (671 pp., 155 figures; 1984)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-020784-7
<BR>
Price: 1560 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B>
<A NAME=34>Safety Analysis Methodologies for Radioactive Waste
Repositories
in Shallow Ground</A>  
<BR>
<I>Safety Series No. 64</I>
</B>
<P>
